var QUESTIONS = [{"id":"00006","lastEdit":"30/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"On this approach chart for Fairbanks Alaska there is a snowflake symbol, what does this indicate?","options":{"A":"It indicates the maximum temperature allowed for this approach","B":"It indicates mandatory altitude corrections are to be applied at or below this temperature","C":"It indicates the minimum temperature allowed for this approach","D":"It indicates the ILS transmitter minimum temperature for operation"},"answer":"B","reference":"LIDO LAT 1.7.3.4.2 IAC Plan View"},{"id":"00007","lastEdit":"23/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which of the following is true when the flight control system is operating in secondary mode?","options":{"A":"The primary flight computers (PFCs) are not available","B":"Actuator control electronics (ACEs) are not available","C":"Autopilot and envelope protection are not available","D":"Envelope protection features are available"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Primary Flight Control System Modes, Flight Control System Secondary Mode"},{"id":"00020","lastEdit":"18/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"What happens if EICAS TCAS RA CAPTAIN is displayed?","options":{"A":"TCAS is incapable of displaying RA guidance on the Captain's PFD","B":"TCAS is incapable of displaying RA traffic symbols on the Captain's ND","C":"TCAS is incapable of displaying RA traffic symbols on the F/O's ND","D":"TCAS is incapable of displaying RA guidance on the F/O's PFD"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, EICAS Messages, Warning Systems EICAS Messages, TCAS"},{"id":"00106","lastEdit":"16/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"You're operating a flight to a destination with a scheduled block time of 8 hours with two flight crew members. How do you calculate your FDP?","options":{"A":"OMA 7.21.2 (Calculation of a flying duty period - cabin crew)","B":"OMA 7.6.2 (Max FDP)","C":"Refer to table OMA 7.9.3 (Limits on two flight crew long range ops), then appropriate table from OMA 7.6.2 (Max FDP)","D":"Ask the Purser"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.9.3 Limits on two flight crew long range ops. OMA 7.6.2 Max FDP"},{"id":"00182","lastEdit":"07/03/2024","category":"other","question":"If an airspeed unreliable event occurs on take-off, what does the FCTM guidance state?","options":{"A":"Maintain take-off thrust, smoothly rotate towards 15 degrees pitch, retract the landing gear and maintain flap configuration, climb at the normal take-off pitch attitude until acceleration height and then complete the Airspeed Unreliable NNC","B":"Set 85% N1, smoothly rotate towards 10 degrees pitch, retract the landing gear and maintain flap configuration, climb at the normal take-off pitch attitude until acceleration height and then complete the Airspeed Unreliable NNC","C":"Maintain take-off thrust, smoothly rotate towards 15 degrees pitch, retract the landing gear and maintain flap configuration, climb at the normal take-off pitch attitude until acceleration height and then complete the Airspeed Unreliable memory items","D":"Set 85% N1, smoothly rotate towards 10 degrees pitch, retract the landing gear and maintain flap configuration, climb at the normal take-off pitch attitude until acceleration height and then complete the Airspeed Unreliable memory items"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCTM 8, Non Normal, Air Data Systems Unreliable, Airspeed Unreliable"},{"id":"00223","lastEdit":"28/12/2023","category":"other","question":"What are some examples of required visual references for a visual approach? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Visual with the touchdown zone markings","B":"Visual with the terrain","C":"Visual with the runway environment or a preceding identified aeroplane shall be maintained throughout the approach","D":"Visual with the runway environment"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.2 Required Visual References"},{"id":"00237","lastEdit":"20/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When landing on a flat nose gear tire, what does the FCTM guidance instruct?","options":{"A":"Slowly and gently lower the nose wheels to the runway whilst braking moderately, use full reverse thrust, autobrakes may be used on medium settings, vibration levels may be affected by decreasing or increasing the control column back pressure, hold the nose gear off the runway until 100 knots","B":"Slowly and gently lower the nose wheels to the runway whilst braking firmly, use full reverse thrust, autobrakes may be used on high settings, vibration levels may be affected by decreasing or increasing the control column back pressure, maintain nose gear contact with the runway","C":"Slowly and gently lower the nose wheels to the runway whilst braking lightly, use idle reverse thrust, autobrakes may be used on light settings, vibration levels may be affected by decreasing or increasing the control column back pressure, hold the nose gear off the runway until 100 knots","D":"Slowly and gently lower the nose wheels to the runway whilst braking lightly, runway length permitting use idle reverse thrust, autobrakes may be used on lower settings, vibration levels may be affected by decreasing or increasing the control column back pressure, maintain nose gear contact with the runway"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM 8 Non Normal, Landing Gear, Landing on a flat tire"},{"id":"00309","lastEdit":"25/06/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding Long Range Cruise? (LRC)","options":{"A":"LRC is a variable speed schedule providing the fuel mileage 1% less than the maximum available. The FMC does apply wind corrections to LRC","B":"LRC is a fixed speed schedule providing the fuel mileage 1% less than the maximum available. The FMC does not apply wind corrections to LRC","C":"LRC is a variable speed schedule providing the maximum range for long range operations. It is equivalent to cost index zero. The FMC does apply wind corrections to LRC","D":"LRC is a variable speed schedule providing the fuel mileage 1% less than the maximum available. The FMC does not apply wind corrections to LRC"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM, Climb Cruise Descent and Holding, Cruise, Cruise Speed Determination"},{"id":"00322","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What is the flight crew report time at outstation for an LRV flight?","options":{"A":"STD-1:23","B":"STD-1:00","C":"STD-1:15","D":"STD-1:25"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.E.2 Annex 7.E: LRV - Key Rules and Conditions"},{"id":"00400","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Cold weather temperature altitude corrections have to be applied for which minimum safe altitudes/heights in ISA -30 or colder?","options":{"A":"En route minimum safe altitudes, Approach Minima (DA/MDA)","B":"En route minimum safe altitudes, Approach Minima (DA/MDA), All approach procedure altitudes (IAF, IF, FAP etc)","C":"Approach Minima (DA/MDA)","D":"En route minimum safe altitudes"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.4.1 Aeronautical Information, Met and DIG, Altitude Corrections, General Cold Altitude Corrections"},{"id":"00746","lastEdit":"19/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"When faced with an MEL or CDL with an en-route climb penalty and you opt to fly a different speed than the maximum lift to drag ratio, how can you adjust the en-route climb penalty to ensure performance requirements are met?","options":{"A":"Multiply the penalty by the factor listed in the table in MEL>CDL>Introduction>Enroute Diversion Speed Effects","B":"The enroute climb penalty is never limiting, even in the Himalayan region","C":"Use the graph in RAIG>B777 Performance>Degradation Report","D":"Multiply the penalty by a factor of 3"},"answer":"A","reference":"MEL, CDL, Introduction, Enroute Diversion Speed Effects"},{"id":"00752","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"both","question":"What should a commander do when faced with a sick passenger on ground at the boarding stage?","options":{"A":"Make a PA for a Doctor, nurse, paramedic or midwife","B":"If life threatening contact ground medical services, if not life threatening accept them to travel","C":"If life threatening contact the local emergency medical services and ground medical services, if not life threatening contact ground medical services","D":"Offload them and tell them to contact the airport medical team"},"answer":"C","reference":"OME 11.4.1 Requesting medical support for an on ground medical emergency"},{"id":"00775","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"When a destination is affected by GPS signal interference and there is a CONOTAM enabling use of the QRH procedure, which actions are taken in the procedure? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"GND PROX TERR OVRD - NORM, GPS NAV - OFF, RAD NAV INHIBIT - ON, For all approaches select RNP value of 1","B":"GND PROX TERR OVRD - OVRD, MMR left and right - pull CB and push after waiting 15 seconds, RAD NAV INHIBIT - OFF, For ILS approaches select RNP value of 1","C":"GND PROX TERR OVRD - NORM, RAD NAV INHIBIT - OFF, For approaches select RNP value of 1, crew shall select POS display to reveal map shift errors","D":"GND PROX TERR OVRD - OVRD, GPS NAV - OFF, RAD NAV INHIBIT - OFF, For ILS approaches select RNP value of 1, crew shall select POS display to reveal map shift errors"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Operational information, Other Procedures, Departure or Destination Airport Affected by GPS signal interference"},{"id":"00800","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"What can you say about the EICAS FLAPS DRIVE message?","options":{"A":"The EICAS flap indicator display turns magenta","B":"The flaps will operate in the alternate mode","C":"The flaps will operate in the secondary mode","D":"The message is displayed when the flap drive mechanism has been shut down due to an asymmetry"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Flaps and Slats, Flap and Slat Asymmetry Detection"},{"id":"00865","lastEdit":"30/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"In which document can you find the Crew Oxygen Requirments?","options":{"A":"Maintenance Manual","B":"MEL","C":"FCOM Perfomance Dispatch","D":"QRH NNC CREW OXYGEN LOW"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Performance Dispatch, Section 777-300ER, Enroute, Crew Oxygen Requirements"},{"id":"01384","lastEdit":"06/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"When should flight crew state 'MAYDAY MAYDAY MAYDAY FUEL' to ATC?","options":{"A":"When the EICAS FUEL QTY LOW is triggered","B":"When calculated usable fuel on landing at the nearest adequate aerodrome where a safe landing can be made is less than the final reserve fuel","C":"When having committed to land at specific aerodrome the flight crew calculates that any change to the existing clearance to that aerodrome may result in landing with less than the planned reserve fuel","D":"When having committed to land at specific aerodrome the flight crew calculates that any change to the existing clearance to that aerodrome may result in landing with less than the planned FMC RSV fuel"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.5 Mayday Fuel"},{"id":"01596","lastEdit":"10/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Aircraft approach category is based on?","options":{"A":"Approach speed (VREF)","B":"Nominal threshold speed","C":"Aircraft gear height","D":"Aircraft weight"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCTM 5 Approach Category + LIDO 1.4.5.2 Aircraft Category (LIDO page 1524)"},{"id":"01666","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the correct course of action during a resolution advisory?","options":{"A":"Flight crew shall contact ATC for clarification","B":"Flight crew shall follow all traffic advisories except if traffic has been sighted visually in night VMC","C":"Flight crew shall follow all resolution advisories even if traffic has been sighted visually","D":"Flight crew shall follow all resolution advisories except if traffic has been sighted visually in night VMC"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.6 Policy and Procedures for the use of TCAS"},{"id":"01737","lastEdit":"11/11/2023","category":"other","question":"To what distance is terrain assessed in the Himalayan region? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"5 NM either side of the flight path, except for GOT30 - DS125 and GEOFF - PURPA which is assessed to 10 NM to the northwest of the airway","B":"10 NM either side of the flight path, except for GOT30 - DS125 and GEOFF - PURPA which is assessed to 20 NM to the northwest of the airway","C":"20 NM either side of the flight path","D":"10 NM either side of the flight path"},"answer":"B","reference":"DARD, PREAMBLE, Terrain Clearance"},{"id":"01993","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"Which equipment is required for overflights of Mogadishu airspace?","options":{"A":"SELCAL, HF","B":"ACARS, Both Packs","C":"GPS, SATCOM","D":"Weather Radar, VHF"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO Somalia 3.164.3.1 Minimum Radio and Navigation Equipment (for GPS) + Network Report 2401v2 - See section on transits of Mogadishu FIR requiring CPDLC, VHFx3 and SATCOM"},{"id":"01995","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Up to what speed should the take-off be discontinued if visual reference is lost?","options":{"A":"100 knots","B":"60 knots","C":"80 knots","D":"V1"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH Operational information, Low Visibility Operation, Take-off"},{"id":"02318","lastEdit":"15/11/2023","category":"both","question":"What guidance in the FCTM is written about landing with manual braking on short runways?","options":{"A":"Ensure that the nosewheel is on the ground and the speedbrakes are extended before applying the brakes","B":"Use full brake pressure for short or slippery runways","C":"Initiate light wheel braking using very light pedal pressure and increase pressure as ground speed decreases","D":"Initiate light wheel braking using very light pedal pressure and decrease pressure as ground speed decreases"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCTM 6 Landing, Landing Roll, Wheel Brakes, Manual Braking"},{"id":"02432","lastEdit":"22/06/2024","category":"other","question":"When does the no contact period begin and end on arrival?","options":{"A":"It starts from extension of the landing gear and ends when the aeroplane vacates the runway","B":"It starts from extension of the landing gear and ends when the aeroplane has slowed to taxi speed","C":"It starts from the Purser PA 'Cabin Crew Prepare for Landing' and ends when the aeroplane vacates the runway","D":"It starts from the Purser PA 'Cabin Crew Prepare for Landing' and ends when the aeroplane has slowed to taxi speed"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.1.2 No Contact Period"},{"id":"02464","lastEdit":"07/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What are the earliest recognizable stall warning signs?","options":{"A":"Auto throttle wake up function","B":"Pitch envelope protection","C":"Initial buffet and stall warning horn","D":"Initial buffet or stick shaker"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM Approach to Stall or Stall"},{"id":"02506","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is NOT true regarding the definition of VMC?","options":{"A":"You can operate VMC for short periods of a flight, but not cancel IFR","B":"The definition of VMC is in the LIDO route manual","C":"Visual contact is required at all times","D":"You can operate VMC for short periods of a flight, such as visual approaches"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3 Flight Procedures, VFR/IFR Policy"},{"id":"02531","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"other","question":"On the initial climb with one engine inoperative, what speed does the flight director command?","options":{"A":"V2 to V2+10","B":"V2+15 to V2+25","C":"V2 to V2+15","D":"V2 to V2+25"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCTM 3 Take-off and Initial Climb, Take-off Engine Failure, Rotation and Liftoff - One Engine Inoperative"},{"id":"02835","lastEdit":"15/11/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which is NOT true regarding Flap and Slat operations ?","options":{"A":"Extension from up position is inhibited if the altitude is above 15000","B":"The maximum altitude with flaps extended is 20,000 feet.","C":"Slat and flap operation time in the secondary and alternate modes is greatly increased","D":"selection of flaps 1 commands the slats to move to the midrange position."},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM system description, flight controls, system description, flap & slats"},{"id":"02869","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which bus powers the main battery charger?","options":{"A":"Centre flight control PSA","B":"Right Main DC bus","C":"Left transfer Bus","D":"Ground service bus"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM 6.20 AC Electrical Power Distribution, Ground Service Bus"},{"id":"02949","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"On the OFP what is included in the Minimum Fuel Required adjacent to each waypoint?","options":{"A":"Minimum fuel required = remaining trip fuel + alternate fuel + final reserve fuel","B":"Minimum fuel required = remaining trip fuel + remaining contingency fuel + alternate fuel + final reserve fuel","C":"Minimum fuel required = remaining trip fuel + alternate fuel + final reserve fuel + 30 minutes holding above the destination alternate at 1500 feet in ISA conditions","D":"Minimum fuel required = remaining trip fuel + alternate fuel + FMC reserve fuel"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.1 In Flight Fuel Checks"},{"id":"03196","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"You are operating an 8 hour flight with 3 crewmembers, each crewmember receives 2h 20m rest each in a business class seat. what is the purposes of the extra augmenting crewmember in terms of flight duty period limitations?","options":{"A":"To extend the FDP by Split Duty","B":"To extend the FDP by In-Flight Relief","C":"To extend the FDP by Burnout","D":"To avoid the flight from being considered a multi sector flight for FDP calculation"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 7.9.3 Limits on two flight crew long range ops - if there were only two pilots this table would have to be used as part of the FDP calculation before proceeding to tables at OMA 7.6.2"},{"id":"03197","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When is a visual circuit acceptable?","options":{"A":"Base training and quick returns after departure","B":"When it is the only approach available","C":"Base training and emergencies","D":"Whenever the commander deems it safe"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.17 Selection of Approach Procedure"},{"id":"03215","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the correct CDU entry to create crossing points along the flight plan route starting with N24 degrees Latitude and every 8 degrees thereafter?","options":{"A":"N24-8","B":"N024x8","C":"N24.8","D":"N024/8"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Flight Management System Operation, Lateral Navigation, Waypoints (see manually entered latitude or longitude reporting point waypoints)"},{"id":"03243","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"On an Addis turnaround you discover a thrust reverser fault in the tech log at STD-60 in DXB. (MEL 78-31-01-02). Your flight plan includes tankering fuel to Addis landing at MLW-1%, considering the fault and destination characteristics, what action shall you take?","options":{"A":"Call operations and refuse to depart as the safety margin has been eroded","B":"Reduce or remove the tankering fuel from the flight plan to reduce landing weight, mitigating the risk of runway overrun or brake overheating","C":"Increase autobrake setting to maximum for landing to compensate for the inoperative thrust reverser","D":"Proceed with the original flight plan; trust in the remaining braking systems and runway length"},"answer":"B","reference":"OPT, Run the landing performance for Addis at MLW on a typical day, you'll find either the brakes melt or overrun occurs. Landing weight must be reduced."},{"id":"03425","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When is the EICAS message FUEL PUMP CENTER L displayed?","options":{"A":"Anytime there is no pump output pressure","B":"When the center tank is empty and the pump switch is ON","C":"When the center tank fuel pump is ON and the pump output pressure is low","D":"When the center tank contains fuel and the fuel pump switch is OFF"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, EICAS Messages, EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"03541","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"You're scheduled to fly to an airport with forecast weather that is below approach minima, what operational impacts does this have?","options":{"A":"Extra fuel must be loaded to account for delays","B":"Additional fuel must loaded to account for weather delays","C":"A second alternate must be available on the OFP","D":"The aircraft must be CAT3B capable before dispatch"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.1.6 Destination Alternate Aerodrome"},{"id":"03655","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding transits of Sanaa FIR?","options":{"A":"Minimum planned FL300, minimum FL280. Minimum equipment for dispatch: SATVOICE, SELCAL, Two VHF, one HF and both packs (pack sub-faults are not limiting)","B":"Minimum planned FL320, minimum FL300. Minimum equipment for dispatch from Dubai: SATCOM, ACARS, Three VHF, one HF and both packs (pack sub-faults are limiting)","C":"Minimum planned FL300, minimum FL280. Minimum equipment for dispatch from Dubai: SATCOM, ACARS, Three VHF and both packs (pack sub-faults are not limiting)","D":"Minimum planned FL320, minimum FL300. Minimum equipment for dispatch: SATVOICE, SELCAL, Two VHF and both packs (pack sub-faults are limiting)"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 12.3.3.4.3 Transits of Yemen/Sanaa FIR"},{"id":"03803","lastEdit":"03/06/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct about the emergency flashlight?","options":{"A":"The flashlight can be used on a daily basis","B":"They must be turned on and off by their respective switch after removing it from the bracket","C":"Removing the flashlight from it's bracket will automatically turn the flashlight on, returning the flashlight to it's bracket will automatically turn it off, the battery cannot be recharged","D":"They must be turned on and off by their respective switch after removing it from the bracket, it has a flashing light every 3-4 seconds to indicated adequate power"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, General, 1.45 Flashlights"},{"id":"03828","lastEdit":"18/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"You dispatch with MEL 52-71-01 Door Indication Systems, the engineer informs you the aft cargo door that has the problem. During the take-off roll at 75 knots you get EICAS DOOR AFT CARGO, do you reject?","options":{"A":"Yes, as the QRH states to reject for any master caution below 80 knots","B":"No, as the MEL states to expect such messages on ground and the engineer confirmed the door was closed before pushback","C":"Yes, as it's the safest course of action","D":"No, as you're approaching V1 and it's unsafe to reject for a minor issue"},"answer":"B","reference":"MEL 52-71-01 Door Indication Systems"},{"id":"03886","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does EICAS CREW OXYGEN LOW indicate?","options":{"A":"The oxygen tank valve has not been fully opened","B":"Crew oxygen system has failed","C":"Crew oxygen pressure is low","D":"An individual mask regulator has failed"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, EICAS messages, Oxygen System Messages"},{"id":"03905","lastEdit":"30/06/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement about radio tuning is correct?","options":{"A":"The offside tuning light will only appear on the active radio tuning panel","B":"Any VHF radio can be controlled by any radio tuning panel","C":"The center radio tuning panel can only be used to tune a HF radio if either the left or right panel fails","D":"HF L can only be tuned by the left radio tuning panel"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, System Description, Radio Comms Systems, VHF Comm System"},{"id":"04183","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"Can an aircraft that is NOT equipped with an NDB receiver fly an NDB approach?","options":{"A":"Yes, with GPS position updating enabled and no GPS interference is present","B":"Yes, with GPS or DME/DME position updating enabled","C":"No, as raw data monitoring requirements would not be met","D":"No, as OMA policy would not be met"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.22.2 Category I (CAT I) Approach, Approach Procedure with Vertical Guidance (APV), Non-precision Approach (without vertical guidance) states: 'the respective ground and aeroplane equipment required for the approach shall be operative prior to initiating and during the approach'"},{"id":"04262","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When flying an RNAV approach at minus 10 Celsius at the airfield do you need to apply cold weather temperature corrections? (charted approach minimum temperature limit of minus -5 Celsius)","options":{"A":"No temperature corrections are needed","B":"Yes, it is outside the temperature window for the charted approach, you must fly it to LNAV minima with temperature corrections","C":"Yes, it is outside the temperature window for the charted approach, you must fly it to LNAV/VNAV minima with temperature corrections","D":"No, it is within the temperature limit"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.4.1 General Cold Temperature Altitude Corrections"},{"id":"04313","lastEdit":"31/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding de-icing and anti-icing?","options":{"A":"The decision to de-ice may be made by a Qualified Person or by the flight crew. However once the decision to de-ice has been made, it cannot be over-ridden by either party","B":"The decision to de-ice may is made by the flight crew. Once the decision to de-ice has been made, it cannot be over-ridden without contact with the company tech pilot via NCC","C":"The decision to de-ice may is made by the flight crew. Once the decision to de-ice has been made, it cannot be over-ridden without contact with NCC and MCC","D":"The decision to de-ice may be made by a Qualified Person or by the flight crew. However once the decision to de-ice has been made, it cannot be over-ridden by the other party"},"answer":"D","reference":"GOM Chapter 20 De-icing / Anti-icing, Aircraft Ground De-icing/Anti-icing Procedures, 9.1 General Procedures"},{"id":"04562","lastEdit":"18/03/2024","category":"other","question":"During a balked landing what is the correct sequence of actions by the pilot flying?","options":{"A":"Call 'Go-around Set Thrust', Disengage the autopilot, Disconnect the autothrottle, Set maximum thrust, Once the pilot monitoring has called rotate at VREF pitch towards 15 degrees, once safely airborne do the normal go-around sequence","B":"Call 'Go-around Set Thrust Flap 20', Set maximum thrust, Disconnect the autothrottle, Disengage the autopilot, Once the pilot monitoring has called rotate at VR pitch towards 15 degrees, once safely airborne do the normal go-around sequence","C":"Call 'Go-around Set Thrust', Set maximum thrust, Disconnect the autothrottle, Disengage the autopilot, Once the pilot monitoring has called rotate at VR pitch towards 20 degrees, once safely airborne do the normal go-around sequence","D":"Call 'Go-around Set Thrust Flap 20', Disengage the autopilot, Disconnect the autothrottle, Set maximum thrust, Once the pilot monitoring has called rotate at VREF pitch towards 20 degrees, once safely airborne do the normal go-around sequence"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCTM 5, Approach and Missed Approach, Go-Around and Missed Approach - All Approaches"},{"id":"04755","lastEdit":"20/12/2023","category":"other","question":"During pre-flight when should ceiling be taken into account?","options":{"A":"Circling approaches and visual approaches and non-precision approaches or CAT I approaches at the destination alternate or fuel en-route alternate","B":"Circling approaches and visual approaches and only non-precision approaches approaches at the destination alternate or fuel en-route alternate","C":"Non-precision approaches and visual approaches and circling approaches at the destination airport or destination alternate","D":"Circling approaches and visual approaches and non-precision approaches or CAT I approaches at the destination airport or destination alternate or fuel en-route alternate"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.4 In Flight Minima + OMA 8.1.3.3 Pre Flight Planning Minima"},{"id":"05004","lastEdit":"16/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"Two destination alternate aerodromes shall be selected when?","options":{"A":"Windshear is expected during approach OR fog is present at ETA +/- 1 hour","B":"Fog is forecast at the destination OR thunderstorms are forecast at ETA +/- 1 hour","C":"No meteorological information is available OR destination weather is forecast to be below landing minima at ETA +/- 1 hour","D":"Thunderstorms are forecast at the destination OR windshear is forecast at ETA +/- 1 hour"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.1.6 Destination Alternate Aerodrome"},{"id":"05231","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"What can the First Officer do to regain audio control if his audio control panel fails?","options":{"A":"Position the OBS AUDIO selector to CAPT then use the Captain's audio control panel","B":"Position the OBS AUDIO selector to F/O then use the First Officer's audio control panel","C":"Position the OBS AUDIO selector to F/O for at least one second, then back to NORM and use the First Officer's audio control panel","D":"Position the OBS AUDIO selector to F/O then use the observer's audio control panel"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, Controls and Indicators, Misc Comms Controls, Observer Audio Selector"},{"id":"05236","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"other","question":"On the initial climb with two engines operating, what speed does the flight director command?","options":{"A":"V2+10","B":"V2+10 to V2+20","C":"V2 to V2+25","D":"V2+15 to V2+25"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM 3 Take-off and Initial Climb, Initial Climb - All Engines"},{"id":"05540","lastEdit":"20/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following de-icing and anti-icing fluids is primarily used for de-icing purposes only as it has a very limited hold over time?","options":{"A":"Type IV","B":"Type I","C":"Type III","D":"Type II"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3.9.3"},{"id":"05581","lastEdit":"22/05/2024","category":"other","question":"When on ground the memory items for Engine Autostart L/R are:","options":{"A":"Engine Fire switch - pull","B":"Fuel control switch - cutoff","C":"Fuel control switch - confirm - cutoff","D":"Start selector - off, Fuel control switch - cutoff"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Autostart L/R"},{"id":"05781","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Can the aileron be trimmed with the autopilot engaged?","options":{"A":"Yes, but only if both aileron trim switches are pushed simultaneously","B":"No, aileron trim is inhibited","C":"No, the autopilot will disconnect","D":"Yes"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Roll Control, Aileron Trim"},{"id":"06104","lastEdit":"23/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which type of device is not permitted to be charged onboard?","options":{"A":"A power bank with a lithium battery","B":"A smartwatch with a sodium-ion battery","C":"A tablet device with a sodium-ion battery","D":"An e-cigarette with a lithium battery"},"answer":"D","reference":"OME 3.18.11.11 E-cigarettes"},{"id":"06159","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When is the B777 maximum landing fuel restricted to 12 tonnes for flights longer than 4 hours?","options":{"A":"When the destination temperature is above 20C","B":"When the destination temperature is below 10C","C":"When the destination temperature is below 20C","D":"When the destination temperature is above 15C"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.6.1 Fuel Tankering With Cold Soaked Fuel"},{"id":"06238","lastEdit":"31/12/2023","category":"other","question":"When shall the conversion of reported meteorological visibility to RVR table NOT be used?","options":{"A":"For calculating RVR's of less than 1000m","B":"For calculating RVR's of less than 550m","C":"For calculating RVR's of less than 800m","D":"For calculating RVR's of less than 400m"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.4 Conversion of Reported Meteorological Visibility to RVR/CMV"},{"id":"06373","lastEdit":"16/06/2024","category":"other","question":"When is it acceptable to correct towards the VASIS on an approach?","options":{"A":"When the approach is ILS, the approach stabilisation criteria can be met and in daylight only","B":"When the approach stabilisation criteria can be met","C":"Never, the electronic glidepath or glideslope must be maintained to the flare","D":"When the approach is ILS and the approach stabilisation criteria can be met"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.29 Visual Approach Slope Indicator Systems"},{"id":"06411","lastEdit":"06/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the navigational performance required for European Free Route Airspace?","options":{"A":"RNP 1","B":"RNAV 5","C":"RNP 5","D":"RNP 0.3"},"answer":"B","reference":"Lido Nav 1.5.7.6.1 Basic Area Navigation (B-RNAV) - The UK and Ireland also have specific documentation under their CRAR's for FRA airspace in their country - Also RNAV 5"},{"id":"06497","lastEdit":"16/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What TECHNIQUE should a pilot employ if, during taxi out at an outstation with an impending airport curfew closing in 15 minutes, a local cabin crew member learns of a relative's death?","options":{"A":"Advise the crew member to manage their grief until the flight concludes","B":"Instruct the crew member to conceal their emotional state from passengers and colleagues","C":"Stand down the affected cabin crew member and continue to the flight's destination","D":"Return to the gate and pay the curfew penalty fine"},"answer":"C","reference":"NO REFERENCE"},{"id":"06639","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is NOT true when EICAS FUEL PRESS ENG L is displayed?","options":{"A":"Crossfeed may be necessary to prevent thrust decay","B":"Both left main fuel tank pumps are inoperative","C":"The left engine suction feeds from the left main fuel tank","D":"The left engine will flame out from fuel starvation"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Suction Feed"},{"id":"06895","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What occurs when engine anti-ice is operating?","options":{"A":"Approach idle is selected","B":"ENGINE ANTI-ICE ON memo message appears","C":"The backup window heat system operates","D":"The backup probe heat activates"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Electronic Engine Control, Engine Idle"},{"id":"07008","lastEdit":"05/12/2024","category":"other","question":"What does a red box around the digital N1 indication mean?","options":{"A":"Normal - Indicator has operated in the normal range","B":"Exceedance - Indicator has operated at or beyond it's maximum limit","C":"Caution - Indicator has operated in the caution range","D":"Normal - Indicator has operated below normal range"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Indications, Normal Display Format"},{"id":"07070","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the policy regarding the monitoring of 121.5?","options":{"A":"VHF 2 shall be used to monitor 121.5 at all times","B":"Whenever possible one VHF shall be used to monitor 121.5, except in Sanaa FIR where 121.5 must be monitored","C":"Whenever possible one VHF shall be used to monitor 121.5, except in the Gulf Region where 121.5 must be monitored","D":"VHF 1 shall be used to monitor 121.5 at all times"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.3 ATC Communication + OMC 12.3.3.4.3 Transits of Yemen/Sanaa FIR"},{"id":"07259","lastEdit":"22/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which of the following is NOT a requirement for a category A airport?","options":{"A":"Night operations capability","B":"Non-standard approach aids and/or approach patterns","C":"Published circling minima not higher than 1000 AAL","D":"At least one runway with no performance penalty"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.1 Aerodrome Categorisation"},{"id":"07276","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the FAULT light under the L ELEC DEMAND selector indicate?","options":{"A":"Hydraulic pump pressure is low or hydraulic pump fluid temperature is high","B":"Left engine oil pressure is low or oil pump temperature is high","C":"Left engine primary fuel pump is inoperative","D":"Automatic systems using the left system are faulty"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, Controls and Indicators, Hydraulic Panel (Item 8)"},{"id":"07384","lastEdit":"13/06/2024","category":"other","question":"The definition of contingency fuel is?","options":{"A":"5% of the trip fuel or 3% of the trip fuel if an en-route alternate is available or 20 minutes of fuel based on the trip fuel consumption or a statistical contingency fuel (STATCON), minimum contingency fuel is holding fuel for 5 minutes in ISA conditions at 1500 feet above the destination aerodrome","B":"5% of the trip fuel or 2% of the trip fuel if an en-route alternate is available or 10 minutes of fuel based on the trip fuel consumption or a statistical contingency fuel (STATCON) or enough fuel to hold at the destination for 20 minutes","C":"5% of the trip fuel or 3% of the trip fuel if an en-route alternate is available or 20 minutes of fuel based on the trip fuel consumption or a statistical contingency fuel (STATCON) or enough fuel to hold at the destination for 30 minutes","D":"4% of the trip fuel or 2% of the trip fuel if an en-route alternate is available or 30 minutes of fuel based on the trip fuel consumption or a statistical contingency fuel (STATCON), minimum contingency fuel is holding fuel for 5 minutes in ISA at 1500 feet above the destination aerodrome"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.3 Contingency Fuel"},{"id":"07478","lastEdit":"11/05/2024","category":"other","question":"When a conflict exists between company regulations and foreign laws, which rules apply?","options":{"A":"Company policies","B":"The more restrictive of company policy or local law","C":"ICAO laws","D":"UAE Civil Aviation Regulations (CAR)"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 1.1.1 Company Regulations and Policies"},{"id":"07479","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What happens when the stabilizer signal is not present or invalid?","options":{"A":"The EICAS message STAB GREENBAND displays","B":"The CDU displays the VERIFY TRIM message in the scratchpad","C":"The green band and the pointer are not displayed","D":"The green band on the indicator turns amber"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, Controls and Indicators, Pitch and Stabilizer Trim System, Stabilizer Trim System"},{"id":"07532","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"During preflight at the aircraft the purser states a cabin crew in economy smells of alcohol. What is a good TECHNIQUE?","options":{"A":"Verify the information and if necessary offload and call the CDM to have them breathalysed. Continue the flight without them if possible, if not wait for a replacement crew member","B":"Call group security and have them offloaded","C":"Verify the information and get the CDM to breathalyse the crew member, depending on the results offload or continue","D":"Call the police and have them offloaded"},"answer":"A","reference":"NO REFERENCE - Technique for a common interview question"},{"id":"07624","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What actions reset the autopilot warning system and cancels the AUTOPILOT DISC message?","options":{"A":"Pushing the autopilot disconnect switch","B":"Pushing the cancel switch below master warning switch","C":"Pushing the cancel/recall switch","D":"Pushing the master warning when the light is illuminated"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Autopilot Disconnect Switch"},{"id":"07635","lastEdit":"19/11/2023","category":"other","question":"If UP is surrounded by a white box on EICAS GEAR INDICATION, which statement is true?","options":{"A":"Landing gear in transit","B":"GEAR UP is displayed for 10 seconds then blanked","C":"Landing gear display remains until gear extended","D":"Landing gear is down and locked"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, Controls and Indicators, Landing Gear System Indications, Landing Gear Position Indications (Item 1)"},{"id":"07759","lastEdit":"10/01/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the supplemental oxygen that must be carried for passengers?","options":{"A":"A supply of oxygen for 30% of the passengers for the entire flight time when the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 14,000 feet but does not exceed 15,000 feet","B":"A supply of oxygen for 30% of the passengers for the entire flight time when the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 10,000 feet but does not exceed 14,000 feet","C":"A supply of oxygen for 30% of the passengers for the entire flight time when the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 15,000 feet","D":"A supply of oxygen for 30% of the passengers for 10 minutes, or the entire flight time the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 15,000 feet, whichever is greater"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.8.3 Oxygen Requirements"},{"id":"07777","lastEdit":"10/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"If both NORM and ALTN annunciators lit on L ENGINE EEC MODE switch (NORM only on the R ENGINE EEC MODE switch), which statement is true?","options":{"A":"Right engine EEC is now in soft alternate mode","B":"The autothrottles have automatically disengaged","C":"The N1 readout, pointer and fill pattern are not displayed on EICAS","D":"Positioning the thrust levers to full forward causes an engine overboost"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Controls and Indicators, Engine Controls, Engine Control Panel"},{"id":"07842","lastEdit":"21/07/2024","category":"other","question":"A route on the OFP is listed as DXBNCEOR1 - what does this mean?","options":{"A":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice via Iran FIR, on an ETOPS routing","B":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice via Iraq or Iran FIR, on a Reduced Contingency Fuel Procedure","C":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice via Iraq FIR, sequence number 1","D":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice via Iraq or Iran FIR, sequence number 1"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.1.4 EK-OFP Decodes (Item 8)"},{"id":"07943","lastEdit":"22/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"If the flightdeck or cabin temperature is unavailable to the pack controller, what average temperature is achieved?","options":{"A":"Either the last temperature set or an average temperature of 24C","B":"Average of 20C","C":"Average of 22C","D":"Average of 18C"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, System Description, 2.20 Temperature Control"},{"id":"08002","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"What are the requirements for refuelling and defuelling with passengers onboard?","options":{"A":"At least two passenger doors are available, at least one flight deck member, the cabin crew and ramp agent are at their stations and communication has been established with the engineer that remains available","B":"At least one passenger door is available, at least one flight deck member, the cabin crew and engineer are at their stations and communication has been established with the engineer that remains available","C":"At least one passenger door is available, at least one flight deck member, the cabin crew and ramp agent are at their stations and communication has been established with the engineer that remains available","D":"At least two passenger doors are available, at least one flight deck member, the cabin crew and engineer are at their stations and communication has been established with the engineer that remains available"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.3 Refuelling or Defuelling when passengers embarking, on board or disembarking"},{"id":"08025","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"A passenger boards who is sick with life threatening issue, who should the Commander ensure is contacted for assistance?","options":{"A":"Ground Medical Services, Aerodrome Medical Clinic, Emirates Doctor Via NCC","B":"Ground Medical Services, Aerodrome Medical Clinic, Get an onboard medical volunteer (doctor, nurse, midwife, paramedic)","C":"Aerodrome Medical Clinic, Ground Medical Services, Local Emergency Services","D":"Local Emergency Medical Services, Contact Ground Medical Services"},"answer":"D","reference":"OME 11.4.1 Requesting medical support for an on ground medical emergency"},{"id":"08027","lastEdit":"08/02/2024","category":"other","question":"For an engine out procedure when do you initiate the acceleration? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"When established on the final track of the engine out procedure and above the minimum acceleration height or above MSA or the aeroplane meets the requirements of described in the applicable non standard EOP","B":"When above the minimum engine out acceleration height prescribed in the OPT","C":"When established on the final track of the engine out procedure and above the minimum acceleration height or above MSA","D":"When established in the hold of the engine out procedure and above the minimum acceleration height or above MGA or the aeroplane meets the requirements of described in the applicable non standard EOP"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.3.6.2 Non Standard Engine Out Procedure (Turning)"},{"id":"08033","lastEdit":"21/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"A cabin crew member is missing at the hotel lobby at an outstation, what is a good TECHNIQUE?","options":{"A":"Depart for the airport in the bus and call the airport manager en-route to investigate and take care of the individual","B":"Call their room, if no answer go to their room with another crew member to investigate, if they can get ready within 10 minutes you wait for them","C":"Get the remaining crew on the bus and depart without them","D":"Go to their room alone and get them on the crew bus immediately"},"answer":"B","reference":"NO REFERENCE - Technique for a common interview question"},{"id":"08066","lastEdit":"29/04/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the company definition of the 'Safety Window'?","options":{"A":"The 'Safety Window' is a training method where pilots practice emergency procedures during the first 2500 ft of ascent after take-off","B":"The 'Safety Window' is when the aircraft is within 25 nautical miles of the airport, indicating a heightened alert for potential issues","C":"The 'Safety Window' occurs whenever flaps are extended, marking a critical phase for monitoring and decision-making","D":"The 'Safety Window' refers to the flight phase below 2500 ft AGL, approximately 8 nm from the airport, where there is limited time to troubleshoot unresolved problems"},"answer":"D","reference":"Crew Resource Management Manual 4.9.4 The Safety Window"},{"id":"08142","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the maximum fuel tank temperature?","options":{"A":"50 Celsius","B":"43 Celsius","C":"48 Celsius","D":"49 Celsius"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Limitations, Operating Limitations, Engines, AFM Limiations, Engine Fuel System"},{"id":"08207","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"At which altitude can we deselect the approach mode?","options":{"A":"Above 1500 feet radio altitude","B":"Below 1500 feet radio altitude","C":"Above 1000 feet radio altitude","D":"Above 600 feet radio altitude"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director Approach Mode Controls"},{"id":"08238","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"When approaching an ETOPS segment you check the ETOPS alternates weather to find they have gone below approach minima, what is your course of action? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Continue","B":"Select another suitable ETOPS alternate or a re-route or divert","C":"Re-route or divert","D":"Divert"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.5.6 ETOPS in flight procedures + OMA 8.5.4.2 In Flight Minima"},{"id":"08332","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Why is the engine failure only scenario never fuel critical in ETOPS?","options":{"A":"Because it assumes the failure occurs at ETOPS entry and exit rather than the equal time point (ETP)","B":"The one engine specific fuel consumption is less than the two engine specific fuel consumption","C":"The one engine diversion speed is more fuel efficient than the two engine diversion speed","D":"The engine failure only case cruises at a higher altitude than the other scenarios"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.5.2.2 ETOPS, ETOPS Fuel Requirements, ETOPS critical fuel scenario"},{"id":"08424","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"Is an aircraft allowed to undertake an IFR flight within the Emirates FIR, without being equipped with ADS-B OUT?","options":{"A":"No","B":"Yes, as long as it has ADS-C operational","C":"Yes, as long as it has a mode S transponder","D":"Yes, as long as it has CPDLC operational"},"answer":"A","reference":"MEL 34-53-01-02A ADS-B Squitter Transmissions - it's also in LIDO CRAR for UAE. See note that exemptions are available through VPNC and UAE ATC for inbound flights."},{"id":"08499","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Prior to engine start with APU off, primary and secondary external power on, how are the busses powered if the right engine is started?","options":{"A":"Right engine generator automatically powers left main bus only","B":"External power continues to supply right main bus until selected off","C":"Right engine generator automatically powers LEFT and RIGHT main busses","D":"Right engine generator automatically powers right main bus only"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, Systems Description, Electrical System, AC Electrical Power Sources (See source order for powering left and right main busses)"},{"id":"08889","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When does the Right Transfer Bus isolate from the right Main Bus?","options":{"A":"When system configures for Autoland","B":"When Main AC busses are powered","C":"Never","D":"During descent"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems Description, Electrical, System Description, Backup AC Electrical System"},{"id":"08896","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the definition of day of discovery?","options":{"A":"The calendar day a malfunction was recorded in the tech log. It is recorded in local calendar day","B":"The calendar day a malfunction was discovered, the malfunction is written into the tech log for the next calendar day","C":"The calendar day a malfunction was recorded in the tech log. This day is included from the calendar days or flights specified in the MEL for repair","D":"The calendar day a malfunction was recorded in the tech log. This day is excluded from the calendar days or flights specified in the MEL for repair"},"answer":"D","reference":"MEL Section 2, MEL Preamble 13, Item 20 - Day of Discovery"},{"id":"09079","lastEdit":"02/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the flight crew oxygen pressure for dispatch out of Dubai and where is that information found?","options":{"A":"1500 psi. Noted in the aircraft's tech log onboard","B":"1500 psi. Found in the daily checklist in the documents folder onboard","C":"1200 psi. Detailed in the Quick Reference Handbook in the flight deck","D":"1200 psi. As referenced in OMA 8.8"},"answer":"B","reference":"Daily checklist in the documents folder onboard has this information - 1500 psi"},{"id":"09124","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which switch engages the autothrottle with the autothrottle switches in arm?","options":{"A":"APP","B":"CLB/CON","C":"A/T","D":"LNAV"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autothrottle System Controls"},{"id":"09263","lastEdit":"20/04/2024","category":"other","question":"After pushback which MEL procedure does not allow you to depart?","options":{"A":"M-CD Crew Deferral procedures","B":"Blank - No procedures","C":"O - Operational procedures","D":"M - Maintenance procedures"},"answer":"D","reference":"MEL, Preamble, Considerations for Dispatch, Item 3.5"},{"id":"09402","lastEdit":"22/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"When should flight crew state 'Minimum fuel' to ATC?","options":{"A":"When calculated usable fuel on landing at the nearest adequate aerodrome where a safe landing can be made is less than the planned final reserve fuel","B":"When having committed to land at specific aerodrome the flight crew calculates that any change to the existing clearance to that aerodrome may result in landing with less than the planned FMC RSV","C":"When having committed to land at specific aerodrome the flight crew calculates that any change to the existing clearance to that aerodrome may result in landing with less than the planned final reserve fuel","D":"When the EICAS FUEL QTY LOW is triggered"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.4 Minimum Fuel"},{"id":"09520","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is true about flap and slat load relief?","options":{"A":"Flap load relief operates in primary mode, only when flap placard speeds are exceeded and a landing flap is selected","B":"Slats retract from midrange to up when slat load relief is activated","C":"Flap load relief operates in primary mode","D":"Slat load relief operates in primary and secondary mode"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Flaps and Slats, Flap/Slat Load Relief"},{"id":"09670","lastEdit":"18/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"After dispatching with MEL 28-22-04 (Fuel Scavenge Systems, both inoperative) you approach your destination with 1300 kgs still in the centre tank. Which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"If FUEL QTY LOW checklist is actioned the centre pumps will be switched on and the fuel will be available to use","B":"If FUEL QTY LOW checklist is actioned the centre pumps will be switched on, however the fuel pumps are inoperative and the fuel will not be available","C":"The fuel is unusable","D":"The fuel is available for use automatically once the main tanks go below 2.1T"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC FUEL QTY LOW"},{"id":"09888","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When flying an RNP-AR approach, the temperature at the airfield is minus 10 degrees Celsius, and the approach temperature limit is minus 5 degrees Celsius. Which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"It is acceptable to make an approach and apply cold weather temperature corrections","B":"It is acceptable to make an approach and cold weather temperature corrections are not allowed","C":"As the temperature is outside the temperature limit, apply cold weather corrections and fly it to LNAV minima","D":"The approach cannot be flown"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM 5 Approach and Missed App, Non ILS Instrument App, Instrument App, RNAV RNP AR - Cold Wx Temp Corr."},{"id":"10039","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the approach ban point?","options":{"A":"For CAT II, CAT III operations the position where to continue or discontinue shall be made is defined in the AOI pages of the respective airport charts","B":"When no outer marker or equivalent position exists, the Commander shall make the decision to continue or abandon the approach before descending below 1500 feet AGL","C":"For circling approaches the Commander shall make the decision to continue or abandon the approach at 1000 feet AGL","D":"If approaching the approach ban point and the reported RVR is less than the RVR required for the charted approach, a missed approach shall be executed"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.24 Commencement and Continuation of Approach"},{"id":"10108","lastEdit":"05/02/2025","category":"other","question":"Except in an emergency, which of the following countries should not be considered for a diversion unless the flight is destined for that country?","options":{"A":"Afghanistan, Iran, Israel, and Russia","B":"Iran, Iraq, Myanmar, and Russia","C":"Afghanistan, Iraq, Israel, and Russia","D":"Iran, Iraq, Venezuela, and Russia"},"answer":"D","reference":"Network Report 2501 v3 (5 FEB 2025)"},{"id":"10190","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"The minimum glideslope angle for an automatic landing is?","options":{"A":"2.9 degrees","B":"3.25 degrees","C":"2.5 degrees","D":"2.75 degrees"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Limitations Autoflight Automatic Landing"},{"id":"10207","lastEdit":"15/09/2024","category":"other","question":"What does EICAS ENG FUEL VALVE R mean?","options":{"A":"Engine fuel valve on right engine is open","B":"Both spar and engine valves on right engine are commanded to same position","C":"The fuel filter bypass valve is not functioning","D":"The spar or engine fuel valve on right engine has not reached it's commanded position"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, EICAS Messages, EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"10467","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"How long is the repair interval of a category A defect?","options":{"A":"3 days (72 hours) including the day of discovery","B":"Specified Interval (flights, sector, cycles, hours etc)","C":"10 days (240 hours) including the day of discovery","D":"3 days (72 hours) excluding the day of discovery"},"answer":"B","reference":"MEL Section 2, MEL Preamble 9 Repair Intervals"},{"id":"10804","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following are data sources for the SAARU?","options":{"A":"Air data modules only","B":"AOA vanes and TAT probe only","C":"Pitot and static ports only","D":"Air data modules, AOA vanes and TAT probe"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Navigation Systems Description, Inertial System, Air Data and Attitude Sources"},{"id":"10833","lastEdit":"24/04/2024","category":"interview","question":"A new commander has 99 hours since the end of their course and is rostered for a category B airport (commander only take-off and landing), what is a good course of action? (TECHNIQUE)","options":{"A":"If rostered then the duty should be legal, however if it's a roster change check with CDM","B":"You can operate as by the time you land at the category B airport you'll have 100+ hours","C":"You cannot operate, call the CDM","D":"You can operate but you let the FO do the takeoff and landing"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 4.1.4 Inexperienced flight crew member (common interview question grey area, if in doubt check with the CDM)"},{"id":"10926","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When can engine anti-ice be operated manually?","options":{"A":"On the ground or in the air","B":"Only when TAT is above 10 degrees Celsius","C":"Only in the air","D":"Only on the ground"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Adverse Weather, Cold Weather Operations, Engine Anti-ice Operation in flight + Engine Anti-ice Operation On the Ground"},{"id":"11001","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are the conditions for Cabin Altitude memory items?","options":{"A":"The cabin altitude is excessive.","B":"Both packs fail","C":"EICAS indication 'CABIN ALTITUDE AUTO'","D":"The differential pressure is 9.3 PSI or greater"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Cabin Altitude"},{"id":"11019","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which statement is true regarding smoking on the aircraft?","options":{"A":"When a lavatory smoke detector triggers, the EICAS is SMOKE LAV","B":"If a passenger is caught smoking and complies with crew instructions to stop smoking, a formal warning shall still be issued","C":"Smoking and tampering with a smoke detector requires the Commander to notify NCC to request local authorities to meet the aircraft on arrival","D":"E-cigarette use and charging is allowed onboard"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.15.2 Smoking in the Cabin/Lavatory"},{"id":"11201","lastEdit":"29/11/2023","category":"other","question":"If bleed air is isolated so that it is unavailable to the right wing, what happens when wing anti-ice is selected ON?","options":{"A":"The TAC monitors and adjusts for asymmetric drag","B":"Wing anti-ice system functions normally on the left wing","C":"Bleed air is diverted from the engine anti-icing system","D":"Wing anti-ice system is deactivated to prevent asymmetrical anti-icing"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, System Description, Anti-Icing Systems, Wing Anti-Icing"},{"id":"11278","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which conditions indicate possible ice crystal icing?","options":{"A":"Green or amber weather returns below the airplane, appearance of liquid water on the windshield at temperatures too warm for rain, Autothrottle disconnect, TAT indication of near -10 Celsius","B":"Amber or red weather returns above the airplane, appearance of liquid water on the windshield at temperatures too cold for snow, Autopilot disconnect, SAT indication of near 0 Celsius","C":"Amber or red weather returns below the airplane, appearance of liquid water on the windshield at temperatures too cold for rain, Autothrottle disconnect, TAT indication of near 0 Celsius","D":"Green or amber weather returns below the airplane, appearance of liquid water on the windshield at temperatures too cold for rain, Autopilot disconnect, SAT indication of near +10 Celsius"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH Ice Crystal Icing"},{"id":"11586","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the essential component in the safe transport of dangerous goods by air?","options":{"A":"Packaging","B":"Classification","C":"Declaration","D":"Labelling"},"answer":"A","reference":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations - Introduction,General Philosophy"},{"id":"12275","lastEdit":"28/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"What predicted airspeed does the airspeed trend vector indicate?","options":{"A":"Airspeed in 12 seconds","B":"Airspeed in 10 seconds","C":"Airspeed in 5 seconds","D":"Airspeed in 6 seconds"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Primary Flight Displays, Airspeed"},{"id":"12340","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"What does amber EICAS DATALINK SYS indicate?","options":{"A":"The datalink system is temporarily lost","B":"The datalink system has failed","C":"The VHF datalink system has failed","D":"The SATCOM datalink system has failed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM System, Comms, EICAS Messages, Comms EICAS Alert Messages, Datalink"},{"id":"12341","lastEdit":"21/10/2024","category":"other","question":"What requirements must be met to operate aircraft in Tripoli FIR?","options":{"A":"At dispatch SATCOM and 3 VHF must be operational. In-flight broadcast procedures must be used, and SLOP offset shall be applied. Level changes can be made in Tripoli FIR","B":"At dispatch TCAS and Transponder Mode S must be operational. In-flight broadcast procedures must be used, and SLOP procedures shall be adhered to. No level changes shall be made in Tripoli FIR","C":"At dispatch TCAS and Transponder Mode S must be operational. In-flight broadcast procedures must be used, and SLOP procedures are optional. Level changes can be made in Tripoli FIR","D":"At dispatch SATCOM and 3 VHF must be operational. In-flight broadcast procedures must be used, and SLOP procedures shall not be used. No level changes shall be made in Tripoli FIR"},"answer":"B","reference":"SCB Tripoli FIR"},{"id":"12446","lastEdit":"20/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which rule of thumb converts IAS to TAS with altitude?","options":{"A":"TAS = IAS * (2 - (Pressure altitude / 25000))","B":"TAS = IAS * (1+ (Density altitude / 50000))","C":"TAS = IAS * sqrt(Density altitude / 10000)","D":"TAS = IAS + (Pressure altitude * 0.02)"},"answer":"B","reference":"eLearning module Hot Weather and High Elevation Destinations (RDT Package 3) 2024/25 - 'As a rule of thumb, TAS increases approximately 2% of IAS with every 1000 ft of density altitude. So, with an IAS of 140, at a density altitude of 4280, TAS will be approximately 152'"},{"id":"12455","lastEdit":"21/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"The EICAS PRI FLIGHT COMPUTERS indicates?","options":{"A":"The system is in the primary mode","B":"The system is in the secondary mode","C":"Flight control modes are not affected","D":"The system is in the direct mode"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Primary Flight Control System Modes, Flight Control System Direct Mode"},{"id":"12934","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which controls disengage the autobrake?","options":{"A":"Rudder pedals, autobrake selector, speedbrake","B":"Autobrake selector only","C":"Parking brake lever","D":"Control column"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, System Description, Brake System, Autobrake System"},{"id":"13029","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the normal position of the aft outflow valve after landing?","options":{"A":"Fully open","B":"10 degrees open","C":"30 degrees open","D":"Fully closed"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization with Automatic Operation"},{"id":"13111","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"The memory items for Dual Engine Fail/Stall are:","options":{"A":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - idle, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull","B":"Fuel control switches (both) - cutoff then run, Ram air turbine - push and hold for one second","C":"Fuel control switches (both) - cutoff then run, Ram air turbine - push","D":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - retard until engine indication stays within limits or the thrust lever is at idle"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA NNC Dual Engine Fail/Stall"},{"id":"13238","lastEdit":"30/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"Pressurization system indications are displayed when","options":{"A":"Cabin differential pressure is in amber above normal range or in red excessive range","B":"Landing altitude MAN is displayed Duct pressure is in Amber below normal range with the respective engine running Cabin differential pressure is in amber above normal range or in red excessive range","C":"Duct pressure is in Amber below normal range with the respective engine running","D":"Landing altitude MAN is displayed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, system description, 2- Air systems, controls and indications, Duct pressure and Pressurization system indications (Real exam answer is 'all of the above')"},{"id":"13243","lastEdit":"02/08/2024","category":"tech","question":"What position should the autopilot disengage bar be in during preflight?","options":{"A":"Out","B":"In","C":"Down","D":"Up"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - Captain"},{"id":"13305","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When does the EEC select approach idle?","options":{"A":"When the flaps are commanded to 25 or greater","B":"When wing anti-ice is ON","C":"When the flaps are out of the UP position","D":"When the engine bleed air valve is open"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Electronic Engine Control, Engine Idle"},{"id":"13590","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"What are the requirements for fuel uplift to be within limits? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"For more uplift than required calculated has to be within 5% and within a maximum of 2000kgs","B":"For more uplift than required calculated has to be within 5% and within a maximum of 2000kgs For less uplift than required calculated has to be within 5% and within a maximum of 1000kgs","C":"For less uplift than required calculated has to be within 5% and within a maximum of 1000kgs","D":"The uplift has to be within +-5%"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.6 Fuel Uplift Check"},{"id":"13646","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"N1 RPM has returned to normal range after an exceedance. How do you clear the indication from EICAS?","options":{"A":"Select the secondary engine indications","B":"Open up Status page","C":"Use Cancel/Recall switch","D":"Open up appropriate exceedence checklist"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Indications, Normal Display Format"},{"id":"13653","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"both","question":"A passenger boards who is sick with a non life threatening issue, who should the Commander contact to assist with load/offload decision making?","options":{"A":"Ground Medical Services, Emirates Doctor Via NCC, Local Emergency Services","B":"Ground Medical Services, Aerodrome Medical Clinic, Get an onboard medical volunteer (doctor, nurse, midwife, paramedic)","C":"Aerodrome Medical Clinic, Ground Medical Services, Local Emergency Services","D":"Ground Medical Services, Aerodrome Medical Clinic, Emirates Doctor Via NCC"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.2.3.2.1 Medical Cases"},{"id":"13698","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"During an in-flight medical emergency with no SATCOM available who should be used to assist?","options":{"A":"GMS","B":"A medical volunteer (doctor, nurse, paramedic, pharmacist)","C":"A medical volunteer (doctor, nurse, paramedic, midwife)","D":"Stockholm Radio"},"answer":"C","reference":"OME 11.4.3 Requesting and Accepting the Assistance of an On Board Medical Volunteer"},{"id":"13711","lastEdit":"12/01/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding enhanced wake turbulence separation? (eWTS using wake turbulence groups)","options":{"A":"A B777 following an A380 on departure requires a minimum of 120 seconds of separation, A B777 following an A380 on arrival requires a minimum separation of 2.5 nautical miles","B":"A B777 following an A380 on departure requires a minimum of 180 seconds of separation, A B777 following an A380 on arrival requires a minimum separation of 5 nautical miles","C":"A B777 following an A380 on departure requires a minimum of 160 seconds of separation, A B777 following an A380 on arrival requires a minimum separation of 3 nautical miles","D":"A B777 following an A380 on departure requires a minimum of 100 seconds of separation, A B777 following an A380 on arrival requires a minimum separation of 4 nautical miles"},"answer":"D","reference":"Lido RAR 1.4.2.12.1.2 Wake Turbulence Separation Minima (Lido page 541) + Lido UAE CRAR (1.4.2.12.1.1) for use of eWTS by wake group rather than wake category"},{"id":"13768","lastEdit":"07/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which long-range communication systems are required outside of VHF range for aircraft operations above and below 80N latitude over the North Atlantic?","options":{"A":"2 HF COMM below 80N; 1 HF COMM and SATVOICE or CPDLC above 80N","B":"SATVOICE and CPDLC required both above and below 80N","C":"1 HF COMM and CPDLC below 80N; 1 HF COMM and 1 SATVOICE above 80N","D":"1 HF COMM and SATVOICE or CPDLC below 80N; 2 HF COMM above 80N"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO 2.3.5.1.2.1 Equipage Requirements + QRH, Ops Info, In-Flight Failed or Downgraded Aircraft Equipment (NAT-HLA only)"},{"id":"13871","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct about RVSM?","options":{"A":"RVSM is applied to flight levels between 290 and 430","B":"RVSM is applied to all flight levels above 300","C":"RVSM is applied to flight levels between 285 and 410","D":"RVSM is applied to flight levels between 290 and 410"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 11.3 En Route Comms, Reduced Vertical Separation Minima"},{"id":"13913","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is NOT true regarding the flap position indication?","options":{"A":"The flap position indicator is on the PFD","B":"The flap position indication displays on EICAS when the flaps begin to extend","C":"There are three flap position indications: Normal (Primary), Expanded (Secondary and Alternate)","D":"Alternate extension is limited to slats midrange and flaps 20"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Flaps and Slats, Flap and Slat Modes"},{"id":"13981","lastEdit":"20/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When landing on a flat main gear tire, what does the FCTM guidance instruct?","options":{"A":"Flat main gear tires cause a loss of braking effectiveness and a yawing moment towards the flat tire with light or no braking, and a yawing moment away from the flat tire if the brakes are applied harder. Maximum use of reverse thrust is recommended, do not use autobrakes","B":"Flat main gear tires cause a loss of braking effectiveness and a yawing moment towards the flat tire with light or no braking, and a yawing moment away from the flat tire if the brakes are applied harder. Runway length permitting, use idle reverse, use high autobrake settings","C":"Flat main gear tires cause a loss of braking effectiveness and a yawing moment away from the flat tire with light or no braking, and a yawing moment towards the flat tire if the brakes are applied harder. Maximum use of reverse thrust is recommended, do not use autobrakes","D":"Flat main gear tires cause a loss of braking effectiveness and a yawing moment away from the flat tire with light or no braking, and a yawing moment towards the flat tire if the brakes are applied harder. Runway length permitting, use idle reverse, use low autobrake settings"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCTM 8 Non Normal, Landing Gear, Landing on a flat tire"},{"id":"13982","lastEdit":"15/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"What constitutes a Continuous Descent Operation (CDO) in the United Kingdom?","options":{"A":"No level segment below 6000 feet exceeding 2.5 nautical miles","B":"No rate of descent less than 500 feet per minute below 6000 feet","C":"No level segment below transition level exceeding 2.5 nautical miles","D":"No level segment below transition level exceeding 5 nautical miles"},"answer":"A","reference":"External UK CAA publication, the CAP 1554. https://www.caa.co.uk/publication/download/16144. AOI pages also contain details at applicable airports. (Eg. EGLL)"},{"id":"14239","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding a flight duty period?","options":{"A":"Flight duty period starts at chauffeur pickup time and ends when the aeroplane lands","B":"Flight duty period starts at ID badge check-in or crew pulse check-in and ends when the aeroplane comes to rest","C":"Flight duty period starts at duty report time and ends when the aeroplane comes to rest","D":"Flight duty period starts at duty report time and ends when the parking brake is set plus 30 minutes"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.5 Definitions, Flight Duty Period"},{"id":"14243","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What are the conditions for EICAS SPEEDBRAKE EXTENDED? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"The radio altitude is above 800 feet or The flap lever is in a landing setting or A thrust lever is not at idle","B":"The radio altitude is between 15 and 800 feet or The flap lever is in a landing setting or A thrust lever is not at idle","C":"The radio altitude is between 15 and 800 feet or One or more spoiler pairs are inoperative or The flap lever is in a landing setting or A thrust lever is not at idle","D":"The radio altitude is between 2 and 1000 feet or One or more spoiler pairs are inoperative or The flap lever is in a landing setting or A thrust lever is not at idle"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, EICAS Messages, Flight Control System EICAS Messages (The actual exam answer is all of the above but due to website design to keep options listed randomly that is not an option)"},{"id":"14307","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"An adequate aerodrome is deemed suitable when the following criteria are within limits: (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Forecasted ceiling, visibility","B":"Forecasted runway surface condition ensures a safe landing","C":"Forecasted ceiling, visibility Crosswind component including gusts Forecasted runway surface condition ensures a safe landing","D":"Crosswind component including gusts"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.5.1.6 Suitable Aerodrome ('all of the above' is the correct answer in the exam)"},{"id":"14410","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"How long does it take for Group Security to assess a bomb threat?","options":{"A":"15-20 minutes when the threat is imminent","B":"15-60 minutes","C":"15-30 minutes when the threat is imminent","D":"10-20 minutes"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 10.5.4.2 Threat Assessment"},{"id":"14432","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is true about alternate pitch trim?","options":{"A":"The alternate pitch trim levers always move the stabilizer directly","B":"Moving the alternate pitch trim levers with the autopilot engaged will disconnect the autopilot","C":"Only one lever has to be moved to command trim changes","D":"Wheel pitch trim commands have priority over alternate pitch trim commands"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, Controls and Indicators, Pitch and Stabilizer Trim System, Stabilizer Trim System"},{"id":"14486","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When does a standby duty begin to reduce the maximum FDP available?","options":{"A":"After 6 hours of standby","B":"After 3 hours of standby","C":"After 5 hours of standby","D":"After 8 hours of standby"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.14.3 Standby Duty Limits"},{"id":"14728","lastEdit":"12/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Above which cabin altitude will the passenger oxygen masks deploy automatically?","options":{"A":"13500 feet","B":"10000 feet","C":"15000 feet","D":"12000 feet"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Oxygen Systems, Passenger Oxygen System"},{"id":"14776","lastEdit":"11/04/2024","category":"other","question":"What times are new FMC wind data available to upload to our aircraft?","options":{"A":"0430, 1030, 1630, 2230 UTC","B":"0000, 0600, 1200, 1800 UTC","C":"0600, 1200 UTC","D":"0030, 1230 UTC"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.1.4 EK-OFP Decodes, Item 13 - WX PROG"},{"id":"14777","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"You plan a CAT3B autoland, which EICAS does NOT affect your approach and landing?","options":{"A":"SGL SOURCE DISPLAYS","B":"SINGLE SOURCE ILS","C":"SGL SOURCE RADALT","D":"SINGLE SOURCE F/D"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM 5, Approach and Missed Approach, ILS Approach, AFDS Autoland Capabilities"},{"id":"15029","lastEdit":"03/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"On the EICAS display what does DOORS AUTO/MANUAL mean?","options":{"A":"Some entry doors are in the armed mode and some are in the disarmed mode","B":"Cabin crew have not yet selected manual on the overhead panel","C":"Some entry doors are in the armed mode, but they will soon be disarmed","D":"All doors are in the disarmed mode"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Airplane General, EICAS Messages, EICAS Messages, Doors and Windows EICAS Messages"},{"id":"15069","lastEdit":"10/12/2023","category":"other","question":"You're operating a flight to an S2 destination. What is the minimum rest period required at the outstation?","options":{"A":"22 hours","B":"At least as long as the preceding duty period, or 20 hours, whichever is greater","C":"14 hours","D":"At least as long as the preceding duty period, or 16 hours, whichever is greater"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 7.E.2(c)(2)"},{"id":"15075","lastEdit":"26/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"If you dispatch with APU inop and both main AC electrical generators fail in flight. What is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Continue to destination","B":"Divert to a company destination","C":"Divert to wherever VPNC decide","D":"Land at the nearest suitable"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non normal Checklists, Non normal checklist operation, Land at the nearest suitable."},{"id":"15178","lastEdit":"16/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"You suffer an in flight failure of ELEC GEN DRIVE L. As per the QRH you start the APU. What extra fuel burn can you expect for the remainder of the flight?","options":{"A":"Increased fuel burn of 2.5% to account for APU usage or use the QRH, Performance In-flight, Engine Inoperative, APU Operation During Flight Table","B":"Increased fuel burn of 2.5% to account for the open APU inlet and 90 kg an hour of fuel for APU usage or use the FCOM, Performance In-flight, Engine Inoperative, APU Operation During Flight Table","C":"Increased fuel burn of 5% to account for APU usage or use the FCOM, Performance In-flight, Engine Inoperative, APU Operation During Flight Table","D":"Increased fuel burn of 2.5% to account for the open APU inlet and 240 kg an hour of fuel for APU usage or use the QRH, Performance In-flight, Engine Inoperative, APU Operation During Flight Table"},"answer":"B","reference":"MEL 24-31-01A (Multiple MEL's carry this information if an MEL instructs you to use the APU in flight) - Also note dispatch is available to give you an inflight flightplan with the appropriate MEL and APU running applied - The MEL 2.5% + 90 kg is more conservative than the FCOM table. Also note despite the reference being for engine inoperative the 'All engines' section for APU operation in flight states refer to the engine inoperative table (i.e. same data)"},{"id":"15244","lastEdit":"21/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"In flight your autobrake fails, what guidance does the FCTM state?","options":{"A":"Apply the wheel brakes smoothly until a satisfactory deceleration rate is reached, maintain the deceleration rate with constant brake pressure until stopping is assured","B":"Apply wheel brakes smoothly with steadily increasing brake pressure until medium level braking is achieved, depending on runway length remaining continue to increase the brake pressure until stopping is assured","C":"Apply wheel brakes smoothly with steadily increasing brake pressure as required for runway condition and length available. Maintain deceleration rate with constant or increasing brake pressure as required","D":"Apply wheel brakes smoothly until maximum brake pressure is reached, slowly decrease the brake pressure when stopping is assured"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCTM, 6 Landing, Landing Roll"},{"id":"15256","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which malfunction during ground start will cause the autostart system to abort the start?","options":{"A":"A hot start","B":"A broken fan blade","C":"High oil temperature","D":"High oil pressure"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Start and Ignition System, Autostart"},{"id":"15416","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How many hydraulic systems are needed to power enough of the flight controls for safe flight?","options":{"A":"Two","B":"Zero","C":"Three","D":"One"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, System Description, Introduction"},{"id":"15524","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is FRA in terms of airspace and navigation?","options":{"A":"Flight Route Analysis - An air traffic management tool to utilize direct routings","B":"Filed Route Assessment - A post flight review done by an air traffic service to review the efficiency of the flights through their airspace","C":"Free Route Airspace - a point to point airspace navigation system","D":"Free Range Airspace - a point to point airspace navigation system"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO, 2.1.2.12.2 Free Route Airspace (FRA) Concept"},{"id":"15571","lastEdit":"04/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"When voluntarily changing the destination or alternate aerodrome in-flight, which minima apply?","options":{"A":"Charted Minima +800m Visibility/RVR and +200 feet DA/H","B":"Charted Minima","C":"ETOPS Minima","D":"Planning Minima"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.5 In-flight Replanning Procedure"},{"id":"15884","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What happens if both C1 and C2 DEMAND pump selectors are positioned to ON?","options":{"A":"Only the C1 demand pump will operate","B":"Both, the C1 and C2 demand pumps will operate only if C1 or C2 PRIMARY pump has low pressure","C":"Both, the C1 and C2 demand pumps will operate","D":"Only the C2 demand pump will operate"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, 13.20 Centre Hydraulic System Demand Pumps"},{"id":"15980","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding lavatory smoke detection?","options":{"A":"An automatic sprinkler system activates if a fire is detected","B":"There is no built-in fire extinguishing system for the lavatories","C":"The lavatory fire extinguishing system is activated by a discharge switch on the overhead panel","D":"An aural warning activates and light illuminates outside the lavatory if smoke is detected"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, Lavatory Fire Protection, Lavatory Fire Detection"},{"id":"16030","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"What makes an adequate aerodrome in terms of ETOPS?","options":{"A":"At the expected time of use the aerodrome will be available and equipped with ATS, lighting, comms, weather reporting, navaids and RFFS, at least one let down aid, passenger facilities are available for disembarkation and accommodation","B":"When the forecasted ceiling, visibility, temperature, crosswind and surface condition are within limits","C":"The applicable performance requirements and runway characteristics are met, at the expected time of use the aerodrome will be available and equipped with ATS, lighting, comms, weather reporting, navaids and RFFS, at least one let down aid","D":"When the forecasted ceiling, visibility, crosswind and surface condition are within limits"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.5.1.5 Adequate Aerodrome"},{"id":"16031","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When is auto-relight activated?","options":{"A":"Whenever landing flaps are set and engine anti-ice is off","B":"Only when landing flaps are set","C":"Whenever engine is at or below idle with fuel control switch in run","D":"Only when start/ignition selector is set to start position"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Start and Ignition System, Auto Relight (Does not explicitly state fuel control switch must be in run, only N2 below idle or rapidly decreasing)"},{"id":"16111","lastEdit":"24/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the ADIRU?","options":{"A":"The ADIRU supplies primary flight data, inertial reference, and air data","B":"The aeroplane can be moved in ALIGN MODE","C":"In flight if the ADIRU is switched OFF the EICAS NAV ADIRU INERTIAL will display","D":"A position update is recommended if the total time in the navigation mode is expected to exceed 48 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Flight Management Nav, Navigation System Description, Inertial System, ADIRU"},{"id":"16325","lastEdit":"30/01/2024","category":"other","question":"Below what height should FLCH not be used on approach?","options":{"A":"500 feet AGL","B":"1000 feet AGL","C":"500 AFE","D":"1000 feet AFE"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Limitations Autoflight Non AFM Operational Information"},{"id":"16353","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the position of an engine anti-ice valve when the engine anti-ice selector is in auto and EAI is displayed?","options":{"A":"Off","B":"On","C":"Open","D":"Closed"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, Controls and Indicators, Engine and Wing Anti Icing, Anti-Ice Panel"},{"id":"16379","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which system is used to extend flap/slats EICAS FLAP/SLAT CONTROL is displayed?","options":{"A":"Secondary mode","B":"Alternate Mode","C":"Primary mode","D":"No further extension possible - controller failure"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC FLAP/SLAT CONTROL"},{"id":"16425","lastEdit":"07/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which one of the following statements about Normal Mode Roll Control is FALSE?","options":{"A":"Spoilers 4 and 11 are mechanically controlled through a cable from the control wheel","B":"The spoilers supplement roll control in response to control wheel commands","C":"At cruise speed, spoilers #5 and #11 are mechanically locked out at high speed","D":"Spoilers begin to extend to augment roll control after several degrees of control wheel rotation"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Roll Control + FCOM, Systems, Flight Control, System Description, Spoilers"},{"id":"16705","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Over Mogadishu you receive an instruction from a suspected unauthorized ATC unit and your SATCOM is inoperative. What is a good TECHNIQUE?","options":{"A":"Offset the airway R2 and follow the ATC instruction","B":"Get a SELCAL check on HF to verify they are a real ATC unit","C":"Ignore the instruction","D":"Follow the instruction"},"answer":"B","reference":"NO REFERENCE"},{"id":"16753","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How are Display Select Panel operations affected when EICAS is displayed on an inboard display unit?","options":{"A":"Any Display Select Panel selection will be displayed on the lower center display unit","B":"All display switches are inoperative except ENG, FUEL and AIR","C":"Inboard display unit can only display EICAS or the secondary engine display","D":"All display panel select panel operations are normal"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Heading Reference and Inboard Displays, Inboard Display Controls"},{"id":"16825","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which one of the following pages is available following dual FMC failure?","options":{"A":"ALTN POS REF","B":"ALTN REF NAV DATA","C":"ALTN PERF INIT","D":"ALTN NAV LEGS"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, FMC Alternate Nav System Description, Alternative Navigation CDU Pages, Alternate Navigation Legs Page"},{"id":"16854","lastEdit":"05/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"Is it required to follow the depressurisation diversion routing to on the OFP?","options":{"A":"Yes, as long as you're below the listed OFP driftdown limited weight","B":"Yes","C":"No, as long as you're not in the Himalayan region","D":"No"},"answer":"D","reference":"The Depressurization Strategies on OFP are for planning purposes only. In- Flight, your strategy and diversion will depend on which airport is adequate/ suitable to the scenario (NOTAMS and WX). There is no Altitude published on the Depressurization Strategy in OFP, but there is MORA, and MGA, MEA, MTCA in MPilot APP. As for the DARD over the Himalayan region, they are escape routes for the day of operation (Guidance and Requirement), in case required for EO or DEP (Not Published in OFP). PAX Oxygen Required above 15,000ft. and Flight Crew Oxygen Required above 10,000ft."},{"id":"16955","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of these following flight control surfaces aid in roll control?","options":{"A":"Kruger Flaps, Slats and Spoilers","B":"Slats and Spoilers","C":"Flaperons and Slats","D":"Ailerons, Flaperons and Spoilers"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Flight Control Surfaces"},{"id":"16980","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When will wing anti-ice operate automatically?","options":{"A":"Only when TAT above 10 Celsius","B":"Only in flight","C":"Only on ground","D":"On the ground or in flight"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, System Description, Anti-Icing Systems, Wing Anti-Icing"},{"id":"17028","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Which flight documents are NOT required to be retained on ground at departure aerodrome?","options":{"A":"Tear of parts of the aircraft tech log","B":"Significant weather charts","C":"Route specific NOTAM documentation","D":"NOTOC copy"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 2.1.3.1 Information Retained on Ground"},{"id":"17033","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"After crossing the NAT HLA under speed control of M0.84, When can you resume normal speed?","options":{"A":"As soon as you exit the NAT HLA","B":"As soon as ATC authorises a change","C":"When under radar control","D":"As soon as you make landfall"},"answer":"B","reference":"Lido 2.3.2.12.9 North Atlantic, RAR, Separation rules, Separation minima for airspace reservation (Lido R-410)"},{"id":"17068","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"How long does the passenger oxygen system last for? (non freighter)","options":{"A":"15 minutes","B":"22 minutes","C":"20 minutes","D":"10 minutes"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Oxygen Systems, Passenger Oxygen System"},{"id":"17137","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What powers the right engine thrust reverser?","options":{"A":"Right engine bleed air","B":"Centre hydraulic system","C":"Right hydraulic system","D":"Left engine bleed air"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, System Description, Left and Right Hydraulic Systems"},{"id":"17386","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"For an aircraft to fly in NAT HLA, what is the lowest level of navigational performance required?","options":{"A":"RNAV 10","B":"RNAV 5","C":"RNP 4","D":"RNP 10"},"answer":"A","reference":"Lido 2.3.2 North Atlantic, RAR, General Flight Rules (RNAV 10 or RNP 4 approval required)"},{"id":"18142","lastEdit":"21/07/2024","category":"other","question":"What type of refuelling operation is NOT allowed?","options":{"A":"Refuelling with one engine running with no passengers onboard","B":"Refuelling with JET B, JP-4 or AVTAG with passengers onboard","C":"Defuelling with JET A1 with passengers boarding","D":"Defuelling with JET A with passengers disembarking"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.3 Refuelling or Defuelling when passengers embarking, on board or disembarking"},{"id":"18329","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When is the selected track or heading line removed from ND?","options":{"A":"After missed approach is initiated","B":"After 10 seconds if the MCP setting has not changed and LNAV is engaged","C":"Anytime LNAV or G/S mode engaged","D":"10 seconds after VNAV descent started and altitude setting has not changed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"18566","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Why does the flight deck receive air from the left pack at a higher pressure than the passenger cabin?","options":{"A":"To ensure positive pressure to the avionics bay","B":"To ensure efficient circulation of air","C":"To prevent smoke and objectionable odours entering the flight deck","D":"To prevent objectionable odours entering the flight deck"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Air Distribution"},{"id":"18692","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"During climb what parameter(s) schedule cabin altitude?","options":{"A":"A constant pressure differential","B":"Airplane climb rate and FMC flight plan cruise altitude","C":"Takeoff and landing field elevation","D":"Airplane flight altitude"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization with Automatic Operation"},{"id":"18736","lastEdit":"03/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"A crewmember is accused of being intoxicated, what is an appropriate response? (TECHNIQUE)","options":{"A":"Verify the information by an independent third party (CSV/Purser), if on ground return to stand and offload the accused crewmember and get them breathalysed. If airborne stand the accused crewmember down and continue","B":"Verify the information by an independent third party (CSV/Purser), if on ground return to stand and offload the accused crewmember and get them breathalysed. If airborne divert to the nearest suitable and have the accused crewmember breathalysed","C":"BLANK","D":"Verify the information by an independent third party (CSV/Purser), if before pushback, offload the accused crewmember and get them breathalysed. After pushback stand the accused crewmember down and continue"},"answer":"D","reference":"Technique"},{"id":"18754","lastEdit":"20/04/2024","category":"other","question":"Which noise standard are our aircraft certified to?","options":{"A":"Chapter 3","B":"Chapter 1","C":"Chapter 4","D":"Chapter 2"},"answer":"C","reference":"Aircraft noise certificate (onboard the aircraft)"},{"id":"18816","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following would not cause a change in allowable assumed temperature? (assumed temperature 46C)","options":{"A":"A change in takeoff runway","B":"A change in takeoff gross weight","C":"A change in takeoff flap","D":"A change in outside temperature from 20Ã‚ÂºC to 30Ã‚ÂºC"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM Takeoff and initial climb, Reduce takeoff thrust, Reduced takeoff thrust (ATM)"},{"id":"19002","lastEdit":"17/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"Under what runway conditions are we required to use full thrust for take-off?","options":{"A":"Never, the use of full thrust is recommended under certain cold weather operations however the final decision is under the authority of the Commander","B":"When the OPT calculations do not permit reduced thrust due to contamination depth limits being exceeded","C":"When the runway is contaminated as defined by the OMA","D":"When airport low visibility procedures are in force"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, Supplementary Procedures, Adverse Weather, Takeoff - Wet or Contaminated Runway Conditions: 'Reduced thrust (ATM) is allowed on a runway contaminated by slush, snow, standing water, or ice, only when calculated by OPT'"},{"id":"19541","lastEdit":"13/12/2023","category":"other","question":"What position is required for the master brightness to have full range of control of an individual panel brightness or display brightness?","options":{"A":"6 o'clock","B":"12 o'clock","C":"2 o'clock","D":"10 o'clock"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Controls and Indicators, Signs and Lighting (see item 9 - master brightness, 'has full adjustment range of all lights when individual brightness controls are set to the centre detent'"},{"id":"19577","lastEdit":"10/03/2024","category":"other","question":"In the event of a nose-high upset recovery, what is the correct sequence of actions for the pilot flying?","options":{"A":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, reduce thrust, apply nose down elevator, roll to adjust bank angle","B":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, apply nose down elevator, reduce thrust, roll to adjust bank angle","C":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, apply nose down elevator, roll to adjust bank angle, reduce thrust","D":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, roll to adjust bank angle, apply nose down elevator, reduce thrust"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH, Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Upset Recovery, Nose High Recovery"},{"id":"19637","lastEdit":"29/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding Precision Runway Monitor (PRM) approaches?","options":{"A":"The approval to operate at an airport is listed in the OMC, dual VHF comm is required","B":"Breakout manoeuvres must be accomplished with the autopilot engaged","C":"If a breakout manoeuvres conflicts with a TCAS RA, you must follow the breakout instructions from ATC","D":"The approval to operate at an airport is listed in the Operations Specification, dual VHF comm is required"},"answer":"D","reference":"Ops Spec Page 3, Item L2. Reference for dual VHF comm is on the individual approach chart"},{"id":"19805","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are the crew responsibilities when accepting a visual approach?","options":{"A":"Terrain clearance, navigation, traffic separation, wake turbulence, establishing the go around requirements","B":"Navigation, traffic separation, wake turbulence, establishing the go around requirements","C":"Terrain clearance, navigation, traffic separation, establishing the go around requirements","D":"Terrain clearance, navigation, traffic separation, wake turbulence, establishing the go around requirements, ensuring the runway is clear for landing"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.22.3 Visual Approach"},{"id":"19852","lastEdit":"01/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"When using discretion to extend an FDP a cabin crew member doesn't want to extend their duty period, what is your course of action (TECHNIQUE)","options":{"A":"Stand the cabin crew down immediately","B":"Get the management pilot on duty to speak to the cabin crew directly via satellite phone","C":"Divert the aircraft before reaching the flight duty period limit","D":"Inform the cabin crew it's the Commander's discretion not their individual discretion, if they still do not wish to operate use them to their flight duty limit and then stand them down"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 7.15 Commander's Discretion to Extend a Flying Duty Period (Despite the OMA reference there is a lot of technique in the marked answer, if you have a better one, let us know)"},{"id":"20150","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"If the fuel remaining at the decision point is less than the required amount under the Reduced Contingency Fuel (RCF) Procedure, what action should the Commander take?","options":{"A":"Apply the In-Flight Fuel Management policy as per 8.3.7.2 as applicable","B":"Divert to the nearest suitable aerodrome","C":"Declare 'Minimum fuel' or 'Mayday fuel' as appropriate and continue to destination","D":"Return to the departure aerodrome"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.2.3 In-flight Fuel Management During Reduced Contingency Fuel Procedure (RCF) - Notwithstanding the above,Ã¢â‚¬â€¹ atÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ the decision point, the CommanderÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ mayÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ decide to applyÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ theÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ Ã¢â‚¬â€¹In-FlightÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ FuelÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ ManagementÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ policy according 8.3.7.2Ã¢â‚¬â€¹ as applicable"},{"id":"20243","lastEdit":"22/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding departures in ice pellet and hail precipiation?","options":{"A":"Departure in heavy ice pellets or hail is not permitted","B":"Departure in moderate or heavy ice pellets or small hail is not permitted","C":"Departure in moderate or heavy ice pellets is not permitted","D":"Departure in heavy ice pellets or small hail is not permitted"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.9 Ice Pellets, Small Hail and Hail (You can depart in light and moderate ice pellets and small hail, but not normal hail)"},{"id":"20274","lastEdit":"28/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Fuel uplift measured by the supplier, shall be within which of the following tolerance?","options":{"A":"Planned uplift greater than calculated uplift; 5% of calculated uplift up to a MAX of 2000kg","B":"Actual uplift less than calculated uplift; 5% of calculated uplift up to a MAX of 2000kg","C":"Actual uplift greater than calculated uplift; 5% of calculated uplift up to a MAX of 2000kg","D":"Planned uplift less than calculated uplift; 5% of calculated uplift up to a MAX of 2000kg"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.6 Fuel Uplift Check"},{"id":"20295","lastEdit":"13/12/2024","category":"other","question":"A route on the OFP is listed as DXBNCEPCR1 - what does this mean?","options":{"A":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice, and is a dispatcher defined route","B":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice, representing a minimum fuel track via Iran or Iraq in a company route","C":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice, representing an optimised minimum time track via Iran or Iraq","D":"It is a route from Dubai to Nice, indicating an optimised cost track via a region/country, such as Iran or Iraq, in a company route"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.1.8.1.4 EK OFP Decodes (Item 8)"},{"id":"20299","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"You're planning an RNP approach to an airport at 6000 feet and 40c. The charted glidepath is at 3.0 degrees. What is your true FPA and ROD on short final assuming a ground speed of 170 knots?","options":{"A":"FPA -3.6 and ROD -1050 FPM","B":"FPA -3.35 and ROD -1000 FPM","C":"FPA -3.0 and ROD -850 FPM","D":"FPA -3.1 and ROD -900 FPM"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.4.3 Vertical Path Angle Deviation Table + LIDO 1.7.7.11 Descent Gradient Table"},{"id":"20361","lastEdit":"16/01/2024","category":"other","question":"You are taxiing out when you are faced with a system fault. You follow the technical fault resolution process in the QRH, upon contact with MCC via SATCOM they advise to cycle a circuit breaker. What is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Call the tech pilot","B":"Inform MCC it's not recommended to cycle a circuit breaker unless directed by the MEL","C":"Inform MCC it's not recommended to cycle a circuit breaker unless directed by a non-normal checklist","D":"Reset the circuit breaker as directed"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non normal Checklists, Non normal checklist operation, Assumptions"},{"id":"20421","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Engine Fire switches are mechanically locked in the normal position. What unlocks them allowing movement to the out position? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Fire warning only","B":"Engine fire override switch pushed only","C":"Fire warning, Fuel Control in cutoff, Engine fire override switch pushed","D":"Fire warning or Engine fire override switch pushed"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM 8.10 Engine Fire Panel, Item 1 and item 4"},{"id":"20437","lastEdit":"10/03/2024","category":"other","question":"In the event of a nose-low upset recovery, what is the correct sequence of actions for the pilot flying?","options":{"A":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, apply nose up elevator, apply nose up trim if needed, roll in the shortest direction to wings level, adjust thrust and drag as needed, if stalled recover from stall","B":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, if stalled recover from stall, apply nose up elevator, roll in the shortest direction to wings level, apply nose up trim if needed, adjust thrust and drag as needed","C":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, if stalled recover from stall, roll in the shortest direction to wings level, apply nose up elevator, apply nose up trim if needed, adjust thrust and drag as needed","D":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, if stalled recover from stall, adjust thrust and drag as needed, roll in the shortest direction to wings level, apply nose up elevator, apply nose up trim if needed"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Upset Recovery, Nose Low Recovery"},{"id":"20443","lastEdit":"07/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"When does EICAS EQUIP COOLING display?","options":{"A":"On the ground when the aft equipment cooling system is inoperative","B":"When the forward equipment cooling is failed","C":"When the bulk compartment temp is too cold for pets","D":"When one of the two supply fans is inoperative"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC EQUIP COOLING"},{"id":"20545","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the EICAS NO LAND 3 message indicate?","options":{"A":"The autopilot disconnect switch has been pushed","B":"Autoland is inoperative","C":"The autopilot is inoperative","D":"The autoland system does not have redundancy for triple channel autoland"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, EICAS Messages, Automatic Flight EICAS Messages"},{"id":"20741","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When does the autobrake application begin after landing?","options":{"A":"After the wheels have spun up and the reverse thrust levers are pulled","B":"After the wheels have spun up and the left main gear strut is compressed","C":"After wheels have spun up","D":"After both thrust levers are retard to idle and the wheels have spun up"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, System Description, Brake System, Autobrake System"},{"id":"20816","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the maximum operating altitude?","options":{"A":"43500 feet pressure altitude","B":"42100 feet pressure altitude","C":"43000 feet pressure altitude","D":"43100 feet pressure altitude"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Limitations Airplane General"},{"id":"20927","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"What should the PF and PM verify on the missed approach just after 400 feet?","options":{"A":"PF: Verify the missed approach altitude is set. PM: Verify the missed approach is tracked","B":"PF: Verify the missed approach is tracked, PM: Verify the missed approach altitude is set","C":"PF: Verify the after takeoff checklist is displayed. PM: Verify CON thrust is set","D":"PF: Verify CON thrust is set, PM: Verify the after takeoff checklist is displayed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Go around and missed approach procedure"},{"id":"20997","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"When is a verbal confirm step not required in a non normal checklist?","options":{"A":"Whenever the captain deems it necessary","B":"It is always required","C":"When an engine fails in the cruise","D":"On the ground"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non normal Checklists, Non normal checklist operation, Confirm Step"},{"id":"21030","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding ETOPS fuel planning?","options":{"A":"ETOPS fuel planning includes the standard fuel scenario to the ETOPS exit point and then a diversion to one of the ETOPS alternates","B":"ETOPS fuel planning includes the standard fuel scenario to the critical equal time point and then a diversion to one of the ETOPS alternates","C":"ETOPS fuel planning includes the standard fuel scenario to the ETOPS entry point and then a diversion to one of the ETOPS alternates","D":"ETOPS fuel planning includes the standard fuel scenario to the ETOPS equal distance point and then a diversion to one of the ETOPS alternates"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.5.2.1 ETOPS Fuel Planning"},{"id":"21141","lastEdit":"12/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What guidance does the FCTM state about low altitude level offs at low gross weights with high thrust?","options":{"A":"Use reduced thrust take-offs, do not engage the autopilot to prevent altitude overshoots","B":"Use reduced thrust take-offs, consider FLCH above 400 feet AGL to reduce the climb thrust, use manual thrust override as necessary","C":"Use reduced thrust take-offs, delay the acceleration to ensure flap is deployed for longer (more drag)","D":"Use reduced thrust take-offs, request a higher altitude from ATC, use VNAV speed intervention to set the speed at the current flap manoeuvring speed"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCTM 4, Climb Cruise Descent and Landing, Climb, Low Altitude Level Off"},{"id":"21525","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is true about TCAS traffic alerts?","options":{"A":"There are four types of traffic alerts: Offscale, Proximate, TA and RA","B":"RA predicts a conflict in approximately 40 to 50 seconds","C":"GPWS immediate windshear alert inhibits all TCAS alerts","D":"The TA symbol is a filled white diamond"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, System Description, Alert Inhibits"},{"id":"21880","lastEdit":"01/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding maximum rates of descent?","options":{"A":"5000 fpm max down to 5000 feet AGL, 3000 fpm max down to 3000 feet AGL, 2000 fpm max down to 2000 feet AGL, 1000 fpm max below 1000 feet AGL","B":"5000 fpm max down to 5000 feet AGL, 3000 fpm max down to 3000 feet AGL, 2000 fpm max down to 1000 feet AGL, 1000 fpm max below 1000 feet AGL","C":"4000 fpm max down to 4000 feet AGL, 3000 fpm max down to 2000 feet AGL, 2000 fpm max down to 1000 feet AGL, 1500 fpm max below 1000 feet AGL","D":"5000 fpm max down to 5000 feet AGL, 3000 fpm max down to 2000 feet AGL, 2000 fpm max down to 2000 feet AGL, 1500 fpm max below 1000 feet AGL"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.21 Rate of Descent"},{"id":"21917","lastEdit":"22/03/2024","category":"other","question":"When departing in precipitation that is either ice pellets or small hail which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"Type II or type IV fluid must be used","B":"Type I or type IV undiluted fluid must be used","C":"Type III or type IV undiluted fluid must be used","D":"Type II or type III fluid must be used"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.9 Ice Pellets, Small Hail and Hail"},{"id":"21923","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"When overflying the Baghdad FIR, what is the minimum flight level, and what must be done if this level is not achieved due to ATC constraints?","options":{"A":"Minimum FL300, climb to FL300 as soon as practicable if not achieved","B":"Minimum FL280, file an ASR if this is not achieved","C":"Minimum FL250, file an ASR if this is not achieved","D":"Minimum FL320, climb to FL320 as soon as practicable if not achieved"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 12.3.7.8.1 Overflight of Iraq/Baghdad FIR states minimum FL300"},{"id":"21935","lastEdit":"05/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"When an MEL or CDL has a penalty to the performance limited weights (PLW) does the OPT calculator ensure the en-route climb performance requirements are met?","options":{"A":"Yes","B":"BLANK","C":"No","D":"BLANK"},"answer":"C","reference":"OPT is used for Takeoff and Landing performance requirements ONLY. OPT does not calculate En- route Climb PLW (Engine- Out Scenarios). CDL along with MEL is used for en- route PLW calculations (Dispatch and FCOM can help figuiring out the penalties)."},{"id":"22186","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding TAC?","options":{"A":"It's available above 60 knots in the normal flight control mode","B":"It's available above 70 knots in the normal flight control mode","C":"It's available above 60 knots in the normal and secondary flight control modes","D":"It's available above 70 knots in the normal and secondary flight control modes"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Yaw Control, Thrust Asymmetry Compensation"},{"id":"22439","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What contract is in place between Stockholm Radio and our company?","options":{"A":"There is no contract in place","B":"There is a contract to provide backup medical support via HF and SATPHONE and Email when GMS is not available","C":"There is a contract to provide backup medical support via HF and SATPHONE when GMS is not available","D":"There is a contract to provide backup medical support via HF when GMS is not available"},"answer":"A","reference":"eLearning - If you know the module let us know"},{"id":"22555","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"If company regulations violate national or international laws or regulations, which rules do you follow?","options":{"A":"ICAO","B":"National or international laws","C":"Company policies","D":"UAE CAR OPS"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 1.1.1 Company Regulations and Policies"},{"id":"22695","lastEdit":"20/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"The actions for the windshear escape manoeuvre in automatic flight are? (in the correct sequence)","options":{"A":"Push either TOGA switch, call 'Windshear TOGA', retract speedbrakes, verify, GA thrust, verify TOGA mode annunciation","B":"Call 'Windshear TOGA', push either TOGA switch, verify GA thrust, verify TOGA mode annunciation, retract speedbrakes","C":"Call 'Windshear TOGA', push either TOGA switch, verify TOGA mode annunciation, verify GA thrust, retract speedbrakes","D":"Call 'Windshear TOGA', push either TOGA switch, retract speedbrakes, verify, GA thrust, verify TOGA mode annunciation"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Windshear, Windshear Warning"},{"id":"22701","lastEdit":"03/01/2024","category":"interview","question":"In regards to METAR RVR information, which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"R36/1000U - Runway 36 has a runway visual range of 1000 metres and an increasing trend in the last 10 minutes","B":"R18/0700D - Runway 18 has a runway visual range of 700 metres and no change in the last 15 minutes","C":"R09/0500D - Runway 09 has a visibility of 500 metres and an decreasing trend in the last 30 minutes","D":"R27/1200U - Runway 27 has a visibility of 1200 metres and an increasing trend in the last 30 minutes"},"answer":"A","reference":"Lido Met 1.3.2.11 Decoding of a TAF, METAR and SPECI (Lido page 550)"},{"id":"22920","lastEdit":"25/12/2023","category":"other","question":"With the start selector in the NORM position and a flameout is detected in an engine, when is continuous ignition automatically provided?","options":{"A":"When a landing flap is selected","B":"When the flap lever is out of the up position or engine anti-ice is on","C":"When the landing gear is down","D":"When the thrust levers reach idle or the landing gear is down"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Start and Ignition System, Engine Ignition"},{"id":"23118","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"both","question":"When should the QRH NNC BOMB ON BOARD be actioned?","options":{"A":"When the threat is assessed as red by group security","B":"When group security are not contactable and the Commander assessed the threat as orange or higher","C":"As soon as the pilots recognise there is a threat to their aircraft","D":"Once the PA"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 10.5.4.2 Threat Assessment"},{"id":"23136","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"The ETOPS critical fuel scenario is defined as?","options":{"A":"Descent from normal cruise altitude, cruise at the required diversion level and speed, first approach as an instrument procedure, landing with final reserve in tanks","B":"Descent from normal cruise altitude, cruise at the required diversion level and speed, first and second approach as instrument procedure, landing with final reserve in tanks","C":"Descent from normal cruise altitude, cruise at the required diversion level and speed, first approach and missed approach as an instrument procedure, second approach as visual circuit","D":"Descent from normal cruise altitude, cruise at the required diversion level and speed, normal descent to 1500 feet above the diversion aerodrome, 15 minutes holding, first approach and missed approach as an instrument procedure, second approach as a visual circuit"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.5.2.2 ETOPS critical fuel scenario"},{"id":"23147","lastEdit":"30/06/2024","category":"other","question":"If the entry door 1L indicates white around black on doors synoptic, what is the condition of the door?","options":{"A":"Entry door 1L flight lock is not in the commanded position","B":"Status signals for passenger entry 1L are not present or invalid","C":"Entry door 1L is open","D":"Entry door 1L is properly closed, latched and locked"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Controls and Indicators, Doors and Windows, Door Synoptic Display"},{"id":"23164","lastEdit":"11/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding status messages?","options":{"A":"The status page will not list any faults until 30 minutes after TOGA is pressed","B":"The status cue will be inhibited until 30 minutes after engine start","C":"The status page will not list any faults until 30 minutes after push back","D":"The status cue will be inhibited until 30 minutes after lift-off"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Warning Systems, System Description, Alert Inhibits, Alerts Inhibited During Takeoff, Status Cue"},{"id":"23186","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Where must human organs be loaded onboard the passenger aircraft?","options":{"A":"Bulk hold only","B":"Holds 1, 2, 3, 4","C":"Holds 3, 4 and bulk or cabin if it fits inside a lockable stowage and contains no blood or dry ice","D":"Holds 3, 4 and bulk"},"answer":"C","reference":"Ground Ops Manual, Chapter 13, Load Processing, 10 Live Human Organs/Blood (LHO)"},{"id":"23191","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Displaced Threshold 550m, how many feet do you add on all crossing altitudes during approach? (except MDA)","options":{"A":"60 ft","B":"100 ft","C":"110 ft","D":"80 ft"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 6.3 Departure, Approach and Missed Approach, Displaced Threshold Guidance Table"},{"id":"23221","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"other","question":"The memory items for Aborted Engine Start L/R are:","options":{"A":"Engine start selector - off, Fuel control switch - cutoff","B":"Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine start selector - off","C":"Fuel control switch - confirm - cutoff","D":"Fuel control switch - cutoff"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH NNC Aborted Engine Start L/R"},{"id":"23299","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"Where can you find holdover times?","options":{"A":"OME","B":"OMC","C":"RAIG","D":"OMA"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3"},{"id":"23516","lastEdit":"06/11/2024","category":"other","question":"When is a Pre-take-off Contamination Inspection NOT to be used?","options":{"A":"In light freezing rain","B":"In heavy snow conditions","C":"In precipitation of either small hail or ice pellets","D":"When the holdover time is 20 minutes or less"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.9 Ice Pellets, Small Hail and Hail"},{"id":"23888","lastEdit":"29/04/2024","category":"other","question":"Where can you find information on the minimum required RVR/visibility after a failure of the approach or runway lighting at an airport?","options":{"A":"LIDO GEN (1950) 1.4.8.9.2 Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (ICAO) or Canada CRAR (C-230) 3.190.7.3 Failed or Downgraded Ground EquipmenÃ¯Â»Â¿t fÃ¯Â»Â¿or NÃ¯Â»Â¿on-Canadian OperatÃ¯Â»Â¿ors (Canada) or QRH, Ops Info, Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (CAR-AIR OPS)","B":"LIDO GEN (1950) 1.4.8.9.2 Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (ICAO) or UK CRAR (C-230) 3.190.7.3 Failed or Downgraded Ground EquipmenÃ¯Â»Â¿t fÃ¯Â»Â¿or NÃ¯Â»Â¿on-UK OperatÃ¯Â»Â¿ors (UK) or QRH, Ops Info, Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (CAR-AIR OPS)","C":"LIDO GEN (1950) 1.4.8.9.2 Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (EASA) or USA CRAR (C-230) 3.190.7.3 Failed or Downgraded Ground EquipmenÃ¯Â»Â¿t fÃ¯Â»Â¿or NÃ¯Â»Â¿on-US OperatÃ¯Â»Â¿ors (USA) or QRH, Ops Info, Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (CAR-AIR OPS)","D":"LIDO GEN (1950) 1.4.8.9.2 Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (EASA) or USA/CANADA CRAR (C-230) 3.190.7.3 Failed or Downgraded Ground EquipmenÃ¯Â»Â¿t fÃ¯Â»Â¿or NÃ¯Â»Â¿on-North American OperatÃ¯Â»Â¿ors (USA/CANADA) or QRH, Ops Info, Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (CAR-AIR OPS)"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO GEN (1950) 1.4.8.9.2 Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (EASA) or USA CRAR (C-230) 3.190.7.3 Failed or Downgraded Ground EquipmenÃ¯Â»Â¿t fÃ¯Â»Â¿or NÃ¯Â»Â¿on-US OperatÃ¯Â»Â¿ors (USA) or QRH, Ops Info, Failed or Downgraded Ground Equipment (CAR-AIR OPS) - Note: The QRH version (CAR OPS) redirects you to use the EASA LIDO GEN table to calculate your new RVR/visibility, however I would also consult the USA version for US ops and take the most conservative result"},{"id":"24027","lastEdit":"21/02/2024","category":"other","question":"Which is not a characteristic of the secondary flap and slat mode?","options":{"A":"There is a slat load relief system","B":"Operation of the slats is electrical","C":"There is a flap load relief system","D":"There is an expanded flap and slat position indication"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Flaps and Slats, Flap/Slat Load Relief"},{"id":"24165","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the Certificate of Release to Service?","options":{"A":"CRS is not required in case of 'NIL DEFECTS' and can be signed by the Commander or engineer","B":"CRS is mandatory in all cases and can be signed by the Commander or engineer","C":"CRS is not required in case of 'NIL DEFECTS' and can be signed by the Commander only","D":"CRS is mandatory in all cases and can be signed by the engineer only"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.11.2 Certificate of Release to Service"},{"id":"24199","lastEdit":"15/05/2024","category":"other","question":"If the APU is in the attended mode what fault causes an immediate automatic shutdown?","options":{"A":"High oil temperature","B":"APU controller failure","C":"Low oil pressure","D":"High EGT"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, APU System Description, APU Operation, APU Operating Modes"},{"id":"24490","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"You plan an RNP approach to an aerodrome in ISA+30 at sea level. What will be the true altitude passing the FAF altitude of 2000 feet?","options":{"A":"2000 feet","B":"1800 feet","C":"2200 feet","D":"1850 feet"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.4.2 Warm Temperature Altitude Considerations"},{"id":"24562","lastEdit":"11/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"When calculating landing performance for a runway described as 'slippery when wet' by NOTAM/CCI, which runway condition shall be used?","options":{"A":"Good to Medium","B":"Good","C":"Medium to Poor","D":"Medium"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, OPT Performance Calculations, OPT Actual Landing Weight Calculation (OPT LANDING ENROUTE), see note ***The Runway Condition (OPT Selection) of a wet runway is 'Good', unless the runway is described as 'Slippery when wet' by the company or any other official source. In this case 'Medium' shall be selected"},{"id":"24569","lastEdit":"13/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"What does the green external power AVAIL light indicate?","options":{"A":"Electrical Power is available to the electrical busses but may not be correct","B":"External Power is connected to all the airplane's electrical busses","C":"External Power is disconnected from the airplane","D":"External Power is available to the airplane, correct and ready to power the electrical busses"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, Controls and Indicators, Electrical Panel"},{"id":"24766","lastEdit":"04/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"When considering departure tarmac delays in the USA which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"The tarmac delay clock starts at brakes release. Passengers must be updated on the status of the delay every 45 minutes, if the delay approaches 2 hours the aircraft must return to the gate","B":"The tarmac delay clock starts at aircraft pushback. Passengers must be updated on the status of the delay every 45 minutes, if the delay approaches 4 hours the aircraft must return to the gate","C":"The tarmac delay clock starts at scheduled departure time. Passengers must be updated on the status of the delay every 30 minutes, if the delay approaches 2 hours the aircraft must return to the gate","D":"The tarmac delay clock starts at doors closed. Passengers must be updated on the status of the delay every 30 minutes, if the delay approaches 4 hours the aircraft must return to the gate"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 14.1.7 Tarmac Delays"},{"id":"24772","lastEdit":"24/12/2024","category":"other","question":"Where can pilots find the reference document outlining Core Competencies and Observable Behaviours, which are used as the basis for grading during the command course?","options":{"A":"OMD - 3.1.2.3 - Core Competencies and Observable Behaviours","B":"Crew Resource Manual - 4.9.2 - Levels of Competence","C":"Command Course Footprint Manual - Competency Standards","D":"Command Handbook - Appendix B - Grading Guidelines"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMD - 3.1.2.3 Core Competencies and Observable Behaviours"},{"id":"25328","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the secondary source of power to the flight control system if one or more PMG's are unpowered?","options":{"A":"Left transfer bus","B":"Hot battery bus","C":"Main AC busses","D":"DC busses"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, Electrical System, Flight control DC Electrical System."},{"id":"25353","lastEdit":"11/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following criteria is NOT a requirement for a CAT A airport?","options":{"A":"Availability of non-standard approach aids and/or approach patterns","B":"Night operations capability","C":"Published circling minima not higher than 1000 feet AAL","D":"At least one runway with no performance limited procedure for take off and/or landing"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.1 Aerodrome Categorisation"},{"id":"25437","lastEdit":"23/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which condition requires a mandatory anti-icing treatment of the aircraft?","options":{"A":"Ice Pellets","B":"Snow","C":"Freezing Fog","D":"Drizzle"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.4 Freezing Fog - It's also worth asking for the engineer to check for fan blade ice"},{"id":"25446","lastEdit":"31/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Icing conditions exist in flight when?","options":{"A":"TAT is 10 Celsius or below and visible moisture (clouds, fog with visibility less than one statute mile or less, rain, snow, sleet, ice crystals, and so on) is present","B":"TAT is 10 Celsius or below and visible moisture (clouds, fog with visibility less than one kilometre or less, rain, snow, sleet, ice crystals, and so on) is present","C":"SAT is 10 Celsius or below and visible moisture (clouds, fog with visibility less than one statute miles or less, rain, snow, sleet, ice crystals, and so on) is present","D":"SAT is 10 Celsius or below and visible moisture (clouds, fog with visibility less than one kilometre or less, rain, snow, sleet, ice crystals, and so on) is present"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Supplementary Procedures, Adverse Weather, Cold Weather Operations"},{"id":"25490","lastEdit":"19/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Is the aircraft and operator certified for CAT1 LTS or CAT 2 OTS approaches?","options":{"A":"CAT 1 LTS: No - CAT 2 OTS: Yes","B":"CAT 1 LTS: Yes - CAT 2 OTS: Yes","C":"CAT 1 LTS: No - CAT 2 OTS: No","D":"CAT 1 LTS: Yes - CAT 2 OTS: No"},"answer":"C","reference":"Ops Spec Page 2, table: see CAT 2 OTS and CAT 1 LTS + OMA 8.1.3.2.1 Precision Approach Procedure"},{"id":"25515","lastEdit":"14/04/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is true for autolands on a contaminated runway?","options":{"A":"AFDS idle mode performance cannot be assured when used on contaminated runway","B":"AFDS flare mode performance cannot be assured when used on contaminated runway","C":"AFDS autobrake mode performance cannot be assured when used on contaminated runway","D":"AFDS rollout mode performance cannot be assured when used on contaminated runway"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, LVO, Approach and Landing, AFDS rollout mode performance cannot be assured when used on contaminated runway"},{"id":"25701","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"Whilst flying over the EU you must execute an emergency descent, what action must you take?","options":{"A":"Initiate a turn away from the assigned route","B":"Maintain airway centreline","C":"Offset 5 miles right of airway centreline","D":"Offset 1 mile right of airway centreline"},"answer":"A","reference":"LIDO RAR 2.1.2.16.1.1 Action by the Pilot in Command"},{"id":"25709","lastEdit":"12/01/2024","category":"other","question":"In cold weather operations you must complete a pre-take-off contamination inspection. Which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"A PCI must be completed within 5 minutes of take-off (rotation)","B":"A PCI must be completed within 5 minutes of take-off clearance","C":"A PCI must be completed within 5 minutes of take-off (application of power)","D":"A PCI must be completed within 5 minutes of take-off clearance acknowledgement"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.6 Step 5 Pre-takeoff Contamination Inspection + MEL Preamble 1.9 (not the best references but there's no argument to state the PCI expiry is within 5 minutes of rotation/airborne)"},{"id":"26085","lastEdit":"26/02/2024","category":"other","question":"Which condition does NOT reduce the holdover times during de-icing/anti-icing operations?","options":{"A":"High Winds","B":"Heavy Precipitation","C":"Low Humidity","D":"Jet Blast"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.11.1 HOT Guidelines for SAE Type I/II/III/IV Fluids"},{"id":"26094","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"Select the true statement about alternate gear extension","options":{"A":"A dedicated DC hydraulic pump delivers pressure to lower the gear. There is no free fall","B":"The landing gear lever has to be in the down position before activating the ALTERNATE GEAR switch","C":"The EICAS landing gear position indication displays the expanded gear position indication","D":"The landing gear can never be retracted following an alternate extension"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, Systems description, Landing Gear Operation, Landing Gear Alternate Extension."},{"id":"26234","lastEdit":"17/12/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which of the following causes the RAT to deploy automatically in flight?","options":{"A":"Left engine is failed and center hydraulic system pressure is low","B":"Left AC transfer bus and right main AC bus are un-powered","C":"Center and right hydraulic system pressure is","D":"Both AC transfer buses are un-powered"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, System Description, Ram Air Turbine"},{"id":"26248","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What happens when an APU fire is detected on the ground and the engines are running?","options":{"A":"The APU shuts down automatically and the fire bottle discharges automatically","B":"The APU shuts down automatically but the fire bottle must be discharged manually","C":"The APU does not shut down automatically but the fire bottle discharges automatically","D":"The APU does not shut down automatically and the fire bottle must be discharged manually"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, APU Fire Protection, APU Fire Detection"},{"id":"26274","lastEdit":"06/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"When using CPDLC during a GPS time shift, which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"FANS connections function with 'UPLINK DELAY EXCEEDED' errors; ATN connections may be rejected or show 'INVALID UPLINK'","B":"Both FANS and ATN connections will cease functioning during a GPS time shift","C":"FANS connections will automatically disconnect with a message 'ATC COMM TERMINATED'","D":"ATN connections always continue without any error messages during a time shift"},"answer":"A","reference":"Bulletin EKIB-58 R4 Global Positioning System Signal Interference, Section 7, Air Traffic Control (ATC) data link"},{"id":"26302","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"At 3000 feet airfield elevation and an airfield temperature of 39 Celsius and approach speed 146 knots (10 knot tailwind) - what kind of descent rate can we expect for a published 3.0 degree RNP approach?","options":{"A":"850 ft/min","B":"1050 ft/min","C":"750 ft/min","D":"950 ft/min"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO 1.7.7.11 LAT, Unit Conversion and tables, Descent Gradient Table + OMC 10.4.2 Warm Temperature Altitude Considerations (ISA+30 to give us an extra 10% altitude, thus the approach becomes approximately 3.25 degrees) + IAS to TAS conversion of 2% extra per 1000 feet"},{"id":"26460","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Above what altitude can you disengage the approach mode by pushing the APP switch a second time?","options":{"A":"1500 feet AAL","B":"500 RA","C":"1500 feet RA","D":"1000 AAL"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director Approach Mode Controls"},{"id":"26502","lastEdit":"30/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"What does EICAS LANDING ALTITUDE indicate?","options":{"A":"Automatic pressurization control is failed or both outflow valve switches are in manual","B":"The aircraft is at low altitude and the cabin pressure has not achieved the targeted landing altitude","C":"The FMC does not supply a landing altitude The landing altitude selector is pulled","D":"The landing altitude selector is pulled and set to below -2000 feet or above +10000 feet"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, 2.50 Air Systems EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"26720","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"What does EICAS SATCOM indicate?","options":{"A":"A SATCOM voice call has been received and is waiting to be answered","B":"SATCOM system has failed","C":"SATCOM capability is temporarily lost","D":"SATCOM datalink has failed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, EICAS Messages, Comms EICAS Alert Messages, SATCOM"},{"id":"26763","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding low visibility take-offs?","options":{"A":"Low Visibility Procedures shall be in force when the RVR is less than 1500m","B":"When no reported meteorological visibility or RVR is available a take-off may only be commenced if the Airport Authority and the Commander can determine that the RVR/visibility along the take-off run is equal to or better than the required minimum","C":"The reported RVR/visibility shall be at or above the visibility shown on the Lido CCI plus 500m","D":"When the reported meteorological visibility is below that required for take-off and RVR is not reported, a take-off may only be commenced if the Commander can determine that the RVR/visibility along the take-off run is equal to or better than the required minimum"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.2 Takeoff Minima"},{"id":"26839","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When flying an approach at minus 5 Celsius at the airfield do you need to apply cold weather temperature corrections? (charted approach minimum temperature limit of minus 10 Celsius)","options":{"A":"Yes, the airfield is at or below 0 Celsius","B":"Yes, as per the NOTAM","C":"No, at the commanders discretion","D":"No, the airfield temperature is above the charted temperature limit"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.4.1 General Cold Temperature Altitude Corrections"},{"id":"26846","lastEdit":"05/02/2025","category":"interview","question":"During an emergency landing or ditching which PA's should be made to the passengers and crew?","options":{"A":"At approximately two minutes to touchdown or 2000 feet 'Attention crew at stations' and at approximately 30 seconds to impact 'Brace, brace'","B":"At approximately two minutes to touchdown or 2000 feet 'This is the Captain, attention crew at stations' and at approximately 30 seconds to impact 'This is the Captain, brace brace'","C":"At approximately three minutes to touchdown or 3000 feet 'This is the Captain, attention crew at stations' and at approximately one minute to impact 'This is the Captain, brace brace'","D":"At approximately three minutes to touchdown or 3000 feet 'Attention crew at stations' and at approximately one minute to impact 'Brace, brace'"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, Non Normal Announcements"},{"id":"26874","lastEdit":"13/08/2024","category":"tech","question":"Antiskid protection is provided in which systems?","options":{"A":"Normal and Alternate Brake Systems","B":"Normal Brake System","C":"Alternate Brake System","D":"Normal Brake System, Alternate Brake System, Antiskid protection is also provided when the brake system is being supplied pressure only from the brake accumulator"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, Brake System, Antiskid Protection"},{"id":"26889","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding takeoff alternates? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"The maximum distance a takeoff alternate must be is 840 nautical miles except when in the USA when it is 420 nautical miles","B":"When non ETOPS the maximum distance a takeoff alternate must be is 420 nautical miles. If ETOPS then it can be up to 840 nautical miles away (excluding USA)","C":"The maximum distance a takeoff alternate must be is 420 nautical miles","D":"When non ETOPS the maximum distance a takeoff alternate must be is 420 nautical miles. If ETOPS then it can be up to 840 nautical miles away"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.1 Takeoff Alternate Aerodrome"},{"id":"26929","lastEdit":"10/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"What triggers the 'altimeter setting' callout?","options":{"A":"The RAAS triggers the callout below transition altitude when the ADC and GPS altitudes differ. It repeats once after 8 seconds","B":"The RAAS triggers the callout below transition level when the ADC and GPS altitudes differ. It repeats once after 8 seconds","C":"The EGPWS triggers the callout below transition altitude when the ADC and GPS altitudes differ. It repeats once after 8 seconds","D":"The EGPWS triggers the callout below transition level when the ADC and GPS altitudes differ. It repeats once after 8 seconds"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Warning Systems, System Description, SmartLanding System, Altimeter Monitor - Advisory"},{"id":"27020","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"When the RAT deploys automatically due to system failures, what does it hydraulically power?","options":{"A":"Alternate gear extension","B":"Only spoilers 3 and 12 and the stabilizer","C":"Primary Flight Control components normally powered by the center hydraulic system","D":"Normal brakes (after landing and airspeed <60 kts)"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, System Description, Ram Air Turbine"},{"id":"27056","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"If left engine vibration displays 2.5 N2 and the right engine vibration displays 1.8 N1, which of the following is true?","options":{"A":"Right engine vibrations are higher than the left","B":"The N2 rotor is the source of highest vibrations on right engine","C":"N1 vibrations are indicated on the left engine","D":"The N2 rotor is the source of highest vibration on left engine"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Controls and Indicators, Secondary Engine Indications, Engine Vibration Indications"},{"id":"27162","lastEdit":"27/12/2024","category":"other","question":"Which airports feature enhanced security communication procedures as per the OMC? (activated by co-notam)","options":{"A":"Basra, Baghdad, Tehran, Istanbul","B":"Tehran, Larnaca, Lahore, Amman","C":"Amman, Baghdad, Larnaca, Cairo","D":"Basra, Baghdad, Erbil, Tehran"},"answer":"D","reference":"Co-notam as appropriate for each airfield, Beirut is expected to feature but the route is still suspended"},{"id":"27216","lastEdit":"04/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"What does PBCS stand for, and how does it contribute to reduced separation in the NAT HLA?","options":{"A":"Primary-Based Control System; it replaces SATCOM with HF radio for oceanic operations","B":"Precision-Based Control System; it improves only vertical separation through autopilot enhancements","C":"Performance-Based Communication and Surveillance; it enables reduced separation by requiring aircraft to meet specific communication and navigation performance standards","D":"Predictive-Based Coordination Standards; it forecasts traffic flow without enhancing separation"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 11.1 Performance Based Communication and Surveillance (PBCS)"},{"id":"27239","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"The aircraft tech log system allows the commander to satisfy themselves the aircraft is airworthy in accordance with which documents?","options":{"A":"MEL, CDL","B":"MEL, CDL, OMA","C":"MEL, CDL, OME","D":"FCOM"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1 Flight Preparation Instructions, (from the alphabetical list, CDL, MEL and 'Operations manual in respect of fuel, oil oxygen etc - i.e. OMA)"},{"id":"27256","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the minimum and maximum landing elevation limits for the pressurization system in automatic and manual mode?","options":{"A":"Automatic: minimum: -1000 feet, Maximum 13000 feet, Manual: minimum: -2000 feet, Maximum 14000 feet","B":"Automatic: minimum: -1400 feet, Maximum 10000 feet, Manual: minimum: -1400 feet, Maximum 14000 feet","C":"Automatic: minimum: -1000 feet, Maximum 14000 feet, Manual: minimum: -2000 feet, Maximum 14000 feet","D":"Automatic: minimum: -1400 feet, Maximum 8400 feet, Manual: minimum: -1400 feet, Maximum 14000 feet"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization with Automatic Operation"},{"id":"27327","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of these flight control surfaces droop when the trailing edge flaps extend?","options":{"A":"Slats only","B":"Flaperons and Slats","C":"Kruger Flaps and Slats","D":"Flaperons"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Flight Control Surfaces (Note Slats are not listed as a flight control surface)"},{"id":"27398","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When flight crew need assistance in flight from NCC or flight dispatcher during a non normal or emergency which message should be sent?","options":{"A":"XFLASH","B":"GFLASH","C":"Free text message","D":"AFLASH"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 1.3.2.1.1.1 XFLASH"},{"id":"27609","lastEdit":"02/08/2024","category":"other","question":"What indication provides positive confirmation that an evacuation slide/raft girt bar is engaged with the door sill?","options":{"A":"Black flag showing through the girt bar engaged view window","B":"Door handle in the closed position","C":"Yellow flag showing through the girt bar engaged view window","D":"Orange flag showing through the girt bar engaged view window"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Doors, Controls and Indicators, Entry Door"},{"id":"27879","lastEdit":"07/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the max FDP for an LRV flight with 4 flight crew members?","options":{"A":"Max FDP 20 hours","B":"Max FDP 18 hours","C":"Max FDP 15 hours","D":"Max FDP 22 hours"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 7.E.7 Unforeseen circumstances after reporting time"},{"id":"28071","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are the initial steps to extend the flaps using the alternate flap system?","options":{"A":"Arm ALT FLAPS ARM switch. Select ALT FLAPS Selector to EXT","B":"Push ALT FLAPS ARM switch to OFF. Select ALT FLAPS selector to EXT","C":"Arm ALT FLAPS ARM switch. Select ALT FLAPS selector to OFF","D":"Arm ALT FLAPS ARM switch. Select NORMAL FLAPS Selector to 20"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC FLAP/SLAT CONTROL"},{"id":"28077","lastEdit":"24/06/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which are the PRI Flight Controls modes?","options":{"A":"Primary, secondary, alternate","B":"Normal, secondary, alternate","C":"Normal, secondary, direct","D":"Primary, secondary, direct"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, Primary Flight Control System Modes"},{"id":"28250","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"The operator must ensure that dangerous goods recurrent training must take place within how many months after previous training?","options":{"A":"36","B":"12","C":"24","D":"6"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMD 2.1.3.4 Training Syllabi and Checking Programmes, Flight Crew, Recurrent Training, Dangerous Goods"},{"id":"28317","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the flight crew report time in Dubai for an LRV flight?","options":{"A":"STD-1:23","B":"STD-1:25","C":"STD-1:00","D":"STD-1:15"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 7.E.2 Annex 7.E: LRV - Key Rules and Conditions"},{"id":"28329","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the conditions for the Engine Limit Surge Stall L/R memory items?","options":{"A":"Engine thrust is less than the commanded thrust","B":"Airframe vibrations with abnormal engine indications, engine separation","C":"Engine indications are abnormal, engine indications show an exceedance, abnormal engine noises are heard, possibly without airframe vibration, There is no response to thrust lever movement or the response is abnormal, Flames in the exhaust only are reported","D":"Engine indications are abnormal, engine indications are quickly nearing or show an exceedance, abnormal engine noises are heard, possibly with airframe vibration, There is no response to thrust lever movement or the response is abnormal, Flames in the inlet or exhaust are reported"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Limit Surge Stall L/R"},{"id":"28413","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"The FMA reads: THR REF LNAV VNAV SPD - which of the following are true?","options":{"A":"Pitch is controlling vertical speed","B":"VNAV SPD is a climb mode only","C":"Pitch is controlling FMC selected airspeed","D":"Thrust is set to the selected thrust limit displayed on EICAS"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, System Description, Autopilot Flight Director System, AFDS Flight Mode Annunciations"},{"id":"28417","lastEdit":"27/01/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the flight crew report time at outstation for a non LRV flight?","options":{"A":"STD-1:15","B":"STD-1:00","C":"STD-1:23","D":"STD-1:25"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 7.6.1 Report time - Flight crew"},{"id":"28510","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"both","question":"When conducting an in-flight fuel check that indicates the usable fuel expected to remain upon landing at the destination aerodrome is less than the required alternate fuel plus the final reserve fuel, what must the Commander ensure to continue towards the destination aerodrome?","options":{"A":"The flight is within two hours of flying time from the destination aerodrome, considering fuel burn due to likely ATC delays","B":"The flight can reach at least one alternate aerodrome with alternate fuel plus twice the quantity of the final reserve fuel","C":"A safe landing can be achieved at two different aerodromes with not less than final reserve fuel","D":"The Expected Approach Time (EAT) is known, and weather forecasts indicate a high probability of landing success"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.2.1 Continue Towards Destination Aerodrome"},{"id":"28573","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"With the autopilot and LNAV engaged, what will happen if the last active route waypoint is passed?","options":{"A":"The autopilot will turn the airplane towards the destination","B":"LNAV maintains current heading","C":"LNAV will disengage","D":"HDG HOLD will engage"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director Roll and Pitch Controls"},{"id":"28607","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Is the Commander responsible for Safety Cards?","options":{"A":"Yes - The Commander delegates to the Cabin Crew and the Purser ensures it is done","B":"Yes - If there is no safety video","C":"No","D":"Yes - If there is no engineer present"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.16 Passenger Briefing Procedures"},{"id":"28689","lastEdit":"04/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"Where can you find a table that converts groundspeed and glidepath into rate of descent in feet per minute?","options":{"A":"QRH Performance Inflight, Aircraft Type, Advisory Information, Groundspeed Conversion Table","B":"FCTM 1, Warm Temperature Altitude Corrections","C":"OMC 10.4.3","D":"LIDO LAT 1.7.7.11"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO LAT 1.7.7.11 Descent Gradient Table"},{"id":"28885","lastEdit":"17/01/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is true regarding autopilot disengagement?","options":{"A":"When the rudder pedals are moved without LAND2 or LAND3 annunciated the autopilot will disengage","B":"The autopilot will not disengage if there is a system fault, it will only change to the degraded mode","C":"When an override force is sufficient to move the control column the autopilot will disengage","D":"The MCP Autopilot disengage bar is spring loaded to return to the UP position"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Automatic Flight, System Description, Autopilot Flight Director System, Autopilot Disengagement"},{"id":"28918","lastEdit":"11/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"On the 777F how is forward cargo heated?","options":{"A":"The lower forward cargo compartment is heated by electrical elements in the fuselage sidewalls","B":"The lower forward cargo compartment is heated by warm air from the forward equipment ventilation system","C":"The lower forward cargo compartment is heated by an independent bleed air heating system","D":"The lower forward cargo compartment is heated by recirculation fans that draw warm main deck air into the cargo compartment"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Cargo Temperature Control System, Cargo Heat System"},{"id":"28969","lastEdit":"11/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"During pushback a cabin crew member cannot arm their door due a malfunction, what is the correct course of action?","options":{"A":"Continue to destination without the door armed","B":"Have the Purser open and close the door to clear the jam","C":"Return to stand","D":"Use crew deferral to continue to destination"},"answer":"C","reference":"MEL 52-11-01-01A Main Entry Doors, Passengers Carried has a maintenance task therefore you must return to stand as per the technical fault resolution flowchart in the QRH"},{"id":"29153","lastEdit":"02/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which configuration is the landing climb gradient calculation assuming?","options":{"A":"One engine inoperative, go-around flaps, landing gear up","B":"One engine inoperative, approach flaps, landing gear up","C":"All engines operating, approach flaps, landing gear down","D":"All engines operating, landing flaps, landing gear down"},"answer":"D","reference":"B777 OPT Users Manual, Table of Contents, Other Available Functions, D) Viewing Airport Information"},{"id":"29209","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"What automatic switching will occur when you start the APU with the External Power connected?","options":{"A":"The APU starts but the generator doesn't come online until the the External Power is disconnected","B":"The APU connects to the Bus Tie and replaces Primary External Power","C":"The APU connects to the Bus Tie switches but does not power either Main Bus","D":"The APU connects to the Bus Tie and replaces Secondary External Power on the Left Main Bus"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, Systems Description, Electrical System, AC Electrical Power Sources (section under APU Generator)"},{"id":"29421","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which documents authorizes the company to carry dangerous goods?","options":{"A":"Air Operator Certificate.","B":"NOTOC","C":"IATA Dangerous Goods Certificate.","D":"GCAA Dangerous Goods Certificate and Operation Specification."},"answer":"D","reference":"Boeing 777 Regulatory Permits and Certificates, Ops Spec + GCAA Dangerous Goods Certificate"},{"id":"29562","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Which levers and switches require a verbal 'confirm' step before action is taken?","options":{"A":"Autothrottle arm switches, generator drive disconnect switch, ram air turbine","B":"Autothrottle arm switches, generator drive disconnect switch","C":"Stabilizer cut out switches","D":"Autothrottle arm switches, generator drive disconnect switch, fuel jettison switches"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non normal Checklists, Non normal checklist operation, Confirm Step"},{"id":"29754","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"In a non-Himalayan context, if the Operational Flight Plan (OFP) indicates the driftdown limit weight as ATOW+6, what is the true limit for driftdown in most cases?","options":{"A":"ATOW","B":"ATOW + 12000 kgs","C":"MTOW","D":"ATOW + 6000 kgs"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.1.4 EK OFP Decodes (Item 67)"},{"id":"29795","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"After which occurrence must a landing be made at the nearest suitable airport?","options":{"A":"A fire on board an aircraft and firefighting is effective","B":"Bomb threat","C":"An engine failure on a two engine aircraft","D":"Loss of both engine driven main generators"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC 7 Engine Failure L/R - Checklist states land at the nearest suitable."},{"id":"29815","lastEdit":"17/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"In which METAR precipitation should the Snowfall Intensities as a Function of Prevailing Visibility table not be used?","options":{"A":"BLSN","B":"SNFG (above 0c)","C":"SNIC","D":"SNFZFG"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3.1.2 Snowfall Intensities as a Function of Prevailing Visibility"},{"id":"29817","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"When carrying an expectant mother, what needs to be ascertained to assess if she can fly?","options":{"A":"Pregnancy duration in weeks, single or multiple pregnancy, any medical certificates from doctors","B":"Pregnancy duration in weeks, seat number, companions travelling with the woman","C":"Medical history including any previous pregnancy complications","D":"Pregnancy duration in weeks, complicated or uncomplicated, single or multiple pregnancy, any medical certificates from doctors or the company medical services"},"answer":"D","reference":"OME 11.11.1 Aviation First Aid, Aviation First Aid, Expectant Mothers Guidelines, Carriage of Expectant Mothers"},{"id":"29842","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding the ADS-B mandate for the North Atlantic?","options":{"A":"There is no ADS-B mandate in the North Atlantic","B":"ADS-B is mandated only on routes T9 and T290","C":"ADS-B is mandated below 80N","D":"ADS-B is mandated for the NAT HLA"},"answer":"B","reference":"LIDO 2.3.5.7.1 ATS Surveillance Services in the NAT HLA - Also note the T9 and T290 routes are not typical routings for us"},{"id":"29897","lastEdit":"24/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"When departing in precipitation that is either ice pellets or small hail which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"A pre-takeoff contamination inspection must be done within 5 minutes of takeoff","B":"Dispatch is not allowed in either precipitation","C":"Snow holdover times should be used","D":"Special holdover tables specifically designed for ice pellets should be used depending on if the anti-icing fluid is propylene glycol or ethylene glycol based"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.3.13 Operations in Ice Pellet and Small Hail Conditions, see tables 46 and 47"},{"id":"30079","lastEdit":"19/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are indications that the aircraft is in windshear?","options":{"A":"Airspeed abnormal by 5 knots, vertical speed abnormal by 1000 fpm, pitch abnormal by 1.5 degrees, 2 dot glideslope deviation, unusual thrust lever position","B":"Airspeed abnormal by 10 knots, vertical speed abnormal by 300 fpm, pitch abnormal by 4 degrees, 1 dot glideslope deviation, unusual thrust lever position","C":"Airspeed abnormal by 15 knots, vertical speed abnormal by 500 fpm, pitch abnormal by 5 degrees, 1 dot glideslope deviation, unusual thrust lever position","D":"Airspeed abnormal by 10 knots, vertical speed abnormal by 1500 fpm, pitch abnormal by 3 degrees, 1 dot glideslope deviation, unusual thrust lever position"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Windshear, Windshear Warning"},{"id":"30147","lastEdit":"23/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"When applying a TAF for the destination aerodrome, under what circumstances may weather deteriorations such as those indicated by PROB30, PROB40, or TEMPO be disregarded, and which weather conditions must still be fully considered?","options":{"A":"Deteriorations as PROB30 may be disregarded, however PROB40 and TEMPO must be considered","B":"Transient conditions like thunderstorms and showers must be considered. However, persistent conditions such as fog, mist, haze, or continuous precipitation may be disregarded","C":"Deteriorations as PROB30 and PROB40 may be disregarded, however TEMPO must be considered","D":"Transient conditions like thunderstorms and showers may be disregarded. However, persistent conditions such as fog, mist, haze, or continuous precipitation must be considered"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.6.1 Application of Aerodrome Forecast"},{"id":"30180","lastEdit":"21/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"When faced with an MEL or CDL with an en-route climb penalty what is a good TECHNIQUE for ensuring the performance requirements are met?","options":{"A":"Enter the MEL or CDL into the OPT and check the performance for landing and take-off","B":"Check the FCTM Driftdown level off altitude tables","C":"Adjust speed penalty using MEL>CDL>Enroute Diversion Speed Effects. If penalty is greater than 6000 kg, consult dispatch or FCOM driftdown tables. If less than 6000 kg, proceed; the OFP accounts for it","D":"The enroute climb penalty is never limiting, even in the Himalayan region"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.1.4 EK OFP Decodes (Item 67) + MEL, CDL, Enroute Diversion Speed Effects - As an absolute minimum the driftdown calculation weight on the OFP is actual takeoff weight plus 6000 kg (however usually MTOW) - if it exceeds 6000 kg then it's worth getting dispatch to check it again with the new data or check a driftdown table from the FCOM or QRH"},{"id":"30193","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"If a flight goes from N78E030 to N78E020 is it considered polar?","options":{"A":"No, it is south of N80","B":"Yes, it is north of N78 between these points","C":"Yes, it is south of N78 between these points","D":"No, it is south of N82"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 12.3.5.1 General (scroll down to the second image to see the polar region map) + QRH, Ops Info, Polar Ops + FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Flight Management System Operation, Lateral Navigation (see reference to LNAV using a great circle navigation) + LIDO NAV 1.5.11.1 Great Circle Distance and Track Tables"},{"id":"30203","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are some examples of required visual references for a CAT IIIB approach with DH? (Select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Three consecutive centre line lights","B":"Touchdown zone lights","C":"No visual reference is required","D":"At least one centre line light"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.2 Required Visual References"},{"id":"30240","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct about the OFP routes?","options":{"A":"MTT is minimum touchdown time. If followed by /R it means there are not restrictions","B":"MTT is minimum transatlantic trajectory. If followed by /R it means there are restrictions","C":"MTT is minimum time tactical. If followed by /R it means there are not restrictions","D":"MFT is minimum fuel track. If followed by /R it means there are restrictions"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.1.4 EK OFP Decodes (Item 8)"},{"id":"30435","lastEdit":"02/01/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the pro's and con's of a reduced thrust take-off vs TOGA take-off?","options":{"A":"A reduced thrust take-off increases engine wear, a TOGA take-off decreases the safety margin to avoid obstacles and runway overruns","B":"A reduced thrust take-off increases engine life, a TOGA take-off increases the safety margin to avoid obstacles and runway overruns","C":"A TOGA take-off reduces engine wear, a reduced thrust take-off decreases the take-off roll distance","D":"A TOGA take-off increases engine life, a reduced thrust take-off increases the safety margin to avoid obstacles and runway overruns"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Flight Management Computer, Thrust Management, Reduced Thrust Takeoff + OPT"},{"id":"30569","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"both","question":"What is a WCHS?","options":{"A":"Passengers who are completely immobile and require wheelchairs to/from the aeroplane and to/from their cabin seats","B":"Passengers who prefer the use of wheelchairs for convenience in airports but are capable of walking independently to and from their cabin seats without assistance","C":"Passengers who cannot ascend/descend steps but can make their own way slowly to/from the cabin seats","D":"Passengers who can ascend/descend steps steps and make their own way to/from their cabin seats but cannot walk long distances"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.2.2.1.2.3 Wheelchair Passengers"},{"id":"30576","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Both engine anti-ice selectors are on with EICAS ANTI-ICE ON displayed, how would you remove this message?","options":{"A":"Cancel EICAS","B":"Select both anti-ice selectors to auto","C":"Select both anti-ice selectors to norm","D":"Select both anti-ice selectors to on"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC, Anti-Ice-On"},{"id":"30639","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Balancing fuel requires the use of:","options":{"A":"Both crossfeed valves and both pumps in the low main tank","B":"Both crossfeed valves and both pumps in the high main tank","C":"Either crossfeed valve and both pumps in the high main tank","D":"Either crossfeed valve and both pumps in the low main tank"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Pumps (pump count ref) + FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Crossfeed and Imbalance (crossfeed ref)"},{"id":"30701","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which autobrake selector setting will you see immediately after takeoff?","options":{"A":"DISARM","B":"MAX AUTO","C":"OFF","D":"RTO"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, System Description, Brake System, Autobrake System"},{"id":"30975","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"What is an ERG code?","options":{"A":"Emergency Response Drill code","B":"Emergency Reaction Guide code","C":"Emergency Regulation Guidance code","D":"Explosive Regulatory Group code"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 9.11.1 Notification to Captain (NOTOC) - Section M"},{"id":"31002","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which item among the listed aircraft equipment, does NOT relate to refuelling precautions?","options":{"A":"HF radio","B":"VHF radio","C":"Weather Radar","D":"Strobes"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Limitations Non AFM operational information (HF radios) + OMA 8.2.1.2 Safety Precautions during refueling (strobes + weather radar)"},{"id":"31092","lastEdit":"26/06/2024","category":"both","question":"What are the alerts if lavatory smoke is detected?","options":{"A":"SMOKE LAVATORY or SMOKE LAV/COMPT displays and flight deck must contact the cabin crew to search for the lavatory fire","B":"An aural alert sounds in the cabin only and the EICAS advisory message SMOKE LAVATORY or SMOKE LAV/COMPT displays","C":"An aural alert sounds in the lavatory and in the cabin and the EICAS advisory message SMOKE LAVATORY or SMOKE LAV/COMPT displays and the master call light at the associated attendant station flashes","D":"An aural alert sounds in the lavatory and in the cabin and the EICAS caution message SMOKE LAV or SMOKE LAV/CPT displays and all cabin attendant stations display LAV FIRE"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, Lavatory Fire Protection, Lavatory Fire Detection"},{"id":"31223","lastEdit":"11/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"Where can you find aircraft modification status before you get to the aircraft?","options":{"A":"Operation Specification","B":"FCOM, Systems Description, Aircraft Modification Status","C":"Groupworld Portal, Operational, Aircraft Modification Status","D":"RAIG, Boeing 777 Performance, Aircraft Modification Status"},"answer":"C","reference":"Groupworld Portal, Operational, Aircraft Modification Status."},{"id":"31243","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which alerts can be displayed on the PFD?","options":{"A":"WINDSHEAR, ENG FAIL, TRAFFIC","B":"WINDSHEAR, ENG FAIL, PULL UP","C":"ENG FAIL, PULL UP, AIRSPEED LOW","D":"GO AROUND, TERRAIN, WINDSHEAR"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Primary Displays, Introduction"},{"id":"31339","lastEdit":"29/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the meaning of EICAS ICING WING?","options":{"A":"Wing anti-icing is functioning normally","B":"Wing anti-icing has failed","C":"Icing conditions exist and wing anti-ice is OFF or icing conditions exist and wing anti-icing is inhibited after take-off","D":"Icing conditions exist and wing anti-ice is functioning asymmetrically"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, EICAS Messages, Anti-ice rain system EICAS messages"},{"id":"31675","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Under normal conditions what is the source of bleed air to start the second engine?","options":{"A":"The engine already running","B":"Ground pneumatic cart","C":"Main battery","D":"APU"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Start and Ignition System"},{"id":"31709","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In cold weather ops the aircraft has ice that needs to be removed from the area underneath the wings. Which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"The aircraft must receive a full de-icing and anti-icing treatment","B":"Ice on the underside of the fuel tanks is acceptable and does not need deicing","C":"Local area deicing can be carried out as long as there is no precipitation or active frost, the aircraft must be treated symmetrically and holdover times do not apply","D":"The flaps must be extended fully before a de-icing treatment is applied"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.3.5 Removal of Local area Contamination"},{"id":"31714","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"On the OFP below the section where the ATC clearance is written it states DEFRTE followed by the waypoints and airways. What is Meant by DEFRTE?","options":{"A":"Minimum Cost Track","B":"Minimum Fuel Track","C":"Dispatcher Defined Route","D":"Default Route"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.1.4 EK OFP Decodes (Item 8)"},{"id":"31807","lastEdit":"19/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"The flight deck access system consists of:","options":{"A":"An emergency access panel, a chime module, a door lock selector, two indicator lights and an access system switch.","B":"An emergency access panel, a chime module, a door lock selector and an access system switch.","C":"An emergency access panel, a chime module, three indicator lights, a door lock selector and an access system switch.","D":"A chime module, a door lock selector and an access system switch."},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM 1.5 Flight Deck Door + OME 6.2.2.3 Normal Access Procedure. Do not confuse the indicator lights, there is a two light indicator on the aft aisle stand and three indicator lights on the access panel outside the flight deck."},{"id":"32032","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the sequence of steps to change airspeed with VNAV engaged, using speed intervention?","options":{"A":"Change the IAS/MACH window to the new airspeed, then push FLCH","B":"Push the IAS/MACH selector, then change the IAS/MACH window to the new airspeed","C":"Push the FLCH, change the IAS/MACH window to new airspeed","D":"Change the IAS/MACH window to the new airspeed, then push the IAS/MACH selector"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Flight Management System Operation, Vertical Navigation, MCP Speed Intervention"},{"id":"32155","lastEdit":"06/03/2024","category":"other","question":"When a TCAS RA is triggered, what is the correct sequence of steps? (not in the landing configuration)","options":{"A":"Disconnect autothrottle, disengage autopilot, smoothly adjust pitch and thrust to satisfy the RA command, do not deviate from the lateral flightpath unless ATC instructs you otherwise","B":"Disconnect autothrottle, disengage autopilot, smoothly adjust pitch and thrust to satisfy the RA command, follow the lateral flightpath unless visual contact indicates otherwise","C":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, smoothly adjust pitch and thrust to satisfy the RA command, follow the lateral flightpath unless visual contact indicates otherwise","D":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle, smoothly adjust pitch and thrust to satisfy the RA command, do not deviate from the lateral flightpath unless ATC instructs you otherwise"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Manouvres, Non Normal Manouvres, Traffic Avoidance"},{"id":"32175","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"You complete the HYD PRESS SYS C checklist and prompt CHECKLIST COMPLETE EXCEPT DEFERRED ITEMS is displayed. Which of the following is true?","options":{"A":"The deferred items cannot be completed on the approach checklist","B":"The deferred items cannot be completed on this checklist","C":"This checklist is complete only when deferred items are accomplished","D":"The deferred items can be completed on this checklist but should be completed on the approach checklist"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Electronic Checklist Description, Checklist Line Items, Deferred Line Items"},{"id":"32179","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are the conditions for Fire Engine L/R memory items?","options":{"A":"A fire is detected in the affected engine","B":"An engine tailpipe fire occurs on the ground with no engine fire warning","C":"A fire is observed in the affected engine","D":"EICAS indication 'DET FIRE ENG L/R'"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Fire Engine L/R (Not to be confused with Fire Engine on Ground L/R)"},{"id":"32309","lastEdit":"21/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"In which country can you NOT commit to destination?","options":{"A":"Philippines","B":"Hong Kong","C":"China","D":"Vietnam"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 12.3.8.2.9 Special Operation in Chinese Airspace"},{"id":"32477","lastEdit":"17/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which altitude is shown on the OFP navigation log?","options":{"A":"MORA","B":"MTCA","C":"MEA","D":"MGA"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.3.1 OFP Nav Log Decodes"},{"id":"32775","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"both","question":"Which is the applicable circling minima for a destination?","options":{"A":"Circling minima as per enhanced coded approach procedure or 8km vis, whichever is higher","B":"Circling minima as per enhanced coded approach procedure","C":"VMC","D":"Circling minima as per enhanced coded approach procedure or 5km vis, whichever is higher"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.3 Pre Flight Planning Minima"},{"id":"32981","lastEdit":"05/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Main gear steering is commanded when?","options":{"A":"When the nose wheel steering angle exceeds 13 degrees","B":"When the nose wheel steering angle exceeds 7 degrees","C":"When nose wheel angle exceeds 70 degrees","D":"When rudder pedals reach maximum deflection"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, Systems description, Nose Wheel and Main Gear Aft Axle Steering"},{"id":"33027","lastEdit":"03/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"How is the Cabin Altitude controlled with the Pressurization system in Manual Operation?","options":{"A":"FMC altitude information is bypassed and the cabin altitude controller uses internal rate schedules to control cabin altitude","B":"The AFT and FWD outflow valves control the cabin automatically as long as the OUTFLOW VALVE switches are in MAN","C":"The pressurization system is fully automatic and no selections need to be changed","D":"Setting the OUTFLOW VALVE switches to MAN and holding the related OUTFLOW VALVE MANUAL switch to OPEN or CLOSE"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM 2.30 Pressurization System Manual Operation"},{"id":"33177","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the difference between RNAV and RNP?","options":{"A":"RNP has an alerting element","B":"RNAV has an alerting element","C":"RNAV uses ADIRU, RNP uses GPS","D":"They're the same."},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 11.2.2 RNP En route comms/nav procedures, performance based navigation, RNP"},{"id":"33223","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"In which weather condition will an aerodrome be considered closed?","options":{"A":"If an airport weather report or forecast includes moderate or heavy freezing rain","B":"A surface mean windspeed of 60 knots or more","C":"If an airport weather report or forecast includes heavy freezing rain","D":"A surface windspeed (including gusts) of 60 knots or more"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.8.1 Dispatch Policy"},{"id":"33239","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What are some examples of required visual references for a CAT IIIB approach with no DH? (Select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"At least 3 consecutive centre line lights","B":"No visual reference required","C":"Touchdown zone lights","D":"One centre line light"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.2 Required Visual References"},{"id":"33295","lastEdit":"09/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Which category has the highest load acceptance priority? (Gets offloaded last)","options":{"A":"Perishable cargo","B":"Company mail","C":"Live animals","D":"Courier mail"},"answer":"B","reference":"Ground Ops Manual Chapter 13 Load Processing, Load Acceptance - Go Show Priorities (current tech exam has the following options: Documents prepared by skycargo, live animals, international mail, commercial staff, question has been modified as the GOM doesn't specify for documents from skycargo or international mail)"},{"id":"33559","lastEdit":"21/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is pseudo burnout?","options":{"A":"A system that automatically extends the flight duty period for crew members without considering their rest needs","B":"A scenario where the augmenting crew member is able to complete the flight without needing to be stood down from duty","C":"A strategy used to artificially inflate the maximum allowable flight duty period by altering the reporting times","D":"A provision that permits the crew to determine their own rest periods regardless of flight schedules or safety regulations"},"answer":"B","reference":"Groupworld Portal, Burnout Policy (last published 25 Jan 2024) - For example if you only need to extend your FDP by one hour to avoid discretion you could simply use equal rest between 3 crew members i.e. pseudo burnout. If you're extremely delayed then use burnout as per OMA 7."},{"id":"33594","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"In terms of Dangerous Goods - what is an overpack?","options":{"A":"Enclosure used by a single shipper to contain one or more packages and to form one handling unit for convenience of handling and stowage","B":"An oversized packing which needs special processing","C":"Container packing with goods vertically aligned and not exceeding maximum cargo hold height","D":"Ripped package due to tight packing"},"answer":"A","reference":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations - Appendix A - Glossary - Overpack"},{"id":"33648","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does EICAS warning CONFIG DOORS indicate in combination with DOOR ENTRY 2L advisory message?","options":{"A":"Door 2L is not secure and either engine are in the takeoff thrust range on the ground or in flight","B":"At least 2 doors are not closed, latched and locked and either engine are in the takeoff thrust range","C":"At least 2 doors are not closed, latched and locked and both engines are in the takeoff thrust range","D":"Door 2L is not secure and either engine are in the takeoff thrust range on the ground"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, EICAS Messages, Warning Systems EICAS Messages, Configuration"},{"id":"33697","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"In the direct mode which of the following components of the primary flight control system are not operating?","options":{"A":"Actuator Control Electronics (ACEs)","B":"Control surface actuators","C":"All components are operating","D":"Primary Flight Computers (PFCs)"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Primary Flight Control System Modes, Flight Control System Direct Mode"},{"id":"33769","lastEdit":"30/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"Where can we check engine oil quantity indications?","options":{"A":"Status Display","B":"Synoptic Display","C":"Maintenance Access Terminal","D":"Secondary Engine indications and Compact Engine Indications"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM - 7 Engines, APU - Controls and indicators - Secondary Engine Indications - Oil Quantity Indications"},{"id":"33805","lastEdit":"14/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"During preflight you receive the latest weather, ENGM 021120Z 02011KT 2500 R01R/0800D -SN VV011 M01/M04 Q0997= What extra steps must you consider before you calculate your holdover time?","options":{"A":"Consult the OMC table 10.3.1.2 Table 48 for Snowfall intensity as a function of prevailing visibility, using temperature, daylight or night and visibility or RVR (whichever is less)","B":"Consult the OMC table 10.3.1.2 Table 48 for Snowfall intensity as a function of prevailing visibility, using temperature, daylight or night and visibility","C":"Consult the OMC table 10.3.1.2 Table 48 for Snowfall intensity as a function of prevailing visibility, using temperature, daylight or night and visibility or RVR (whichever is greater)","D":"Consult the OMC table 10.3.1.2 Table 48 for Snowfall intensity as a function of prevailing visibility, using temperature, daylight or night and RVR"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 10.3.1.2 Table 48: Snowfall Intensity as a function of prevailing visibility (see notes regarding to NOT use RVR data)"},{"id":"33821","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the EICAS CONFIG WARNING SYS indicate if displayed in-flight?","options":{"A":"Takeoff config warning system and master warning lights inop","B":"Landing config warning system and master caution lights inop","C":"Takeoff and landing config warning systems, master warning lights, master caution lights and warning loudspeakers inop","D":"A fault is detected in the configuration warning system"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, EICAS Messages, Warning Systems EICAS Messages, Configuration"},{"id":"33853","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"During a flight you experience a generator failure and start the APU, this puts you below the required fuel at en-route fuel checks. You have an ETOPS critical fuel scenario ahead, what is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Re-route or divert","B":"Continue","C":"Climb above the FMC max altitude to gain fuel efficiency","D":"Shutdown the APU"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.5.6 ETOPS in flight procedures (item c)"},{"id":"33993","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"What is the company policy on avoidance of thunderstorms?","options":{"A":"Strong weather radar echoes should be avoided by at least 5 NM at or below FL200, and by at least 10 NM above FL200","B":"Strong weather radar echoes should be avoided by at least 10 NM at or below FL200, and by at least 20 NM above FL200","C":"Moderate or strong weather radar echoes should be avoided by at least 5 NM at or below FL200, and by at least 10 NM above FL200","D":"Moderate or strong weather radar echoes should be avoided by at least 10 NM at or below FL200, and by at least 20 NM above FL200"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.8.2 Thunderstorms"},{"id":"34402","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What happens if the ADIRU switch is left on and then primary power is removed from the airplane and the battery switch is turned off?","options":{"A":"The ON BAT light extinguishes when the BATTERY switch is turned off","B":"The ON BAT light illuminates and the ground crew call horn sounds","C":"The ON BAT light illuminates and the EICAS memo message ADIRU ON BAT displays","D":"Nothing. The ADIRU switch is always left on when securing the airplane"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Navigation Systems Description, Inertial System, Air Data Inertial Reference Unit (See ADIRU Power)"},{"id":"34777","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of these statements may be true if the offside tuning light is illuminated on the left radio tuning panel?","options":{"A":"The left radio tuning panel is tuning a radio normally tuned by one of the other tuning panels","B":"The frequency is being transferred from the STANDBY to the ACTIVE window","C":"The left radio tuning panel is inoperative","D":"The selected frequency is not in the normal frequency range"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, Controls and Indicators, Radio System, Radio Tuning Panel"},{"id":"35105","lastEdit":"16/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"With both the Left and Right Hydraulic System failed, the aircraft is still controllable. TRUE/FALSE?","options":{"A":"True","B":"False","C":"BLANK","D":"BLANK"},"answer":"A","reference":"HYD PRESS SYS L+C / FCTM Systems Description - 13. Hydraulics - Flight control system components are distributed so that any one hydraulic system can provide adequate airplane controllability"},{"id":"35116","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"You dispatch with MEL 24-11-01 Engine Driven Generator Systems (ELEC GEN OFF L) which requires continuous APU operation throughout the flight, 10 minutes before your first ETOPS entry point the APU fails. What is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Divert as the ETOPS critical fuel will be negatively impacted","B":"Continue as the aircraft meets the minimum generator requirements approaching the ETOPS entry point","C":"Continue as the aircraft has dispatched and the MEL does not apply","D":"Divert as the APU is required for ETOPS operations in this scenario"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.5 has no reference to required equipment prior to the entry point and the MEL shouldn't be used after dispatch, therefore any in-flight failures are irrelevant in terms of ETOPS"},{"id":"35228","lastEdit":"12/04/2024","category":"other","question":"When reducing rest away from home base, what is the minimum required time at the hotel, assuming travel does not exceed one hour?","options":{"A":"11 hours - using off duty and on duty times","B":"10 hours - using accommodation check-in and check-out times","C":"11 hours - using accommodation check-in and check-out times","D":"10 hours - using off duty and on duty times"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 7.16.1.2"},{"id":"35262","lastEdit":"09/01/2024","category":"other","question":"When calculating your holdover time which temperature should be used?","options":{"A":"The lower of wing temperature (fuel temperature before refuelling) and outside air temperature","B":"The lower of TAT with APU running and outside air temperature","C":"The lower of wing temperature (fuel temperature after refuelling) and outside air temperature","D":"Outside air temperature"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.9.7 LOUT + OMC 10.3.7.2 Wing Skin Temperature"},{"id":"35435","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the definition of local night for the purpose of flight time limitations?","options":{"A":"A period of 10 hours between 2200 and 0800 local time","B":"A period of 8 hours between 2200 and 0800 local time","C":"A period of 8 hours between 2000 and 0800 local time","D":"A period of 7 hours between 2300 and 0700 local time"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 7.5 Definitions, Local Night."},{"id":"35465","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What shall the cabin crew briefing include?","options":{"A":"Flight crew introduction, flight crew roles and responsibilities, taxi time, flight time, cruise altitudes, expected weather en-route, policy to access the flight deck, flight or layover security requirements","B":"Flight crew introduction, flight crew roles, flight time, cruise altitudes, expected weather en-route, policy to access the flight deck, crew changes, wake up call","C":"Flight crew introduction, flight crew roles, flight time, flight routing, cruise altitudes, expected weather en-route, policy to access the flight deck, crew changes, aircraft defects","D":"Flight crew introduction, flight crew roles, flight time, flight routing, cruise altitudes, expected weather en-route, policy to access the flight deck, crew changes, aircraft defects, flight or layover security requirements"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.1 Cabin Crew Briefing"},{"id":"35550","lastEdit":"31/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Is the aircraft and operator certified for A-RNP approaches?","options":{"A":"Only if the RNP for the approach is less than 0.3","B":"Only if the RNP for the approach is less than 0.1","C":"Yes","D":"No"},"answer":"D","reference":"Ops Spec Page 2, table: see A-RNP"},{"id":"35799","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What is the CCI definition of a high aerodrome elevation?","options":{"A":"5000 feet","B":"2000 feet","C":"4000 feet","D":"3000 feet"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.1.6.5.2 Decode"},{"id":"35814","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the time of useful consciousness at FL400 in moderate activity?","options":{"A":"12 seconds","B":"30 seconds","C":"18 seconds","D":"9 seconds"},"answer":"C","reference":"OME 4.1.2"},{"id":"35933","lastEdit":"16/04/2024","category":"interview","question":"When considering pre-flight planning minima for a destination alternate, which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"If the planned approach is CAT II or CAT III the forecast must be CAT I or better. If a CAT I approach is planned the forecast must be Non Precision or better. If the planned approach is Non Precision the forecast must be Non Precision +200 feet and 1000m","B":"If the planned approach is ILS the forecast must be CAT I, If the planned approach is Non Precision the forecast must be Non Precision +200 feet and 800m","C":"If the planned approach is CAT III or CAT II or CAT I the forecast must be CAT I + 200 feet and 800m, If the planned approach is Non Precision the forecast must be Non Precision +200 feet and 800m","D":"If the planned approach is CAT III the forecast must be CAT II or better, If the planned approach is CAT II the forecast must be CAT I or better, If the planned approach is CAT I the forecast must be Non Precision or better, If the planned approach is Non Precision the forecast must be Non Precision +200 feet and 1000m"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.3 Pre Flight Planning Minima"},{"id":"35936","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What do the EAI symbols on EICAS indicate?","options":{"A":"Engine anti-ice has failed","B":"Engine anti-ice valve is open","C":"Engine anti-ice is armed","D":"Engine anti-ice should be turned off"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, Controls and Indicators, Engine and Wing Anti Icing, Anti-Ice Indications"},{"id":"36013","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What happens when TOGA switches are pressed after 80 knots on the take-off roll?","options":{"A":"The autothrottle activates in THR REF","B":"LNAV/VNAV are disarmed","C":"Nothing","D":"The thrust de-rate is removed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Automatic Flight, System Description, Automatic Flight Operations, Automatic Flight Takeoff and Climb"},{"id":"36041","lastEdit":"31/12/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the primary source of standby electrical power if the RAT sheds electrical power because of low hydraulic pressure?","options":{"A":"DC busses","B":"Backup generators","C":"APU","D":"Main battery"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM System, Electrical, Systems Description, Standby Electrical System, Ram Air Turbine Generator"},{"id":"36114","lastEdit":"20/08/2024","category":"other","question":"When flying a cold weather approach, you calculate you need to adjust the FAF altitude of 1500 feet by 90 feet higher. What should the FAF altitude in the FMC be set to?","options":{"A":"1545 feet","B":"1590 feet","C":"1410 feet","D":"1500 feet"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.4.1.2 Cold weather altitude corrections - (Do not apply corrections to FMC coded altitudes of less than 100 feet)"},{"id":"36313","lastEdit":"14/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"The lavatory/galley vent fans draw air across temperature sensors in each compartment. If both vent fans fail, cargo heat is not provided.","options":{"A":"BLANK","B":"False","C":"BLANK","D":"True"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Systems Description, Air Systems, 2.20.6 Cargo Heat System"},{"id":"36799","lastEdit":"17/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"When operating to Moscow (UUDD/DME) which OPT runway condition should be used?","options":{"A":"The most conservative of the GRF RWYCC and the type and depth of contaminant reported in the SNOWTAM","B":"The most conservative of the MOTNE braking action (friction co-efficient) and the type and depth of contaminant reported in the SNOWTAM","C":"Only the type and depth of contaminant reported in the SNOWTAM","D":"The most conservative of the previous landing aircraft's braking report and MOTNE braking action (friction co-efficient)"},"answer":"B","reference":"CO-NOTAM 1658/23 for UUDD/DME airport, also see Russia CRAR, 3.151.13 Miscellaneous - use the table with Normative Friction Ã¢â‚¬â€¹Co-efficient to obtain braking action"},{"id":"36988","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding approaches planned with an autoland?","options":{"A":"Training or practice of CAT II/III approaches including autoland without LVP in force can be conducted during normal operations as long as ATC are informed","B":"Training or practice of CAT II/III approaches including autoland without LVP in force can be conducted during normal operations as long as the weather conditions are CAT I or better","C":"When the airfield is not in low visibility procedures CAT II/III approaches followed by an autoland may be conducted when required during flight test or an emergency","D":"When the airfield is not in low visibility procedures CAT II/III approaches followed by an autoland are not authorised under any circumstances"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.4.2.1 CAT II/III Approaches without LVP"},{"id":"37136","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the EICAS CONFIG DOORS message indicate?","options":{"A":"An entry, forward cargo, main deck cargo or after cargo door is not closed, latched and locked when either engine is in the takeoff range on the ground or in flight","B":"An entry, forward cargo, main deck cargo or after cargo door is not closed, latched and locked when either engine is in the takeoff range on the ground or in flight","C":"An entry, forward cargo, main deck cargo or after cargo door is not closed, latched and locked when either engine is in the takeoff range on the ground","D":"An entry, forward cargo, main deck cargo or after cargo door is not closed and armed when either engine is in the takeoff range on the ground"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, EICAS Messages, Warning Systems EICAS Messages, Configuration"},{"id":"37177","lastEdit":"30/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"In flight, what causes the APU to automatically start?","options":{"A":"In flight, if both AC transfer buses lose power, the APU automatically starts, regardless of APU selector position","B":"In flight, if both AC main buses lose power","C":"In flight, if on both IDGÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s low oil pressure is sensed","D":"In flight, if there has an engine failure occurred"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, system description, 7- Engines, APU, APU system description, APU operation, APU automatic start"},{"id":"37237","lastEdit":"24/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"After receiving an LMC, what does the Commander NOT need to verify?","options":{"A":"The center of gravity stays within the allowed limits","B":"The load limitations of compartments and loading positions are not exceeded","C":"The cargo is loaded in accordance with the trim sheet","D":"Individual or total LMC is 500 kg or less"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.8.6.2 Last Minute Change (LMC)"},{"id":"37311","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"Who is responsible for keeping a valid medical licence?","options":{"A":"Licensing department","B":"Individual crew member","C":"Documents Keeper","D":"GCAA"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 6.4 GCAA Medical Certificate"},{"id":"37667","lastEdit":"28/12/2023","category":"other","question":"When the does the no contact period begin and end on departure?","options":{"A":"It's from the start of the take-off roll and ends when the landing gear retracts","B":"It starts from the point at which the aircraft enters the runway and ends when the cabin crew are released for service","C":"It starts from the point at which the flight deck make the PA 'Cabin Crew Prepare for Departure' and ends 3 minutes after airborne","D":"It starts from the point at which the flight deck make the PA 'Cabin Crew Prepare for Departure' and ends when the landing gear retracts"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.1.2 No Contact Period"},{"id":"37756","lastEdit":"01/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"During taxi out for departure you discover a malfunction with the aircraft, which company documentation can assist with your decision making?","options":{"A":"FCOM, Supplementary Procedures, Flight Management, System Error Rectification Procedure","B":"QRH, Ops Info, General, Technical Fault Resolution Process","C":"Electronic Forms, Dispatch, Operational Anomaly Resolution Guide","D":"FCTM 2, Preflight, Technical Fault Resolution Process"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, General, Technical Fault Resolution Process"},{"id":"37783","lastEdit":"12/01/2024","category":"other","question":"When can flight crew reset a tripped circuit breaker on ground?","options":{"A":"Whenever the Commander deems necessary","B":"Never","C":"When directed by a non-normal checklist","D":"After maintenance has determined it's safe to do so"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non normal Checklists, Non normal checklist operation, Assumptions"},{"id":"37825","lastEdit":"06/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"After refuelling the aircraft has 96.0 tons of fuel onboard, you requested 95.8 tons. Before refuelling the aircraft had 7.5 tons. Actual uplift is 29300 US gallons at a specific gravity of 0.79. Are the requirements of the fuel uplift check met?","options":{"A":"Yes, the refuelling check is satisfactory","B":"No, the applicable tolerance of 2000 kg has been exceeded","C":"No, the applicable tolerance of 1000 kg has been exceeded","D":"No, the applicable tolerance of 5% has been exceeded"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.6 Fuel Uplift Check: Indicated FOB 96000 - Indicated FOB pre-refuel 7500 = FOB Difference 88500. Actual Uplift (29300 USG x 3.785 x 0.79 = 87611) - FOB Difference 88500 = Discrepancy -889. (Discrepancy -889 / FOB Difference 88500) x 100 = -1% & less than 1000kg's"},{"id":"37826","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"After refuelling the aircraft has 84.5 tons of fuel onboard, you requested 84.0 tons. Before refuelling the aircraft had 5.0 tons. Actual uplift is 26600 US gallons at a specific gravity of 0.81. Are the requirements of the fuel uplift check met?","options":{"A":"Yes, the refuelling check is satisfactory","B":"No, the applicable tolerance of 1000 kg has been exceeded","C":"No, the applicable tolerance of 2000 kg has been exceeded","D":"No, the applicable tolerance of 5% has been exceeded"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.6 Fuel Uplift Check"},{"id":"37827","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"After refuelling the aircraft has 23.1 tons of fuel onboard, you requested 22.6 tons. Before refuelling the aircraft had 10.0 tons. Actual uplift is 15000 litres at a specific gravity of 0.825. Are the requirements of the fuel uplift check met?","options":{"A":"No, the applicable tolerance of 2000 kg has been exceeded","B":"Yes, the refuelling check is satisfactory","C":"No, the applicable tolerance of 1000 kg has been exceeded","D":"No, the applicable tolerance of 5% has been exceeded"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.6 Fuel Uplift Check"},{"id":"37828","lastEdit":"03/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"After refuelling the aircraft has 30.1 tons of fuel onboard. Before refuelling the aircraft had 5.0 tons. Actual uplift is 30000 litres at a specific gravity of 0.8 - Is there any attention needed?","options":{"A":"Yes. The actual fuel uplift exceeded the allowable 5%","B":"Yes. The actual fuel uplift exceeded the allowable value of minus 1000 kg","C":"No. The refuelling check is satisfactory","D":"Yes. The actual fuel uplift exceeded the allowable value of plus 2000 kg"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.6 Fuel Uplift Check (Actual uplift: 30000L * 0.8 SG = 24000 KG. Calculated Uplift: 30.1T - 5.0T = 25.1T, i.e. we are 1100 KG short, exceeding the 1000 KG limit)"},{"id":"37848","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"The conditions for Engine Severe Damage Separation L/R are:","options":{"A":"Airframe vibrations with normal engine indications or engine separation","B":"Abnormal engine noises are heard, possibly with airframe vibration or Flames in the engine inlet or exhaust are reported","C":"Airframe vibrations with abnormal engine indications or engine separation","D":"Abnormal engine indications or engine separation"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Severe Damage Separation L/R"},{"id":"37980","lastEdit":"18/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the freezing points for Jet A-1 and Jet A fuels, and what actions can be taken to mitigate the risk of fuel freezing?","options":{"A":"Jet A-1: -43C, Jet A: -37C. Actions: Increase Mach number, descend to lower altitude, deviate to warmer air mass","B":"Jet A-1: -47C, Jet A: -40C. Actions: Decrease Mach number, climb to higher altitude, deviate to colder air mass","C":"Jet A-1: -47C, Jet A: -40C. Actions: Increase Mach number, descend to lower altitude, deviate to warmer air mass","D":"Jet A-1: -40C, Jet A: -47C. Actions: Increase Mach number, descend to lower altitude, deviate to warmer air mass"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC FUEL TEMP LOW + OMA 8.2.1.7 Fuel Freezing Point"},{"id":"38002","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct referring to Persons in Custody (Prisoners)?","options":{"A":"The Captain and Purser must be advised, they must be restrained and have at least 1 escort","B":"The Captain and Group Security must be advised, they may be restrained and have at least 2 escorts from Dubai Police","C":"The Captain and Group Security must be advised, they may be restrained and have at least 1 escort","D":"The Captain and Purser must be advised, they may be restrained and have at least 2 escorts"},"answer":"D","reference":"OME 10.5.18.3 Aviation Security, Security Measures, Inadmissible, Persons in Custody (Prisoners)"},{"id":"38044","lastEdit":"01/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"In day VMC into Dubai you experience a GPWS PULL UP while established on the approach, what is your response?","options":{"A":"Do nothing","B":"Confirm that the GPWS is erroneous and continue the approach","C":"Continue the approach","D":"Ask the Captain what he thinks"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Ground Proximity Warning System Response, GPWS Warning"},{"id":"38205","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"When can you start to use contingency fuel?","options":{"A":"After pushback","B":"After the thrust levers are advanced for takeoff","C":"After all main cabin doors are closed","D":"After completion of refuelling and release of the fuel bowser"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.7 Determination of the Quantity of Fuel and Oil Carried"},{"id":"38262","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"On the OFP the section below the planned flight levels and waypoints it reads: 'OFP: 10/1/0' - What does the middle digit 1 specify?","options":{"A":"This flight plan is ETOPS","B":"This flightplan has a decision point procedure","C":"This flightplan is restricted by a curfew at the destination airport","D":"This flightplan has a mandatory tech stop to refuel"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.1.4 EK OFP Decodes (Item 12)"},{"id":"38816","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When is the bank limit selector effective at maintaining bank angles within the selected limit?","options":{"A":"When in LNAV, track select or heading select","B":"When in track or heading select","C":"When in LNAV only","D":"When in LNAV and the bank limit selector is in auto"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director Heading Track and Bank Angle Controls"},{"id":"38828","lastEdit":"13/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"The cabin master temperature is set to 26 degrees Celsius. The cabin crew wish to set one zone to 30 degrees Celsius. Is this possible?","options":{"A":"No","B":"Yes","C":"BLANK","D":"BLANK"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Temperature Control (Cabin crew control range is +/- 6C within a temperature range of 18C to 29C)"},{"id":"38911","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Can you depart with the crew oxygen system inoperative?","options":{"A":"Yes, as long as the flight is conducted at or below 20000 feet and portable crew oxygen bottles are readily available","B":"Yes, as long as the flight is conducted at or below 25000 feet and smoke hoods are readily available","C":"No","D":"Yes, as long as the flight is conducted at or below 25000 feet and portable crew oxygen bottles are readily available"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.8.1 Oxygen Requirements"},{"id":"38934","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When can wing anti-ice be operated manually?","options":{"A":"On the ground or in the air","B":"Only on ground","C":"Only when TAT is above 10 Celsius","D":"Only in flight"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, System Description, Anti-Icing Systems, Wing Anti-Icing - 'on the ground, wing anti icing valves are commanded closed regardless of the selector position'"},{"id":"39165","lastEdit":"14/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is NOT an example of a GPWS look ahead aural warning?","options":{"A":"TRAFFIC TRAFFIC","B":"CAUTION OBSTACLE","C":"CAUTION TERRAIN","D":"TOO LOW, TERRAIN"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Description, Warning Systems, 15.20"},{"id":"39215","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the EICAS ENG OIL TEMP L message mean?","options":{"A":"Engine oil temperature is low","B":"Engine oil pressure is high","C":"Engine oil pressure is low","D":"Engine oil temperature is high"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, EICAS Messages, EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"39368","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When is the pack off light illuminated amber?","options":{"A":"During equipment cooling override condition, pack or compressor high temperature condition, bleed air pressure is inadequate, during APU to pack procedure, pack is off","B":"When CACTCS has failed, during an engine fire, during equipment cooling override condition","C":"During engine start, pack or compressor low temperature condition, when trim air is too high a temperature, pack is off","D":"During engine start, pack or compressor high temperature condition, bleed air pressure is inadequate, during APU to pack procedure, pack is off"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Air Conditioning System, Air Conditioning Panel (See Pack Switches)"},{"id":"39498","lastEdit":"09/02/2024","category":"other","question":"The conditions for Stabilizer memory items are:","options":{"A":"Flight controls are restricted in pitch","B":"Unexpected nose up or down control column forces","C":"One Stabilizer control path has failed","D":"Stabilizer movement without a signal to trim or the Stabilizer is failed"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH NNC Stabilizer"},{"id":"39530","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What is the minimum visibility for a circling approach?","options":{"A":"Minima as per the enhanced coded approach procedure + 1500m","B":"Minima as per the approach procedure","C":"Minima as per the enhanced coded approach procedure","D":"5000m"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.4 In Flight Minima"},{"id":"39610","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the correct contingency procedure for a pilot to follow when needing to deviate from the assigned route in oceanic airspace? (not weather related)","options":{"A":"Turn at least 30 degrees right or left to intercept and maintain a parallel track 10 nm offset from the original route, minimize the rate of descent until offset, maintain flight level if possible, squawk 7700 if appropriate, and broadcast the situation on 123.45","B":"Turn at least 30 degrees right or left to intercept and maintain a parallel track 5 nm offset from the original route, minimize the rate of descent until offset, maintain flight level if possible, squawk 7700 if appropriate, and broadcast the situation on 121.5","C":"Turn at least 45 degrees right to intercept and maintain a parallel track 15 nm offset from the original route, minimize the rate of descent until offset, maintain flight level if possible, squawk 7700 if appropriate, and broadcast the situation on 123.45","D":"Turn at least 45 degrees right or left to intercept and maintain a parallel track 5 nm offset from the original route, minimize the rate of descent until offset, maintain flight level if possible, squawk 7700 if appropriate, and broadcast the situation on 121.5"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 12.5.2.1 General Procedures - Contingency Procedures if Prior ATC Clearance Cannot be Obtained (Non-weather)"},{"id":"39632","lastEdit":"10/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the pre-flight planning minima for takeoff alternates?","options":{"A":"The applicable landing minima plus 200 feet and 1000m","B":"The applicable landing minima","C":"The same as destination alternates","D":"At least CAT I conditions"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.3 Pre Flight Planning Minima"},{"id":"39745","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"During pre-flight what position should the forward and aft outflow valve switches and landing altitude selector be in?","options":{"A":"Outflow valve switches in norm and landing altitude selector pushed in","B":"Outflow valve switches in auto and landing altitude selector pushed in","C":"Outflow valve switches in man and landing altitude selector pulled out","D":"Outflow valve switches on and landing altitude selector pushed in"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - First Officer"},{"id":"39870","lastEdit":"09/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"You arrive at the aircraft for departure in Stockholm, the aircraft has arrived with 16,000 kgs of fuel at -16 Celsius, the airport metar indicates moderate rain at +2 Celsius. What is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Get a new OFP with a lower cruise altitude to avoid low fuel temperatures in flight","B":"File an ASR as the aircraft should not have arrived with more than 12,000 kgs of fuel","C":"Load extra fuel to increase the wing skin temperature or wait for the wing skin temperature to warm up or use the warmer OAT and perform a PCI","D":"Put the fuel pumps on to warm the fuel"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.7.2 Wing Skin Temperature"},{"id":"40290","lastEdit":"31/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What are the standard passenger masses?","options":{"A":"Male 85 kg, Female 70 kg, Children 30 kg, infant 0 kg","B":"Male 88 kg, Female 75 kg, Children 35 kg, infant 10 kg","C":"Male 88 kg, Female 70 kg, Children 35 kg, infant 0 kg","D":"Male 80 kg, Female 65 kg, Children 35 kg, infant 0 kg"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.8.5 Standard Mass Values for Passenger"},{"id":"40406","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is true regarding autobrake operation?","options":{"A":"If MAX AUTO is selected it is limited to AUTOBRAKE 3 until pitch is below 2 degrees","B":"If MAX AUTO is selected it is limited to AUTOBRAKE 4 until pitch is below 1 degree","C":"If MAX AUTO is selected it is limited to AUTOBRAKE 4 until nose gear is on the ground","D":"If MAX AUTO is selected it is limited to AUTOBRAKE 3 until nose gear is on the ground"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, System Description, Brake System, Autobrake System"},{"id":"40444","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"both","question":"What condition must be met for the Commander to commit to landing at a specific aerodrome?","options":{"A":"Regardless of the number of runways, the flight can continue towards the destination aerodrome or hold, as long as landing is assured with at least final reserve fuel remaining, based on the Commander's judgement of weather deterioration and single failures of ground or airborne facilities","B":"The Commander has considered all operational factors that may cause a delay to land and has determined that a safe landing can be achieved with not less than final reserve fuel","C":"A safe landing is considered assured as long as the Expected Approach Time (EAT) is not known, and it is possible to reach at least two aerodromes at which a landing is assured with at least final reserve fuel remaining at touchdown","D":"Two separate and independent runways at a single aerodrome within two hours of flying time are available, considering fuel burn due to any likely ATC delay, making them equivalent to two aerodromes"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.2.2 Commit to Land"},{"id":"40788","lastEdit":"07/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which flap setting should be used for landing overweight at 350 tons for a sea level airfield above 38 degrees Celsius?","options":{"A":"Use flaps 30 for landing and flaps 20 for go-around","B":"Use flaps 25 for landing and flaps 5 for go-around","C":"Use flaps 20 for landing and flaps 5 for go-around","D":"Use flaps 25 for landing and flaps 20 for go-around"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Miscellaneous, Overweight Landing + FCOM, Performance Dispatch, 777-300ER, Landing, Approach or Landing Climb Limited Weight (enter the table with 38c and 0 airport pressure altitude, aircraft performance is restricted above 38c)"},{"id":"40802","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When will the true light illuminate on the heading reference switch?","options":{"A":"Any time true heading is in use","B":"Above 82Ã‚Â° N/S latitude or in the vicinity of the magnetic poles","C":"Above 78Ã‚Â° N/S latitude or in the vicinity of the magnetic poles","D":"Whenever the heading reference switch is in the true position"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Heading Reference and Inboard Displays"},{"id":"40933","lastEdit":"14/04/2024","category":"other","question":"Which electronic checklists disappear from the EICAS after the memory items are complete?","options":{"A":"FIRE ENG ON GROUND L/R and FIRE APU","B":"STABILIZER and ENG AUTOSTART L/R","C":"ENG SVR DAMAGE/SEP L/R and ENG LIM/SURGE/STALL L/R","D":"ABORTED ENGINE START L/R and STABILIZER"},"answer":"B","reference":"NO REFERENCE"},{"id":"40964","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What restrictions apply to Falcons?","options":{"A":"Maximum 10 per flight in the passenger cabin, in an additional business class seat the maximum is 1 per seat, in an additional first class seat the maximum is 2 per seat","B":"Maximum 15 per flight in the passenger cabin, in an additional business class seat the maximum is 2 per seat, in an additional first class seat the maximum is 3 per seat","C":"Maximum 10 per flight in the passenger cabin, in an additional business class seat the maximum is 2 per seat, in an additional first class seat the maximum is 3 per seat","D":"Maximum 15 per flight in the passenger cabin, in an additional business class seat the maximum is 1 per seat, in an additional first class seat the maximum is 2 per seat"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.2.2.4.2.2 Falcons"},{"id":"41273","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"During takeoff which flight control surfaces move down to increase lift?","options":{"A":"Ailerons and flaperons","B":"Slats","C":"Flaperons and slats","D":"Stabilizer"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Flight Control Surfaces (admittedly a terrible question as slats extend downwards, however slats are not listed as a flight control surface in the FCOM)"},{"id":"41335","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement about the ADIRU is true?","options":{"A":"The inertial reference position is updated using information from the air data modules","B":"If the ADIRU fails the PFDs blank","C":"The ADIRU sends magnetic variation data to the FMCs to convert true heading to magnetic heading","D":"The ADIRU receives the same data inputs as the SAARU but compares and validates the data independently"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Navigation Systems Description, Inertial System, Air Data and Attitude Sources"},{"id":"41376","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following are data sources for the ADIRU?","options":{"A":"Air data modules, AOA vanes and TAT probe","B":"Pitot and static ports only","C":"Air data modules only","D":"AOA vanes and TAT probe only"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Navigation Systems Description, Inertial System, Air Data and Attitude Sources"},{"id":"41517","lastEdit":"23/04/2024","category":"both","question":"During cruise you suffer an autopilot failure which forces you below RVSM airspace, where can you find information to calculate your fuel burn and time?","options":{"A":"QRH, Performance inflight, <Aircraft model>, General, Long Range Cruise Diversion Fuel and Time","B":"QRH, Performance inflight, <Aircraft model>, All Engine, Long Range Cruise Enroute Fuel and Time - Low Altitudes","C":"FCOM, Performance inflight, <Aircraft model>, General, Long Range Cruise Diversion Fuel and Time","D":"FCOM, Performance inflight, <Aircraft model>, All Engine, Long Range Cruise Enroute Fuel and Time - Low Altitudes"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Performance inflight, <Aircraft model>, All Engine, Long Range Cruise Enroute Fuel and Time - Low Altitudes"},{"id":"41638","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"During take-off with edge lighting and centre line lighting RVR may not be less than? (assume not high intensity - real exam does not state this)","options":{"A":"400m","B":"200m","C":"150m","D":"300m"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.2 Take-off Minima"},{"id":"41647","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the primary L ENG hydraulic pump FAULT light indicate?","options":{"A":"The left engine is faulty","B":"The left engine primary pump is inoperative","C":"Engine EGT is high or engine speed low","D":"Hydraulic pump pressure is low or temperature is high"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, Controls and Indicators, Hydraulic Panel"},{"id":"41751","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"both","question":"What is the definition of acclimatised?","options":{"A":"A crew member who has spent two consecutive local nights on the ground in within a time zone that is 3 hours wide. The crewmember will remain acclimatised until a duty that finishes in a place where the time zone differs by more than 3 hours from the point of departure","B":"A crew member who has spent one local night on the ground in within a time zone that is 2 hours wide. The crewmember will remain acclimatised until a duty that finishes in a place where the time zone differs by more than 2 hours from the point of departure","C":"A crew member who has spent three consecutive local nights on the ground in within a time zone that is 4 hours wide. The crewmember will remain acclimatised until a duty that finishes in a place where the time zone differs by more than 4 hours from the point of departure","D":"A crew member who has spent three consecutive local nights on the ground in within a time zone that is 2 hours wide. The crewmember will remain acclimatised until a duty that finishes in a place where the time zone differs by more than 2 hours from the point of departure"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 7.5 Definitions, acclimatised."},{"id":"41823","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"With the autostart system on when do you move the fuel control switch to run?","options":{"A":"After engine stabilized at idle","B":"After 25% N2 has been reached","C":"After start has been selected on the start/ignition selector","D":"After reaching maximum motoring speed"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Engine Start Procedure"},{"id":"41854","lastEdit":"13/12/2023","category":"other","question":"When conducting a Pre-takeoff Contamination Inspection which areas is fluid most likely to fail first?","options":{"A":"Wing root","B":"Leading or trailing edges of the wing","C":"Mid-chord section of the wing","D":"Wing tip"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3.6.3 First Areas of Fluid Failure"},{"id":"41922","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"When there is a fuel imbalance of more than 500 Kgs the EICAS display shows a fuel imbalance pointer to the main tank that has the least fuel. Which of the following statements is NOT correct?","options":{"A":"If fuel balancing is in the wrong direction the pointer flashes amber","B":"The pointer stays until the imbalance is less than 100 Kgs","C":"If a crossfeed valve is open, a fuel imbalance more than 200 kgs causes the pointer to show","D":"A solid amber fuel imbalance pointer replaces the white pointer if the FUEL IMBALANCE message is displayed"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, Controls and Indicators, EICAS Fuel Synoptic Display (item 11)"},{"id":"42300","lastEdit":"05/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In case ACU not connected in Dubai, what is the target temperature at which the engineer will start the APU to control cabin temperature?","options":{"A":"40C","B":"30C","C":"35C","D":"25C"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 1.2.2.2.2 Company Procedures, Operational Efficiency, Cabin Temperature Control DXB, Boeing 777, ACU not connected or ACU not operating"},{"id":"42636","lastEdit":"14/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"What causes the EICAS EMER LIGHTS to be displayed? (Select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"The emergency lighting system has been manually activated or the emergency lights switch is OFF The emergency lights have been activated by the flight attendant switch panel","B":"The emergency light switch is not in the ARMED position","C":"The emergency light switch is not in the ARMED position The emergency lighting system has been manually activated or the emergency lights switch is OFF The emergency lights have been activated by the flight attendant switch panel","D":"The emergency light switch is not in the ARMED position The emergency lighting system has been manually activated or the emergency lights switch is OFF"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Lighting Systems, Emergency Lighting - The real exam features Ã¢â‚¬Ëœall of the aboveÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ as the correct answer"},{"id":"42681","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the maximum taxi speed during low visibility operations?","options":{"A":"30 knots","B":"20 knots","C":"10 knots","D":"15 knots"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.7 Taxi"},{"id":"42857","lastEdit":"24/04/2024","category":"interview","question":"You're about to commence an approach into Larnaca runway 04 for the VOR/DME approach (wind 040/16 knots, overcast cloud base at minima), GPS interference is occurring and the FMC is using inertial data only as there is insufficient DME coverage. You then have a status message VOR L. What is your course of action? (TECHNIQUE)","options":{"A":"Continue the VOR/DME approach in LNAV/VNAV","B":"Continue the VOR/DME approach in basic modes (e.g. TRK SEL and V/S) using VOR R data","C":"Make an approach for the ILS 22 with a 16 knot tailwind","D":"Divert as there is insufficient redundancy"},"answer":"B","reference":"MEL 34-51-01 VOR Navigation Systems states: 'Crew should consider whether the in-flight failure of any FMS sensor allows safe navigation with the remaining operative sensors and equipment' - however the MEL isn't applicable after airborne..."},{"id":"42881","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the supplemental oxygen that must be carried for passengers?","options":{"A":"A supply of oxygen for 100% of the passengers for 22 minutes, or the entire flight time the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 15,000 feet, whichever is greater","B":"A supply of oxygen for 100% of the passengers for 22 minutes, or the entire flight time the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 14,000 feet, whichever is greater","C":"A supply of oxygen for 100% of the passengers for 10 minutes, or the entire flight time the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 10,000 feet, whichever is greater","D":"A supply of oxygen for 100% of the passengers for 10 minutes, or the entire flight time the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 15,000 feet, whichever is greater"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.8.3 Passengers"},{"id":"43162","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Are dangerous goods in 'excepted quantities' required to be shown on the NOTOC?","options":{"A":"No, but they must be labelled with a special red hatched label","B":"Yes","C":"Dangerous goods in 'excepted quantities' are subject of Captains acceptance","D":"No, and there is no labelling required"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 9.9.1 Additional Handling Labels and Marks"},{"id":"43243","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Which levers and switches require a verbal 'confirm' step before action is taken?","options":{"A":"Ram air turbine","B":"Engine thrust lever, fuel control switch","C":"Engine thrust lever, fuel control switch, fuel jettison arm switches","D":"Engine thrust lever, fuel control switch, pulling a circuit breaker"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non normal Checklists, Non normal checklist operation, Confirm Step"},{"id":"43292","lastEdit":"24/04/2024","category":"interview","question":"During taxi out the Purser informs you of a cabin crew member who has been on standby and will run out of duty time before the flight lands, what is your course of action? (TECHNIQUE)","options":{"A":"Return to the gate to offload them","B":"Continue to taxi out for departure and stand them down immediately after airborne","C":"Continue to taxi out for departure and divert at an appropriate point to offload them","D":"Continue to taxi out for departure and give the individual as much rest as possible to extend their duty limit, and if necessary stand them down"},"answer":"D","reference":"TECHNIQUE - The OMA Chapter 7 only gives guidance on standing down augmented flight crew members during burnout ops, but if you know of a reference let us know"},{"id":"43308","lastEdit":"06/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"At what speed does passenger entry door flight lock?","options":{"A":"Above 100 knots","B":"When in flight","C":"Above 60 knots","D":"Above 80 knots"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Supernumerary Area, Entry Door"},{"id":"43348","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"How long is the repair interval of a category C defect?","options":{"A":"10 days (240 hours) excluding the day of discovery","B":"3 days (72 hours) including the day of discovery","C":"120 days (2880 hours) excluding the day of the discovery","D":"10 days (240 hours) including the day of discovery"},"answer":"A","reference":"MEL Section 2, MEL Preamble 9 Repair Intervals"},{"id":"43350","lastEdit":"24/12/2023","category":"interview","question":"In which country must you only divert to the alternate listed on the flight plan? (excluding emergencies)","options":{"A":"Thailand","B":"China","C":"Russia","D":"India"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 12.3.8.2.9 Special Operation in Chinese Airspace"},{"id":"43410","lastEdit":"21/02/2024","category":"other","question":"Why would the heading reference symbol beside present heading at top of ND display TRU?","options":{"A":"The airplane is in vicinity of magnetic pole or true heading has been automatically selected by the ADIRU","B":"The airplane is above 78 degrees N or S latitude or true heading has been manually selected in the FMC","C":"The airplane is above 82 degrees N or S latitude or true heading has been automatically selected or heading reference has been selected to true","D":"The airplane is in vicinity of magnetic pole or true heading has been automatically selected by the PFCs"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Heading Reference and Inboard Displays"},{"id":"43485","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the departure timeline target for all doors closed?","options":{"A":"STD-1","B":"STD-10","C":"STD-5","D":"STD-3"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 1.1.5 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP- Departure Target Timeline"},{"id":"43578","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What does the WINDOWS EICAS advisory message indicate?","options":{"A":"The right side window is open or unlocked","B":"The left side window is open or unlocked","C":"Forward and side window heat is inoperative or switched off","D":"The left and right side windows are open or unlocked"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, EICAS messages, Doors and Windows EICAS Messages"},{"id":"43623","lastEdit":"03/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"Who should the commander call in case of a passenger sickness at the gate or boarding stage?","options":{"A":"Ground Medical Services","B":"Airport Fire Service","C":"Get the passenger reviewed by the Aerodrome Medical Clinic for fitness to fly","D":"Contact an Emirates doctor, contactable through the Network Operations"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 11.4.1 Requesting medical support for an on ground medical emergency - The real tech exam references getting a gate clearance from Ground Medical Support (an old procedure that is a decade out of date)"},{"id":"43637","lastEdit":"19/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"When calculating your rate of descent in feet per minute for an approach, what is the formula?","options":{"A":"FPM = TAN(Approach Gradient) * 318 * Airspeed","B":"FPM = SIN(Approach Gradient) * 1000 * Groundspeed","C":"FPM = COS(Approach Gradient) * 5 * Airspeed","D":"FPM = TAN(Approach Gradient) * 100 * Groundspeed"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO 1.7.7.11 Descent Gradient Table only has groundspeeds up to 180 knots. Thus a rule of thumb must be used. Ensure corrections for true approach slope, i.e. account for temperature errors for non precision approaches"},{"id":"43657","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"When is a copy of the NAT track message required on flights across the North Atlantic?","options":{"A":"When using the organized track system","B":"Whenever the organized track system is active during their crossing","C":"It is always required","D":"When above FL290"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO North Atlantic 2.3.2.13.3.1 General > Routings > Item C"},{"id":"43730","lastEdit":"07/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"On an LRV operation where the CRC is unavailable and no other aircraft is available, in which cabin classes should the flight crew and cabin crew rest?","options":{"A":"All crew rest in Economy Class","B":"Flight Crew rest in Business Class, Cabin Crew rest in Economy Class","C":"Flight Crew rest in First Class, Cabin Crew rest in Business Class","D":"The flight cannot depart without a serviceable CRC"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.7.1.2 Allocated Rest Positions"},{"id":"43829","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the cabin altitude at maximum airplane operating altitude?","options":{"A":"8.8 psi","B":"8000 feet","C":"6000 feet","D":"10000 feet"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization system automatic operation"},{"id":"43929","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"What is the FCTM definition of a slippery surface?","options":{"A":"A surface where braking capability is less than a dry surface due to wetness, ice, snow, or contaminants","B":"A surface where braking capability is less than a dry surface due to loose debris","C":"A surface where braking capability is less than a dry surface due de-icing fluid residues","D":"A surface where braking capability is less than a wet surface due to ice, snow, or contaminants"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCTM 2, Ground Operations, Taxi, Taxi - Adverse Weather"},{"id":"44254","lastEdit":"27/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the timings of the Organized Track System in the North Atlantic?","options":{"A":"Westbound OTS 19:30 to 03:00 at 30W and Eastbound OTS 07:30 to 15:00 at 30W","B":"Westbound OTS 07:30 to 15:00 at 30W and Eastbound OTS 19:30 to 03:00 at 30W","C":"Westbound OTS 01:00 to 08:00 at 30W and Eastbound OTS 11:30 to 19:00 at 30W","D":"Westbound 11:30 to 19:00 at 30W and Eastbound OTS 01:00 to 08:00 at 30W"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO NAT 2.3.2.13.1.1 General"},{"id":"44395","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What precaution should be taken if a tail strike occurs during takeoff?","options":{"A":"No special precautions are necessary","B":"Pressurise the airplane to a lower cabin altitude","C":"Airplane should not be pressurised","D":"Outflow valves should be closed"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC TAIL STRIKE"},{"id":"44558","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"The runway width shall not be less than?","options":{"A":"35m","B":"40m","C":"30m","D":"45m"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.2 Minimum Pavement Width"},{"id":"44598","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which controls cause range marks to be displayed in VOR expanded mode?","options":{"A":"Range Selector","B":"Range marks are always displayed","C":"WXR or TFC switch","D":"CTR switch"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, EFIS Control Panels, EFIS Control Panel ND Controls"},{"id":"44692","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When engine fire switch pulled which of the following are turned off?","options":{"A":"The opposite engine fuel spar valve","B":"Engine driven and demand hydraulic pump","C":"Engine driven hydraulic pump","D":"Demand hydraulic pump"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, Controls and Indicators, Engine Fire Protection, Engine Fire Panel (Item 1)"},{"id":"44826","lastEdit":"03/10/2024","category":"other","question":"When does the BRAKE SOURCE light illuminate?","options":{"A":"When the reserve system is NOT selected manually after a loss of the right hydraulic system","B":"After loss of the right hydraulic system","C":"When the left and center/reserve hydraulic system have low pressure","D":"When the right and center/reserve hydraulic system pressures are low"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, System Description, Brake System (Note the real exam states that right and center/reserve hydraulic pressures are lost - not low)"},{"id":"44902","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding the ETOPS critical fuel scenario?","options":{"A":"The depressurisation and depressurisation with an engine failure scenarios both include descents from cruise level to FL100 at VMO/MMO and speedbrakes extended","B":"The depressurisation and depressurisation with an engine failure scenarios both include descents from cruise level to FL100 at indicated cruise speed in knots and speedbrakes extended","C":"The depressurisation and depressurisation with an engine failure scenarios both include descents from cruise level to FL100 at VMO/MMO and speedbrakes extended with gear down","D":"The depressurisation and depressurisation with an engine failure scenarios and engine failure only all include descents from cruise level to FL100 at indicated cruise speed in knots and speedbrakes extended"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.5.2.2 ETOPS Critical Fuel Scenario"},{"id":"44965","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Who is responsible for the manuals and documents to be valid during the entire flight?","options":{"A":"Dispatch","B":"Engineer","C":"Commander","D":"First Officer"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 1.5.3 Specific Responsibilities (Commander, item U)"},{"id":"44995","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding uncomplicated and single pregnancies?","options":{"A":"No medical certificate is required for 0 - 28 weeks, for 29 - 36 weeks a medical certificate is required (must be issued by a doctor or midwife)","B":"No medical certificate is required for 0 - 27 weeks, for 28 - 33 weeks a medical certificate is required (must be issued by a doctor or nurse)","C":"No medical certificate is required for 0 - 29 weeks, for 30 - 36 weeks a medical certificate is required (must be issued by a doctor or nurse)","D":"No medical certificate is required for 0 - 29 weeks, for 30 - 36 weeks a medical certificate is required (must be issued by a doctor or midwife)"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 11.11.1 Carriage of Expectant Mothers + OME 11.11.1.1 Pregnant Passengers - Medical Certificate Guidelines"},{"id":"45078","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"During normal bleed air operation what position should the left, centre and right bleed air isolation switches be in?","options":{"A":"Auto","B":"Off","C":"On","D":"Norm"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - First Officer"},{"id":"45369","lastEdit":"19/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"How often is a complete ADIRU alignment recommended?","options":{"A":"Whenever the total time in the navigation mode is expected to exceed 24 hours","B":"Every 15 hours","C":"Every 24 hours","D":"Whenever the total time in the navigation mode is expected to exceed 15 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Flight Management, Navigation Systems Description, ADIRU, ADIRU Alignment - see note"},{"id":"45670","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What will a second push of the TO/GA switch do during takeoff","options":{"A":"Disarms LNAV and VNAV","B":"Engages LNAV and disarms VNAV","C":"Disarms LNAV and engages VNAV","D":"Engages LNAV and VNAV"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Autothrottle Disconnect and TOGA Switches"},{"id":"45803","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Where can you find a map of SITA VHF datalink coverage?","options":{"A":"LIDO, Region (e.g. Middle East / Asia), Appendix, SITA VHF AIRCOM ACARS Service Coverage","B":"OMC 4.1 Communications Service Providers and Networks (CSP)","C":"OMC 12.3 Area Briefings, Region (e.g. Africa), Miscellaneous, VHF Datalink Coverage","D":"There are no VHF datalink coverage maps"},"answer":"A","reference":"LIDO, Region (e.g. Middle East / Asia), Appendix, SITA VHF AIRCOM ACARS Service Coverage"},{"id":"45804","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When do the control wheel stab trim switches control stabilizer movement directly?","options":{"A":"All the time","B":"During one engine go-around","C":"Only on ground in the normal mode","D":"Only in flight in the normal mode"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, Controls and Indicators, Pitch and Stabilizer Trim System, Control Wheel and Column"},{"id":"45852","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What powers the left main bus if the left engine is shut down, the right generator is running, the APU generator is not running?","options":{"A":"The main battery bus","B":"The APU generator powers the left main bus","C":"The right engine generator powers the left main bus","D":"Secondary external power supplies the left main"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, AC Electrical System, AC Electrical Power Distribution, AC Main busses"},{"id":"45886","lastEdit":"08/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"Can the flight crew inspect Dangerous Goods?","options":{"A":"Yes","B":"Yes, but only if they suspect there is a leak or broken boxes","C":"No, if there is an issue they must get a Load Master or authorised staff to do the inspection","D":"Never"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 9.3.1 - All Emirates staff with responsibilities in relation to the carriage of Dangerous Goods are trained in the requirements commensurate with their responsibilities. Inspection of DGs is not listed as a responsibility and the training required as not been provided."},{"id":"46036","lastEdit":"02/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"When calculating landing performance what factors does the OPT adjust the headwind and tailwind by?","options":{"A":"The headwind is reduced by 50%, the tailwind is increased by 50%","B":"The headwind is reduced by 10%, the tailwind is increased by 10%","C":"The headwind is reduced by 33%, the tailwind is increased by 33%","D":"The headwind is reduced by 25%, the tailwind is increased by 25%"},"answer":"A","reference":"OPT Calculation to prove this: OLD landing distance at 251-ton landing weight, autobrake 1 on an ISA day: Nil wind requires 3076m, 1 knot headwind requires 3059m, and 1 knot tailwind requires 3126m. The true correction for 1 knot wind is approximately 34m. Headwind correction (3076m - 3059m) = 17m; 17m / 0.5 Ã¢â€°Ë† 34m. Tailwind correction (3126m - 3076m) = 50m; 50m / 1.5 Ã¢â€°Ë† 34m. It is also listed in CAR-OPS 1.495 Take-off obstacle clearance, section b4."},{"id":"46114","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"both","question":"What failures do you need to inform ATC about when in RVSM airspace?","options":{"A":"Loss of one autopilot","B":"Loss of one hydraulic system","C":"Loss of entire GPS system","D":"Loss of one altimetry system"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO 1.5.9.4 Flight Crew Operating Procedures, item H - 'equipment failures should be notified to ATC...Loss of redundancy of altimetry systems, or any part of these, on board the ACFT' (Side note: we have 3 altimetry systems, RVSM requires 2, so it still shouldn't force you to go below RVSM until another failure occurs and SGL SOURCE AIR DATA or AIR DATA SYS displays, also note: FCOM Limitations, RVSM Operations - 'the standby altimeter does not meet RVSM requirements')"},{"id":"46158","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"other","question":"How does the trim air system meet zone temperature requirements?","options":{"A":"It cools conditioned air","B":"It heats bleed air","C":"It heats conditioned air","D":"It controls pack air temperature"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Temperature Control"},{"id":"46222","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Why minimize the low altitude flying time for EQUIP COOLING OVRD message?","options":{"A":"Pack temperature may cause damage","B":"Recirculation fans may not cool equipment adequately","C":"Aft and bulked cargo compartment may overheat","D":"Electronic equipment and displays may fail"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH NNC Equip Cooling Ovrd"},{"id":"46355","lastEdit":"03/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"If a take-off is to be performed from a runway which has reduced take-off distance, what has to be checked before take-off?","options":{"A":"Take-off distance available on airport charts against NOTAM declared take-off distance","B":"Take-off performance derived from EFB against RTOW charts","C":"Compare the airport chart with the QRH/FCOM performance tables","D":"Take-off distance in the performance software against those published in the NOTAM or AIP Supplement"},"answer":"D","reference":"Boeing 777 OPT user manual page 22 states to compare OPT TORA against charted data - however it doesn't account for the reduced take-off distance as in this question, so common sense would state compare the OPT vs the NOTAM"},{"id":"46583","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"With no AC power available, what supplies fuel to operate the APU?","options":{"A":"Left FWD AC main tank fuel pump","B":"Left main tank DC fuel pump","C":"Left main tank jettison pump","D":"The APU is on suction feed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, APU Fuel Feed"},{"id":"46710","lastEdit":"27/04/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is NOT a required visual reference for a CAT I ILS?","options":{"A":"Runway centreline lights","B":"Runway edge lights","C":"Touchdown zone","D":"Runway threshold lights"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.2 Required Visual References"},{"id":"46740","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"other","question":"With REV in GREEN above left engine and REV in AMBER above right engine, what best describes the conditions of the reverser sleeves on left and right side?","options":{"A":"Left engine is in reverse, the right engine has a reverser fault","B":"Left engine is in transition, the right engine is in reverse","C":"Left engine is in forward idle, the right engine has a reverser fault","D":"Left engine is in reverse and right engine is in transition"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Thrust Reverser System, Thrust Reverser Schematic"},{"id":"46827","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"What represents the letter 'L' or 'R' next to the barometric setting on the PFD?","options":{"A":"Respective EFIS control panel's barometric setting reference for the autopilot and flight director","B":"Respective EFIS control panel's barometric setting reference for the FMC","C":"Respective EFIS control panel's barometric setting reference for the autopilot","D":"Respective EFIS control panel's barometric setting reference for the flight director"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Primary Flight Display, PFD Barometric Indications"},{"id":"46869","lastEdit":"22/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the correct electrical panel configuration for normal flight?","options":{"A":"Bus Tie Switch in ISLN, Battery switch ON, Generator Control Switch ON","B":"Bus Tie Switch in AUTO, Battery switch ON, Generator Control Switch ON","C":"Bus Tie Switch in AUTO, Battery switch OFF, Generator Control Switch ON","D":"Bus Tie Switch ISLN, Battery switch ON, Generator Control Switch OFF"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - First Officer"},{"id":"47030","lastEdit":"13/04/2024","category":"interview","question":"A flight crew member goes sick just before departure on an LRV flight to Dubai which is 16 hours flight time. It was originally planned with 4 flight crew members, can you continue with 3 flight crew members?","options":{"A":"No, the maximum flight time is 15 hours","B":"Yes, the maximum flight time is 20 hours","C":"Yes, the maximum flight time is 18 hours","D":"No, the maximum flight time is 14 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.E.8 Other unforeseen circumstances, Section F, Paragraph 5"},{"id":"47094","lastEdit":"17/12/2024","category":"tech","question":"What does EICAS BLEED LEAK STRUT L mean?","options":{"A":"A bleed air leak is detected in the wing or pack bay area","B":"The bleed leak strut detection system has failed","C":"A bleed air leak is detected in the strut area","D":"A bleed air leak is detected in the strut area of either wing"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Air Systems EICAS Messages, Air Systems EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"47159","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When can VNAV be engaged?","options":{"A":"After liftoff","B":"Above 400 feet from the FMC reference altitude at 100 knots on the takeoff roll","C":"Above 400 feet from the FMC reference altitude at 80 knots on the takeoff roll","D":"Above 50 feet"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, System Description, Autopilot Flight Director System, AFDS Flight Mode Annunciations + Systems Description, Automatic Flight Operations, Automatic Flight Takeoff and Climb"},{"id":"47181","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"other","question":"How long must you wait after giving blood before you can fly?","options":{"A":"48 hours","B":"72 hours","C":"12 hours","D":"24 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 6.1.15 Blood/Bone Marrow Donation"},{"id":"47377","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"When dispatch has planned you at MLW minus 1% for a tankering flight, can you add more fuel?","options":{"A":"No, limit is MLW or RLW minus 1%","B":"No, the limit is MTOW minus 1%","C":"Yes, up to the limit of MLW or RLW","D":"Yes, up to the limit of MTOW"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.6 Fuel Tankering"},{"id":"47489","lastEdit":"29/04/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding increasing the missed approach gradient?","options":{"A":"Increase the missed approach gradient by 0.3% for any missed approach executed in icing conditions","B":"Increase the missed approach gradient by 0.8% if the missed approach is performed during adverse weather conditions","C":"Increase the missed approach gradient by 0.6% if the missed approach procedure includes a turn","D":"Increase the missed approach gradient by 0.5% if the aircraftÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s weight exceeds the maximum landing weight at the time of the missed approach"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, OPT Performance Calculations, OPT Actual Landing Weight Calculation (OPT LANDING ENROUTE), see table under 'G/A'"},{"id":"47724","lastEdit":"25/04/2024","category":"other","question":"What FCTM guidance is there when the aircraft is difficult to control?","options":{"A":"Consider cycling the primary flight control computers off then on","B":"Consider switching off hydraulic pumps during a hydraulic leak until the aircraft is at a low altitude to reduce hydraulic fluid loss","C":"Consider disconnecting the primary flight control computers","D":"Consider deploying the Ram Air Turbine"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCTM 8, Non Normal, Situations Beyond the Scope of Non-Normal Checklists, Damage Assessment and Airplane Handling Evaluation"},{"id":"47842","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is included in FMC RSV fuel?","options":{"A":"Enough fuel for a missed approach, diversion, arrival procedure, approach procedure, hold at the alternate at 1500 feet above aerodrome for 30 minutes in ISA at the aircraft mass at the alternate","B":"Enough fuel for a missed approach, diversion, arrival procedure, approach procedure, hold at the alternate at 1500 feet above aerodrome for 30 minutes in actual conditions at the aircraft mass at the alternate","C":"Enough fuel for a missed approach, diversion, approach procedure, hold at the alternate at 1500 feet above aerodrome for 30 minutes in ISA at the aircraft mass at the original destination","D":"Enough fuel for a diversion, arrival procedure, approach procedure, hold at the alternate at 1500 feet above aerodrome for 30 minutes in ISA at the aircraft mass at the original destination"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.4 + OMA 8.1.7.1.5 Flight Preparation Instructions, Determination of the quantity of fuel and oil carried, definitions, alternate fuel + final reserve fuel"},{"id":"47931","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the flight crew report time in Dubai for a non LRV flight?","options":{"A":"STD-1:15","B":"STD-1:23","C":"STD-1:25","D":"STD-1:00"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.6.1 Report time - Flight crew"},{"id":"48007","lastEdit":"22/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Why does the pressurization system schedule cabin altitude slightly below landing elevation?","options":{"A":"Due to software restrictions","B":"To ensure a small positive pressurization at touchdown","C":"So the aircraft lands unpressurized","D":"To allow for a more gradual adjustment of cabin pressure in case of a go-around"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization with Automatic Operation"},{"id":"48018","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"The flight deck door has a 6 button keypad, along with red, amber and green lights. Which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"When there is a system failure the red light illuminates","B":"When the correct non-normal code is entered the red light flashes","C":"The green light indicates the system is functioning normally","D":"When the correct non-normal code is entered the amber light illuminates"},"answer":"D","reference":"OME 6.2.2.3 B777 Aircraft Type, Flight Deck, Flight Deck Door, Normal Access Procedure"},{"id":"48105","lastEdit":"02/08/2024","category":"other","question":"If an in-flight emergency occurs the pilot in command must as soon as the situation permits inform ATS unit of any dangerous goods carried including:","options":{"A":"Proper Shipping Names and UN numbers, class and division for class one, the compatibility group, quantity and location on board the aircraft or a telephone number where a copy of the information can be obtained","B":"Quantity and location on board the aircraft","C":"Class/divisions and identified subsidiary risks, location on board the aircraft and any live animal locations","D":"Proper Shipping Names and UN numbers and location on board the aircraft"},"answer":"A","reference":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations - 9.5.1.3 Information by the pilot in command in case of in flight emergency"},{"id":"48155","lastEdit":"09/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding automatic landings on the passenger fleet?","options":{"A":"The 777-300ER and 777-200LR is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 25 or Flap 30, with both engines operative or one engine inoperative. Overweight landings are not recommended","B":"The 777-300ER and 777-200LR is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 25 or Flap 30, with both engines operative only. Overweight automatic landings are not permitted","C":"The 777-300ER and 777-200LR is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 30, with both engines operative only. Overweight automatic landings are not permitted","D":"The 777-300ER and 777-200LR is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 30, with both engines operative or one engine inoperative. Overweight landings are not recommended"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Limitations, Operating Limitations, Autoflight, AFM Limitations, Automatic Landing + FCTM 6, Overweight Landing, Overweight Autolands Policy"},{"id":"48462","lastEdit":"14/04/2024","category":"interview","question":"What guidance is there on how to assess intoxicated passengers?","options":{"A":"OME 10.3.6.4 The Traffic Light Guide","B":"OME 11.9.17 Substance Misuse","C":"OME 10.3.4.5 The 4D's","D":"OME 10.3.3 Levels of Threat"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 10.3.6.4 The Traffic Light Guide"},{"id":"48717","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"Autoland is inoperative for which of the following conditions?","options":{"A":"Left hydraulic system pressure low","B":"Right hydraulic system pressure low","C":"After RAT deployment","D":"Center hydraulic system pressure low"},"answer":"A","reference":"eLearning CBT Hydraulics"},{"id":"48744","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How are the busses powered if the right engine is started with APU powering the Left bus system and External Power powering the Right bus system?","options":{"A":"External power continues to supply the right main bus","B":"The right engine generator waits for external power to be disconnected before powering the right main bus","C":"The right engine generator automatically powers both main busses","D":"The right engine generator automatically powers the right main bus"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, AC Electrical System, AC Electrical System Power Sources"},{"id":"48778","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding sterile flight deck on departure?","options":{"A":"It begins entering the runway for departure and ends at 15000 AAL","B":"It begins at pushback and ends at 25000 AAL","C":"It begins at final door closure and ends at 10000 AAL","D":"It begins at parking brake release and ends at 20000 AAL"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.1 Sterile Flight Deck"},{"id":"48791","lastEdit":"25/02/2024","category":"other","question":"The actions for a stall warning in the correct sequence are?","options":{"A":"Rapidly apply nose down elevator until buffet or stick shaker stops, advance thrust levers as needed, roll wings level, retract the speedbrakes, do not change gear or flap configuration except during liftoff (call for flaps 1)","B":"Rapidly apply nose down elevator until buffer or stall warning stops, roll wings level, advance thrust levers as needed, retract the speedbrakes, do not change gear or flap configuration except during liftoff (call for flaps 5)","C":"Smoothly apply nose down elevator until buffet or stick shaker stops, roll wings level, advance thrust levers as needed, do not change gear or flap configuration except during liftoff (call for flaps 5), retract the speedbrakes","D":"Smoothly apply nose down elevator until buffet or stick shaker stops, roll wings level, advance thrust levers as needed, retract the speedbrakes, do not change gear or flap configuration except during liftoff (call for flaps 1)"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH, Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Approach to Stall or Stall Recovery"},{"id":"48813","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What indication provides confirmation that an evacuation slide/raft girt bar is disengaged with door sill?","options":{"A":"Black flag showing through girt bar engaged view window","B":"Door handle in the closed position","C":"Orange flag showing through girt bar engaged view window","D":"Yellow flag showing through girt bar engaged view window"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Controls and Indicators, Doors and Windows, Entry Door"},{"id":"48929","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What does taxi fuel consist of?","options":{"A":"The fuel used prior to takeoff, local conditions and APU consumption are taken into account","B":"The fuel used prior to takeoff, local conditions are taken into account","C":"Fuel to start the engines and taxi out to the runway expected for departure","D":"Fuel to start the engines and taxi out to the furthest runway for departure"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.1 Definitions"},{"id":"48941","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"On the B777F when the main deck temperature selector is in the 12 o'clock position, what temperature is selected?","options":{"A":"24 degrees Celsius","B":"18 degrees Celsius","C":"12 degrees Celsius","D":"16 degrees Celsius"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Air conditioning system. air conditioning panel (see 777F)"},{"id":"48983","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding frost?","options":{"A":"Regulations allow a small layer of frost on top of the fuselage","B":"Regulations allow a small layer of frost on top of the wing","C":"Regulations allow a small layer of frost on the fan blades","D":"No level of frost is acceptable"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.2.4 De-icing and anti-icing on the ground"},{"id":"49131","lastEdit":"04/01/2024","category":"other","question":"When conducting an approach in low visibility ops which warnings should trigger you to immediately go around below 200 feet AGL?","options":{"A":"NO AUTOLAND, AUTOPILOT, AIR DATA SYS, AUTO SPEEDBRAKE","B":"NO AUTOLAND, AUTOPILOT, SPEEDBRAKE EXTENDED, AUTOTHROTTLE DISC","C":"NO AUTOLAND, AUTOPILOT, SPOILERS, AUTOTHROTTLE DISC","D":"NO AUTOLAND, AUTOPILOT, SGL SOURCE AIR DATA, NO LAND 3"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH Operational information, Low Visibility Operation, Failed or Downgraded Aircraft Equipment"},{"id":"49258","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What happens when an APU fire is detected on the ground and the engines are shut down?","options":{"A":"The APU shuts down automatically but the fire bottle must be discharged manually","B":"The APU shuts down automatically and the fire bottle discharges automatically","C":"The APU does not shut down automatically and the fire bottle must be discharged manually","D":"The APU does not shut down automatically but the fire bottle discharges automatically"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, APU Fire Protection, APU Fire Extinguishing"},{"id":"49263","lastEdit":"23/01/2025","category":"other","question":"In managing a conflict between two cabin crew members during a flight or on a layover, which approach is a good TECHNIQUE?","options":{"A":"At work: Arrange for the conflict to be settled by the Purser. On layover: Require them to write and exchange letters of apology","B":"At work: Separate them into different cabins, inform NCC, and arrange for HR to meet with them in a private room upon arrival. On layover: Attempt to defuse the situation internally with the presence of an independent crew member as a witness, using local police only as a last resort","C":"At work: Inform NCC, and arrange for HR to meet with them in a private room upon arrival. On layover: Defuse the situation with the use of the local police with the Commander and Purser present","D":"At work: Have them swap roles for the duration of the flight to understand each other's responsibilities. On layover: Arrange for separate hotels and instruct them to reflect on their behaviour"},"answer":"B","reference":"NO REFERENCE - Technique for a common interview question"},{"id":"49396","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Once the center tank pumps are turned off in flight some fuel remains in the center tank as unusable fuel. Is this statement true?","options":{"A":"Yes. The center tank fuel valves automatically close","B":"No. A scavenge system transfers remaining fuel","C":"No. The pumps can be turned on again to empty the center tank","D":"Yes. Main tank pump pressure prevents any further fuel transfer"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Pumps, Fuel Pump Operations (See Center Tank Fuel Scavenge)"},{"id":"49420","lastEdit":"15/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which configuration is the approach climb gradient calculation assuming?","options":{"A":"All engines operating, approach flaps, landing gear down","B":"One engine inoperative, approach flaps, landing gear up","C":"All engines operating, landing flaps, landing gear down","D":"One engine inoperative, landing flaps, landing gear up"},"answer":"B","reference":"B777 OPT Users Manual, Table of Contents, Other Available Functions, D) Viewing Airport Information"},{"id":"49515","lastEdit":"27/01/2024","category":"other","question":"Your maximum holdover time has expired using types II, III or IV fluid, which statement is true? (holdover time calculated: minimum: 25 mins, maximum 40 mins)","options":{"A":"The aircraft must receive an external PCI or return for a complete de-icing treatment to remove all fluid residues before applying a new anti-icing step","B":"The aircraft cannot receive an external PCI and the aircraft must have all the fluid removed and a new anti-icing layer applied","C":"The aircraft cannot receive an external PCI and the aircraft must have a new application of anti-icing layer applied on top of the previous fluid","D":"The aircraft must receive an external PCI or return for a new anti-icing application"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.3.6 Step 5 Pre-takeoff Contamination Inspection (under the large highlighted orange box)"},{"id":"49640","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the max FDP for an LRV flight to an S1 destination? (No waivers or extensions applied)","options":{"A":"Max FDP 15 hours","B":"Max FDP 22 hours","C":"Max FDP 18 hours","D":"Max FDP 20 hours"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.E.5 FDPs"},{"id":"49662","lastEdit":"13/12/2023","category":"other","question":"You dispatch with MEL 32-42-04A (Autobrake system) - it contains only a maintenance procedure with no operational notes. What needs to be changed in your departure briefing?","options":{"A":"As there are no operational notes, no changes need to be made","B":"The departure briefing must be amended to use manual braking as antiskid will also not function","C":"The departure briefing must be amended to use manual braking incase of a rejected takeoff or quick return","D":"The BTMS must be checked 10-15 minutes after departure"},"answer":"C","reference":"MEL 32-42-04A - Common interview question"},{"id":"49752","lastEdit":"14/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statements are correct about the Equipment Cooling Override mode?","options":{"A":"The mode can only be selected manually, the EICAS message EQUIP COOLING is displayed, there is not a non normal procedure for this message","B":"The mode can be selected automatically, the EICAS message EQUIP COOLING OVRD is displayed, there is a non normal procedure for this message","C":"The mode can only be selected manually, the EICAS message EQUIP COOLING OVRD is displayed, there is a non normal procedure for this message","D":"The mode can be selected automatically, the EICAS message EQUIP COOLING OVRD is displayed, there is not a non normal procedure for this message"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC Equipment Cooling Ovrd + FCOM Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Air Conditioning Panel, Equipment Cooling + FCOM Systems, Air, Air Systems EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"49779","lastEdit":"05/12/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which lights are turned on by the storm light switch?","options":{"A":"Left and right panel flood lights, glare shield flood lights, dome lights, aisle stand flood light and all illuminated annunciator lights switch to full brightness","B":"All flight deck lights","C":"Map lights, left and right panel flood lights, glare shield flood lights, dome lights, aisle stand flood light and all illuminated annunciator lights switch to full brightness","D":"Landing lights, navigation lights, strobe lights and wing lights"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOMS System, Airplane General, System Description, Light Systems, Flight deck lighting"},{"id":"49899","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"During cruise approaching a GPS signal interference area. Which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"Ensure TERR OVRD is in NORM and fly the GPWS Escape Manoeuvre as needed","B":"Select TERR OVRD if EGPWS warnings become distracting","C":"Select TERR OVRD once any GPS interference effects occur and after verifying that the aircraft is operating above the minimum safe altitude","D":"Follow the QRH procedure for GPS interference at destination"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, GPS Signal Interference"},{"id":"49965","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What is represented by the colour magenta in weather radar returns?","options":{"A":"Clear air turbulence","B":"Moderate precipitation","C":"Heavy precipitation","D":"Turbulence within precipitation"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management, Navigation System Description, Weather Radar, Threat Assessment Feature (note: it cannot be clear air turbulence, that is red for predictive overflight)"},{"id":"50095","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"both","question":"At what flight level can the Commander be relieved in flight by a First Officer with an ATPL?","options":{"A":"Above FL250","B":"Above FL200","C":"Above 10000 feet","D":"Above FL100"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 5.2.3 Pilot Relieving the pilot in command"},{"id":"50149","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"During an approach in IMC and below MSA at an airport with a CONOTAM to apply the QRH procedure for GPS Interference at Destination, a GPWS 'PULL UP' warning is triggered, what is the appropriate response?","options":{"A":"Execute the GPWS escape manoeuvre immediately","B":"Go-around and verify your position with ATC","C":"Select TERR OVRD to reduce distractions and continue the approach","D":"Continue the approach as planned as the warning due to GPS interference"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMD 2.1.1.6.19 TAWS - If the TAWS/EGPWS is disabled by select TERR OVRD you're left with just GPWS which is based primarily on radio altitude, barometric altitude, airspeed and rate of descent and not GPS - i.e. the remaining alerts are valid and should be followed"},{"id":"50381","lastEdit":"05/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"If landing altitude is unavailable from the FMC and not set in MAN, what EICAS advisory message and landing altitude is assumed?","options":{"A":"EICAS advisory message LANDING ALT and assumed landing altitude of 400 ft","B":"EICAS advisory message LANDING ALT and assumed landing altitude of 2000 ft","C":"EICAS advisory message LANDING ALT and assumed landing altitude of 1000 ft","D":"EICAS advisory message LANDING ALT and assumed landing altitude of 500 ft"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM 2.30 Cabin Altitude Controller Automatic Operation With Loss of Landing Altitude"},{"id":"50569","lastEdit":"10/01/2024","category":"other","question":"During pre-flight what position should the engine bleed air switches be in?","options":{"A":"On","B":"Off","C":"Auto","D":"Norm"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - First Officer"},{"id":"50606","lastEdit":"11/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"If 'VERIFY POSITION' is shown in the scratchpad in flight, what should you consider?","options":{"A":"Bulletin regarding 'ANP Fluctuation Caused by GPS Erroneous Output'. There is also FCOM Supp Procedure 10: 'FMS Position Correction'","B":"Bulletin regarding 'GPS Signal Interference'. There is also FCOM Supp Procedure 9: 'FMS Position Errors'","C":"Bulletins regarding 'GPS Signal Interference' and 'ANP Fluctuation Caused by ADIRU Erroneous Output'. There is also FCOM Supp Procedure 11: 'FMS Position Update'","D":"Nothing - erase it"},"answer":"C","reference":"Bulletin GPS Signal Interference and Bulletin ANP Fluctuation Caused by ADIRU Erroneous Output and FCOM Supp Procedure 11 all contain considerations and actions for when 'VERIFY POSITION' is displayed"},{"id":"50751","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which is the best example of ATC communications when a pilot is conducting both the PF duties and the PM duties at the same time?","options":{"A":"ATC: Emirates 123 descend FL290, Pilot: Descending FL290 Emirates 123","B":"ATC: Emirates 123 descend FL290, Pilot: Emirates 123 Descending FL290","C":"ATC: Emirates 123 descend FL290, Pilot: Descend FL290 Emirates 123","D":"ATC: Emirates 123 descend FL290, Pilot: Descend FL290 Emirates 123, Pilot: Emirates 123 Leaving FL310 descending FL290"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.3 ATC Communication"},{"id":"50883","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which one of the following is inoperative with dual FMC failure?","options":{"A":"LNAV","B":"Both CDUs","C":"MAP display","D":"VNAV"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Flight Management Computer, FMC Failure, Dual FMC Failure (Both LNAV and VNAV fail but LNAV can be reselected)"},{"id":"50909","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which autobrake setting provides the highest deceleration rate for landing?","options":{"A":"AUTOBRAKE 3","B":"AUTOBRAKE MAX","C":"AUTOBRAKE 1","D":"AUTOBRAKE 4"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Performance Inflight, 777-300ER, Advisory Information, Normal Configuration Landing Distance (see FLAP 30 table shows Max Auto is distance than Autobrake 4)"},{"id":"50920","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which EICAS message do you see when the ADIRU is in alignment mode?","options":{"A":"EICAS alert message NAV ALIGN MODE","B":"CDU scratchpad message ADIRU ALIGN","C":"CDU scratchpad message ENTER ADIRU POSITION","D":"EICAS memo message ADIRU ALIGN MODE"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, EICAS Messages, Navigation EICAS Messages"},{"id":"50945","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"After a diversion due to medical reasons, does the ETOPS Supplement Maintenance Check remain valid for the subsequent ETOPS flight?","options":{"A":"Yes, as long as it is confirmed that the ETOPS serviceability requirements have not changed since the last signed ETOPS Supplement Maintenance Check","B":"No, the ETOPS Supplement Maintenance Check must be redone regardless of the reason for diversion","C":"Yes, ETOPS Supplement Maintenance Check remains valid in the case of a diversion","D":"No, the ETOPS Supplement Maintenance Check must be completed for each ETOPS sector"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.5.5.1 MEL/CDL Considerations"},{"id":"50975","lastEdit":"14/04/2024","category":"other","question":"During pre-flight you notice the EICAS BOTTLE 1 DISCH ENG message, what does this mean?","options":{"A":"Fire bottle 1 has discharged","B":"This is a normal indication prior APU start","C":"The fire bottle squibs are inoperative","D":"Ground maintenance is servicing fire bottle 1"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, Engine Fire Protection, Engine Fire Extinguishing"},{"id":"50988","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the correct course of action during a traffic advisory?","options":{"A":"Flight crew shall prepare for appropriate action if a resolution advisory occurs","B":"Flight crew shall contact ATC and state 'TCAS RA'","C":"Flight crew shall file an ASR","D":"Flight crew shall manoeuvre accordingly to the traffic advisory"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.6 Policy and Procedures for the use of TCAS"},{"id":"50992","lastEdit":"06/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Climbing at FL150 you enter severe turbulence, what speed do you fly?","options":{"A":"270 knots","B":"280 knots or M0.82 whichever is less","C":"250 knots","D":"270 knots or M0.82 whichever is less"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Limitations Severe Turbulent Air Penetration Speed"},{"id":"51117","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"With the engine EECs manually selected to the alternate mode, which statement is true?","options":{"A":"The autothrottle automatically disengages","B":"The EEC schedules N2 as a function of thrust lever position","C":"Both engine EECs are now in the soft alternate mode","D":"Positioning of the thrust levers to the full forward position will cause an engine limit to be exceeded"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Electronic Engine Control, Alternate Mode"},{"id":"51119","lastEdit":"09/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In order to conduct an approach in LNAV/VNAV what criteria must be met?","options":{"A":"Approach must be line selectable, course within 2 degrees, glidepath within 0.1 degrees, distance FAF to RW or MAWP within 0.1 NM, minimum crossing altitudes 100 feet","B":"Approach must have approved charts, course within 3 degrees, glidepath within 0.1 degrees, distance FAF to RW or MAWP within 1 NM, minimum crossing altitudes 10 feet","C":"Approach must have approved charts, Course within 2 degrees, glidepath within 0.1 degrees, distance FAF to RW or MAWP within 0.1 NM, minimum crossing altitudes 100 feet","D":"Approach must be line selectable, course within 3 degrees, glidepath within 0.1 degrees, distance FAF to RW or MAWP within 1 NM, minimum crossing altitudes 10 feet"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.22.2 Category I Approach, Approach Procedure with Vertical Guidance, Non Precision Approach"},{"id":"51125","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"When deviating for weather in oceanic airspace without an ATC clearance which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"When within 10 miles of route no flight level change is required, when deviating more than 10 miles south of route climb 300 feet, when deviating more than 10 miles north of route, descend 300 feet","B":"When within 5 miles of route no flight level change is required, when deviating more than 5 miles south of route climb 300 feet, when deviating more than 5 miles north of route, descend 300 feet","C":"When within 10 miles of route no flight level change is required, when deviating more than 10 miles south of route descend 300 feet, when deviating more than 10 miles north of route, climb 300 feet","D":"When within 5 miles of route no flight level change is required, when deviating more than 5 miles south of route descend 300 feet, when deviating more than 5 miles north of route, climb 300 feet"},"answer":"B","reference":"LIDO 1.4.2.17.4.2 Weather Deviation Procedures (LIDO page 1220), see section Actions To Be Taken If A Revised ATC Clearance Cannot Be Obtained"},{"id":"51411","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the maximum range at which turbulence returns can be displayed on ND?","options":{"A":"10nm","B":"80nm","C":"20nm","D":"40nm"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Weather Radar Panel"},{"id":"51482","lastEdit":"27/05/2024","category":"other","question":"An acrid smell, chest constrictions, coughing, headache, eye irritation are symptoms of what?","options":{"A":"Volcanic ash","B":"Ice crystal icing","C":"Ozone","D":"Electrical burning"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.2.2.4.2 Operational Procedures, Ozone"},{"id":"51575","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does a square icon next to an EICAS message indicate?","options":{"A":"There is no electronic checklist associated with this message","B":"There is an electronic checklist associated with this message and the checklist is complete","C":"There is an electronic checklist associated with this message and the checklist is not complete","D":"The non-normal condition is no longer present"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, Controls and Indicators, EICAS, EICAS Messages"},{"id":"51733","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the minimum visibility for take-off when the RVR are reported in all the relevant areas and with runway centre light lights spaced at 15m or less and high intensity edge lights spaced at 60m or less?","options":{"A":"150m","B":"125m","C":"200m","D":"250m"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.2 Takeoff Minima"},{"id":"51749","lastEdit":"08/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding tailstrikes? (777-300ER)","options":{"A":"Once the pitch is above 10 degrees on take-off and 7.6 degrees on landing a tail strike is likely to occur","B":"Once the pitch is above 10 degrees on take-off and 10.2 degrees on landing a tail strike is likely to occur","C":"Once the pitch is above 10 degrees on take-off and 12.1 degrees on landing a tail strike is likely to occur","D":"Once the pitch is above 12.1 degrees on take-off and 8.9 degrees on landing a tail strike is likely to occur"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCTM 6, Landing, Flare and Touchdown, Normal Touchdown Attitude"},{"id":"51866","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"An altitude that safely ensures aircraft are above terrain by 1000 feet or 2000 feet by a route width of +/-5 nautical miles on SIDs and STARs and +/-10 nautical miles on airways is the definition of what?","options":{"A":"MSA","B":"MEA","C":"MGA","D":"MTCA"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO 1.4.2.11.1.12 Minimum Terrain Clearance Altitude"},{"id":"52016","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"During cruise with normal engine EEC modes configured, you manually position the thrust levers to the full forward position. What happens next?","options":{"A":"The engines will produce maximum cruise thrust","B":"The engines will exceed the maximum thrust limit","C":"The engines will produce maximum rated thrust","D":"The EEC alternate mode will automatically engage"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Electronic Engine Control, Normal Mode"},{"id":"52062","lastEdit":"14/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In terms of dangerous goods - what is blue square shape with magnet in middle facing a compass indicate?","options":{"A":"Packages containing radioactive materials","B":"Packages that are not permitted on pax aircraft","C":"Packages containing magnetized materials","D":"Packages containing miscellaneous dangerous goods"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 9.9.1 Additional Handling Labels and Marks"},{"id":"52285","lastEdit":"29/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When are the pitot-static probes heated for anti-icing protection?","options":{"A":"When either engine is operating","B":"Whenever the DC busses are powered","C":"When icing conditions are detected","D":"In flight"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, System Description, Probe Heat"},{"id":"52352","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"If you are acclimatised and then operate a night turnaround are you acclimatised after your duty?","options":{"A":"Yes, you remain acclimatised until you finish a duty where the time zone differs by more than 2 hours","B":"No, you have no longer had 3 local nights rest on ground","C":"Yes, after 12 hours rest or preceding duty length","D":"Depends if it was an S1 or S2 destination"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.5 Definitions, acclimatised"},{"id":"52425","lastEdit":"14/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"After using the emergency oxygen masks in the cockpit, how do you reset the communication system to use the boom microphone?","options":{"A":"Close the right hand oxygen compartment door and then push the RESET/TEST switch. Oxygen flow is not affected","B":"Close the left hand oxygen compartment door and then push the RESET/TEST switch. Oxygen flow is not affected","C":"Close the left hand oxygen compartment door and then push the RESET/TEST switch. This also shuts off the oxygen to the mask. The oxygen flow can be restored at any time by opening the left oxygen panel door","D":"Close the right hand oxygen compartment door and then push the RESET/TEST switch. This also shuts off the oxygen to the mask. The oxygen flow can be restored at any time by opening the right oxygen panel door"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Supplementary Procedures, Emergency Oxygen Use + FCOM 5.20 Audio Control Panel + FCOM 1.30 Oxygen Mask Panel"},{"id":"52539","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When a flight crew member is incapacitated what should the remaining pilot do?","options":{"A":"Diversion shall be accomplished to an aerodrome with at least 5000m visibility and a cloud ceiling of 1000 feet or higher","B":"Diversion should be accomplished to an aerodrome with CAT I weather or better, First Officers may conduct an autoland if needed","C":"Diversion shall be accomplished to an aerodrome with CAT I weather or better, First Officers are not permitted to use autoland","D":"Diversion shall be accomplished to an aerodrome with at least 10km visibility and a cloud ceiling of 1000 feet or higher"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.14.1 (Incapacitation of) Flight Crew Member"},{"id":"52583","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding volcanic ash?","options":{"A":"When operating in night/IMC you can operate above, below and but not within the ASHTAM area. For Ash reported above FL100, keep a minimum of 6000 feet vertical distance when operating above or below the ASHTAM area","B":"When operating in day/VMC you can operate above, below and but not within the ASHTAM area. A tech log entry is required for operations near the ASHTAM area","C":"When operating in day/VMC you can operate above, below and within the ASHTAM area. But not within visible ash. A tech log entry is required for operations within the ASHTAM area","D":"When operating in night/IMC you can operate above, below and within the ASHTAM area. For Ash reported below FL100, keep a minimum of 5000 feet vertical distance when operating below the ASHTAM area"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.2.2.4.2 Operational Procedures, Volcanic Ash"},{"id":"52674","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"Approaching the North Atlantic crossing you have a single GPS failure, what is the most likely outcome from negotiations with ATC? (assuming original routing is not PBCS)","options":{"A":"You can still continue with RNP 4 performance capability. You must re-route or climb or descend to avoid datalink mandated airspace as you only have two long range navigation system (LRNS)","B":"You can still continue with RNAV 10 performance capability. You can continue on your normal routing and flight level as you still have two long range navigation system (LRNS)","C":"You can still continue with RNAV 10 performance capability. You must fly above or below the NAT HLA as you only have two long range navigation system (LRNS)","D":"You can still continue with RNAV 10 performance capability. You must re-route or climb or descend to avoid datalink mandated airspace as you only have two long range navigation system (LRNS)"},"answer":"B","reference":"LIDO NAT 2.3.4.2.2 Loss of Navigation/FMS Capability (R-1220) - See the section on: One System Fails Before the OCA Boundary is Reached - (Bearing in mind we need 2 LRNS, and we effectively have 3 (GPS+GPS+ADIRU) + Ref for RNAV 10: Lido 2.3.2 North Atlantic, RAR, General Flight Rules (RNAV 10 or RNP 4 approval required)"},{"id":"52723","lastEdit":"17/12/2024","category":"tech","question":"What happens to the electrical busses during autoland?","options":{"A":"The busses isolate to allow three independent sources to power the three autopilots","B":"The utility busses disconnect to prevent power surges to non-essential systems","C":"All busses switch to battery power to ensure uninterrupted supply","D":"The backup system powers the left AC transfer bus and the left main DC bus, and the first officer's flight instrument bus"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM 6.20 AC Electrical Power Distribution, Autoland"},{"id":"52805","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What exemptions are allowed for RFFS for our passenger fleet?","options":{"A":"Departure and destination can be two categories below authorised in accordance with ICAO movement provisions, flight operations applies/monitors this provision. Departure and destination can also be three categories below by NOTAM for less than one week (168 hours)","B":"Departure, destination, takeoff alternate, en-route, destination alternate can be one category below authorised in accordance with ICAO movement provisions, flight operations applies/monitors this provision. Departure, destination, take-off alternate, en-route, destination alternate can be two categories below by NOTAM for less than 72 hours","C":"Departure and destination can be two categories below authorised in accordance with ICAO movement provisions, flight operations applies/monitors this provision. Departure, destination and ETOPS alternate can also be two categories below by NOTAM for less than 48 hours","D":"Departure and destination can be one category below authorised in accordance with ICAO movement provisions, flight operations applies/monitors this provision. Departure and destination can be two categories below by NOTAM for less than 72 hours"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.4 Rescue and Fire Fighting Services (RFFS)"},{"id":"52941","lastEdit":"09/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the Commanders responsibility when a crime is committed onboard?","options":{"A":"The Commander is responsible from doors closed to doors open, they cannot detain anyone on suspicion of a crime and must contact authorities to meet the aircraft on arrival","B":"The Commander is responsible from takeoff to landing, they can detain anyone on suspicion of a crime and hand them over to authorities on arrival","C":"The Commander is responsible from doors closed to doors open, they can detain anyone on suspicion of a crime and hand them over to authorities on arrival","D":"The Commander is responsible from takeoff to landing, they cannot detain anyone on suspicion of a crime and must contact authorities to meet the aircraft on arrival"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 10.3 Crime On Board"},{"id":"53031","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"What external aircraft lights are isolated by the CABIN/UTILITY power switch?","options":{"A":"No external lights are isolated by the Cabin/Utility power switch as it is for internal fittings","B":"Taxi lights and strobes","C":"Logo and landing lights","D":"Beacon, logo and wing lights"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM 6.20 Cabin and Utility Systems"},{"id":"53105","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"At what altitude is APU bleed air available?","options":{"A":"25000 feet","B":"15000 feet","C":"22000 feet","D":"43100 feet"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air systems, APU Bleed air supply"},{"id":"53117","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"When are cold weather temperature corrections required?","options":{"A":"When the reported aerodrome temperature is 10c or colder","B":"When the reported aerodrome temperature is ISA - 15 or colder","C":"When the reported aerodrome temperature is 0c or colder","D":"When the reported aerodrome temperature is 1c or colder"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.4.1 General - Cold Temperature Altitude Corrections"},{"id":"53249","lastEdit":"03/01/2024","category":"other","question":"When a single passenger must be offloaded as part of a non-family group of passengers, what happens to the bags?","options":{"A":"The entire group of passenger's bags get offloaded","B":"The entire group's bags can remain onboard subject to approval from VPNC","C":"The entire group of passenger's bags get offloaded or the individual's bag gets offloaded after a baggage ID by the remaining passengers","D":"The entire group's bags can remain onboard subject to the Senior Airport Service Officials discretion"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.2.2.4.1 Offloading of Pooled Baggage"},{"id":"53258","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When should pilot incapacitation be suspected? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Unresponsive to two verbal communications above 1000 AGL One verbal communication below 1000 AGL any verbal communication associated with significant deviation from the intended flight path","B":"Unresponsive to one verbal communication below 1000 AGL","C":"Any verbal communication associated with significant deviation from the intended flight path","D":"Unresponsive to two verbal communications above 1000 AGL"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.14.1 (Incapacitation of) Flight Crew Member (Actual exam answer is 'all of the above')"},{"id":"53354","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"What are the maximum DEPU and DEPA allowed onboard a flight?","options":{"A":"A DEPU is an unaccompanied deportee (max 5 onboard), A DEPA is an accompanied deportee (max 1 onboard)","B":"A DEPU is an unaccompanied deportee (max 8 onboard), A DEPA is an accompanied deportee (max 1 onboard or a family)","C":"A DEPU is an unaccompanied deportee (max 1 onboard), A DEPA is an accompanied deportee (max 1 onboard)","D":"A DEPU is an unaccompanied deportee (unlimited onboard), A DEPA is an accompanied deportee (max 1 onboard)"},"answer":"B","reference":"OME 10.5.18.2 Aviation Security, Security Measures, Inadmissible, Deportees"},{"id":"53374","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What actions should you take if the EICAS EQUIP COOLING OVRD is displayed during cruise?","options":{"A":"Increase flight deck temperatures","B":"Plan descent for minimum time at low altitudes","C":"Turn off recirculation fans","D":"Descend to low altitude and continue flight"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC Equip Cooling Ovrd"},{"id":"53397","lastEdit":"11/04/2024","category":"other","question":"When can flight crew jettison fuel without NCC approval?","options":{"A":"In an abnormal/non-normal situation","B":"When at least 4000 feet above bodies of water","C":"When a MAYDAY has been declared","D":"When a MAYDAY or PAN PAN has been declared"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.3.10 Overweight Landing"},{"id":"53499","lastEdit":"09/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What does the WXR FAIL R/T message indicate?","options":{"A":"Weather radar receiver transmitter has failed","B":"Weather radar radio telephone failure","C":"Weather radar antenna failure","D":"Weather radar auto tilt failure"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"53537","lastEdit":"16/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is true about the rudder pedals?","options":{"A":"The rudder pedals should not be used for sharp turns","B":"The rudder pedals are locked to centre at high speeds","C":"The rudder pedals control nose wheel steering, the rudder and brakes","D":"The rudder pedals control nose wheel steering, main gear steering and the rudder"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Yaw Control + FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, Controls and Indications, Brake System, Rudder/Brake Pedals"},{"id":"53622","lastEdit":"21/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is true concerning the alternate EEC mode?","options":{"A":"In the hard alternate mode, EEC uses EPR as controlling parameter","B":"Overspeed protection is NOT available in the hard alternate mode (ENG RPM LIMITED L/R EICAS and EEC reduces Fuel flow when approaching an overspeed)","C":"Engine thrust limit protection is provided in both normal and hard alternate modes","D":"If a fault occurs in normal mode, EEC automatically switches to soft alternate mode"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Electronic Engine Control, Overspeed Protection"},{"id":"53626","lastEdit":"30/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the Technical Fault Resolution Process?","options":{"A":"The Technical Fault Resolution Process is found in the OMC, Company Procedures","B":"It can be used after aircraft tech log acceptance and before take-off","C":"It can be used after brakes release and before take-off","D":"The Technical Fault Resolution Process is found in the QRH, Operational Information, Other Procedures"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, General, Technical Fault Resolution Process"},{"id":"53650","lastEdit":"17/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"When the battery is first switched on without AC power connected, which systems are powered?","options":{"A":"The ground handling bus","B":"The DC pump in the right main tank and cabin utility lighting","C":"The utility bus","D":"Some switch annunciator lights are illuminated and it allows the APU to be started"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Electrical, Controls and Indicators, Electrical Panel, Item 1"},{"id":"53719","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What does the fuel planning calculation take into account?","options":{"A":"FCOM provided fuel consumption data, anticipated aircraft masses","B":"Meteorological conditions, realistic fuel consumption data, maximum aircraft masses","C":"Meteorological conditions, realistic fuel consumption data, anticipated aircraft masses, air service navigation provider restrictions","D":"FCOM provided fuel consumption data, maximum aircraft masses, air service navigation provider restrictions"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7 Determination of the Quantity of Fuel and Oil Carried"},{"id":"54128","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which of the following ND modes cannot display weather radar returns?","options":{"A":"VOR expanded","B":"MAP centered","C":"APP expanded","D":"APP centered"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"54189","lastEdit":"29/04/2024","category":"other","question":"What action does the EEC take when N1 or N2 approaches overspeed?","options":{"A":"The EEC increases fuel flow to compensate for the increased engine speed","B":"The EEC switches the engine operation to alternate mode","C":"The EEC disengages the autothrottles to allow manual control of engine speed","D":"The EEC commands reduced fuel flow to the engine"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Engine APU, Engine System Description, EEC, Overspeed Protection"},{"id":"54366","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"During taxi out DET FIRE APU EICAS is displayed. What does this indicate?","options":{"A":"APU fire detection system has automatically reconfigured to single loop operation","B":"APU fire detection is no longer available","C":"A fire has been detected in the APU","D":"The APU fire bottle squibs are inoperative"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, APU Fire Protection, APU Fire Detection"},{"id":"54385","lastEdit":"04/02/2024","category":"other","question":"When en-route and the ISA temperature deviation from the OFP is ISA-30, which altitudes shall be corrected for cold weather temperature effects?","options":{"A":"MEA, MH, MGA, MOCA, MTCA, MSA","B":"MVA, MOCA, MRA, MEA, MSA, MH","C":"MRA, MVA, MEA, MSA, MGA, MTCA","D":"MIA, MEA, MVA, MH, MTCA, MSA"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.4.1.1 Enroute"},{"id":"54594","lastEdit":"13/03/2024","category":"both","question":"When does the FDP start for an LRV flight?","options":{"A":"1:25 before STD in Dubai, 1:25 before STD at outstations","B":"1:25 before STD in Dubai, 1:00 before STD at outstations","C":"1:25 before STD in Dubai, 1:15 before STD at outstations","D":"1:15 before STD in Dubai, 1:15 before STD at outstations"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.E.2 Annex 7.E: LRV - Key Rules and Conditions"},{"id":"54711","lastEdit":"20/04/2024","category":"interview","question":"When you arrive to the aircraft the previous Captain has not signed the release of the tech log, what do you do?","options":{"A":"Inform MPOD","B":"Inform the Crew Duty Manager","C":"Inform MCC","D":"Inform the Tech Pilot"},"answer":"B","reference":"Aircraft Tech Log Instructions (onboard the aircraft)"},{"id":"54782","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding Wheel to Rudder cross tie?","options":{"A":"It's operative above 70 knots in the normal flight control mode","B":"It's operative above 70 knots in the normal and secondary flight control modes","C":"It's operative in flight below 210 knots in the normal and secondary flight control modes","D":"It's operative in flight below 210 knots in the normal flight control mode"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Yaw Control, Wheel to Rudder Cross tie"},{"id":"55037","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the EICAS DET FIRE CARGO AFT indicate?","options":{"A":"The aft cargo fire heat sensor is inoperative","B":"Smoke detection for the aft cargo compartment is not available","C":"There is a detection zone fault in the smoke detector for the aft cargo compartment","D":"A fire has been detected in the aft cargo compartment"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, Cargo Compartment Fire Protection, Cargo Compartment Smoke Detection"},{"id":"55063","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"At the planning stage your destination is below minima, two alternates are available on the OFP, but how much fuel must be carried?","options":{"A":"The alternate fuel shall be sufficient to proceed to the nearest alternate aerodrome then onwards to the furthest alternate aerodrome","B":"The alternate fuel shall be sufficient to proceed to the furthest of the nearest 4 alternates","C":"The alternate fuel shall be sufficient to proceed to the nearest alternate aerodrome only","D":"The alternate fuel shall be sufficient to proceed to the alternate aerodrome which requires the greater amount of fuel"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.4 Alternate Fuel"},{"id":"55156","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"If the FMC NAV RAD page displays PARK next to the ILS freq/course (which is in small font), how do you select the ILS freq/course for your planned runway?","options":{"A":"You must wait until you are close enough for FMC to autotune","B":"You must manually enter Freq/Course into scratchpad and line select 4L","C":"Line select 4L","D":"You must manually enter Freq/Course into scratchpad and line select 1L"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, FMC Preflight, Preflight Pages 1, Navigation Radio Page (See diagrams, remember the question states the frequency and course is already in line 4L, also see ILS Tuning Status)"},{"id":"55185","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What indicates a properly closed and locked side window?","options":{"A":"A WINDOW NOT CLOSED placard is hidden from view and lock lever in full aft position","B":"A WINDOW CLOSED placard in view","C":"A WINDOW CLOSED placard in view and lock lever in full forward position","D":"A WINDOW NOT CLOSED placard is hidden from view and lock lever in full forward position"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Doors Windows Seats, Doors and Windows, Flight deck number two windows"},{"id":"55284","lastEdit":"07/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which pressure source is providing antiskid protection?","options":{"A":"Right hydraulic system pressure, alternate brake hydraulic system pressure","B":"Left hydraulic system pressure, normal and alternate brake hydraulic system pressure","C":"Left hydraulic system pressure, pressure supplied by the brake accumulator","D":"Normal and alternate brake hydraulic system pressure and pressure supplied by the brake accumulator"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, System Description, Brake System, Antiskid Protection"},{"id":"55318","lastEdit":"13/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the RTOW field of the B777 Final Fuel Figures ACARS message?","options":{"A":"The RTOW field should be left blank during Hot Season Operations in Dubai if dispatch has already calculated a more precise RTOW or if the crew has communicated it earlier","B":"The RTOW field should never be left blank unless the OPT indicates a limiting weight below structural MTOW","C":"The RTOW field should always be left blank to allow for manual calculations by the load control staff at the time of departure","D":"The RTOW field should be left blank if there is an expected delay in departure to allow for last-minute adjustments"},"answer":"A","reference":"Special Crew Brief - Hot Season Operations Procedure (this SCB is deleted for winter)"},{"id":"55325","lastEdit":"09/07/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the departure timeline target for offloading missing passenger baggage?","options":{"A":"STD-20","B":"STD-10","C":"STD-5","D":"STD-15"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 1.1.5 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP- Departure Target Timeline"},{"id":"55410","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What is the green altitude range arc (prediction on ND) based on?","options":{"A":"Vertical speed and indicated airspeed","B":"Only vertical speed","C":"Vertical speed and ground speed","D":"Vertical speed and FMC speed"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"55627","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"In a snowtam what does 'M) RWY 14L SNOWBANK R30 FM CL' mean?","options":{"A":"Snowbanks on the runway 300m from the centreline to the right","B":"Snowbanks on the runway 30m from the centreline to the left","C":"Snowbanks on the runway 30m from the centreline to the right","D":"Snowbanks on the runway 300m from the centreline to the left"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO MET 1.3.9.4 Snowtam Format GRF"},{"id":"55629","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which statement is true regarding smoking on the aircraft?","options":{"A":"E-cigarette use is prohibited on board and is considered unruly and disruptive behaviour","B":"Once a lavatory smoke detector has triggered it should be written into the tech log for engineering to reset","C":"If a passenger is caught smoking and complies with crew instructions to stop smoking, a formal warning shall still be issued","D":"If a passenger is caught smoking the Commander shall notify NCC who will request local authorities to meet the aircraft on arrival"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 3.17.6 Smoking and E-cigarette use on board + OMA 8.3.15.2 Smoking in the Cabin/Lavatory"},{"id":"55717","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When flight crew need assistance on the ground from a flight dispatcher which message should be sent?","options":{"A":"GFLASH","B":"AFLASH","C":"XFLASH","D":"Free text message to ATC"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 1.3.2.1.1.2 GFLASH"},{"id":"55811","lastEdit":"22/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"If both IDG and the APU generator are inoperative, a backup generator powers essential airplane equipment. To reduce electrical loading, which systems are inoperative?","options":{"A":"Right HF, Position and other exterior lights (except nose gear landing lights), All non-essential cabin equipment, passenger cabin lighting (except night, galley and cross-aisle lights)","B":"TCAS, SATCOM, Right HF, Centre tank override/jettison pumps, Position and other exterior lights (except nose gear landing lights), All non-essential cabin equipment, Passenger cabin lighting (except night, galley and cross-aisle lights)","C":"TCAS, SATCOM, Right HF, Position and other exterior lights (except nose gear landing lights), All non-essential cabin equipment, passenger cabin lighting (except night, galley and cross-aisle lights)","D":"TCAS, SATCOM, Right HF, Centre VHF, Centre tank override/jettison pumps, Position and other exterior lights (except nose gear landing lights), All non-essential cabin equipment, passenger cabin lighting (except night, galley and cross-aisle lights)"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM 6.20 Backup Generators"},{"id":"55822","lastEdit":"13/02/2025","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding variable speed ops?","options":{"A":"VSOPS accounts for delays and adjusts the cost index to speed up if late by more than 5 minutes or early by more than 15 minutes","B":"VSOPS accounts for delays and adjusts the cost index to speed up if late by more than 3 minutes or early by more than 10 minutes","C":"VSOPS ignores departure delays and adjusts the cost index to speed up if late by more than 10 minutes or early by more than 10 minutes","D":"VSOPS ignores departure delays and adjusts the cost index to speed up if late by more than 5 minutes or early by more than 15 minutes"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.1.8.1.6 EK OFP Decodes (Item 32)"},{"id":"55843","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the conditions for the Airspeed Unreliable memory items?","options":{"A":"Speed/Attitude not consistent with pitch and thrust setting, Airspeed/Mach failure flags, PFD current airspeed amber, An amber line drawn through one or more PFD flight mode annunciations, Blank or fluctuating airspeed display, Variation between Captains and First officers airspeed displays, Radome damage or loss, Overspeed warning, Simultaneous overspeed and stall warnings","B":"Speed/Attitude not consistent with pitch and thrust setting, Airspeed/Mach failure flags, PFD current airspeed amber, Autothrottle disconnection, Blank or fluctuating airspeed display, Variation between Captains and standby airspeed displays, Radome damage or loss, Overspeed warning, Simultaneous overspeed and stall warnings","C":"Aircraft upset, Airspeed failure flags, PFD current airspeed amber, An amber line drawn through one or more PFD flight mode annunciations, Fluctuating airspeed display, Variation between Captains and First officers airspeed displays, Ground proximity warning, Overspeed warning, Simultaneous overspeed and stall warnings","D":"Speed/Attitude not consistent with pitch and thrust setting, Airspeed/Mach failure flags, PFD current airspeed red, An amber line drawn through one or more PFD flight mode annunciations, High vibration, Variation between Captains and First officers airspeed displays, Radome damage or loss, Overspeed warning, Simultaneous overspeed and stall warnings"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Airspeed Unreliable"},{"id":"55935","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"The air turnback arrival page is accessible under which conditions?","options":{"A":"Less than 100 miles from the origin and nearer to the origin than the destination","B":"Less than 200 miles from the origin and nearer to the origin than the destination","C":"Less than 400 miles from the origin and nearer to the origin than the destination","D":"The air turn back arrival page can always be used during the flight"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, FMC Descent and Approach, Approach"},{"id":"55952","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"In the cruise the autopilot fails, what implications does this have for continued flight?","options":{"A":"Autopilot failure has no impact on flight capabilities or restrictions","B":"You must land at the nearest suitable airport as pilot fatigue will become an issue for prolonged flight","C":"If your routing is via the NAT HLA, you will not be accepted at any flight level or altitude","D":"You are no longer RVSM capable and must descend below FL290, the fuel burn will be increased as a result"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, RVSM"},{"id":"55974","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does stall warning consist of?","options":{"A":"Initial buffet and stick shaker","B":"Autothrottle 'wake up' function","C":"Initial buffet, stick shaker and stall warning horn","D":"Pitch envelope protection"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCTM Manoeuvres, Approach to Stall or Stall"},{"id":"56124","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In flight with EICAS ENG SHUTDOWN R displayed and X-BLD above the right N2 indication. How do you restart the engine?","options":{"A":"First select START on R START/IGNITION selector, THEN select RUN on R FUEL CONTROL switch","B":"Select START on R START/IGNITION selector only","C":"Select RUN on R FUEL CONTROL switch only","D":"First select START on L START/IGNITION selector, THEN select RUN on L FUEL CONTROL switch"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Eng In Flight Start L/R"},{"id":"56166","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"both","question":"Alternate fuel calculations include?","options":{"A":"Enough fuel for a missed approach, climb, cruise, descent, approach, landing and enough fuel to hold for 30 minutes in forecast conditions at 1500 feet above alternate aerodrome. Fuel calculations are based on cost index 10 and a minimum nautical track miles of 100","B":"Enough fuel for a missed approach, climb, cruise, descent, approach and landing taking into account the diversion routing and flight levels and altitudes. Fuel calculations are based on cost index 10 and a minimum nautical track miles of 120","C":"Enough fuel for a missed approach, climb, cruise, descent, approach and landing taking into account the diversion routing and flight levels and altitudes. Fuel calculations are based on cost index 0 and a minimum nautical track miles of 60","D":"Enough fuel for a missed approach, climb, cruise, descent, approach, landing and enough fuel to hold for 15 minutes in ISA conditions at 1500 feet above alternate aerodrome. Fuel calculations are based on cost index 0 and a minimum nautical track miles of 80"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.4 Alternate Fuel"},{"id":"56200","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the on time arrival policy?","options":{"A":"STA -10/+0 min","B":"STA -5/+0 min","C":"STA -15/+5 min","D":"STA -10/+3 min"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 1.1.2.2 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP Departure and Arrival Targets, OTP Arrival Target"},{"id":"56305","lastEdit":"07/09/2024","category":"both","question":"Which fuel pumps are used for fuel jettison?","options":{"A":"The main tank jettison pumps operate. If the center tank override/jettison pumps are on, center tank fuel also jettisons","B":"BLANK","C":"Centre tank override/jettison pumps","D":"Left and right main tank jettison pumps only"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Jettison"},{"id":"56464","lastEdit":"20/03/2024","category":"other","question":"At what speed is TAC operational on takeoff?","options":{"A":"65 knots","B":"80 knots","C":"60 knots","D":"70 knots"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Yaw Control, Thrust Asymmetry Compensation."},{"id":"56580","lastEdit":"14/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"The autopilot must not be engaged below what altitude after takeoff?","options":{"A":"200 feet AGL","B":"200 feet AAL","C":"100 feet AGL","D":"50 feet AAL"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Limitations AFM limitations, Autopilot/Flight director system"},{"id":"56685","lastEdit":"13/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which condition causes the EICAS ELEC GEN DRIVE L/R message to display? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Generator drive oil temperature is high","B":"Generator drive oil temperature is high or generator drive oil pressure is low","C":"Generator drive oil pressure is low","D":"Generator control switch is selected off"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, AC Electrical System, AC Electrical System Power Sources, Integrated Drive Generators (The ELEC GEN DRIVE L/R displays for low oil pressure according to the FCOM EICAS messages, however it also disconnects automatically for high oil temperature, causing the same EICAS message)"},{"id":"56723","lastEdit":"20/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"Regarding jet streams in the significant weather chart: at what wind speed does the heavy line, delineating the jet axis, begin or stop?","options":{"A":"100 knots","B":"40 knots","C":"60 knots","D":"80 knots"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO MET 1.3.1.9.5.6 Notations used in flight documentation"},{"id":"56742","lastEdit":"20/12/2023","category":"interview","question":"During the cabin security search an unusual object is found. What should be applied?","options":{"A":"The HOT principle (Hazardous, Object, Transport)","B":"The HOT principle (Hidden, Object, Tampering)","C":"The HOT principle (Hidden, Obvious, Typical)","D":"The HOT principle (High-risk, Observational, Techniques)"},"answer":"C","reference":"OME 10.5.3.9.1 HOT Principle Questions"},{"id":"56766","lastEdit":"10/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which of the following statements is NOT part of the stabilisation criteria?","options":{"A":"Speedbrakes not deployed below 1000 feet AAL","B":"Speed between VREF-5 and VREF+20","C":"Thrust setting appropriate for the aeroplane configuration","D":"Landing gear down and locked by 1000 feet AAL"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.27 Approach Stabilisation"},{"id":"56866","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"What does the Reduced Contingency Procedure (RCF) entail and what are the specific fuel requirements at the decision point?","options":{"A":"The RCF procedure allows for carrying reduced contingency and alternate fuel. At the decision point the aircraft should have the remaining trip fuel to the destination, the contingency fuel (minimum 800 kgs) and final reserve fuel","B":"The RCF procedure allows for carrying reduced contingency and alternate fuel. At the decision point the aircraft should have the remaining trip fuel to the destination, the contingency fuel (minimum 600 kgs) and final reserve fuel","C":"The RCF procedure allows for carrying reduced contingency fuel. At the decision point the aircraft should have the remaining trip fuel to the destination, the contingency fuel (minimum 800 kgs), destination alternate fuel if required, any additional fuel and final reserve fuel","D":"The RCF procedure allows for carrying reduced contingency fuel. At the decision point the aircraft should have remaining the trip fuel to the destination, the contingency fuel (minimum 600 kgs), destination alternate fuel if required, any additional fuel and final reserve fuel"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.2.3 In-flight FuelÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ ManagementÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ During ReducedÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ ContingencyÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ Fuel (RCF)Ã¢â‚¬â€¹ Ã¢â‚¬â€¹Procedure + OMC 10.1.8.1.4 EK-OFP Decodes, Item 48A"},{"id":"56915","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does EICAS APU LIMIT message mean?","options":{"A":"APU has automatically shut down","B":"APU limit has been exceeded","C":"APU is out of fuel","D":"APU pneumatic output limited"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, EICAS Messages, EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"56946","lastEdit":"11/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"With flight directors switches off, what happens when a TOGA switch is pushed shortly after lift-off (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"The thrust derate is removed","B":"The flight directors display","C":"The thrust derate is removed and flight directors display","D":"Nothing"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director System Controls (Section 4 - Flight director switches, off...greater than 80 knots and flaps out of up)"},{"id":"57095","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In terms of dangerous goods - what is a red diamond shape with flame on top and number 2 on the bottom indicate?","options":{"A":"Division 2.1 Flammable gas","B":"Class 3 Flammable liquid","C":"Division 4.2 Spontaneously combustible","D":"Class 4 Flammable solids"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 9.9 Labelling of packages"},{"id":"57128","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When do the no smoking signs illuminate?","options":{"A":"When the selector is in auto and above 10000 feet and both packs operate normally","B":"When the selector is in auto and above 20000 feet","C":"The no smoking signs are permanently illuminated","D":"When the selector is in auto and above 25000 feet"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Lighting Systems, Cabin Signs"},{"id":"57381","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"both","question":"What are standard CAT1 ILS minima?","options":{"A":"100 feet AGL, 300m RVR","B":"50 feet AGL, 75m RVR","C":"200 feet AGL, 550m RVR","D":"200 feet AGL, 800mRVR"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.1 Precision Approaches"},{"id":"57389","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which system supplies trim air to the flight deck?","options":{"A":"The left recirculation system","B":"Both right and left trim air systems","C":"Left trim air system","D":"Right trim air system"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Air Distribution"},{"id":"57525","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the first action flight crew should do after receiving a red bomb threat in flight?","options":{"A":"Maintain contact with EGS via NCC","B":"Make a PA 'Purser to the flight deck'","C":"Follow FCOM/QRH procedures","D":"Notify ATC"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 10.5.4.4.3 Threat to aircraft assessed red in flight"},{"id":"57546","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"During cruise you notice the OVERHEAT ENG R message displayed on EICAS, what has occurred?","options":{"A":"Fire detection in the right engine has failed","B":"An overheat condition in the right engine","C":"A fire condition exists in the right engine","D":"Overheat detection in the right engine has failed"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Overheat L/R"},{"id":"57587","lastEdit":"13/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the primary source of Main DC power during normal flight?","options":{"A":"DC Generators","B":"Transformer Rectifier Units","C":"Main Battery","D":"Permanent Magnet Generators"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, Systems Description, Electrical System, Main DC Electrical System"},{"id":"57628","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When using in flight relief, split duty or burnout how much rest needs to be availed by the operating crew to extend the FDP?","options":{"A":"3 hours","B":"2 hours","C":"4 hours","D":"5 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.7.1.3 Calculation of the extension of FDP. OMA 7.7.1.4 Burnout Policy. OMA 7.7.2 Extension of flying duty period by split duty."},{"id":"57704","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What happens when bulk cargo temperature selector is positioned to high?","options":{"A":"The bleed air system maintains a temperature between 18 and 29 Celsius","B":"The bleed air system maintains a temperature between 18 and 24 Celsius and ventilation fans operate continuously","C":"The bleed air system maintains a temperature between 4 and 10 Celsius and ventilation fans operate continuously","D":"The bleed air system maintains a temperature between 4 and 27 Celsius"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Air Conditioning System, Cargo temperature control"},{"id":"57800","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which windows are heated for both anti-ice and anti-fog?","options":{"A":"Captain's forward window only","B":"All flightdeck windows","C":"Left and right side windows and forward windows","D":"Both forward windows"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, System Description, Flight Deck Windows"},{"id":"57948","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Following an overweight landing what items should be reported in the techlog?","options":{"A":"The G force recorded by the maintenance access terminal","B":"The sink rate at touchdown in vertical speed","C":"The ground speed at touchdown in knots","D":"The actual landing weight"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.3.10 Overweight Landing"},{"id":"57962","lastEdit":"28/03/2024","category":"other","question":"How can the flight crew make a passenger address announcement to all areas of the cabin?","options":{"A":"Select PA on the centre CDU and key a MIC or pressing the dedicated PA button on the centre console","B":"Select MIC to PA and key any microphone, using the flight deck handset to dial any PA area and pushing the push to talk switch, Selecting CAB on the audio control panel and pushing the MIC/INT switch to MIC and dialling in a station in the centre CDU","C":"Pickup the centre console handset and it immediately broadcasts live to the PA","D":"Select PA on the centre CDU and key a MIC"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, Controls and Indicators, Audio Control Panel + Comms, Interphone Systems, Cabin Interphone System"},{"id":"58304","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"Who is the company's ACARS network provider?","options":{"A":"Inmarsat","B":"Iridium","C":"SociÃƒÂ©tÃƒÂ© Internationale de TÃƒÂ©lÃƒÂ©communications AÃƒÂ©ronautiques (SITA)","D":"Aeronautical Radio Incorporated (ARINC)"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 4.1 Communications Service Providers and Networks"},{"id":"58392","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which statement regarding the requirements of how to complete the OFP is correct?","options":{"A":"Fuel checks must be carried out at intervals not greater than 60 minutes","B":"Fuel checks must be carried out at intervals not greater than 30 minutes","C":"Fuel checks must be carried out at intervals not greater than 90 minutes","D":"Fuel checks must be carried out at top of climb and descent"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.7 Flight Procedures, Policy and Procedures for in flight Fuel Management"},{"id":"58433","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"What are the limitations of an inexperienced flight crew member?","options":{"A":"Cannot fly LRV flights or category B airports or category C airports until they have completed 100 hours and 10 sectors within 120 days","B":"Cannot fly LRV flights or commander only take-off/landing restriction airports or category C airports until they have completed 100 hours and 10 sectors within 120 days","C":"Cannot fly LRV flights or commander only take-off/landing restriction airports or category C airports until they have completed 100 hours and 8 sectors within 150 days","D":"Cannot fly LRV flights or category B airports or category C airports until they have completed 100 hours and 8 sectors within 150 days"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 4.1.4 Inexperienced flight crew member"},{"id":"58460","lastEdit":"02/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"After pushback the engineer does not show the steering bypass pin, what is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Taxi carefully, testing the steering before the first turn","B":"Do not taxi and get towed back to stand","C":"Do not taxi until the ground handling agent has confirmed the bypass pin has been removed","D":"Do not taxi and call ground ATC to confirm the pin is removed"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.7 Taxi, item A. Although this is the standard SOP one must also be practical when an engineer has not followed SOP."},{"id":"58481","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What switch resets the autothrottle system and clears the EICAS AUTOTHROTTLE DISC message?","options":{"A":"Master caution switch","B":"Autopilot disconnect switch","C":"Autopilot disengage bar","D":"Autothrottle disconnect switch"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, System Description, Autothrottle System, Autothrottle Disconnect"},{"id":"58584","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What does the EICAS ENG REV LIMITED L message indicate?","options":{"A":"The left engine reverse thrust is limited to ground operation only","B":"The left engine reverser will not deploy or will be limited to idle","C":"The left engine reverser is limited to one hydraulic source","D":"Engine reverse thrust is limited to the left engine only"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, EICAS Messages, EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"58626","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Approaching the North Atlantic crossing you have a dual GPS failure, what is the most likely outcome from negotiations with ATC? (assume original routing is not a PBCS track)","options":{"A":"You can still continue with RNP 4 performance capability. You must fly above or below the NAT HLA as you only have one long range navigation system (LRNS)","B":"You can still continue with RNAV 10 performance capability. You can continue on your normal routing and flight level as you still have two long range navigation system (LRNS)","C":"You can still continue with RNAV 10 performance capability. You must re-route or climb or descend to avoid datalink mandated airspace as you only have one long range navigation system (LRNS)","D":"You can still continue with RNP 4 performance capability. You must re-route or climb or descend to avoid datalink mandated airspace as you only have one long range navigation system (LRNS)"},"answer":"B","reference":"Ref for RNAV 10: Lido 2.3.2 North Atlantic, RAR, General Flight Rules (RNAV 10 or RNP 4 approval required) + Ref for FMC effectively being an LRNS: LIDO R-130 'one navigation system (read as FMC) using inputs from one or more inertial reference system or any other sensor system complying with the NAT HLA requirement' - It is still certified for RNAV 10 with both FMC's using ADIRU only (a single source). This was clarified with the tech pilots by email."},{"id":"58695","lastEdit":"11/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the definition of a DEPO?","options":{"A":"A person who is refused entry by the customs authorities","B":"A person charged with a criminal offence and is wanted by the authorities","C":"It's a person who has been admitted into a country and have had their permits rescinded and are subsequently ordered out of the country","D":"A person who is refused entry by the immigration authorities"},"answer":"C","reference":"OME 10.5.18.2 Aviation Security, Security Measures, Inadmissible, Deportees"},{"id":"58768","lastEdit":"13/12/2023","category":"other","question":"When conducting a pre-takeoff contamination inspection which area of the wing should be inspected as a representative surface?","options":{"A":"From the first engine pylon to the wingtip including the entire chord of the wing, both sides of the aeroplane should be checked as the downwind wing will become contaminated first","B":"From the wing root extending to the first engine pylon including the entire chord of the wing, both sides of the aeroplane should be checked as the downwind wing will become contaminated first","C":"From the first engine pylon to the wingtip including the entire chord of the wing, both sides of the aeroplane should be checked as the upwind wing will become contaminated first","D":"From the wing root extending to the first engine pylon including the entire chord of the wing, both sides of the aeroplane should be checked as the upwind wing will become contaminated first"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3.6.1 PCI Conducted from Inside the Cabin + OMC 10.3.6 Step 5 - Pre Take-off Contamination Inspection"},{"id":"58770","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When is a takeoff alternate required? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"When performance, operational or meteorological conditions preclude a return to the departure aerodrome","B":"When meteorological conditions preclude a return to the departure aerodrome","C":"When the airport is due to close after your departure","D":"A takeoff alternate is always required"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.1.1 Takeoff Alternate Aerodrome"},{"id":"58802","lastEdit":"04/04/2024","category":"other","question":"During moderate or severe turbulence which PA shall be made by the flight crew to secure the cabin?","options":{"A":"Cabin crew take your seats","B":"Cabin crew take your seats now","C":"This is the Captain, Attention crew at stations","D":"This is the Captain, Cabin crew take your seats now"},"answer":"B","reference":"OME 4.3.4.2 Moderate and Severe Turbulence"},{"id":"58806","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When does the holdover time start?","options":{"A":"The holdover time starts the at the beginning of the de-icing procedure","B":"The holdover time starts the at the end of the anti-icing procedure","C":"For a single step procedure the holdover time starts the at the end of the de-icing/anti-icing procedure, for a two step procedure the holdover time starts at the end of the anti-icing procedure","D":"For a single step procedure the holdover time starts the at the beginning of the de-icing/anti-icing procedure, for a two step procedure the holdover time starts at the beginning of the anti-icing procedure"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.3.3.4 Two Step Procedure OMC 10.3.3.3 One Step Procedure"},{"id":"58881","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When does the seatbelt sign automatically illuminate?","options":{"A":"When the seatbelts selector is off and the oxygen masks deploy","B":"When the seatbelts selector is in auto and the aircraft is in turbulence above 1.3g in the last 10 minutes","C":"When the seatbelts selector is in auto and the aircraft is below 5000 feet AAL","D":"When the seatbelts selector is in auto and the aircraft is below 20000 feet"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Lighting Systems, Cabin Signs"},{"id":"59072","lastEdit":"08/03/2024","category":"other","question":"The memory items for Stabilizer are?","options":{"A":"Fuel control switches - cutoff, Do not exceed the current airspeed","B":"Stab cutout switches (both) - cutout, Do not exceed the current airspeed","C":"Stab cutout switches (both) - cutout, Do not reduce below the current airspeed","D":"Stab cutout switches (affected side) - cutout, Do not exceed the current airspeed"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC Stabilizer"},{"id":"59151","lastEdit":"03/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"What does the POS map switch display?","options":{"A":"FMC present position data","B":"Waypoint ETA and altitude","C":"ADIRU, GPS position and VOR raw data radials","D":"Latitude/Longitude data for all waypoints"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, EFIS Control Panels, EFIS Control Panel ND Controls"},{"id":"59171","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following requirements has NOT to be met, to allow qualified crews reducing their takeoff minima to 150 or 125 m respectively?","options":{"A":"High Intensity edge lights are spaced 60 m or less and are in operation","B":"The REIL must be in operation","C":"High intensity runway centerline lights are spaced 15 m or less and are in operation","D":"Low Visibility Procedures are in force"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.2 Takeoff Minima"},{"id":"59189","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"In accordance with company documentation, in which FIRs should medical diversions be specifically avoided?","options":{"A":"Tehran FIR, Tel Aviv FIR","B":"Baghdad FIR, Tripoli FIR","C":"Addis Ababa FIR, Khartoum FIR","D":"Minsk FIR, Rostov FIR"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 12.3.7.8.2 Overflight of Iran/Tehran FIR + SCB for Tel Aviv Overflight"},{"id":"59195","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"Select the true statement about alternate gear extension?","options":{"A":"Landing gear cannot be retracted after alternate extension","B":"The Gear lever has to be down","C":"The landing gear free falls to the down and locked position","D":"Normal hydraulic pressure extends the landing gear"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Landing Gear, Systems description, Landing Gear Operation, Land gear alternate extension"},{"id":"59236","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the limits to flying outside radio navigation aid coverage without GPS?","options":{"A":"8.1 hours since ADIRU alignment, 4.9 hours since last FMC DME/DME update","B":"6.2 hours since ADIRU alignment, 5.9 hours since last FMC DME/DME update","C":"8.4 hours since ADIRU alignment, 5.5 hours since last FMC DME/DME update","D":"7.2 hours since ADIRU alignment, 6.5 hours since last FMC DME/DME update"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, Performance Based Navigation, In Flight Failed or Downgraded Aircraft Equipment - Also note we have no idea if it's 'and' or 'or' for those restrictions, if you have any logic or better reference, let us know"},{"id":"59301","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which switch on the flight deck isolates power to the cabin power window shades?","options":{"A":"GASPER","B":"IFE/PASS SEATS","C":"CABIN/UTILITY","D":"EQUIP COOLING"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM 6.10 Electrical Panel, Item 19"},{"id":"59492","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"If the Pilot-in-Command deems that a crime has been committed on board the aircraft, to whom must they report the case after landing?","options":{"A":"VPNC and EGS","B":"ATC","C":"Local police/State authorities via Emirates Airport Services Manager/CompanyÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s representative","D":"Nearest embassy via the airlineÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s legal department"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 10.3.1 Reporting Requirements"},{"id":"59516","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the supplemental oxygen that must be carried for passengers?","options":{"A":"A supply of oxygen for 10% of the passengers for 10 minutes, or the entire flight time the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 15,000 feet, whichever is greater","B":"A supply of oxygen for 10% of the passengers for the entire flight time the when the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 14,000 feet, but does not exceed 15,000 feet, after the first 10 minutes at these altitudes","C":"A supply of oxygen for 10% of the passengers for the entire flight time the when the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 10,000 feet, but does not exceed 14,000 feet, after the first 30 minutes at these altitudes","D":"A supply of oxygen for 10% of the passengers for the entire flight time the when the cabin pressure altitude exceeds 10,000 feet, but does not exceed 15,000 feet, after the first 30 minutes at these altitudes"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.8.1 Oxygen Requirements"},{"id":"59614","lastEdit":"03/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"During pre-flight, you note that all main and center tank fuel pump switches are OFF, but the left forward pump PRESS light is not displayed. Are these indications correct if the APU is operating?","options":{"A":"No. The right forward PRESS light should also be extinguished","B":"Yes. The left forward PRESS light is extinguished, indicating the APU is on and automatically using that pump AC fuel pump","C":"No. All of the PRESS lights should be extinguished when the fuel pumps are commanded off","D":"Yes. The left forward PRESS light is extinguished, indicating the DC pump is on"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM 12.20 Fuel Pumps"},{"id":"59953","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following is not an example of an ATC requested report that can be armed for automatic downlink to ATC?","options":{"A":"PASSING XXX","B":"MAINTAINING FL330","C":"LEVEL FL330","D":"LEAVING FL330"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, MFD Comms Functions, ATC Reports, Armable Report"},{"id":"59992","lastEdit":"07/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Can we operate aircraft in Tripoli FIR?","options":{"A":"No, the entire FIR is banned for our operations","B":"Only on airway V400 with operational TCAS and Transponder Mode S","C":"Only on airway R778 - above FL300","D":"Yes, the entire FIR is available for our operations"},"answer":"C","reference":"SCB Tripoli FIR"},{"id":"60128","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When is the B777 maximum landing fuel restricted to 12 tonnes for flights less than 2 hours?","options":{"A":"Never","B":"When the destination temperature is below 20C","C":"When the destination temperature is below 10C","D":"Always"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.6.1 Fuel Tankering With Cold Soaked Fuel"},{"id":"60279","lastEdit":"16/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"What defines RVSM Airspace?","options":{"A":"PBCS","B":"Any route between FL290-410 inclusive where separation is reduced to 1000Ã¢â‚¬â„¢","C":"European airspace","D":"NAT airspace"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 11.3 Reduced Vertical Separation Minima"},{"id":"60303","lastEdit":"31/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which trim control is inhibited when the autopilot is engaged?","options":{"A":"Control wheel pitch trim switches","B":"Manual Trim Selector","C":"Alternate pitch trim levers","D":"Rudder trim with TAC enabled"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Pitch Control, Primary Pitch Trim Control"},{"id":"60469","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"The memory items for Fire Engine L/R are:","options":{"A":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - retard until engine indications stay within limits or the thrust lever is at idle","B":"There are no memory items for Fire Engine L/R","C":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - idle, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull, If the Fire Engine message shows - Engine fire switch - Rotate to the stop and hold for 1 second","D":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - idle, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC Fire Engine L/R"},{"id":"60512","lastEdit":"10/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"During preflight you receive the latest weather, EGPF 151250Z 04015KT 1300 R05/0400D -SN M03/M06 Q0990= Which precipitation type and intensity do you use to calculate your holdover times?","options":{"A":"Light Freezing Rain","B":"Light Snow","C":"Moderate Snow","D":"Heavy Snow"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.1.2 Table 48: Snowfall Intensities as a Function of Prevailing Visibility - Note: Use daylight due to the time of 1250z, use visibility not RVR"},{"id":"60628","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"The maximum glideslope for automatic landings is?","options":{"A":"2.5 degrees","B":"3.25 degrees","C":"3.0 degrees","D":"3.5 degrees"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Limitations Autoflight Automatic Landing"},{"id":"60974","lastEdit":"12/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"The APU to pack function can be used at any field elevation and pressure altitude?","options":{"A":"True","B":"BLANK","C":"False","D":"BLANK"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Supplementary Procedures, Air Systems, Air Conditioning Packs, APU to Pack Takeoff (limited to 6900 feet pressure altitude)"},{"id":"61367","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What temperature do the packs maintain after a loss of CACTCS?","options":{"A":"Pack flow rate is modulated to achieve a pack outlet temperature of 15 and 25 Celsius","B":"Bleed air flow rate is modulated to achieve a pack outlet temperature of 5 and 43 Celsius","C":"Pack flow rate is modulated to achieve a pack outlet temperature of 5 and 43 Celsius","D":"Bleed air flow rate is modulated to achieve a pack outlet temperature of 15 and 25 Celsius"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Temperature Control, Operation with a complete loss of cabin temperature controllers"},{"id":"61395","lastEdit":"26/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"With MEL 28-31-03-02 applied - Main Tanks Jettison Pumps - One pump inoperative, which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"Only the centre tank fuel can be jettisoned and at a rate of 1400 kgs/min","B":"Only the centre tank fuel can be jettisoned and at a rate of 2500 kgs/min","C":"Only the centre tank fuel can be jettisoned and at a rate of 1100 kgs/min","D":"With centre tank fuel the jettison rate will be 1800 kgs/min, once the centre tank is empty the remaining main tank can be jettisoned at 700 kgs/min"},"answer":"B","reference":"MEL 28-31-03-02 states the Main tank jettison pump is inoperative on the opposite side, therefore the only remaining jettison pumps are from the centre tank. + QRH NNC FUEL AUTO JETTISON states the jettison rate with centre tank fuel is 2500 kgs/min and without centre tank fuel at 1400 kgs/min."},{"id":"61426","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When is TO/GA armed?","options":{"A":"When flaps are not up or glideslope capture","B":"When flaps are not up or glideslope is armed","C":"Below 1500 feet","D":"When the gear is selected down"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, System Description, Autopilot Flight Director System, AFDS Flight Mode Annunciations"},{"id":"61781","lastEdit":"28/11/2024","category":"other","question":"What can you say about the parking brake if the PARKING BRAKE SET message is NOT displayed?","options":{"A":"It is set because the APU RUNNING message is displayed","B":"The parking brake is not set","C":"It cannot be set because the brake accumulator pressure is 1500 psi","D":"The APU RUNNING message will hide the PARKING BRAKE SET message"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, System Description, Brake System, Parking Brake"},{"id":"61860","lastEdit":"06/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"You're on a flight to Dubai International, you arrive at VUTEB to hold for 1 hour due to congestion, you have 30 minutes of holding fuel with Muscat as your alternate. What conditions must be forecasted in Dubai World Central to re-nominate it as your new alternate?","options":{"A":"Non-precision","B":"CAT III conditions","C":"CAT I conditions","D":"Non-precision plus 200ft/1,000m"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.5 In-flight Replanning Procedure states me must use the planning minima, i.e. for an alternate that is CAT III like OMDW, it requires CAT I conditions. See OMA 8.1.3.3 Pre-Flight Planning Minima."},{"id":"61906","lastEdit":"09/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct about the standard runway lights? (on runways greater than 1800m)","options":{"A":"The centreline lights are alternating yellow and white for the last 900m, except for the last 300m where they are all yellow. The edge lights are red for the last 600m","B":"The centreline lights are alternating red and white for the last 600m, except for the last 200m where they are all red. The edge lights are yellow for the last 500m","C":"The centreline lights are alternating red and white for the last 900m, except for the last 300m where they are all red. The edge lights are yellow for the last 600m","D":"The centreline lights are alternating red and white for the last 900m, except for the last 600m where they are all red. The edge lights are yellow for the last 300m"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO ADR 1.2.1.6 Standard Runway Lighting Systems and Markings"},{"id":"61937","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"During a North Atlantic crossing you are instructed to RESUME NORMAL SPEED, what must ATC be informed of when selecting ECON SPD? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"If the Mach number changes by 0.03 or more then ATC must be notified","B":"If the Mach number changes by 0.02 or more then ATC must be notified","C":"If the Mach number decreases by more than 0.01 or increases by more than 0.02 ATC must be notified","D":"If the Mach number changes by 0.01 or more then ATC must be notified"},"answer":"B","reference":"LIDO 2.3.4.1.2 Flight Operations and Navigation Procedures (see Maintain Assigned Mach) - LIDO Page R-1110 + LIDO 2.3.2.12.8 Application of Mach number technique (R-400)"},{"id":"62015","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How long should a ADIRU switch remain off when manually realigning the ADIRU?","options":{"A":"30 seconds","B":"1 second","C":"24 seconds","D":"45 seconds"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Flight Management Naviation, ADIRU Alignment/Position Update"},{"id":"62034","lastEdit":"23/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"When operating in ice pellet conditions, under what circumstances can anti-icing fluid remain effective after precipitation stops?","options":{"A":"The fluid remains effective for up to 90 minutes from the start of application if precipitation has stopped provided a PCI is carried out within 5 minutes of take-off","B":"The fluid remains effective for up to 60 minutes from the start of application if precipitation has stopped, the holdover time has not been exceeded, and the OAT remains constant or decreases","C":"The fluid remains effective for up to 60 minutes from the start of application if precipitation has stopped provided a PCI is carried out within 5 minutes of take-off","D":"The fluid remains effective for up to 90 minutes from the start of application if precipitation has stopped, the holdover time has not been exceeded, and the OAT remains constant or increases"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.9 Ice Pellets, Small Hail and Hail"},{"id":"62095","lastEdit":"04/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"After pushback a strap is found in a cabin door and needs to be removed. What is the correct procedure?","options":{"A":"Return to stand and once stairs, airbridge or platform are in place open the door to remove the strap","B":"Continue for departure as the strap cannot cause any damage during flight","C":"Return to stand and open the door to remove the strap without any stairs, airbridge or platform connected","D":"Crack open the door without fully opening it to remove the strap whilst away from the stand"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 3.10.6 Cabin Door Normal Operation SOPs"},{"id":"62255","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"In terms of NAT HLA, what does RCP stand for?","options":{"A":"Required Communication Performance","B":"Real-time Cockpit Projections","C":"Radio Communication Post","D":"Route Change Procedure"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 11.2.2 RNP En route comms/nav procedures, Performance based comms and surveillance, RCP"},{"id":"62318","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Select the true statement about alternate gear extension?","options":{"A":"Alternate gear extension uses normal system hydraulic pressure to extend the landing gear","B":"Landing gear may be retracted after alternate extension, if hydraulic pressure is available","C":"After the landing gear is extended the main gear doors retract","D":"The normal landing gear indication is displayed on EICAS"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, Systems description, Landing Gear Operation, Land gear alternate extension."},{"id":"62404","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"During a dual GPS failure, which other system is affected?","options":{"A":"ADS-B","B":"SATCOM","C":"Transponder mode C function","D":"TCAS"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC GPS"},{"id":"62560","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"With EICAS ELEC GEN DRIVE L which statement is true?","options":{"A":"The general drive bus has failed","B":"The EICAS is caused by low oil pressure and the generator drive automatically disconnects","C":"The checklist will lead us to manually disconnect the generator drive","D":"The generator control switch will need cycling off, then on"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC ELEC GEN DRIVE L/R"},{"id":"62661","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following components are part of the fly by wire flight control system?","options":{"A":"AFDCs, PACEs and PCUs","B":"CDUs, ACEs and FMSs","C":"AFDCs, ACEs and PCUs","D":"PFCs and ACEs"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Pilot Controls"},{"id":"62740","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When is the Pitch Limit Indication displayed?","options":{"A":"If airspeed is close to VMO / MMO","B":"When flaps are not up or airspeed is low with flaps up","C":"After takeoff until passing 20000 feet","D":"Only when the flaps are not in the up position"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Primary Flight Display, PFD Attitude Indications"},{"id":"62792","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Why should the cabin temperature selector be set to mid position?","options":{"A":"To allow full temperature range adjustment (18-29) in cabin zones on cabin attendant panel","B":"If prevents pack overheating","C":"It allows cabin attendant to adjust actual temperatures","D":"It turns on pack and air trim system"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Temperature Control"},{"id":"62894","lastEdit":"11/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"When does the Stabilizer position on the pedestal NOT display?","options":{"A":"When the stabilizer signal is not present or invalid","B":"When the left hydraulic system pressure has failed","C":"When the nosewheel pressure switch and the green band disagree","D":"When STAB GREENBAND is displayed on the EICAS"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Flight Controls, Systems Description, Stabilizer Hydraulic Power and non-normal Operation, Stabilizer Position Indication and Green Band"},{"id":"62896","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"How can the FDP be legally extended? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Split duty","B":"Commander's discretion","C":"In-flight relief Split duty Commander's discretion","D":"In-flight relief"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.7.1 Extension of a Flight Duty Period by In-flight Relief + OMA 7.7.2 Extension of a Flying Duty by Split Duty + OMA 7.15 Commander's Discretion to Extend a Flying Duty Period (The actual exam answer is 'all of the above')"},{"id":"63057","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is true regarding the restraint kit?","options":{"A":"The restraint kit is located at the L1 secured locker. It can be used without the Commander's permission but they must be informed immediately","B":"The restraint kit is located under the Purser's jump seat. It can only be used with the Commander's permission","C":"The restraint kit is located under the Purser's jump seat. It can be used without the Commander's permission","D":"The restraint kit is located at the L1 secured locker. It can only be used with the Commander's permission"},"answer":"B","reference":"OME 10.3.7.1 Restraining an Endangering Passenger + OME 10.3.7.6 Restraint Kit"},{"id":"63274","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the on time policy for departure?","options":{"A":"STD -20/+3 min","B":"STD -15/+3min","C":"STD -10/+5 min","D":"STD -10/+3 min"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 1.1.2.1 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP Departure and Arrival Targets, OTP Departure Target"},{"id":"63325","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the max FDP for an LRV flight to an S2 destination? (No waivers or extensions applied)","options":{"A":"Max FDP 20 hours","B":"Max FDP 15 hours","C":"Max FDP 18 hours","D":"Max FDP 22 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.E.5 FDPs"},{"id":"63333","lastEdit":"16/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"What does the PACK MODE R EICAS message indicate?","options":{"A":"The STBY COOLING MODE is inoperative","B":"The pack will operate in the STBY COOLING MODE and The right pack is in the Standby Mode","C":"The airplane is in unfavourable conditions and the pack output temperature is too high","D":"The STBY COOLING MODE has failed"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air Systems, Air conditioning system description, Air conditioning packs, Standby cooling mode"},{"id":"63664","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"Whilst at the gate for boarding at an outstation, a cabin crew member realises she has left her licence in the hotel lobby by mistake. Can they operate?","options":{"A":"No","B":"Yes, the only mandatory documents required at outstation is a passport and company ID card","C":"Yes, with approval from UAE GCAA coordinated via NCC","D":"Yes, with approval from NCC"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.12.2 List of Documents Carried by Crews"},{"id":"63733","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the legal minimum cabin crew requirement based on?","options":{"A":"As required by service delivery","B":"The number of seats fitted to an aircraft","C":"The number of emergency exits","D":"As required by the manufacturer"},"answer":"B","reference":"OME 1.8.1 Minimum Required Cabin Crew Complement"},{"id":"63812","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When are the annunciations, CDU L, C, R, displayed on the ND?","options":{"A":"Navigation source switch in CDU, or dual FMC failure","B":"Only after a single FMC failure","C":"Only if one navigation source switch is selected","D":"When the multifunction display switches have failed"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"63838","lastEdit":"28/03/2024","category":"other","question":"At the planning stage contingency fuel compensates for deviations in?","options":{"A":"Taxi fuel","B":"Zero fuel mass","C":"Takeoff mass","D":"Meteorological conditions"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.3 Contingency Fuel"},{"id":"63885","lastEdit":"11/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding EGPWS?","options":{"A":"The primary function of EGPWS is to provide runway awareness advisories (RAAS), focusing on navigational assistance during approach and landing phases, rather than terrain avoidance","B":"EGPWS advisories are generated based on the aircraft's proximity to terrain features manually entered by the flight crew before each flight","C":"The Smart Landing system is exclusive to GPWS, providing advisories for unstabilized approaches without the need for EGPWS's enhanced terrain database","D":"EGPWS includes a forward-looking terrain avoidance function using a terrain database, whereas GPWS does not"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMD, 2.1.1.6.19 TAWS + More information available online, especially Honeywell EGPWS line maintenance manuals"},{"id":"64129","lastEdit":"17/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"The pressurization system is manually operated by?","options":{"A":"Setting the OUTFLOW VALVE switches to AUTO and holding the FWD OUTFLOW VALVE MANUAL switch to OPEN and holding the AFT OUTFLOW VALVE MANUAL switch to CLOSE","B":"Setting the OUTFLOW VALVE switches to MAN and holding the related OUTFLOW VALVE MANUAL switch to OPEN or CLOSE","C":"Holding the related OUTFLOW VALVE MANUAL switch to OPEN or CLOSE and setting the OUTFLOW VALVE switches to MAN","D":"Setting the OUTFLOW VALVE switches to AUTO and holding the related OUTFLOW VALVE MANUAL switch to OPEN or CLOSE"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization System Manual Operation"},{"id":"64333","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"Which sequence is correct regarding Precision Runway Monitor breakout manoeuvres?","options":{"A":"PF: Verify autopilot is engaged, Set MCP heading and Altitude and engage heading select and FLCH SPD or V/S -1000 FPM. PM: Readback breakout instructions and verify all actions and call out any omissions","B":"PF: Disengage the autopilot and announce Breakout left/right, Climb/descend as instructed (limiting decent rates to -1000 FPM). PM: Switch both flight directors off, set breakout heading and altitude in the MCP","C":"PF: Verify autopilot is engaged, Set MCP heading and Altitude and engage heading select and FLCH SPD or V/S -1000 FPM. PM: Readback breakout instructions and verify actions","D":"PF: Disengage the autopilot and announce Breakout left/right, Climb/descend as instructed (limiting decent rates to -500 FPM). PM: Switch both flight directors off, set breakout heading and altitude in the MCP"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH Operational information, Other Procedures, ILS PRM/RNAV GPS PRM/SOIA"},{"id":"64389","lastEdit":"14/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"When an augmenting flight crew member is on a flight how much time do they log?","options":{"A":"Time in the operating seat","B":"Time in the air","C":"Time from 'blocks off' to 'blocks on'","D":"Time on the flightdeck"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.7.1.3 Calculation of the extension of FDP (see the last paragraph)"},{"id":"64585","lastEdit":"06/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding sterile flight deck on arrival?","options":{"A":"It begins at 20000 AAL and ends when the runway is vacated","B":"It begins at 25000 AAL and ends when the first aeroplane door is opened","C":"It begins at 10000 AAL and ends when the parking brake is set","D":"It begins at 15000 AAL and ends when the engines are shut down"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.1 Sterile Flight Deck"},{"id":"64711","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"You plan an ILS approach to an aerodrome in ISA+30 at sea level. What will be the true altitude passing the FAP altitude of 2000 feet?","options":{"A":"1750 feet","B":"2000 feet","C":"2200 feet","D":"1800 feet"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.4.2 Warm Temperature Altitude Considerations - However you're flying an ILS thus you will be at the correct geometric altitude as per the chart. The altimeter however will read approx 1800 feet passing the FAP."},{"id":"64754","lastEdit":"28/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"During pushback you receive EICAS SMOKE LAVATORY, what is the most likely cause?","options":{"A":"High humidity goods in the cargo hold have triggered the smoke detector in the toilet","B":"Fumigation spray from the cabin crew has triggered the smoke detector","C":"During engine start a power transfer erroneously activated a smoke detector","D":"A passenger is smoking in the toilet"},"answer":"C","reference":"Bulletin EAD-90 R2 Nuisance Visual and Aural Smoke Alarm Annunciations in Lavatories, Crew Rest Compartments and Other Cabin Compartments"},{"id":"64804","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"During the cruise CPDLC stops working, you are due to enter the North Atlantic airspace in 1 hour, what is the most likely outcome when negotiating with ATC?","options":{"A":"The flight will be re-routed via Blue Spruce routes","B":"The flight will be accepted into the North Atlantic","C":"The flight will not be accepted into North Atlantic airspace","D":"The flight will be accepted into the North Atlantic on a tactical basis"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO North Atlantic 2.3.2.13.5 NAT Data Link Mandate Airspace (a few pages beyond this reference, currently in LIDO page R-702, see 'Equipment Failure of either ADS-C or CPDLC systems')"},{"id":"65089","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What does the EICAS WINDOW HEAT message mean?","options":{"A":"Two or more window heats are off","B":"The backup window heat system is inoperative","C":"The windows are using backup heat","D":"A single overheat or fault has occurred"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, EICAS Messages, Anti-Ice Rain System EICAS Messages"},{"id":"65151","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Before engine start on the ground, the right centre tank pump PRESS light is illuminated without the EICAS message FUEL PUMP CENTRE R displayed. Is this condition correct?","options":{"A":"No. The EICAS message is never inhibited","B":"No. The EICAS message will be displayed after a short sensing delay","C":"Yes. Centre tank fuel is not used during engine start and the message is inhibited","D":"Yes. One pump is electrically load shed and the message is inhibited"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Pumps"},{"id":"65242","lastEdit":"20/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which configuration is the go-around gradient calculation assuming?","options":{"A":"One engine inoperative, landing flap, landing gear up","B":"All engines operating, approach flaps, landing gear down","C":"All engines operating, approach flaps, landing gear up","D":"One engine inoperative, flaps 20, gear up"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Performance Dispatch, B777-300ER, Landing, Go-Around Climb Gradient - Configuration states 'Flaps 20, Gear Up'. Above it states 'ENGINE INOP'."},{"id":"65259","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding datalink mandated airspace?","options":{"A":"Datalink mandated airspace is from FL285-430, it is geographically the same as the NAT HLA","B":"Datalink mandated airspace is from FL290-410, it is geographically the same as the NAT HLA","C":"Datalink mandated airspace is from FL290-410, a map of it can be found in the North Atlantic section of Lido","D":"Datalink mandated airspace is from FL285-430, a map of it can be found in the North Atlantic section of Lido"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO 2.3.2.13.5 NAT Data Link Mandate (DLM) Airspace or LIDO page R-684"},{"id":"65389","lastEdit":"09/01/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the recommended pitch when responding to TCAS RA?","options":{"A":"Anywhere inside the RA trapezium","B":"No more than 10 degrees nose up","C":"Anywhere outside the RA trapezium","D":"Along the red line of RA trapezium"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, Controls and Indicators, Traffic Collision Avoidance System, TCAS PFD Vertical Guidance"},{"id":"65478","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which of the following conditions indicate Ice Crystal Icing?","options":{"A":"Blanked or decreasing N1 target, Light to moderate turbulence, Static discharge around the windshield, smell of sulphur or ozone, humidity increase, Increased engine vibration","B":"Blanked or decreasing airspeed, Little or light turbulence, Static discharge around the windshield, smell of sulphur or ozone, increasing pitch angle of attack, engines at the thrust limit","C":"Blanked or decreasing N1, Light to moderate turbulence, Static discharge around the windshield, smell of damp wood, humidity increase, Increased engine vibration","D":"Blanked or increasing N1 target, Moderate to severe turbulence, Static discharge around the wingtips, smell of electrical burning, humidity decrease, Increased airframe vibration"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Anti Ice and Rain, Ice Crystal Icing"},{"id":"65489","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When are pitch trim changes required with the 777 fly by wire system?","options":{"A":"During airspeed changes only","B":"For all configuration changes","C":"When landing gear is extended","D":"When thrust is changed"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, Normal Mode Pitch Control, Primary Pitch Trim Control"},{"id":"65621","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"During flight you receive EICAS SATCOM, does CPDLC still work?","options":{"A":"No, it relies on SATCOM to function correctly","B":"Yes, only the SATCOM voice communication has failed","C":"Yes, it is not affected by SATCOM failure in any region","D":"Yes, but only in areas covered by VHF datalink"},"answer":"D","reference":"MEL 23-15-01B Satellite Communication Systems"},{"id":"65716","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the requirements for a pregnant passenger's medical certificate to be accepted for flight?","options":{"A":"The certificate must mention that the pregnant passenger is fit to fly, the expected date of delivery, and be issued by a doctor or midwife","B":"The certificate must mention the passenger's dietary restrictions","C":"The certificate needs to specify the hospital where the delivery will take place","D":"The certificate should only be issued by a doctor"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 11.11.1.1 Aviation First Aid, Aviation First Aid, Expectant Mothers Guidelines, Pregnant Passengers, Medical Certificate Guidelines"},{"id":"65727","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"interview","question":"When is an external PCI used to allow take-off in cold weather operations?","options":{"A":"When the minimum holdover time has expired, ensuring the minimum holdover time is 20 minutes or more","B":"When the maximum holdover time has expired, ensuring the minimum holdover time is 20 minutes or more","C":"When the minimum holdover time has expired, ensuring the maximum holdover time is 20 minutes or more","D":"When the maximum holdover time has expired, ensuring the maximum holdover time is 20 minutes or more"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3.6 Step 5 Pre-takeoff Contamination Inspection"},{"id":"65826","lastEdit":"18/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"What are some examples of bleed air sources?","options":{"A":"Trim Air","B":"Ground air cart and APU","C":"Packs","D":"Demand Pumps"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Bleed Air System Description, Introduction"},{"id":"65869","lastEdit":"04/02/2024","category":"other","question":"When in LNAV, what is the sequence of steps to turn onto a new heading in heading select mode? (assume non polar ops)","options":{"A":"Heading/track selector - rotate, heading/track select switch - push, heading/track reference switch - push","B":"Heading/track select switch - push, heading/track reference switch - push, heading/track selector - rotate","C":"Heading/track reference switch - push, heading/track select switch - push, heading/track selector - rotate","D":"Heading/track selector - rotate, heading/track reference switch - push, heading/track select switch - push"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Automatic Flight, AFDS, Heading Select"},{"id":"66106","lastEdit":"07/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the max FDP for an LRV flight with 3 flight crew members?","options":{"A":"Max FDP 18 hours","B":"Max FDP 15 hours","C":"Max FDP 20 hours","D":"Max FDP 22 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.E.7 Unforeseen circumstances after reporting time"},{"id":"66274","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"You're cruising over Pakistan or the United Kingdom and you must execute an emergency descent, what course of action should you take?","options":{"A":"Offset 10 miles right or left of centreline","B":"Offset 5 miles right or left of centreline","C":"Maintain airway centreline","D":"Offset 5 miles right of centreline"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO 3.189.12.3 Emergency Descents (UK) + LIDO 3.140.10.4 (Pakistan) (It also says maintain the centreline unless doing so would endanger the aircraft)"},{"id":"66341","lastEdit":"06/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"When in the United Kingdom which clearance releases you from any vertical restrictions on an SID?","options":{"A":"CLIMB FÃ¯Â»Â¿L120","B":"CLIMB VIA SID FÃ¯Â»Â¿L120","C":"CLIMB IMMEDIATELY FL120","D":"CLIMB NÃ¯Â»Â¿OW FÃ¯Â»Â¿L120"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO CRAR, United Kingdom, 3.189.5.2 Level Restrictions"},{"id":"66504","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"When is takeoff bump available?","options":{"A":"Below 2000 feet and between 26 and 41 degrees Celsius","B":"Below 4000 feet and between 30 and 43 degrees Celsius","C":"Below 3000 feet and between 32 and 53 degrees Celsius","D":"Below 2000 feet and between 29 and 45 degrees Celsius"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, FMC Preflight, Preflight Pages 2, Thrust Limit Page"},{"id":"66609","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Without LAND 2 or LAND 3 annunciated, the autopilot must be disengaged below what altitude?","options":{"A":"100 feet AGL","B":"100 feet AAL","C":"200 feet AGL","D":"200 feet AAL"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Limitations AFM limitations, Autopilot/Flight director system"},{"id":"66651","lastEdit":"02/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the minimum number of cabin crew allowed on a B777-300ER and B777-200LR and are exemptions available?","options":{"A":"300ER - 13, 200LR - 12, Yes as long as DSVP-FO authorizes it and a GCAA report is filed","B":"300ER - 10, 200LR - 8, Yes as long as the unattended door is considered inoperative and DSVP-FO authorizes it and a GCAA report is filed","C":"300ER - 12, 200LR - 10, No exemptions are available","D":"300ER - 13, 200LR - 11, Yes as long as the unattended door is considered inoperative and DCP Boeing authorizes it"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 4.3.2 Crew Composition, Cabin Crew Complement, Operation with less than minimum cabin crew complement"},{"id":"66783","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"The memory items for Limit Surge Stall L/R are as follows","options":{"A":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - retard until engine indications stay within limits","B":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - idle","C":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - retard until engine indications stay within limits or the thrust lever is at idle","D":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - retard to midrange position"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Limit Surge Stall"},{"id":"66819","lastEdit":"07/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"Under which conditions are service animals allowed to be transported in the cabin, and how many service dogs are permitted per cabin?","options":{"A":"Service animals are allowed if the Purser informs the Commander, and no more than one service dog is permitted per cabin","B":"Service animals are allowed if the Ground Dispatcher informs the Commander, and no more than one service dog are permitted onboard","C":"Service animals are not allowed onboard under any circumstances","D":"Service animals are allowed if the Crew Duty Manager informs the Commander, and no more than two service dogs are permitted onboard"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.2.2.4.2.1 Service Animals"},{"id":"66891","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"How is the ETOPS distance determined?","options":{"A":"At the two engine cruise speed under still air conditions","B":"At the one engine inoperative cruise speed under forecasted weather conditions","C":"At the two engine cruise speed under forecasted weather conditions","D":"At the one engine inoperative cruise speed under still air conditions"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.5 Extended Range Operation with Two Engine Aeroplanes"},{"id":"67014","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When the landing altitude selector is pulled and rotated what increments do the first and second detent change the selection respectively?","options":{"A":"50 and 500 feet","B":"150 and 500 feet","C":"100 and 500 feet","D":"200 and 500 feet"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air Systems, Controls and Indicators, Pressurization System, Pressurization Panel"},{"id":"67052","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What does the illumination of the Offside Tuning light mean?","options":{"A":"The selected VHF radio is inoperative","B":"The microphone is keyed and transmitting on the selected frequency","C":"You have a call from VPNC","D":"One of the other radio tuning panel is tuning a radio normally tuned by this panel"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, Controls and Indicators, Radio System, Radio Tuning Panel"},{"id":"67166","lastEdit":"23/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"For operations with a cabin crew complement below the regulatory minimum, what considerations and requirements must be met, and which door is ideally blocked to maximise passenger capacity?","options":{"A":"An unattended cabin door must be considered inoperative, the operation must be authorised by DSVP-FO or their designee, a report must be submitted to the UAE GCAA, and blocking the R3/L3 door is usually best to maximise passenger capacity, as detailed in MEL 52-11-01-01A","B":"Unattended doors do not affect operations, the operation must be authorised by the CDM and MPOD, a PSR must be filed","C":"An unattended cabin door must be considered inoperative, the operation must be authorised by DSVP-FO or their designee, a report must be submitted to the UAE GCAA, and blocking the R1 door is usually best to maximise passenger capacity, as detailed in MEL 52-11-01-01A","D":"An unattended cabin door must be considered inoperative, the operation must be authorised by DSVP-FO or their designee, a report must be submitted to the UAE GCAA, and blocking the R4/R5 door is usually best to maximise passenger capacity, as detailed in MEL 52-11-01-01A"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 4.3.2 Operation with Less than Minimum Cabin Crew Complement + MEL 52-11-01-01A Main Entry Doors/Slides - Passengers Carried"},{"id":"67276","lastEdit":"03/09/2024","category":"interview","question":"During pre-flight there is no GPS position on POS INIT 1/3 however the ND states GPS and POS REF 3/3 states two GPS positions, is this normal?","options":{"A":"It is normal, it may not display due to satellite availability, performance or unfavourable geometry","B":"It is not normal, the MMR's have not yet been reset by the engineers from the previous flight with GPS interference","C":"It is normal, it may not display due to GPS spoofing","D":"It is not normal, it is due to GPS jamming at your location"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, FMC Preflight, Preflight Pages - Part 1, Position Initialization Page 1/3, Item 6, GPS Position"},{"id":"67311","lastEdit":"04/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"When can a Commander NOT use the in-flight re-planning procedure?","options":{"A":"Weather deterioration, technical reasons","B":"Holding delays at the destination airport","C":"BLANK","D":"Commercial reasons"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.5 In-flight Replanning Procedure"},{"id":"67363","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What does amber EICAS SATCOM VOICE indicate?","options":{"A":"SATCOM system has failed","B":"A SATCOM voice call has been received and waiting to be answered","C":"SATCOM voice communication has failed","D":"SATCOM voice communication is temporarily lost"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, EICAS Messages, Comms EICAS Alert Messages, SATCOM"},{"id":"67433","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which EICAS display is the result of disconnecting the left generator drive?","options":{"A":"ELEC GEN DRIVE L and ELEC GEN OFF L","B":"ELEC DRIVE L","C":"ELEC DRIVE L and ELEC BUS ISLN L","D":"ELEC BACKUP GEN"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC ELEC GEN DRIVE L/R - An imperfect reference however it confirms ELEC GEN OFF also displays"},{"id":"67446","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the primary source of Standby Power if all normal sources fail?","options":{"A":"APU","B":"Backup generators","C":"Main battery and RAT","D":"APU Battery"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, Systems Description, Standby Electrical System"},{"id":"67466","lastEdit":"18/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"What authority does the CRO have regarding the acceptance of PRMs on flights to and from the USA?","options":{"A":"The CRO can issue fitness to fly certificates","B":"The CRO has the authority to direct Emirates personnel to resolve problems, except the Commander on safety matters","C":"The CRO can override the CommanderÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s decisions on all matters","D":"The CRO can only make recommendations"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.2.2.1.2.10 Acceptance of Persons with Reduced Mobility (PRM) section b"},{"id":"67478","lastEdit":"16/06/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the correct sequence of modifications that flight crew can do to increase RTOW?","options":{"A":"Inform load control to provide a loadsheet with ALT CG, use APU to packs or packs off, use take-off Bump","B":"Use take-off Bump, use APU to packs or packs off, ensure EEC's are in the alternate mode","C":"Use APU to packs or packs off, use take-off Bump","D":"Inform load control to provide a loadsheet with FWD CG, use APU to packs or packs off, use take-off Bump"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH Operational information, OPT Performance Calculations, OPT RTOW Calc Dispatch (Also don't forget to use the full length of the runway first)"},{"id":"67483","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What is a normal Go Around sequence?","options":{"A":"(1) PF: Press TOGA and call 'Go around set thrust, flap 20'. (2) PM Moves flap to 20, calls 'Thrust set'. (3) PF: Reads FMA. (4) PM: 'Positive Climb'. (5) PF: Calls 'Gear up'","B":"(1) PF: Press TOGA and call 'Go around set thrust, flap 20'. (2) PM Moves flap to 20. (3) PF: Reads FMA. (4) PM: Calls 'Thrust set' (5) PM: 'Positive Climb'. (6) PF: Calls 'Gear up'","C":"(1) PF: Press TOGA and call 'Go around flap 20, set thrust'. (2) PM Moves flap to 20, calls 'Thrust set' and moves the gear lever up. (3) PF: Reads FMA. (4) PM: 'Positive Climb'","D":"(1) PF: Press TOGA and call 'Go around flap 20, set thrust'. (2) PM Moves flap to 20, calls 'Thrust set'. (3) PF: Reads FMA. (4) PM: 'Positive Climb'. (5) PF: Calls 'Gear up'"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Go around and missed approach procedure"},{"id":"67601","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the planning minima for a destination alternate if the only approach type is non precision?","options":{"A":"Circling minima plus 200 feet height and plus 1000 metres visibility","B":"Circling minima","C":"Non precision minima plus 200 feet height and plus 1000 metres visibility","D":"Non precision approach minima"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.3 Flight Preparation Instructions, Methods of the Determination of Aerodrome Operating Minima, Pre flight planning minima"},{"id":"67701","lastEdit":"26/12/2024","category":"other","question":"Which airports have specific deviations for volcanic ash operational procedures, and what are the additional mitigations required before deviating from these procedures?","options":{"A":"The airports are MEX, NLU and DPS. Mitigations include confirmation of no ash overhead the airfield, delaying flights to arrive in daylight if feasible, using satellite-based mass concentration data, and obtaining final approval from MPOD","B":"The airports are NLU, MEX, and BOG. Mitigations include confirmation of no ash overhead the airfield, delaying flights to arrive in daylight if feasible, using satellite-based mass concentration data, and obtaining final approval from MPOD","C":"The airports are MEX, BOG and UIO. Mitigations include confirmation of no ash overhead the airfield, delaying flights to arrive in daylight if feasible, using satellite-based mass concentration data, and obtaining final approval from MPOD","D":"The airports are UIO, BOG and DPS. Mitigations include confirmation of no ash overhead the airfield, delaying flights to arrive in daylight if feasible, using satellite-based mass concentration data, and obtaining final approval from MPOD"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.2.2.4.3 - Special Operational Procedures at MEX, NLU and DPS"},{"id":"67834","lastEdit":"06/12/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which of the following is NOT a correct statement regarding fuel remaining on touchdown?","options":{"A":"For Alternate = Final Reserve Fuel","B":"For Destination (committed) = Final Reserve Fuel","C":"For Destination = Alternate + Final Reserve Fuel","D":"For Destination = Alternate Fuel"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.3 Fuel at Touchdown"},{"id":"67869","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In flight the EICAS message FUEL IN CENTER is displayed when?","options":{"A":"When both centre fuel pump switches are off with fuel in the centre tank","B":"When both centre fuel pump switches are on and the tank contains less than 1400 kgs of fuel","C":"When both centre fuel pump switches are off","D":"When both centre fuel pumps detect low pressure"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Pumps, Fuel Pump Operations"},{"id":"67948","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"When using ACARS in ATN B1 airspace which datalink systems are in use?","options":{"A":"VHF datalink, Satcom datalink","B":"VHF datalink","C":"VHF datalink, HF datalink, ADS-B datalink","D":"VHF datalink, HF datalink"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 4.1 Communications Service Providers and Networks"},{"id":"68415","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"After the forward cargo fire arm switch has been armed, what happens when the cargo fire discharge switch is pushed?","options":{"A":"All 5 or 6 bottles discharge into the forward cargo compartment","B":"Two rapid dump bottles discharge into the forward cargo compartment","C":"One of the metered bottles discharges into the forward cargo compartment","D":"All 5 or 6 fire bottles arm and airflow around the cargo compartment is reduced"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, Cargo Compartment Fire Protection, Lower Cargo Compartment Fire Extinguishing"},{"id":"68750","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What are the subsequent approach limitations?","options":{"A":"If three approaches were unsuccessful due to weather the Commander shall divert if able","B":"If three approaches were unsuccessful for any reason the Commander shall divert if able","C":"If two approaches were unsuccessful for any reason the Commander shall divert if able","D":"If two approaches were unsuccessful due to weather the Commander shall divert if able"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.32.2 Subsequent Approaches Following a Missed Approach"},{"id":"69075","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"When a commitment to land at a specific destination aerodrome is made which requirement shall be met?","options":{"A":"The flight must have received an updated weather forecast indicating stable conditions for at least two hours post the expected landing time","B":"There must be no weather condition that could adversely affect the approach and landing","C":"The Commander must be pilot flying for landing","D":"The runway must be uncontaminated, the weather trend in the last two hours must be acceptable to assure a successful landing, and there must be no forecast thunderstorms, fog or high winds"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.2.2 Commit to Land"},{"id":"69079","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"In the cruise you receive the EICAS FUEL SCAVENGE SYS - what are the implications?","options":{"A":"The flight crew should switch on the centre pumps until the centre tank is empty","B":"The aircraft's maximum landing weight will reduce by 1300 kg to compensate for the unusable centre tank fuel","C":"Approximately 1300 kg of fuel will be unusable in the centre tank. The FMC fuel reserves must be increased to account for the unusable fuel","D":"The flight crew shall recycle the jettison and centre pumps to reset the scavenge system"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC FUEL SCAVENGE SYS - There are also implications going forward for any future departures if it isn't fixed, a reduction in MZFW for example - see the MEL"},{"id":"69132","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How do you test the weather radar?","options":{"A":"Push WXR map then TEST switch","B":"Push WX mode then WXR map switches","C":"Push TEST then WXR map switches","D":"Push TEST then DATA map switches"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Weather Radar Panel"},{"id":"69153","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which conditions indicate a volcanic ash encounter?","options":{"A":"Poor radio reception, smoke or dust in the flight deck, acrid odour, multiple engine malfunctions, Saint Elmo's fire, orange glow around the engine inlets","B":"High engine vibration, multiple EEC failures, high exhaust gas temperatures, orange glow around the engine exhausts","C":"Blanked or decreasing N1 target, Light to moderate turbulence, Static discharge around the windshield, smell of sulphur or ozone, humidity increase, Increased engine vibration","D":"An acrid smell, chest constrictions, coughing, headache or eye irritation"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.2.2.4.2 Operational Procedures, Volcanic Ash"},{"id":"69486","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"When is a Pre-Take-off Contamination Inspection (PCI) required? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"When the minimum HOT has expired and precipitation has occurred since the initiation of the anti-icing fluid or in heavy snow conditions or when a cabin crew or passenger suggests a failure of the fluid","B":"When the minimum HOT has expired and precipitation has occurred since the initiation of the anti-icing fluid or in heavy snow conditions or when a positioning flight crew member suggests a failure of the fluid","C":"When the maximum HOT has expired or in heavy snow conditions or when a cabin crew or passenger suggests a failure of the fluid","D":"When the minimum HOT has expired or in heavy snow and ice pellet conditions or when a cabin crew or passenger suggests a failure of the fluid"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.3.6 Aeronautical Info, MET and DIG, Deicing Anti-icing Guide, Step 5, Pre Takeoff Contamination Inspection"},{"id":"69847","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is true regarding maximum taxi speeds?","options":{"A":"Not slippery surfaces: 25 knots, Slippery surfaces: 10 knots, Low visibility operations: 20 knots","B":"Not slippery surfaces: 30 knots, Slippery surfaces: 10 knots, Low visibility operations: 10 knots","C":"Not slippery surfaces: 20 knots, Slippery surfaces: 20 knots, Low visibility operations: 10 knots","D":"Not slippery surfaces: 30 knots, Slippery surfaces: 10 knots, Low visibility operations: 20 knots"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.7 Taxi"},{"id":"69966","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Is defueling allowed with passengers embarking, onboard or disembarking?","options":{"A":"No","B":"Yes, but only with JET A, JET A1, JP8, TS1, RT, TH","C":"Yes","D":"Yes, as long at least two fire trucks are in attendance"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.3 Refuelling or Defuelling when passengers embarking, on board or disembarking + GOM 17.4 Fuelling Operations, Fuelling Operations with Passengers Embarking On Board or Disembarking"},{"id":"70058","lastEdit":"11/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the minimum altitude for a crew change?","options":{"A":"20,000 AGL","B":"10,000 AAL","C":"10,000 AGL","D":"20,000 AAL"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.10.1 Crew members at their stations, Flight crew"},{"id":"70394","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the electrical configuration during Autoland?","options":{"A":"The left transfer bus isolate from the right transfer bus","B":"The left transfer Bus isolate from the right main Bus","C":"The right transfer bus isolates from the right main AC bus","D":"There is no change from normal"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, AC Electrical System, AC Power Distribution"},{"id":"70424","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are the steps to select the Flight Control Synoptic on the right inboard display unit?","options":{"A":"Select R INBD switch, then select DOOR switch","B":"Select R INBD switch, then select FCTL switch","C":"Select L INBD switch, then select FCTL switch","D":"Select LWR CTR switch, then select FCTL switch"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, System Description, Display Selection and Control, Display Selection and Control Examples"},{"id":"70466","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"Fully automatic operation of cabin altitude is NOT possible with one outflow valve operating automatically and the other outflow valve not operating?","options":{"A":"BLANK","B":"BLANK","C":"False","D":"True"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization System Automatic Operation"},{"id":"70610","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the airplane symbol on plan display represent?","options":{"A":"Radio position","B":"FMC position","C":"GPS position","D":"ADIRU position"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology (by deduction that GPS/ADIRU/Radio all have their own symbols, thus FMC position is the only logical choice)"},{"id":"70617","lastEdit":"28/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct about fuel temperature?","options":{"A":"No flight will be dispatched on routes through areas with a SAT of minus 65 or below for a period of more than 90 minutes","B":"No flight is permitted to fly through areas with a SAT of minus 65 or below for a period of more than 90 minutes","C":"No flight will be dispatched on routes through areas with a SAT of minus 65 or below for a period of more than 60 minutes","D":"No flight is permitted to fly through areas with a SAT of minus 65 or below for a period of more than 60 minutes"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 12.3.5.2.1 Pre-flight, Fuel Temperature"},{"id":"70654","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"both","question":"Which law must be applied onboard an EK aircraft outside UAE airspace?","options":{"A":"National law","B":"You must comply with the state laws you are operating in","C":"UAE law","D":"International law"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 1.1.1 Company Regulations and Policies"},{"id":"70718","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Where is your most critical point during ETOPS?","options":{"A":"The critical point is at the ETOPS entry, marking the start of fuel-critical operations","B":"The Critical Equal Time Point (ETP) during an ETOPS flight is typically the last ETP, marking the point with the lowest fuel surplus or highest deficit, as earlier ETPs are met with higher fuel levels","C":"The mid-oceanic point, assuming it to be the furthest from any suitable landing option and critical for fuel calculations","D":"The ETOPS exit point, as it signifies the transition out of the ETOPS area"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.5.2.1 ETOPS Fuel Planning - 'The Critical ETP is the ETP exhibiting the lowest fuel surplus or the highest fuel deficit' - However common sense dictates that if you have multiple ETP's between multiple alternates A, B, C, D for example the ETP between alternates C and D would be the most critical point."},{"id":"70912","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When does the cabin altitude controller change from departure airport elevation to the destination airport elevation?","options":{"A":"400 nmiles from departure or halfway along the route","B":"Within 500 nmiles from destination","C":"Within 5 minutes from top of descent","D":"Within 500 nmiles from destination or halfway along the route"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, FMC Descent and Approach, Approach"},{"id":"71116","lastEdit":"10/05/2024","category":"both","question":"What causes the EICAS STAB GREENBAND message?","options":{"A":"Invalid stabilizer position data","B":"Main gear oleo pressure switch has failed","C":"Nose gear pressure switch disagrees with computed stabilizer green band","D":"Alternate pitch trim levers have failed"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, Controls and Indicators, Pitch and Stabilizer Trim System, Stabilizer Trim System"},{"id":"71239","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the departure target timeline for flightdeck and cabin crew to board the aircraft?","options":{"A":"STD-60 for flight deck, STD-55 for cabin crew","B":"STD-65 for flight deck, STD-60 for cabin crew","C":"STD-60 for flight deck, STD-50 for cabin crew","D":"STD-60 for flight deck, STD-60 for cabin crew"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 1.1.5 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP- Departure Target Timeline (current tech exam still states some old numbers, challenge it if seen)"},{"id":"71366","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is necessary to converse with the mechanic servicing the engines at the engine nacelle?","options":{"A":"You cannot speak with any of the ground crew except at the Nose wheel well","B":"Position the Observer Audio Selector to Captain","C":"Use the CDU and line select Service Interphone","D":"Position the service interphone switch to ON"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, Interphone Comms Systems, Service Interphone System"},{"id":"71392","lastEdit":"15/09/2024","category":"other","question":"What kind of dangerous goods labels are in use?","options":{"A":"Consumer warning labels","B":"Handling and Hazard labels","C":"Hazard labels","D":"Handling labels"},"answer":"B","reference":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations - Section 7, Marking and Labelling, see 7.3 and 7.4 + OME 3.18.3"},{"id":"71539","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"Which modifications shall be made to the ETOPS additional fuel reserves? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Contingency (5%), performance factor the individual aircraft, APU fuel consumption, icing penalty (wing + engine anti-ice at 10,000 feet) + CDL/MEL items as appropriate","B":"Contingency (3%), performance factor the individual aircraft, APU fuel consumption, icing penalty (engine anti-ice at 10,000 feet) + MEL items as appropriate","C":"Contingency (3%), performance factor the fleet, APU inlet door, icing penalty (wing + engine anti-ice at 10,000 feet) + CDL/MEL items as appropriate","D":"Contingency (5%), performance factor the individual aircraft, APU fuel consumption, icing penalty (engine anti-ice at 10,000 feet) + CDL items as appropriate"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.5.2.3 Additional Fuel Reserves"},{"id":"71672","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Is it permitted to take-off in freezing rain?","options":{"A":"No","B":"Yes, but only light or moderate freezing rain","C":"Yes, but only with after using a type II or type IV fluid and a PCI within 5 minutes of take-off","D":"Yes, but only light freezing rain"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.6 Light Freezing Rain/Drizzle"},{"id":"71684","lastEdit":"11/05/2024","category":"other","question":"The flight deck door has a 6 button keypad, along with red, amber and green lights. Which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"When the door is unlocked the green light illuminates","B":"The green light indicates the system is functioning normally","C":"When there is a system failure the red light illuminates","D":"When the correct normal code is entered the amber light illuminates"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 6.2.2.3 B777 Aircraft Type, Flight Deck, Flight Deck Door, Normal Access Procedure"},{"id":"71696","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"The two communication protocols for CPDLC are?","options":{"A":"FANS and ATN","B":"Inmarsat and Iridium","C":"PDC and DCL","D":"ACARS and SATCOM"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 4.4 Communication Navigation and Surveillance/Air Traffic Management Systems, Controller Pilot Data Link Communications."},{"id":"71788","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"The term Polar Operations describes the operation of flights north of which latitude?","options":{"A":"79N","B":"83N","C":"82N","D":"78N"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Operational Information, Polar Ops"},{"id":"72071","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding volcanic ash?","options":{"A":"When operating in day/VMC you can operate above, below and within the ASHTAM area. Operations in visibile/discernible ash is allowed for brief encounters, a tech log entry is required","B":"When operating in day/VMC you can operate above, below and but not within the ASHTAM area. A tech log entry is required for operations near the ASHTAM area","C":"When operating in night/IMC you can operate above, below and within the ASHTAM area. For Ash reported below FL100, keep a minimum of 5000 feet vertical distance when operating below the ASHTAM area","D":"When operating in night/IMC you can operate above, below and but not within the ASHTAM area. For Ash reported above FL100, keep a minimum of 5000 feet vertical distance when operating above or below the ASHTAM area"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.2.2.4.2 Operational Procedures, Volcanic Ash"},{"id":"72304","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the maximum number of millimeters of frost allowed on the underside of the wing?","options":{"A":"2mm","B":"1mm","C":"3mm","D":"3mm due to cold soaked fuel"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.2.4 De-icing and anti-icing on the ground"},{"id":"72338","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding ADS-B requirements in Addis FIR?","options":{"A":"ADS-B must be equipped for flights above FL200","B":"ADS-B must be equipped for flights without ADS-C","C":"There are no ADS-B requirements","D":"ADS-B must be equipped for flights between FL290-FL410"},"answer":"D","reference":"CRAR, Ethiopia, 3.60.5.2 ADS-B Service"},{"id":"72347","lastEdit":"31/12/2023","category":"other","question":"If you adhere to the IATA Dangerous Goods regulations you will?","options":{"A":"Be in compliance with ICAO and National DG Regs","B":"Not comply with ICAO DG regulations","C":"Not comply with DOT DG regulations","D":"Be in violation of National Guidelines"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 9.2 Policy for transport of dangerous goods."},{"id":"72471","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How many quick donning oxygen masks are available in the flight deck?","options":{"A":"One for each operating pilot and one observer mask","B":"One for each operating pilot and three observer masks","C":"One for each crew member","D":"One for each operating pilot"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Oxygen Systems, Passenger Oxygen System"},{"id":"72522","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Any call made on the PA during a state of alert, shall be preceded by the call?","options":{"A":"This is the Commander","B":"This is the Purser","C":"This is the Captain","D":"This is the Captain/First Officer as appropriate"},"answer":"C","reference":"OME 5.4.1 State of Alert"},{"id":"72642","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the source of supplemental heat for the aft and bulk cargo compartment?","options":{"A":"Recirculation fans","B":"Forward equipment cooling exhaust air","C":"Independent bleed heat system","D":"Electric heater"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Cargo Temperature Control System, Cargo Heat System"},{"id":"72847","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which bus operates only on the ground?","options":{"A":"The ground handling bus","B":"The right main transfer bus","C":"The left main AC bus","D":"The ground service bus"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, AC Electrical System, AC Electrical Power Distribution, Ground Handling Bus"},{"id":"72851","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the assumptions for the DARD routings on the OFP? (non Himalayan)","options":{"A":"Terrain is assessed +/-10 nmiles with a clearance of 1000 feet at 300 knots","B":"Terrain is assessed +/-5 nmiles with a clearance of 1000 feet at 320 knots","C":"Terrain is assessed +/-10 nmiles with a clearance of 2000 feet at VMO/MMO","D":"Terrain is assessed +/-5 nmiles with a clearance of 2000 feet at VMO/MMO"},"answer":"D","reference":"RAIG H2.3.2.2 Terrain Clearance"},{"id":"72963","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When calculating holdover times, how should snow grains and snow pellets be treated?","options":{"A":"As ice pellets","B":"As freezing fog","C":"As snow","D":"As freezing rain"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.8 Snow Grains and Snow Pellets"},{"id":"72980","lastEdit":"26/11/2024","category":"tech","question":"Where will you find the list of airport categories?","options":{"A":"OMD","B":"OMC","C":"OME","D":"OMA"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 12 Aerodrome Categorisation Classification and Authorisation and Area Briefings"},{"id":"73193","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"How long is the repair interval of a category B defect?","options":{"A":"3 days (72 hours) including the day of discovery","B":"3 days (72 hours) excluding the day of discovery","C":"Specified Interval (flights, sector, cycles, hours etc)","D":"10 days (240 hours) excluding the day of discovery"},"answer":"B","reference":"MEL Section 2, MEL Preamble 9 Repair Intervals"},{"id":"73266","lastEdit":"30/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding take-offs with 3mm wet snow of contamination?","options":{"A":"Reduced thrust take-off is allowed, the FO can be pilot flying","B":"Reduced thrust take-off is allowed, the Captain must be pilot flying","C":"Reduced thrust take-off is not permitted, the Captain must be pilot flying","D":"Reduced thrust take-off is not permitted, the FO can be pilot flying"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM SP 16 Takeoff - Wet or Contaminated Runway Conditions + QRH, Ops Info, OPT Performance Calculations, OPT Actual Landing Weight Calculation (OPT LANDING ENROUTE) (there is no RWYCC conversion for take-off, but there is for landing) + OMA 5.2.4.4 First Officer Operational Restrictions notes runway condition less than 5 the FO cannot conduct the take-off or landing (RWYCC in this case is 5)"},{"id":"73279","lastEdit":"21/04/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding weather requirements for take-off alternates? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"A take-off alternate can be used if weather reports or forecasts indicate that during a period commencing one hour before and ending one hour after the ETA at the aerodrome the weather conditions will be at or above the applicable landing minima","B":"A take-off alternate can be used if weather reports indicate that during a period commencing one hour before and ending one hour after the ETA at the aerodrome the weather conditions will be at or above the applicable landing minima","C":"A take-off alternate can be used if weather reports indicate that at the time of departure the weather conditions will be at or above the applicable landing minima","D":"A take-off alternate can be used if weather reports or forecasts indicate that at the time of departure the weather conditions will be at or above the applicable landing minima"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.1.1 Takeoff Alternate Aerodrome"},{"id":"73410","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following statements about FMC CDU pages is true?","options":{"A":"Dashes indicate data input is optional","B":"The RTE page title is white when inactive","C":"'ERASE' is used to delete data in a single line","D":"Page titles are magenta when active"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management, Controls and Indicators, Flight Management System, CDU Page Components (see item 6 - dashes)"},{"id":"73441","lastEdit":"15/12/2023","category":"other","question":"You push back and receive EICAS ENG REV LIMITED L. You follow the technical fault resolution process from the QRH, it advises you to contact MCC for advice. They suggest cycling the thrust reverser on the left engine, what is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Ignore their advice and return to stand to apply the MEL maintenance procedure","B":"Ask them to provide the reference in the documentation whereby this will fix the issue before continuing","C":"Ignore their advice and continue for takeoff","D":"Cycle the thrust reverser as suggested"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.6.3 Use of MEL and CDL - 'Flight crews shall not assist in airborne or ground troubleshooting of defects unless such procedures are documented...'"},{"id":"73457","lastEdit":"29/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When in Ice Crystal Icing conditions which indications can be unreliable?","options":{"A":"IAS, TAT, SAT, ECON SPD, LRC","B":"IAS, TAT, SAT, N2, Engine Vibration indicators","C":"TAS, TAT, SAT, N2, Engine Vibration indicators","D":"TAS, TAT, SAT, ECON SPD, LRC"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Ice Crystal Icing"},{"id":"73521","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"What is NOT a First Officer restriction?","options":{"A":"Wet Runways","B":"Any relevant RVR is 500m or less for take-off","C":"Any runway condition code less than 5","D":"Crosswind exceeding 20 knots including gusts"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 5.2.4.4 First Officer Operational Restrictions"},{"id":"73833","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Each segment of the position trend vector on top of the airplane symbol (dashed line) represents the aircraft's position prediction after how many seconds?","options":{"A":"30 seconds","B":"45 seconds","C":"15 seconds","D":"60 seconds"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"74411","lastEdit":"03/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"On final approach with flap 30 set you receive EICAS STABILIZER C as pilot flying in the left hand seat, what is the best decision?","options":{"A":"Complete the stabilizer memory items and execute a missed approach and configure for a flap 20 landing","B":"Continue the approach using the manual trim levers as needed","C":"BLANK","D":"Continue the approach as PF as the FO trim switches may have failed"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC Stabilizer C"},{"id":"74546","lastEdit":"15/05/2024","category":"other","question":"If your minimum holdover time expires, but your maximum holdover time has not expired, what is required?","options":{"A":"Pre-takeoff Contamination Inspection","B":"Critical surface inspection","C":"Post treatment critical surfaces inspection","D":"Pre-takeoff assessment"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.3.1.1 Timeline After Start of Anti-icing"},{"id":"74712","lastEdit":"04/04/2024","category":"other","question":"Which last minute change is not acceptable?","options":{"A":"LMC offload: minus 0 kg, LMC load: 500 kg, LMC total: +500 kg","B":"LMC offload: minus 500 kg, LMC load: 200 kg, LMC total: -300 kg","C":"LMC offload: minus 500 kg, LMC load: 500 kg, LMC total: 0 kg","D":"LMC offload: minus 400 kg, LMC load: 600 kg, LMC total: +100 kg"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.8.6.2 Last Minute Change (LMC)"},{"id":"74899","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How can you power the Ground Handling Bus before shutdown if no external power is available?","options":{"A":"Isolate the left bus tie","B":"Select the ground handling bus on","C":"Start the APU","D":"The bus is powered as long as the right main bus is powered"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, AC Electrical System, AC Electrical Power Distribution, Ground Handling Bus"},{"id":"74900","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which CDU page allows NAVAID INHIBIT?","options":{"A":"NAVAID INHIBIT is not an available function","B":"NAV RADIO","C":"POS REF 3/3","D":"REF NAV DATA"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Flight Management Naviation, Navaid Inhibit or Enable"},{"id":"74975","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What position should the engine anti-ice selectors be in for taxing in icing conditions?","options":{"A":"Auto","B":"On","C":"Off","D":"Norm"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Adverse Weather, Cold Weather Operations, Engine Anti-ice Operation On the Ground"},{"id":"75035","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the departure timeline target for passenger boarding? (not PRM's or Pre-boards)","options":{"A":"STD-35","B":"STD-50","C":"STD-45","D":"STD-40"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 1.1.5 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP- Departure Target Timeline"},{"id":"75182","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"AC power sources are never connected in parallel?","options":{"A":"True","B":"False","C":"BLANK","D":"BLANK"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM 6.20 AC Electrical System Power Sources"},{"id":"75266","lastEdit":"13/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the circling approach minima?","options":{"A":"As per the charted minima","B":"The higher of the charted minima or 5000m visibility","C":"The higher of the charted minima or 3000m visibility","D":"As per the charted minima + 1000m"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.4 In Flight Minima"},{"id":"75459","lastEdit":"30/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding the emergency lights?","options":{"A":"They're powered by batteries and last 15 minutes. They can be selected on from the flight deck or cabin crew panel","B":"They're powered by remote batteries and last 15 minutes. They can be selected on from the flight deck or cabin crew panel, or automatically if AC power fails","C":"They're powered by batteries and last 30 minutes. They can be selected on from the flight deck","D":"They're powered by remote batteries and last 15 minutes. They can be selected on from the flight deck or cabin crew panel, or automatically if DC power fails"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Lighting Systems, Emergency Lighting"},{"id":"75579","lastEdit":"23/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"When can the burnout policy be applied?","options":{"A":"When a CO-NOTAM is issued for a specific pairing or as a last resort when all other extensions have been considered","B":"When a CO-NOTAM is issued for a specific pairing or when VPNC approves burnout due to unexpected delays","C":"Whenever deemed necessary by the Commander","D":"When a CO-NOTAM is issued for a specific pairing only"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.7.1.4 Burnout Policy"},{"id":"75596","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What are the pro's and con's of flap 20 vs flap 30 landing with one engine out?","options":{"A":"Flap 30 has better runway stopping performance, flap 20 has better go around performance. The aircraft can fly level at MLW at flap 30 with one engine inoperative (if required by a level segment)","B":"Flap 20 has better runway stopping performance, flap 30 has better handling and go around performance","C":"Flap 30 has better runway stopping performance, flap 20 has better go around performance. The aircraft cannot fly level at MLW at flap 30 with one engine inoperative (if required by a level segment)","D":"Flap 30 has better handling and stopping performance, flap 20 has better go around performance"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Performance Inflight, 777-300ER GE90-115, Engine Inoperative, Gear Down Inoperative Rate of Climb Available (reference for inability to fly level at MLW) + OPT Calculator for stopping performance and go around performance"},{"id":"75855","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What precautions must be made when using a halon or hafex fire extinguisher?","options":{"A":"Always wear smoke goggles","B":"Always wear fire gloves","C":"Always open the flight deck side windows","D":"Always wear protective breathing equipment"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Emergency Equipment, Fire Extinguishers, Halon and Halon Equivalent Fire Extinguishers"},{"id":"75955","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"How do you disengage approach mode below 1500 feet?","options":{"A":"By pushing the APP switch","B":"Disengaging the autopilot and turning both flight director switches off","C":"By disconnecting the autothrottles","D":"By selecting V/S or FLCH"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director Approach Mode Controls"},{"id":"76066","lastEdit":"16/05/2024","category":"other","question":"What cost index is Maximum Range Cruise? (MRC)","options":{"A":"CI 10","B":"CI Zero","C":"CI 140","D":"CI 180"},"answer":"B","reference":"Boeing 777 Flight Management System, Flight Management, Functions, Performance"},{"id":"76175","lastEdit":"16/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"Where are hydraulic system quantities displayed? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Status page and hydraulic synoptic display","B":"Maintenance access terminal only","C":"Hydraulic synoptic display","D":"Status page"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, Controls and Indicators, Hydraulic System Indications (The real exam correct answer is 'Both A and B' however it has been modified for this question bank to keep answers in a random sequence)"},{"id":"76274","lastEdit":"09/01/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which runway contaminant and depth converts to equivalent slush?","options":{"A":"Wet snow greater than 3mm","B":"Water on top of compacted snow greater than 12.7mm","C":"Compacted snow greater than 5mm","D":"Dry snow greater than 2mm"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH Operational information, OPT Performance Calculations, OPT RTOW Calc Dispatch"},{"id":"76458","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is indicated by an Amber offscale message on ND?","options":{"A":"TCAS has detected a potential traffic threat that is beyond the current selected display range of the ND","B":"TCAS cannot display vertical guidance symbols on the ND","C":"ATC transponder is off","D":"TCAS has failed"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, Controls and Indicators, Traffic Collision Avoidance System, TCAS Traffic and Alert Message Traffic Display"},{"id":"76569","lastEdit":"05/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"The bank angle limit selector is set to 20 degrees and LNAV is engaged, LNAV will maintain a bank angle of less than 20 degrees?","options":{"A":"BLANK","B":"True","C":"BLANK","D":"False"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director Heading Track and Bank Angle Controls"},{"id":"76802","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are the steps to descend in flight path angle?","options":{"A":"Altitude selector - rotate, vertical speed/flight path angle selector - rotate, vertical speed/flight path angle switch - push, vertical speed/flight path angle reference switch - push, verify FMA","B":"Altitude selector - rotate, vertical speed/flight path angle reference switch - push, vertical speed/flight path angle switch - push, verify FMA, vertical speed/flight path angle selector - rotate","C":"Altitude selector - rotate, vertical speed/flight path angle selector - rotate, vertical speed/flight path angle reference switch - push, vertical speed/flight path angle switch - push, verify FMA","D":"Altitude selector - rotate, vertical speed/flight path angle switch - push, vertical speed/flight path angle reference switch - push, verify FMA, vertical speed/flight path angle selector - rotate"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Automatic Flight, AFDS, Flight Path Angle Climb or Descent"},{"id":"77124","lastEdit":"11/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is TERPS, and how does it differ from the ICAO standard PANS-OPS in terms of obstacle clearance criteria?","options":{"A":"TERPS (Terrain Evaluation and Risk Protection Standard) is the ICAO standard for designing instrument flight procedures, used mainly in the USA and Canada, with differences in obstacle clearance, holding speeds, and circling parameters compared to FAA standards","B":"TERPS (Traffic Entry and Routing Procedures Standard) is the ICAO standard for designing instrument flight procedures, used mainly in the USA and Canada, with differences in obstacle clearance, holding speeds, and circling parameters compared to FAA standards","C":"TERPS (Terminal Instrument Procedures) is the FAA standard for designing instrument flight procedures, used mainly in the USA and Canada, with differences in obstacle clearance, holding speeds, and circling parameters compared to ICAO's PANS-OPS","D":"TERPS (Terrain Elevation Reference Planning System) is the FAA standard for designing instrument flight procedures, used mainly in the USA and Canada, with differences in obstacle clearance, holding speeds, and circling parameters compared to ICAO's PANS-OPS"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO 1.4.6.1. Comparison between ICAO PANS-OPS and FAA TERPS"},{"id":"77136","lastEdit":"09/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding automatic landings on the freighter fleet? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"The 777F is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 25 or Flap 30, with both engines operative or one engine inoperative. Overweight automatic landings are not recommended","B":"The 777F is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 25 or Flap 30, with both engines operative or one engine inoperative. Overweight automatic landings are not permitted","C":"The 777F is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 30, with both engines operative or one engine inoperative. Overweight automatic landings are not recommended","D":"The 777F is certified for automatic landings Flap 20 or Flap 30, with both engines operative or one engine inoperative. Overweight automatic landings are not permitted"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM, Limitations, Operating Limitations, Autoflight, AFM Limitations, Automatic Landing + FCTM 6, Overweight Landing, Overweight Autolands Policy"},{"id":"77271","lastEdit":"08/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding heavy snow? (select the most correct)","options":{"A":"The aircraft must receive an undiluted type III or undiluted type IV fluid and a PCI within 5 minutes of takeoff","B":"The aircraft must receive a type II or type III or type IV fluid","C":"The aircraft must receive an undiluted type II or undiluted type IV fluid and a PCI within 5 minutes of takeoff","D":"The aircraft must receive an undiluted type II or undiluted type III or undiluted type IV fluid"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.3.12.2 Takeoff in Heavy Snow Conditions"},{"id":"77306","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Can the landing lights be switched on with the gear retracted?","options":{"A":"Yes, all landing lights","B":"Yes, but only the landing lights located in the wing root and only in dim mode","C":"Yes, but only the lights located in the wing root at full brightness","D":"No"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Lighting Systems, Exterior Lighting. - Nose taxi light inhibited when gear is up (one assumes nose landing light as well), and wing lights are dim when gear is up"},{"id":"77351","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What provides DC power on this airplane?","options":{"A":"DC Backup Generators (PMG's)","B":"Transformer Rectifier Units","C":"Standby Inverters","D":"Transfer Busses"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, DC Electrical System, Main DC Electrical System (Not to be confused with Flight control DC Electrical System which uses the PMG's)"},{"id":"77414","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Above which cabin altitude shall the passengers use oxygen?","options":{"A":"15000 feet","B":"13500 feet","C":"14000 feet","D":"10000 feet"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.8.3 Passengers"},{"id":"77561","lastEdit":"11/05/2024","category":"interview","question":"What does the '1 in 60' rule refer to?","options":{"A":"An approximation stating that for every 60 knots of head or tailwind, a one minute time increase/decrease will occur every hour","B":"An approximation stating that for every 60 nautical miles flown a 1 minute time increase will occur for every degree of error","C":"An approximation stating that for every 60 nautical miles flown a 1 nautical mile deviation of cross track error occurs for each degree of track error","D":"An approximation stating that for every 60 minutes of flight time a 1 minute deviation of cross track error will occur for for each degree of error based on the aircraft's groundspeed"},"answer":"C","reference":"https://skybrary.aero/articles/rules-thumb"},{"id":"77564","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement about the VHF radios is true?","options":{"A":"Only VHF C can be configured for data communication","B":"The data mode can only be changed on the MFD COMM page","C":"VHF C and VHF R can operate in the data mode at the same time","D":"VHF L is configured for voice communication only"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, System Description, Radio Comms Systems, VHF Comm System"},{"id":"77601","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the automatic landing wind limits for a non USA airport?","options":{"A":"Tailwind 15 knots, headwind and crosswind 25 knots","B":"Tailwind 15 knots, headwind and crosswind 20 knots","C":"Tailwind 10 knots, headwind and crosswind 15 knots","D":"Tailwind 10 knots, headwind and crosswind 10 knots"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Limitations AFM limitations, Automatic Landing"},{"id":"77661","lastEdit":"18/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"During cruise you receive a EICAS TCAS. After discussing with VPNC they manage to issue waivers for the remaining FIRs on your route. Do you continue? (TECHNIQUE)","options":{"A":"Continue with an offset of left 5 nautical miles","B":"Continue the flight since VPNC has issued the necessary waivers","C":"No, divert to a suitable airport","D":"Continue if the remaining FIRs are in radar-covered areas with good ATC services"},"answer":"D","reference":"MEL 34-45-01 Traffic Collision and Avoidance System (not applicable in flight, but just for info) - This question keeps re-occurring at interview, there is an argument to continue also with the waivers as the transponder is still working and therefore the other aircraft's TCAS will still work - it all depends how you explain the situation at interview. Apparently it's unlikely in reality you'd actually get any waivers from any FIR's."},{"id":"77826","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"During flight you receive EICAS GPS, does CPDLC and SATCOM still work?","options":{"A":"Yes","B":"BLANK","C":"BLANK","D":"No"},"answer":"A","reference":"SATCOM is available after the FMC receives an inertial position input during pre-flight and once the ADIRU has aligned - No direct text reference, but works in practice. CPDLC also still works as it's based on VHF datalink or SATCOM datalink - as evidenced by OMC 4.1 Communications Service Providers and Networks (CSP) - If you can improve this reference feel free to assist"},{"id":"77912","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"How do you know if your North Atlantic routing is PBCS?","options":{"A":"Any level between FL350-FL390 in the NAT HLA requires PBCS approval","B":"The PBCS tracks are identified in Remark #3 of the NAT OTS track message","C":"A list of the published PBCS tracks is in the OMC","D":"A query must be made to ATC or dispatch"},"answer":"B","reference":"LIDO 2.3.2.12.4.1 Overview (a few pages deep) or LIDO R-360 (bottom of the page) - Quote 'All PBCS tracks and fÃ¯Â»Â¿light levels are unÃ¯Â»Â¿iquely idenÃ¯Â»Â¿tÃ¯Â»Â¿ifÃ¯Â»Â¿ied in 'Remark 3' of tÃ¯Â»Â¿he OTS Track Message'"},{"id":"78163","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is true about cost index?","options":{"A":"The ECON speed is NOT based on the cost index","B":"LRC speed may be obtained by entering a cost index of 0","C":"Larger values decrease ECON speed","D":"Larger values increase ECON speed"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Flight Management System Operation, Terminology"},{"id":"78194","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the pressurization system target for landing in automatic mode?","options":{"A":"Slightly below FMC field altitude to ensure a positive pressure for touchdown","B":"FMC field altitude to ensure a positive pressure for touchdown","C":"Slightly above FMC field altitude to ensure a negative pressure for touchdown","D":"Internal rate schedule"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization with Automatic Operation"},{"id":"78498","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"In terms of NAT HLA, what does RSP stand for?","options":{"A":"Required Surveillance Performance","B":"Remote Sensing Package","C":"Regional Sector Plan","D":"Route Sync Point"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 11.1.2 RNP En route comms/nav procedures, Performance based comms and surveillance, RSP"},{"id":"78507","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What causes the CDU-L source status to display on ND?","options":{"A":"Pending route modifications using CDU L","B":"ADIRU failure","C":"Left NAV source switch in CDU","D":"A single CDU failure"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"78530","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"What action is required for EICAS DOOR FWD CARGO caution?","options":{"A":"Cabin pressure differential must be reduced to minimize risk of door separation","B":"No action required if pressurization is normal","C":"No action required","D":"Cabin pressure differential must be increased"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC DOOR FWD CARGO"},{"id":"78789","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which packing group represents the lowest degree of danger?","options":{"A":"Packing group II","B":"Packing group I","C":"Packing group III","D":"Packing Group IV"},"answer":"C","reference":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations - Appendix A - Glossary - Packing Groups"},{"id":"78816","lastEdit":"17/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What are the indications given for an excessive glideslope deviation and under what conditions?","options":{"A":"Any time deviation exceeds 1 dot","B":"The scale turns amber and the pointer flashes at low radio altitudes with the autopilot or flight director engaged","C":"The scale remains magenta and the pointer flashes at radio altitudes below 800 feet","D":"Amber scale flashing with an automated aural Ã¢â‚¬Å“Localizer LocalizerÃ¢â‚¬â€¢"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Primary Flight Display, PFD Instrument Landing System Indications"},{"id":"78849","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"other","question":"EKCH 12301027 04L 3/3/3 100/100/100 03/03/03 DRY SNOW/DRY SNOW/DRY SNOW RWY 04L SLIPPERY PORTIONS ON RWY. RWY 04L DOWNGRADED. Which runway condition selection will you make for landing in the OPT?","options":{"A":"Medium","B":"Good","C":"Good to medium","D":"Medium to poor"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.6.2 General"},{"id":"78854","lastEdit":"07/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What does cyan colour indicate in the electronic checklist?","options":{"A":"The step must be reset","B":"The steps are not applicable","C":"The step was performed wrong","D":"The step must be repeated"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Electronic Checklist Description, Checklist Line Items, Open Loop Conditional Line Items"},{"id":"79003","lastEdit":"20/12/2023","category":"other","question":"In the approach stabilisation criteria, at what altitude must the checklist be completed and the speed between VREF and VAPP + 10 knots and the thrust setting appropriate for the aeroplane configuration?","options":{"A":"1000 feet above aerodrome elevation","B":"500 feet above aerodrome elevation","C":"500 feet above runway threshold elevation","D":"1000 feet above runway threshold elevation"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.27 Approach Stabilisation"},{"id":"79072","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What action should you take if the fire switch remains locked after a fire is detected?","options":{"A":"Pull the fire switch to override the lock","B":"Wait until the fire light extinguishes","C":"Rotate the fire switch","D":"Push the fire override switch, then pull the fire switch"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, Controls and Indicators, Engine Fire Protection, Engine Fire Panel (Item 4)"},{"id":"79543","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What does the MAN position on the flight deck temperature control do?","options":{"A":"It removes control at the cabin attendant panel","B":"It causes the packs to provide air at an average mid temperature range","C":"It allows the trim air valve to operate manually","D":"It removes power from the trim air system"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Temperature Control"},{"id":"79589","lastEdit":"24/01/2024","category":"both","question":"Which statement is correct regarding runway condition code downgrades?","options":{"A":"An airport operator can downgrade a runway condition code from the initial PCN value if the pavement condition has deteriorated below acceptable levels","B":"An aircraft operator can downgrade a runway condition code (RWYCC) if a friction measurement, AIREP or other observations indicate that the deceleration or lateral control capability is worse than the RWYCC that was initially determined by runway surface observations","C":"An aircraft operator can downgrade a runway condition code from the initial PCN value if the pavement condition has deteriorated below acceptable levels","D":"An airport operator can downgrade a runway condition code (RWYCC) if a friction measurement, AIREP or other observations indicate that the deceleration or lateral control capability is worse than the RWYCC that was initially determined by runway surface observations"},"answer":"D","reference":"Lido Met 1.3.9.3 Runway Condition Assessment Matrix (see Downgrading the RWYCC) - Lido page 1330"},{"id":"79601","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which aircraft system is not to be used in an aircraft hangar?","options":{"A":"Weather radar","B":"HF radios","C":"Refuelling","D":"Satcom"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Limitations Autoflight Non AFM Operational Information"},{"id":"79712","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does an amber EGT box or amber digital readout or amber pointer indicate?","options":{"A":"Normal range","B":"Exceeding maximum limit","C":"Below Normal","D":"Caution range"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Indications, Normal Display Format"},{"id":"80085","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the level of urgency for a time critical warning?","options":{"A":"A time critical warning requires crew awareness and may require that crew action be accomplished as time permits","B":"A time critical warning requires immediate crew awareness and may require that crew action be performed in a timely manner","C":"A time critical warning is a crew reminder of the current state of manually or automatically configured airplane systems","D":"A time critical warning requires immediate crew awareness and an immediate response and is usually associated with flight path control"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, System Description, EICAS, Crew Alerting and EICAS Message Design Philosophy"},{"id":"80109","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct about frost?","options":{"A":"No permissible amount of frost is acceptable","B":"A light coating of frost is permissible on top of the fuselage and up to 3mm below the wing","C":"A light coating of frost is permissible on top of the fuselage and up to 3mm below the wing due to cold soaked fuel","D":"Up to 3mm is permissible on top of the fuselage and up to 3mm below the wing"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.2 Ground Handling Instructions, De-icing and Anti-icing on the Ground"},{"id":"80139","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the DET FIRE ENG R EICAS message indicate?","options":{"A":"The right engine fire bottle squibs are inoperative","B":"A fire has been detected in the right engine","C":"Fire detection for this engine is no longer available","D":"The fire detection system has automatically reconfigured to single loop operation"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, Engine Fire Protection, Engine Fire and Overheat Protection"},{"id":"80319","lastEdit":"05/06/2024","category":"other","question":"For which fluid types is a Pre-takeoff Contamination Inspection allowed?","options":{"A":"II, IV only","B":"II, III, IV only","C":"I, II, III, IV","D":"III, IV only"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3.6. Step 5 - Pre- Takeoff Contamination Inspection (PCI): Only to be applied to Types II, III, IV anti- icing fluids (in Bold)."},{"id":"80352","lastEdit":"04/08/2024","category":"other","question":"During a flight over South Sudan, under the South Sudan Contingency Plan, what is the minimum flight level for dispatch, and what procedures must be followed regarding ADS-B, IFBP, and in-flight rest?","options":{"A":"The minimum flight level for dispatch over South Sudan is FL320. ADS-B must be operational, the IFBP on 126.9 MHz must be followed, and controlled rest is allowed during the overflight","B":"The minimum flight level for dispatch over South Sudan is FL320. ADS-B must be equipped, the IFBP on 121.5 MHz must be followed, and no controlled rest is allowed during the overflight","C":"The minimum flight level for dispatch over South Sudan is FL300. ADS-B must be equipped, the IFBP on 121.5 MHz must be followed, and controlled rest is allowed during the overflight","D":"The minimum flight level for dispatch over South Sudan is FL300. ADS-B must be operational, the IFBP on 126.9 MHz must be followed, and no controlled rest is allowed during the overflight"},"answer":"D","reference":"SCB - Khartoum UIR - South Sudan Contingency Plan"},{"id":"80373","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What do the colours of the two cabin temperature displayed on air synoptic represent?","options":{"A":"Cyan is target temperature, magenta is actual temperature","B":"Magenta is target temperature, white is actual temperature","C":"Magenta is target temperature, cyan is actual temperature","D":"White is target temperature, magenta is actual temperature"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Air Synoptic Display"},{"id":"80415","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"How much distance does an autoland add to your landing distance requirement?","options":{"A":"300m","B":"400m","C":"200m","D":"500m"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH, Performance Inflight, 777 Model, Advisory Information, Normal Configuration Landing Distance. See notes below table: 'For autoland, increase reference distance by 400m'"},{"id":"80708","lastEdit":"03/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which North Atlantic FIR has failed to implement Oceanic Clearance Removal?","options":{"A":"Shanwick","B":"Santa Maria","C":"Gander","D":"Bodo"},"answer":"A","reference":"Network Report 2412 V2 (29NOV2024)"},{"id":"80909","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"How many minutes before STD should we switch from GPU to APU?","options":{"A":"20","B":"30","C":"25","D":"40"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 1.1.5 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP- Departure Target Timeline"},{"id":"80945","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which of the following data values does not provide crew feedback by turning green when you comply with ATC uplink message?","options":{"A":"Barometer setting","B":"VHF frequency","C":"MCP HEADING","D":"VOR frequency"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, MFD Comms Functions, ATC Datalink, Crew Feedback"},{"id":"81018","lastEdit":"10/11/2023","category":"other","question":"For approach stabilisation when must the wings be level? (excluding charted approach procedures or specifically authorized by co-notam or CCI)","options":{"A":"300 feet AAL","B":"400 feet AAL","C":"200 feet AAL","D":"500 feet AAL"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.27 Approach Stabilisation"},{"id":"81026","lastEdit":"28/04/2024","category":"other","question":"What does NMATE or RMATE stand for?","options":{"A":"Non-Normal Recognition, Maintain Aircraft Control, Analyze the Situation, Take the Proper Action, Evaluate the need to land","B":"Non-Normal Recognition, Maintain Aircraft Control, Assess the need to land, Troubleshoot, Evaluate the need to land at the nearest suitable airport","C":"Navigate, Maintain Awareness, Activate Automation, Track, Evaluate the need to land","D":"Non-Normal Recognition, Maintain Aircraft Control, Assess the need to land, Take the Proper Action, Evaluate"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non-Normal Checklists, Non-normal Situation Guidelines Overview"},{"id":"81066","lastEdit":"25/06/2024","category":"other","question":"What are the conditions for the Dual Engine Fail/Stall memory items?","options":{"A":"Engine speed is not at the commanded position.","B":"Engine speed for both engines is below idle.","C":"Engine exhaust gas temperature is below 350 degrees Celsius.","D":"Engine indications are abnormal."},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH Dual Engine Fail L/R"},{"id":"81085","lastEdit":"28/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What differentiates freezing fog from fog?","options":{"A":"If the wind chill brings the effective temperature below 0 Celsius","B":"Temperatures less than 10 Celsius","C":"Nothing, they're the same","D":"Negative temperatures, typically in the range of -0 Celsius to -20 Celsius"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO ABB 1.8.2.6 F - Freezing Fog"},{"id":"81246","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"With LOC and G/S ARMED, which is true in order to capture the localizer?","options":{"A":"Aircraft track must be within 120 degrees of the localizer course","B":"Aircraft heading must be within 120 degrees of the localizer course","C":"Aircraft heading must be within 90 degrees of the localizer course","D":"Aircraft track must be within 90 degrees of the localizer course"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director Approach Mode Controls"},{"id":"81397","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"For ETOPS pre-flight planning minima, what additions need to be made to the approach RVR/Visibility and DA/H?","options":{"A":"For CAT I, II, III: RVR + 1000m and + 300 feet DA/H. For Non Precision/APV: RVR/Visibility + 2000m and MDA/H + 500","B":"For CAT I, II, III: RVR + 500m and DA/H + 200 feet . For Non Precision/APV: RVR/Visibility + 1000m and MDA/H + 400","C":"For CAT I, II, III: RVR + 1000m and + 200 feet DA/H. For Non Precision/APV: RVR/Visibility + 2000m and MDA/H + 400","D":"For CAT I, II, III: RVR + 800m and DA/H + 200 feet. For Non Precision/APV: RVR/Visibility + 1500m and MDA/H + 400"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.5.4.1 Pre Flight Planning Minima"},{"id":"81641","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct about the secondary flight control mode?","options":{"A":"Thrust Asymmetry Compensation is not available","B":"Autopilot is available","C":"Thrust Asymmetry Compensation is available","D":"Autospeed brakes are available"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Primary Flight Control System Modes, Flight Control System Secondary Modes"},{"id":"81712","lastEdit":"02/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the operational significance of the airspace above Newcastle?","options":{"A":"The airspace is class F uncontrolled and a limited ATC service will be provided","B":"The airspace is class D uncontrolled and a limited ATC service will be provided","C":"The airspace is class E uncontrolled and a limited ATC service will be provided","D":"The airspace is class G - uncontrolled and a limited ATC service will be provided"},"answer":"D","reference":"Lido mPilot app - airspace above EGNT + CRAR for United Kingdom under deconfliction service (Can we improve this question? Does anyone have a better understanding of how this question unfolds at interview?)"},{"id":"81790","lastEdit":"08/01/2024","category":"other","question":"When taking in flight rest in a first class suite how much FDP extension can be applied (non LRV)?","options":{"A":"FDP extension is equal to one third of the rest taken. Max FDP 15 hours","B":"FDP extension is equal to half of the rest taken. Max FDP 15 hours","C":"FDP extension is equal to half of the rest taken. Max FDP 18 hours","D":"FDP extension is equal to one third of the rest taken. Max FDP 18 hours"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.7.1.3 Calculation of the extension of FDP"},{"id":"81791","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"other","question":"When taking rest in a bunk how much FDP extension can be applied on a non LRV flight?","options":{"A":"FDP extension is equal to half of the rest taken. Max FDP 15 hours","B":"FDP extension is equal to one third of the rest taken. Max FDP 18 hours","C":"FDP extension is equal to half of the rest taken. Max FDP 18 hours","D":"FDP extension is equal to one third of the rest taken. Max FDP 15 hours"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.7.1.3 Calculation of the extension of FDP"},{"id":"81792","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"When taking in flight rest in a seat how much FDP extension can be applied?","options":{"A":"FDP extension is equal to one third of the rest taken. Max FDP 18 hours","B":"FDP extension is equal to half of the rest taken. Max FDP 15 hours","C":"FDP extension is equal to half of the rest taken. Max FDP 18 hours","D":"FDP extension is equal to one third of the rest taken. Max FDP 15 hours"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 7.7.1.3 Calculation of the extension of FDP"},{"id":"81793","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"If a person onboard has a non infectious disease how is the commander expected to report it on arrival?","options":{"A":"Verbally to Ground Staff","B":"The aerodrome medical or health authority","C":"On the appropriate part of the General Declaration","D":"Through ACARS to GMS"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 6.5 Crew Health Precautions, International Health Regulations"},{"id":"81801","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the maximum takeoff and landing tailwind component?","options":{"A":"5 knots","B":"15 knots","C":"20 knots","D":"10 knots"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Limitations Airplane General"},{"id":"81864","lastEdit":"25/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is correct regarding turbulence briefing requirements?","options":{"A":"The Flight Crew should inform the Cabin Crew about turbulence severity only, leaving the decision on cabin service levels, including the serving of hot beverages, to the discretion of individual cabin crew members","B":"When briefing the Cabin Crew about expected turbulence, the Flight Crew must communicate the anticipated level of turbulence, its duration, the time available to secure the cabin and the level of cabin service","C":"It is the Purser's role to infer the appropriate level of cabin service based on information about the flight's conditions provided by the Flight Crew, without specific advisories on turbulence or service adjustments","D":"The Flight Crew must brief the Cabin Crew on the expected level and areas of turbulence, its duration, and the time available to secure the cabin. They should also specify cabin service adjustments and inform the passengers via the public address system"},"answer":"B","reference":"OME 4.3.4.1 Light Turbulence + OME 4.3.1 Turbulence, Pre-flight"},{"id":"81894","lastEdit":"10/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is correct regarding alcohol?","options":{"A":"Crew members shall not consume alcohol in any form within 10 hours of pickup time, until after the end of the assigned duty","B":"Crew members shall not consume alcohol in any form within 12 hours of pickup time, until after the end of the assigned duty","C":"Crew members shall not consume alcohol in any form within 12 hours of commencing any duty, until after the end of the assigned duty","D":"Crew members shall not consume alcohol in any form within 10 hours of commencing any duty, until after the end of the assigned duty"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 6.1.1 Alcohol and Substance Abuse"},{"id":"81964","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is true about supplying fuel to operate the APU prior to establishing AC power?","options":{"A":"The APU will operate without a fuel pump","B":"The center tank has a DC fuel pump to operate the APU","C":"The APU cannot operate because there is no fuel pressure","D":"The left main tank has a DC fuel pump to operate the APU"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, APU Fuel Feed"},{"id":"82007","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"other","question":"How long is a daily maintenance check valid?","options":{"A":"48 hours starting on midnight on the next UTC day","B":"48 hours from the time the engineer signs the tech log","C":"24 hours starting on midnight on the next UTC day","D":"24 hours from the time the engineer signs the tech log"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.11.2.1 Stations with an Authorised Engineer"},{"id":"82337","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When is the B777 maximum landing fuel restricted to 12 tonnes for flights between 2 and 4 hours with precipitation forecasted?","options":{"A":"When the destination temperature is above 20C","B":"When the destination temperature is below 20C","C":"When the destination temperature is below 10C","D":"When the destination temperature is above 15C"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.6.1 Fuel Tankering With Cold Soaked Fuel"},{"id":"82364","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"Until which point are status messages applicable for use in the MEL before departure?","options":{"A":"Until the aircraft acceptance in the technical log","B":"The point at which the pilot physically begins to apply power to initiate the takeoff","C":"Until engine start","D":"Until pushback"},"answer":"C","reference":"MEL Section 2, MEL Preamble 3.1 Consideration for Dispatch + QRH Operational Information, General, Technical Fault Resolution Process, first flowchart box - \"Status message (before engine start)\""},{"id":"82378","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"How many minutes before STD should the Preliminary Loadsheet arrive?","options":{"A":"35","B":"40","C":"20","D":"45"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 1.1.5 Company Procedures, On Time Performance, OTP- Departure Target Timeline"},{"id":"82435","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When does the ground crew horn sound?","options":{"A":"Before engine starting","B":"When forward equipment cooling is inoperative","C":"When hydraulics are pressurized","D":"In case of an APU fire"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air Conditioning System Description, Equipment Cooling, Equipment Ventilation, Lavatory and Galley Ventilation."},{"id":"82571","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"What times are space weather issued?","options":{"A":"0430, 1030, 1630, 2230 UTC","B":"0030 and 1230 UTC","C":"0000 and 1200 UTC","D":"0600 and 1800 UTC"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.5.1 Space Weather Monitoring and Alerting"},{"id":"82657","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When is the B777 maximum landing fuel restricted to 12 tonnes for flights between 2 and 4 hours?","options":{"A":"When the destination temperature is above 20C","B":"When the destination temperature is below 15C with haze forecasted","C":"When the destination temperature is below 10C with no precipitation or condensation forecasted","D":"When the destination temperature is below 20C with no forecasted precipitation"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.6.1 Fuel Tankering With Cold Soaked Fuel"},{"id":"82705","lastEdit":"05/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"The Commander shall not commence a flight unless they are satisfied that: (Select the statement which is NOT true)","options":{"A":"The aeroplane is airworthy","B":"The aeroplane configuration is in accordance with the CDL","C":"The aeroplane has at least 21 units of oil per engine","D":"The load is properly distributed and safely secured"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1 Flight Preparation Instructions"},{"id":"82706","lastEdit":"05/04/2024","category":"both","question":"What should cabin crew do after hearing 'This is the captain, purser to the flightdeck'?","options":{"A":"Return to your allocated station and await further communication","B":"Clear the cabin of all service carts, return to their allocated station, check emergency equipment is serviceable","C":"Clear the cabin of all service carts, return to their allocated station, review emergency SOP's and await further communication","D":"Clear the cabin of all service carts, get to the nearest available seat, prepare mentally for a potential emergency"},"answer":"C","reference":"OME 5.5.6 Cabin Crew Action upon Hearing the Flight Crew Command - I suspect the actual tech exam states 'review OME' rather than the correct answer which is 'review emergency SOP's'"},{"id":"82783","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"For an aircraft to fly NAT HLA PBCS route what navigational performance is required?","options":{"A":"RNAV 5","B":"RNAV 10","C":"RNP 10","D":"RNP 4"},"answer":"D","reference":"Lido 2.3.2.12.4.2 North Atlantic, RAR, Separation Rules, PBCS Separation Minima, Operator/Aircraft Eligibility (Page R-350, see table)"},{"id":"82816","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the automatic landing wind limits for a USA airport?","options":{"A":"Tailwind 15 knots, headwind and crosswind 20 knots","B":"Tailwind 15 knots, headwind and crosswind 25 knots","C":"Headwind 15 knots, tailwind and crosswind 10 knots","D":"Headwind 25 knots, tailwind and crosswind 15 knots"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Operational information, Low Visibility Operation, Approach and Landing"},{"id":"82940","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the planned ETOPS diversion speeds?","options":{"A":"1D - 250 knots, 1E - LRC, 2D - 250 knots","B":"1D - 300 knots, 1E - 280 knots, 2D - 300 knots","C":"1D - 300 knots, 1E - LRC, 2D - LRC","D":"1D - 250 knots, 1E - MRC, 2D - LRC"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.5.1 Decode OFP ETOPS"},{"id":"82999","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"other","question":"Which levers and switches require a verbal 'confirm' step before action is taken?","options":{"A":"Engine fire switches, APU fire switch, fuel jettison switches","B":"Engine fire switches, APU fire switch, ram air turbine","C":"Engine fire switches, APU fire switch, cargo fire arm switches","D":"Engine fire switches, APU fire switch, GPWS flap override switch"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non normal Checklists, Non normal checklist operation, Confirm Step"},{"id":"83294","lastEdit":"16/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"When is tankering fuel not recommended?","options":{"A":"When operating to high altitude airports","B":"When close to MTOW","C":"When taking off or landing on a contaminated runway","D":"When close to MLW"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.6 Fuel Tankering - The Commander shall assess the overall risk before fuel tankering with actual or forecasted contaminated runway surface conditions for take-off or landing"},{"id":"83432","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"During preflight the Purser comes to the flight deck explaining there are 3 DEPA onboard, what is your course of action?","options":{"A":"Explain it's fine to have up to 8 DEPA onboard any flight","B":"Explain it's fine to have up to 5 DEPA onboard any flight","C":"Immediately offload as only 1 DEPA is allowed per flight","D":"Ask the Purser to assess if they are travelling as a family"},"answer":"D","reference":"OME 10.5.18.1 Aviation Security, Aviation Security, Security Measures, Inadmissible, Deportees"},{"id":"83637","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"If ADIRU is ON and the ON BAT light is illuminated, which of the following is true?","options":{"A":"The ADIRU is operating on its internal battery","B":"The ADIRU is performing a self-test","C":"Primary power was removed, the BATTERY switch is OFF and the ground call horn is on","D":"The airplane was secured, primary power was left ON, and the ADIRU was left ON"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Controls and Indicators, Air Data Interial Reference Unit (item 1)"},{"id":"83679","lastEdit":"14/10/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the missed approach procedure for a circling approach?","options":{"A":"Make an initial climbing turn toward the intended landing runway and continue overhead the aerodrome where the pilot will establish the aeroplane on the instrument missed approach track","B":"Make an initial climbing turn toward the intended landing runway and join the circuit to make another approach","C":"Make an initial climbing turn toward the intended landing runway and continue on the missed approach track for the planned landing runway","D":"Make an initial climbing turn toward the intended landing runway and enter a climbing orbit until further instructions from ATC"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.22.4 Circling Approach"},{"id":"83713","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are key factors a leader must consider when making decisions in a flight-deck environment?","options":{"A":"The assignment, the group, the circumstances","B":"The task, the team, the individual","C":"The strategy, the team, the situation","D":"The mission, the crew, the outcome"},"answer":"B","reference":"Crew Resource Management Manual 4.4.2.2 Action-Centered Leadership"},{"id":"83778","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"When accepting a last minute change (LMC), what must the Commander verify?","options":{"A":"The LMC does not exceed any mass limitation of the aeroplane, the centre of gravity stays doesn't change more than 2.4% and a new loadsheet is requested from load control","B":"The LMC does not exceed any mass limitation of the aeroplane, the load limitations of the compartments are not exceeded, the centre of gravity stays within limits","C":"The LMC does not exceed any mass limitation of the aeroplane, the centre of gravity stays within limits","D":"The LMC does not exceed any mass limitation of the aeroplane, the centre of gravity stays doesn't change more than 2.4%"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.8.6.2 Last Minute Change (LMC)"},{"id":"84069","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the definition of LOUT in terms of cold weather ops?","options":{"A":"Lift-off unimpeded by temperature - the lowest temperature at which a fluid will flow off an aeroplane wing in an acceptable manner whilst maintaining the freezing point buffer. (5c buffer for types I and II, 3c buffer for types III and IV)","B":"Lift-off unimpeded by temperature - the lowest temperature at which a fluid will flow off an aeroplane wing in an acceptable manner whilst maintaining the freezing point buffer. (10c buffer for all fluid types)","C":"Lowest operational use temperature - the lowest temperature at which a fluid will flow off an aeroplane wing in an acceptable manner whilst maintaining the freezing point buffer. (3c buffer for type I, 5c buffer for types II, III, IV)","D":"Lowest operational use temperature - the lowest temperature at which a fluid will flow off an aeroplane wing in an acceptable manner whilst maintaining the freezing point buffer. (10c buffer for type I, 7c buffer for types II, III, IV)"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.3.9.7 LOUT + GOM, Chapter 20 Deicing Anticing, References, 5.3 Definitions - Lowest Operational Use Temperature (LOUT)"},{"id":"84140","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Select the correct statement regarding fuel jettison:","options":{"A":"Fuel may be jettisoned to a minimum quantity 4200kg or 3600kg in each main tank","B":"Fuel may be jettisoned to any minimum quantity at or above MLW","C":"Fuel may be jettisoned to a minimum quantity 5200kg or 3800kg in each main tank","D":"Fuel may be jettisoned to any quantity at or below MLW"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Jettison"},{"id":"84281","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In terms of dangerous goods, why are some classes split into divisions?","options":{"A":"Due to packing instruction requirements","B":"Due to the wide scope of the class","C":"Dangerous goods may meet the classification criteria of more than one 'Class'","D":"To show a numbering system that implies a relative degree of danger"},"answer":"B","reference":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations - Section 3 Classification, General Principles, Hazard Classes"},{"id":"84300","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What action is required during pre-flight, if the EICAS LANDING ALTITUDE message is displayed with the FWD and AFT outflow valve switches in auto?","options":{"A":"Press and hold the AIR COND RESET for one second","B":"Push the LDG ALT selector IN","C":"Pull the LDG ALT selector OUT","D":"Select the FWD and AFT OUTFLOW VALVE switches to MAN"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Pressurization System, Pressurization Panel"},{"id":"84395","lastEdit":"19/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"The actions in the correct sequence for the windshear escape manoeuvre in manual flight are?","options":{"A":"Call 'Windshear TOGA', Autopilot - disengage, Push either TOGA switch, aggressively apply maximum thrust, Autothrottle - disconnect, Roll wings level and pitch for 15 degrees, Retract speedbrakes, Follow the flight director","B":"Call 'Windshear TOGA', Push either TOGA switch, Autopilot - disengage, aggressively apply maximum thrust, Autothrottle - disconnect, Roll wings level and pitch for 15 degrees, Retract speedbrakes, Follow the flight director","C":"Call 'Windshear TOGA', Autothrottle - disconnect, Push either TOGA switch, aggressively apply maximum thrust, Autopilot - disengage, Roll wings level and pitch for 15 degrees, Retract speedbrakes, Follow the flight director","D":"Call 'Windshear TOGA', Push either TOGA switch, Autopilot - disengage, aggressively apply maximum thrust, Autothrottle - disconnect, Roll wings level and pitch for 20 degrees, Follow the flight director, Retract speedbrakes"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH, Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Windshear, Windshear Warning"},{"id":"84440","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"interview","question":"When approaching or departing Newcastle (EGNT) ATC asks what service you require, what is your response?","options":{"A":"A procedural service","B":"A deconfliction service","C":"A traffic service","D":"A basic service"},"answer":"B","reference":"LIDO 3.189.1.1 Types of ATS Surveillance Service (United Kingdom)"},{"id":"84494","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"What does contingency fuel compensate for?","options":{"A":"Deviations in individual aircraft fuel flow performance, deviations from meteorological conditions, deviations from planned routings and levels, deviations from the speed profile (cost index)","B":"Deviations from meteorological conditions, deviations from planned routings and levels, deviations from the speed profile (cost index)","C":"Deviations in individual aircraft fuel flow performance, deviations from meteorological conditions, deviations from planned routings and levels","D":"Deviations in individual aircraft fuel flow performance, deviation from planned routings and levels, deviations from normal drag profile by technical defects (APU door, flap track fairing missing, etc)"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.3 Contingency Fuel"},{"id":"84510","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"other","question":"What does the WINDOW HEAT R FWD EICAS message mean?","options":{"A":"The window is in the warm up cycle","B":"The window is cracked","C":"The window is open","D":"The WINDOW HEAT R FWD switch is off or an overheat/fault has occurred"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOMFCOM Systems, Anti Ice, Controls and Indicators, Window Heat Panel, Window Heat Switches"},{"id":"84537","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are some examples of required visual references for a CAT IIIA approach? (Select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"No visual reference is required","B":"The runway centre line lights (at least 1 light)","C":"The touchdown zone lights including a lateral element","D":"The runway centre line lights (at least 3 consecutive lights)"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.2 Required Visual References"},{"id":"84559","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"With EECs in hard alternate mode, what are your actions for ENG LIMIT PROT L and ENG LIMIT PROT R EICAS?","options":{"A":"Select CLB CON","B":"Cancel EICAS warning","C":"Reduce thrust","D":"De-select the Alternate mode"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Limit Prot L/R"},{"id":"84772","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"In North Atlantic operations below 80N, if all HF radios fail in-flight but prior to oceanic entry, under what conditions might ATC grant an exemption to continue the flight without HF communication?","options":{"A":"Exemptions can be granted if the flight is operating below FL290","B":"Exemptions can be granted if the aircraft still has functioning CPDLC and planned on a random route","C":"Exemptions can be granted if the aircraft is returning to base for repairs or on a ferry or delivery flight","D":"No exemptions are granted; the flight must divert to the nearest suitable airport"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO 2.3.5.1.2.1 Equipage Requirements"},{"id":"84789","lastEdit":"20/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"What does the OMC state regarding crew requirements and conduct within or in the vicinity of Chinese airspace?","options":{"A":"The Commander must wear their headset, ensure controlled rest takes place outside Chinese airspace, minimise distractions such as consuming food or toilet breaks","B":"Crew must wear headsets or ensure the speakers are at sufficient volume, minimize in-flight controlled rest, and minimise distractions such as cabin crew visits and time spent outside the flight deck","C":"The pilot monitoring must wear their headset, ensure the non-resting pilot is fully aware of route and airspace procedures during controlled rest, minimise distractions such as consuming food or toilet breaks","D":"Crew must wear headsets, ensure the non-resting pilot is fully aware of route and airspace procedures during controlled rest, and minimise distractions such as cabin crew visits and time spent outside the flight deck"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 12.3.8.2.9 Special Operation in Chinese Airspace"},{"id":"84823","lastEdit":"24/01/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the fuel jettison rate?","options":{"A":"Fuel in center tank - 2500 kgs/minute, Center tank empty - 1400 kgs/minute","B":"Fuel in center tank - 2400 kgs/minute, Center tank empty - 1500 kgs/minute","C":"1800 kgs/minute","D":"Fuel in center tank - 2600 kgs/minute, Center tank empty - 1300 kgs/minute"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH Fuel Auto Jettison"},{"id":"84931","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"When do the pitch trim levers move the stabilizer?","options":{"A":"Only on the ground","B":"These levers move the trim reference speed (normal mode) and also move the stabilizer (all modes)","C":"Only in secondary and direct modes","D":"When the autopilot is disengaged"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, Controls and Indicators, Pitch and Stabilizer Trim System, Stabilizer Trim System"},{"id":"85263","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which thrust reference mode provides maximum rated takeoff thrust?","options":{"A":"D-TO","B":"D-TO 1","C":"TO","D":"TO 1"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems Engines APU, Thrust Reference Mode"},{"id":"85406","lastEdit":"22/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which statement is true regarding the TCAS alerts?","options":{"A":"RA is a filled amber circle","B":"RA predicts conflict in the next 40-50 seconds","C":"RA predicts conflict in the next 15-35 seconds","D":"TA is represented by a white filled diamond"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Warning Systems, System Description, TCAS, Resolution Advisories and Display"},{"id":"85456","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"other","question":"Once a passenger with a disability has been accepted by the CRO on a flight to, from, or transiting the USA, under what circumstances can the Commander refuse carriage, and within what timeframe must a written report justifying the decision be submitted?","options":{"A":"For safety reasons, within 18 hours","B":"For medical reasons, within 24 hours","C":"For any reason, within 12 hours","D":"For operational reasons, within 36 hours"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.2.2.1.2.10 Acceptance of Persons with Reduced Mobility (PRM) section b"},{"id":"85707","lastEdit":"02/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the purpose of the Special Crew Briefing for the Hot Season Operations Procedure?","options":{"A":"It provides pilots with specific procedures and guidelines to manage the challenges of high temperatures and low QNH on flights to destinations that are high altitude destinations with potential performance penalties that need to be accounted for before departure","B":"It provides pilots with specific procedures and guidelines to manage the challenges of high temperatures and low QNH on take-off performance in Dubai during the hot season, ensuring the safety and efficiency of flights with potentially limiting estimated take-off weights","C":"It provides pilots with specific procedures and guidelines to manage the challenges of high temperatures and high humidity on take-off performance in Dubai during the hot season, ensuring the safety and efficiency of flights with potentially limiting estimated take-off weights","D":"It provides pilots with specific procedures and guidelines to manage the challenges of high temperatures and high humidity on flights to destinations that are high altitude destinations with potential performance penalties that need to be accounted for before departure"},"answer":"B","reference":"Special Crew Brief - Hot Season Operations Procedure (currently this SCB is deleted for winter)"},{"id":"85831","lastEdit":"02/01/2025","category":"tech","question":"During Pre-Flight what position should the APU Bleed Air switch be in?","options":{"A":"Off","B":"Auto","C":"Norm","D":"On"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - First Officer"},{"id":"86047","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the purpose of the aeroplane system status messages?","options":{"A":"Status messages are used by maintenance personnel only","B":"To provide crew awareness of system faults that may affect airplane dispatch","C":"To inform the crew that a malfunction is about to occur","D":"To alert the crew of impending system malfunctions"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, System Description, EICAS, EICAS Messages"},{"id":"86121","lastEdit":"09/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What are the requirements for a legal orbit? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Must be at or above 1500 AAL, autopilot engaged, compliant with approach stabilization, must be under radar control","B":"Must be at or above 1500 AAL or AGL, whichever is higher, autopilot engaged, compliant with approach stabilization, if not under radar control it must be day VMC","C":"Must be at or above 2000 AGL, flight director on, compliant with approach stabilization, must be visual with the terrain","D":"Must be at or above 2000 AGL, autopilot engaged, compliance approach stabilization, must be visual with the terrain"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.26 Orbits/360 Turns"},{"id":"86129","lastEdit":"21/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"How much discretion does a Commander have to extend a Flying Duty Period (FDP) on a multi-sector flight, prior to the last sector? (Non LRV duty)","options":{"A":"Up to 2.5 hours of discretion for any sector, with an additional 1 hour for the last sector if required for safety reasons","B":"Up to 2 hours of discretion, except for the last sector, where it can be extended to 3 hours","C":"A maximum of 4 hours, provided it does not lead to crew fatigue","D":"Up to 2 hours of discretion for operational flexibility"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 7.15 Commander's Discretion to Extend a Flying Duty Period - Also note it has to be non LRV as OMA 7.E.8, Item A (see waiver)"},{"id":"86152","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"What happens if you adjust an individual panel brightness or display brightness control when the master brightness system is on?","options":{"A":"The brightness of all panel lights and all displays change by a small amount","B":"The master brightness system turns off","C":"The brightness of the individual panel light or display changes by a small amount","D":"It has no effect"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Lighting Systems, Flight deck lighting"},{"id":"86228","lastEdit":"16/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Above which ground speed does the RTO autobrake setting command maximum braking pressure during RTO?","options":{"A":"65 knots","B":"70 knots","C":"Anytime during takeoff if both thrust levers are retarded to idle","D":"85 knots"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Landing Gear, Systems description, Brake System, Autobrake System"},{"id":"86309","lastEdit":"03/01/2024","category":"other","question":"Is take-off permitted in freezing drizzle?","options":{"A":"Only in light freezing drizzle","B":"Only with 100% undiluted fluid types II, III or IV and a PCI within 5 minutes of take-off","C":"No","D":"Yes"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.3.8.6 Light Freezing Rain/Drizzle - it does not specify any restrictions for drizzle, also if you check a holdover table it states under light freezing drizzle it's acceptable to use in light, moderate or heavy drizzle"},{"id":"86341","lastEdit":"17/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is true after dual FMC failure?","options":{"A":"Initializing the alternate navigation does not require any pilot action and occurs automatically after 60 seconds after the last FMC fails","B":"LNAV is not available for the remainder of the flight","C":"The CDU's supply route data to the ND's, and one of the CDU's supplies LNAV guidance to the autopilot","D":"Autotuning will still be operative through each CDU"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Flight Management Nav, Flight Management Computer, FMC Failure, Dual FMC Failure"},{"id":"86475","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the function of the negative pressure relief valve?","options":{"A":"To prevent negative pressure differentials","B":"To improve smoke removal and ventilation","C":"To regulate cabin pressure during climb","D":"To minimise cabin overpressure conditions"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description"},{"id":"86726","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Approaching your ETOPS entry point you experience a pack failure, what is the optimal decision? (no critical fuel issues)","options":{"A":"Re-route or divert to ensure you have a non-ETOPS routing","B":"Land at the nearest suitable airport","C":"Continue to destination as the MEL is not applicable in flight","D":"Descend to FL330 or below and continue flight to destination if fuel permits"},"answer":"C","reference":"MEL Premable 3.2 'The MEL is applicable prior to the beginning of the take-off roll' + OMA 8.5.6 ETOPS In-flight Procedures states only re-route/divert if ETOPS critical fuel is affected"},{"id":"86771","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"Does the Windshear Manoeuvre allow for turns?","options":{"A":"Yes, as desired","B":"No, the procedure specifies wings level","C":"Yes, for obstacle clearance","D":"No, the procedure specifies do not turn as the aircraft will waste energy turning at a reduced rate of climb"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Windshear, Windshear Warning"},{"id":"86985","lastEdit":"04/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the definition of a contaminated runway?","options":{"A":"A runway with more than 25% of one third of the runway surface area within the length and width being used is covered by one or more of the runway surface condition descriptors","B":"A runway with more than one third of 25% of the runway surface area within the length being used is covered by one or more of the runway surface condition descriptors","C":"A runway with more than 25% of one third of the runway surface area within the length being used is covered by one or more of the runway surface condition descriptors","D":"A runway with more than one third of 25% of the runway surface area within the length and width being used is covered by one or more of the runway surface condition descriptors"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.6.1.4 Contaminated Runway"},{"id":"87107","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What are the memory items for airspeed unreliable?","options":{"A":"Autothrottle arm switches - off, Autopilot - disconnect, Flight directors - off, Set the following gear up pitch attitude and thrust, Flaps extended 85% N1 and 10 degrees pitch, Flaps up 70% N1 and 4 degrees pitch","B":"Autopilot - disconnect, Autothrottle arm switches - off, Flight directors - off, Set the following gear up pitch attitude and thrust, Flaps extended 85% N1 and 10 degrees pitch, Flaps up 70% N1 and 4 degrees pitch","C":"Autopilot - disconnect, Flight directors - off, Autothrottle arm switches - off, Set the following gear up pitch attitude and thrust, Flaps extended 85% N1 and 10 degrees pitch, Flaps up 70% N1 and 4 degrees pitch","D":"Autopilot - disconnect, Flight directors - off, Autothrottle arm switches - off, Set the following gear up pitch attitude and thrust, Flaps extended 70% N1 and 4 degrees pitch, Flaps up 85% N1 and 10 degrees pitch"},"answer":"B","reference":"QRH NNC Airspeed Unreliable"},{"id":"87285","lastEdit":"17/04/2024","category":"other","question":"Can we fly to LPV minima on an RNAV/RNP approach?","options":{"A":"Yes","B":"BLANK","C":"BLANK","D":"No"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.8.1 Decode ICAO of ATS Flight Plan, see item B - which is not fitted to our aircraft nor declared on our ATS flight plan. + LIDO NAV 1.5.3.1.7.1 General, see second paragraph about LPV requires GPS with an augmentation system"},{"id":"87326","lastEdit":"05/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which electrical source powers the Flight controls?","options":{"A":"The Captain's Flight Instrument Bus is used by individual power supply assemblies (PSAs) to provide DC power to the three flight control DC busses","B":"PMG AC power is used by individual power supply assemblies (PSAs) to provide DC power to the three flight control DC busses","C":"The Main AC Bus is employed by individual power supply assemblies (PSAs) to deliver DC power to the three flight control DC busses","D":"The Hot Battery Bus is utilised by individual power supply assemblies (PSAs) to supply DC power to the three flight control DC busses"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Electrical, System Description, DC Electrical System, Flight Control DC Electrical System"},{"id":"87432","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the primary source for Fly-by-wire?","options":{"A":"Main AC busses","B":"Main Battery","C":"Permanent Magnet Generators","D":"APU"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, DC Electrical System, Flight Controls DC Electrical System"},{"id":"87436","lastEdit":"02/05/2024","category":"other","question":"On this LIDO approach chart minima box, which statement is correct?","options":{"A":"We can use the ACFT MAX 65/7 minima if the runway is wider than 60 metres","B":"We cannot use the ACFT MAX 65/7 minima as our aircraft is greater than 65 tons","C":"We can use the ACFT MAX 65/7 minima as our wingspan is less than 65 metres and the distance between the main landingÃ¢â‚¬â€¹ gear and glide path antenna in the landing configuration vertically is less than 7 metres","D":"We can use the ACFT MAX 65/7 minima as the aircraft weight is greater than 65 tons and the main gear height is greater than 7 metres"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO LAT 1.7.3.4.6.1.2 NAVAID Boxes (LIDO page 990) - See the section under AircrafÃ¯Â»Â¿t Size Limitations and note the only aircraft which exceed the limit are A388 and B748. + Fun fact: When the gear is up the glideslope antenna used is in the nose, once the gear goes down the glideslope antenna switches to a lower antenna in the nose landing gear, to keep the aircraft within the 7 metres vertical distance between the main landing gear and glideslope antenna requirements - a common line training question"},{"id":"87458","lastEdit":"07/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What action should you take if the EICAS ICE DETECTORS appears?","options":{"A":"Run the engine and wing anti-ice systems manually","B":"Avoid icing conditions","C":"Turn all anti-ice selectors off for 10 seconds and then back to auto to reset the system","D":"Turn all anti-ice selectors on regardless of icing conditions or not"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Ice Detectors"},{"id":"87650","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What are some examples of required visual references for a CAT II approach? (select the most correct)","options":{"A":"The threshold markings","B":"The touchdown zone lights including a lateral element","C":"The touchdown zone lights","D":"The visual glide slope indicator"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.2 Required Visual References"},{"id":"87710","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"Your holdover time expires at 20:45 UTC. You taxi out at 20:00. At 20:15 you commence the takeoff roll but have to reject at 70 knots due to ATC. What are your actions?","options":{"A":"Return to stand for a further de-icing/anti-icing treatment as your HOT has now expired","B":"Get permission off VPNC to depart again","C":"Return to the holding point for another takeoff as you still have 30 minutes remaining of HOT","D":"Return to stand for a further anti-icing treatment as your HOT has now expired"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.3.6 Step 5 Pre-takeoff Contamination Inspection"},{"id":"87805","lastEdit":"21/11/2024","category":"tech","question":"Where can the provisions for Dangerous Goods carried by passengers and crew be found?","options":{"A":"Boeing 777 Regulatory Permits and Certificates, Page 3, Table 2.3.A","B":"OMA 9, Limitations, Table 2.3.A","C":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations, Limitations, Table 2.3.A","D":"OME 11.18.11.13 Provisions for Dangerous Goods, Table 2.3.A"},"answer":"C","reference":"IATA Dangerous Goods Regulations, Limitations, Table 2.3.A, It can also be found at OME 3.18.11.13 Provisions for Dangerous Goods, Table 2.3.A (the OME version being a copy, but it's a more user friendly format).Also OMA 9.4.3.3 Provisions for Dangerous Goods Carried by Passengers or Crew"},{"id":"87806","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"What does FICON stand for in aviation?","options":{"A":"Field Contamination NOTAM","B":"Federal Interagency Committee on Noise","C":"Field Condition NOTAM","D":"Field Interface for Climatic Observation and Navigation"},"answer":"C","reference":"Lido 1.8.1.6 F (Abbreviations)"},{"id":"87844","lastEdit":"09/03/2024","category":"other","question":"In the approach stabilisation criteria, at what altitude must the gear be locked down, the flaps set in the landing configuration and the speedbrake not deployed?","options":{"A":"1000 feet above aerodrome elevation","B":"500 feet above aerodrome elevation","C":"500 feet above runway threshold elevation","D":"1000 feet above runway threshold elevation"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.27 Approach Stabilisation"},{"id":"87851","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What are the conditions for Engine Autostart L/R?","options":{"A":"One of these occurs: Autostart did not start the engine or Fuel control switch is in run at low engine RPM with the autostart switch off","B":"Autostart did not start the engine","C":"No N2 Rotation","D":"The engine parameters exceed their starting limits"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Autostart L/R"},{"id":"88125","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What are types of TCAS traffic alerts?","options":{"A":"TA/RA, TA ONLY, Proximate, Other","B":"Other Advisory, Proximate Traffic, Traffic Advisory, Traffic Resolution","C":"Other, Proximate, Traffic Advisory, Resolution Advisory","D":"None, Approximate, Traffic Resolution, Other Advisory"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Warning Systems, System Description, Traffic Alert and Collision Avoidance System"},{"id":"88141","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"For an ILS or APV approach, given that RVR or visibility is required at the approach ban point, is ceiling also required?","options":{"A":"Only ILS needs ceiling, while APV does not","B":"Only APV needs ceiling, while ILS does not","C":"They do not require ceiling at the approach ban point","D":"Both approaches mandate ceiling at the ban point"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.4 In-Flight Minima"},{"id":"88204","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"When using ACARS in FANS 1/A airspace which datalink systems are in use on our B777's?","options":{"A":"VHF datalink","B":"VHF datalink, HF datalink, ADS-B datalink","C":"VHF datalink, HF datalink, SATCOM datalink","D":"VHF datalink, SATCOM datalink"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 4.1 Communications Service Providers and Networks (HF datalink is possible, but not installed on the B777, ATC flight plan would include J2)"},{"id":"88300","lastEdit":"13/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What is the maximum runway slope?","options":{"A":"0%","B":"+/-2%","C":"There is no limitation","D":"+/-3%"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Limitations, AFM limitations"},{"id":"88432","lastEdit":"07/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"Up until which point is the MEL applicable?","options":{"A":"The closure of the last main cabin door","B":"The point at which the pilot physically begins to apply power to initiate the takeoff","C":"The pushback from the terminal stand","D":"The point at which the legal Commander signs the technical log for departure"},"answer":"B","reference":"MEL Section 2, MEL Preamble 1.9"},{"id":"88591","lastEdit":"18/06/2024","category":"interview","question":"Where is the turbulence strongest when flying close to a Polar Jet Stream?","options":{"A":"On the cold/low pressure side, next to and just below the axis of the Jet Stream","B":"On the warm/high pressure side, next to and just below the axis of the Jet Stream","C":"On the cold/low pressure side, next to and just above the axis of the Jet Stream","D":"On the warm/high pressure side, next to and just above the axis of the Jet Stream"},"answer":"A","reference":"https://skybrary.aero/articles/jet-stream + Limited information in the OMA 8.3.8.6 Jetstream"},{"id":"88633","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"The side flightdeck windows may be opened under which circumstances? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"They may not be opened","B":"The windows may be opened if the aircraft is depressurised","C":"They may be opened","D":"They may be opened as long as airspeed is less than 200 knots"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Doors Windows Seats, Doors and Windows, Flight deck number two windows (Old feedback stated this question answer was 'Depressurized + Manoeuvre speed for the current flap setting is a good target speed')"},{"id":"88698","lastEdit":"12/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"Which FIRs restrict ATN CPDLC logons for our aircraft?","options":{"A":"United States (KUSA), Geneva (LSAG), Zurich (LSAZ), Jeddah (OEJN)","B":"Geneva (LSAG), Zurich (LSAZ), Karlsruhe UAC (EDUU), Maastricht Centre (EDYY)","C":"United States (KUSA), Vienna (LOVV), Nicosia (LCCC), Riyadh (OERK)","D":"Karlsruhe UAC (EDUU), Maastricht Centre (EDYY), Magadan (GDXB), Athens (LGGG)"},"answer":"B","reference":"Bulletin EKIB-66 R1"},{"id":"88709","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"If cruise altitude is unavailable from the FMC what does the cabin altitude assume?","options":{"A":"A cruise altitude of 39000 feet","B":"A max differential pressure of 8.4 PSI","C":"A cruise altitude of 43000 feet","D":"A max differential pressure of 8.9 PSI"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Pressurization System Description, Pressurization with Automatic Operation"},{"id":"88796","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"What automatically activates the emergency lighting?","options":{"A":"Loss of left and right AC power","B":"The flight data recorder detecting 4g or more","C":"Loss of main generators, backup generators and APU generator","D":"Loss of DC power or is turned off when the system is armed"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Systems Description, Lighting Systems, Emergency Lighting"},{"id":"88858","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the EICAS SELCAL message indicate?","options":{"A":"A VHF or HF call has been received and is waiting to be answered","B":"The selective calling system has failed","C":"A HF call has been received and is waiting to be answered","D":"A cabin attendant is calling the flight deck"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, EICAS Messages, Comms EICAS Alert Messages, SATCOM + Comms, System Description, Radio Comms Systems, Stuck Mic Protection (see SELCAL system below)"},{"id":"88883","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the pitch limit indication indicate?","options":{"A":"Pitch angle for best climb speed","B":"Proper pitch angle for takeoff","C":"Pitch at which low speed warning will sound","D":"Pitch limit at which stick shaker occurs"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, Primary Flight Display, PFD Attitude Indications"},{"id":"88955","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is true about turn compensation?","options":{"A":"It is not available if the bank angle is above 30 degrees","B":"Elevator input is not required for turns up to 30 degrees of bank","C":"The turn compensation switch is on the overhead panel","D":"It is available only in the primary and secondary modes"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Pitch Control"},{"id":"89004","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"When is it acceptable to conduct a visual approach?","options":{"A":"When requested by ATC to ensure separation requirements or when a visual approach is more efficient than an instrument procedure","B":"Whenever the pilot flying decides it is safe","C":"When requested by ATC to ensure separation requirements or when it is the only approach available","D":"Whenever the commander decides it is safe"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.22.3"},{"id":"89037","lastEdit":"12/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"You are scheduled to fly to a destination where no TAF or METAR is available. How does this affect the operation?","options":{"A":"The OFP must be planned to a airport for which weather data is available that is nearby your destination","B":"Extra fuel must loaded to account for weather uncertainties","C":"Two alternates must be selected on the OFP","D":"Weather forecasts must be made available or you cannot dispatch"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.1.6 Destination Alternate Aerodrome"},{"id":"89139","lastEdit":"23/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"With a range of specific gravity data where can you find fuel tank maximum quantities in kilograms?","options":{"A":"GOM 11.2.1.3.3 B777-300ER Fuel Tank Arrangements","B":"RAIG C.3 Boeing 777-300ER, Fuel Mass/Specific Gravity","C":"OMC 12, Fuel Tank Capacities with Specific Gravity","D":"FCOM, Fuel, Fuel Tank Locations and Capacities"},"answer":"B","reference":"RAIG C.3 Boeing 777-300ER, Fuel Mass/Specific Gravity"},{"id":"89165","lastEdit":"05/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which wheel number is the left middle outboard main wheel?","options":{"A":"#3","B":"#4","C":"#7","D":"#5"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Landing Gear, Controls and Indicators, Landing Gear System Indications, Gear Synoptic Display"},{"id":"89294","lastEdit":"23/10/2024","category":"other","question":"When can checklists be completed from memory?","options":{"A":"When the situation does not allow reference to the checklist or if no hazard is created by such action","B":"When deemed necessary by the Commander","C":"Only when a smoke, fire or fumes situation becomes uncontrollable","D":"Never"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH Checklist Instructions, Non-Normal Checklists, Non-Normal Checklist Operation, Do Reference Items + OMA 8.3.20.1.4 Checklist Usage, Callouts,and Actuation of Critical Controls"},{"id":"89469","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When tankering fuel is needed what is it planned to?","options":{"A":"1% less than MLW or RLW, whichever is lower","B":"1% less than RLW","C":"2% less than MLW","D":"2% less than MLW or RLW, whichever is lower"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.6 Fuel Tankering"},{"id":"89597","lastEdit":"07/01/2024","category":"tech","question":"What happens if the flight deck temperature control is moved to the C position?","options":{"A":"Flight deck temperature will be controlled manually and the trim air valve will move toward closed to supply cool air","B":"It cancels input to the flight deck temperature controller","C":"The pack temperature decreases","D":"It opens the flight deck trim air valve and lowers the temperature"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Air Conditioning Panel, Item 2"},{"id":"89617","lastEdit":"11/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which European FIR's have mandatory CPDLC logon when equipped?","options":{"A":"Budapest, Bucharest, Czech Republic, All French mainland FIR's, Helsinki, Ljubljana, Montenegro, Nicosia, Poland, Serbia, Sofia, Spain and Canaries (early 2025), Sweden, Zagreb","B":"BLANK","C":"There are no mandatory European CPDLC FIR's","D":"All European FIR's require mandatory logon when equipped"},"answer":"A","reference":"France: LIDO 2.1.5.5.13 + Budapest: LIDO 2.1.5.5.16 + Bucharest: LIDO 2.1.5.5.28 - I can't reference them all, but if you search each LIDO for FIR ID and 'CPDLC' and 'MANDATORY' you'll find the reference quickly, e.g. 'EPWW CPDLC MANDATORY'"},{"id":"89623","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the primary source for the Transfer busses?","options":{"A":"Transformer Rectifier Units","B":"Ram Air Turbine","C":"Permanent Magnet Generators","D":"Main AC busses"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Electrical, System Description, AC Electrical System, AC Electrical Power Distribution, AC Main busses"},{"id":"89915","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"interview","question":"What is the standard missed approach gradient under ICAO and FAA?","options":{"A":"ICAO 2.1% and FAA 3.3%","B":"ICAO 3.3% and FAA 2.5%","C":"ICAO 2.5% and FAA 3.3%","D":"ICAO 2.5% and FAA 2.1%"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO 1.4.5.6.1.5.1 RAR, Proc for Air Nav Services - Aircraft ops (8168), App procedures, Instrument App Proc Segments, Missed App Segment (5), Missed App Proc EASA Ops"},{"id":"89983","lastEdit":"25/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When approaching the North Atlantic which failed item does NOT affect your routing?","options":{"A":"Engine failure","B":"FMC failure","C":"SELCAL failure","D":"SATCOM failure"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, Performance Based Navigation, In Flight Failed or Downgraded Aircraft Equipment + QRH, Ops Info, Oceanic/Remote Ops, In Flight Failed or Downgraded Aircraft Equipment"},{"id":"90395","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Which statement is true regarding North Atlantic operations?","options":{"A":"Flights with degraded navigation or communication due to GPS interference should inform Shanwick at least 60 minutes prior to entry and inform Bodo 20 minutes prior to entry, the details shall be passed by voice only on VHF","B":"Flights with degraded navigation or communication due to GPS interference should inform Shanwick at least 60 minutes prior to entry and inform Gander 30 minutes prior to entry, the details shall be passed by voice only on VHF","C":"Flights with degraded navigation or communication due to GPS interference should inform Shanwick at least 30 minutes prior to entry and inform Gander 60 minutes prior to entry, the details shall be included in the oceanic clearance request","D":"Flights with degraded navigation or communication due to GPS interference should inform Shanwick at least 30 minutes prior to entry and inform Bodo 60 minutes prior to entry, the details shall be included in the oceanic request"},"answer":"C","reference":"Network report 2407 v1"},{"id":"90403","lastEdit":"29/10/2024","category":"tech","question":"In which cargo holds are dangerous goods allowed?","options":{"A":"All holds","B":"Forward Cargo Hold only","C":"Aft Cargo Hold Only","D":"All holds, except bulk cargo"},"answer":"A","reference":"GOM - 8.2 - Planning and Handling"},{"id":"90534","lastEdit":"01/02/2024","category":"both","question":"What is the FMC RNP capability when using DME/DME updates only?","options":{"A":"RNP 0.5","B":"RNP 0.3","C":"RNP 1","D":"RNP 2"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCTM 1, General, RNAV Operations, RNP and ANP Definitions - Boeing FMC's have RNP 0.5 capability with DME-DME updating active without GPS updating. Cautionary note: just because the FCTM states RNP 0.5 doesn't make it true, ensure navaid coverage especially at low altitudes"},{"id":"90814","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"How long is the repair interval of a category D defect?","options":{"A":"120 days (2880 hours) excluding the day of the discovery","B":"10 days (240 hours) excluding the day of discovery Image","C":"90 days (2160 hours) including the day of the discovery","D":"120 days (2880 hours) including the day of the discovery"},"answer":"A","reference":"MEL Section 2, MEL Preamble 9 Repair Intervals"},{"id":"90873","lastEdit":"29/04/2024","category":"tech","question":"When a generator has low oil pressure, what is the EICAS message?","options":{"A":"ELEC AC BUS L, R","B":"ELEC GEN DRIVE L, R","C":"ELEC BACKUP GEN L, R","D":"ELEC DRIVE GEN OFF L, R"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, 6.30, Electrical EICAS Messages"},{"id":"90889","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What best describes the leak detection and isolation operation? (not counting the QRH NNC)","options":{"A":"Automatic leak detection, crew action is required","B":"Automatic leak detection and automatic isolation, crew action is not required","C":"Automatic leak detection and manual bleed air transfer, crew action is required","D":"Automatic leak detection and manual isolation, crew action is required"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Air, Bleed Air System Description, Bleed Air Duct System"},{"id":"90923","lastEdit":"02/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"When calculating holdover times, how should light snow with light rain or drizzle be treated?","options":{"A":"As light snow","B":"As light freezing rain","C":"As heavy snow","D":"As rain on a cold soaked wing"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.3.10.2.2 Table 2: Holdover Times for Sae Type I Fluid... - Note 7. Also applies to other fluids, usually note 6 or note 7."},{"id":"90928","lastEdit":"20/10/2024","category":"interview","question":"What corrections are required to convert airfield elevation to density altitude?","options":{"A":"Add/subtract 120 feet per millibar deviation from standard pressure setting using QNH and add/subtract 30 feet per ISA temperature deviation (for lower pressures or higher temperatures density altitude increases)","B":"Add/subtract 120 feet per millibar deviation from standard pressure setting using QNH and add/subtract 50 feet per ISA temperature deviation (for lower pressures or higher temperatures density altitude increases)","C":"Add/subtract 30 feet per millibar deviation from standard pressure setting using QNH and add/subtract 30 feet per ISA temperature deviation (for lower pressures or higher temperatures density altitude increases)","D":"Add/subtract 30 feet per millibar deviation from standard pressure setting using QNH and add/subtract 120 feet per ISA temperature deviation (for lower pressures or higher temperatures density altitude increases)"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO 1.8.2 Definitions, Density altitude (definition only) + eLearning module Hot Weather and High Elevation Destinations (RDT Package 3) 2024/25 (refers to the 30 feet and 120 feet corrections)"},{"id":"90948","lastEdit":"27/04/2024","category":"other","question":"What are some examples of required visual references for a CAT I/APV/Non precision approach? (select the most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Centre line lights - at least 2 consecutive lights","B":"Centre line lights","C":"Centre line lights - at least 1 light","D":"Threshold markings"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.3.2 Required Visual References"},{"id":"91011","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is the missed approach acceleration altitude?","options":{"A":"1000 feet AGL","B":"2500 feet AGL","C":"The missed approach altitude","D":"400 feet AGL"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Go around and missed approach procedure"},{"id":"91135","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"When operating near severe thunderstorms for takeoff, approach and landing what is the minimum distance separation between the aircraft and the thunderstorm?","options":{"A":"2 nautical miles below 1500 feet AGL","B":"3 nautical miles below 1000 feet AGL","C":"5 nautical miles below 10000 feet AGL","D":"5 nautical miles below 2500 feet AGL"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMC 10.2.2.1 Windshear"},{"id":"91188","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Which hydraulic system powers the nose gear steering?","options":{"A":"Backup System","B":"Right System","C":"Left System","D":"Center System"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, System Description, Center Hydraulic System"},{"id":"91254","lastEdit":"25/02/2024","category":"other","question":"The actions for a GPWS warning in the correct sequence are?","options":{"A":"Disengage autopilot, roll wings level and rotate to an initial pitch of 20 degrees, disconnect autothrottle(s), aggressively apply maximum thrust, retract speedbrakes, continue rotation to the pitch limit indicator/stick shaker/initial buffet if terrain remains a threat","B":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle(s), aggressively apply maximum thrust, roll wings level and rotate to an initial pitch of 15 degrees, continue rotation to the pitch limit indicator/stick shaker/initial buffet if terrain remains a threat, retract speedbrakes","C":"Disconnect autothrottle(s), aggressively apply maximum thrust, disengage autopilot, roll wings level and rotate to an initial pitch of 15 degrees, continue rotation to the pitch limit indicator/stick shaker/initial buffet if terrain remains a threat, retract speedbrakes","D":"Disengage autopilot, disconnect autothrottle(s), aggressively apply maximum thrust, roll wings level and rotate to an initial pitch of 20 degrees, retract speedbrakes, continue rotation to the pitch limit indicator/stick shaker/initial buffet if terrain remains a threat"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH, Manoeuvres, Non Normal Manoeuvres, Ground Proximity Warning System Response, GPWS Warning"},{"id":"91560","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"You are climbing though 1000 feet after takeoff, FMA modes are THR REF TOGA TOGA, how do you set CLB thrust?","options":{"A":"Engage FLCH or V/S","B":"Press CLB/CON or FLCH","C":"Engaging V/S or ALT","D":"Engaging V/S or pushing the CLB CON switch"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autothrottle System Controls"},{"id":"91669","lastEdit":"11/03/2024","category":"other","question":"The conditions for the Aborted Engine Start L/R memory items are:","options":{"A":"A tailpipe fire occurs","B":"No N2 rotation","C":"During start the engine indications exceed the limit","D":"On the ground, an aborted engine start is needed"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH Aborted Engine Start L/R"},{"id":"91791","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What actions do you take to eliminate source of an overheat with EICAS HYD OVERHEAT PRI C2 message?","options":{"A":"Turn off the C2 primary hydraulic pump","B":"Turn off the C1 and C2 primary and demand hydraulic pumps","C":"Turn of the C1 and C2 primary hydraulic pumps","D":"Turn off all center system hydraulic sources"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC HYD OVERHEAT PRI C1, C2"},{"id":"91806","lastEdit":"24/12/2024","category":"interview","question":"During the approach on the RNP-AR into the Seychelles in IMC, GPS L appears on the EICAS. What is the correct course of action?","options":{"A":"Go-around","B":"Continue the approach","C":"Continue until VMC","D":"Enter a hold to discuss with MCC"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Automatic Flight, Instrument Approach - RNAV (RNP) AR, Pre-approach requirements. (You're already on the approach so pre-approach requirements don't apply, you're looking for NAV UNABLE RNP or VERIFY POS) + November 2024 training newsletter also states: Crews are tÃ¯Â»Â¿o use airmanship. For example: Waiting for the NAV UNABLE RNP EICAS message or the VERIFY POSITION FMC alert following a dual GPS failure is not the safest course of action in IMC conditions during an approach in a mountainous region"},{"id":"91924","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"When does the APU fire warning horn sound?","options":{"A":"Sounds continuously during ground operation for APU fire only","B":"Sounds intermittently during ground operation for APU fire or fire test","C":"Sounds continuously during ground operation for APU fire or fire test","D":"Sounds intermittently during any APU fire"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM 8.10 APU Ground Control Fire Protection Panel (This question is about the warning horn in the nosewheel, not the flight deck)"},{"id":"92146","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"What is the minimum RFFS category for our passenger fleet? (without exemptions)","options":{"A":"Departure and destination airport: 9. Takeoff, en-route, destination alternate: 7. ETOPS, driftdown, depressurisation alternate: 5","B":"Departure and destination airport: 7. Takeoff, en-route, destination alternate: 5. ETOPS, driftdown, depressurisation alternate: 4","C":"Departure and destination airport: 10. Takeoff, en-route, destination alternate: 9. ETOPS, driftdown, depressurisation alternate: 7","D":"Departure and destination airport: 8. Takeoff, en-route, destination alternate: 6. ETOPS, driftdown, depressurisation alternate: 4"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.4 Rescue and Fire Fighting Services (RFFS)"},{"id":"92172","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What equipment is required for dispatch out of Dubai for overflights of Iranian airspace?","options":{"A":"Transponder, HF radio or SATCOM","B":"Three VHF radios, Transponder","C":"GPS, ACARS","D":"SATCOM, Both Packs and oxygen system"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 12.3.7.8.2 Overflight of Iran/Tehran FIR"},{"id":"92439","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does stall warning consist of?","options":{"A":"Stick shaker followed by a stall warning horn","B":"Stall warning horn and buffet","C":"Stick shaker but no stall warning horn","D":"EICAS message 'STALL'"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systens, Warning Systems, System Description, Airspeed Voice Annunciations and Alerts, Stall Warning"},{"id":"92583","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What are the FMC equipment requirements for flying in the North Atlantic before and after the Oceanic Entry Point, and what must occur if these requirements are not met?","options":{"A":"2 FMCs before entry, and 1 FMC after entry. If these requirements are not met, the aircraft must descend below the NAT HLA","B":"1 FMC before entry, and 1 CDU after entry. If these requirements are not met, the aircraft must divert to the nearest suitable airport","C":"2 FMCs before entry, and 1 CDU after entry. If these requirements are not met, the aircraft must descend below the NAT HLA","D":"2 FMCs before entry, and 1 FMC after entry. If these requirements are not met, the aircraft must divert to the nearest suitable airport"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH, Ops Info, Oceanic/Remote Operations, North Atlantic and Polar Region, See the section about equipment before entry (redirects to QRH, Ops Info, PBN - see RNAV 10 or RNP 4 as appropriate, both requiring 2 FMC's) and also see after entry just 1 CDU required. For reference to FMC/FMS failures see LIDO 2.3.4.2.2 Loss of Navigation/FMS Capability - On the next page it goes on to state aircraft without the required equipment will have to descend below the NAT HLA"},{"id":"92584","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Select the correct statement regarding the fuel system:","options":{"A":"The left and right main tanks each contain two jettison tanks","B":"The center tank contains two override pumps and two separate jettison pumps","C":"The left and right main tanks each contain two AC driven fuel pumps","D":"The APU receives fuel from only the left main tank using a DC or AC driven pump"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fuel, System Description, Fuel Pumps"},{"id":"92632","lastEdit":"03/02/2024","category":"tech","question":"Which minimum altitude is displayed in two digits below FL in the OFP?","options":{"A":"MORA","B":"MVA","C":"MSA","D":"MOCA"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMC 10.1.7.3.1 OFP Nav Log Decodes"},{"id":"92702","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"ADS-C position data is provided from what source?","options":{"A":"ADIRU","B":"GPS L or R depending on transponder selection","C":"Dedicated ADS GPS","D":"FMC"},"answer":"D","reference":"MEL 23-27-01-01 Maintenance Note"},{"id":"92747","lastEdit":"17/12/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the EICAS ENG OIL PRESS R message mean?","options":{"A":"Engine oil pressure is high","B":"Engine oil pressure is too low or too high","C":"Engine oil pressure is low","D":"Engine oil temperature is high"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, EICAS Messages, EICAS Alert Messages"},{"id":"92756","lastEdit":"08/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"Fuel Uplift: Calculated uplift 22900kg, actual uplift 29600 litres, fuel density 0.800 kg/litre. Does this pass the fuel uplift check?","options":{"A":"Yes, the fuel uplift check criteria are fulfilled","B":"No, the applicable tolerance of 3% has been exceeded","C":"No, the applicable tolerance of 5% has been exceeded","D":"No, The applicable tolerance of 1000 kg has been exceeded"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.6 Fuel Uplift Check"},{"id":"92850","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is false about the primary flight computers when the disconnect switch has been positioned to DISC?","options":{"A":"Thrust asymmetry compensation is available","B":"Protection features are not available","C":"Autopilot is not available","D":"The system operates in direct mode"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Primary Flight Control System Modes, Flight Control System Direct Mode"},{"id":"92873","lastEdit":"14/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"The trim air switch shows a fault light illuminated amber, what does this mean?","options":{"A":"The trim air valve is closed failed","B":"BLANK","C":"The trim air valve is closed failed The trim air valve is commanded closed because of a zone supply duct overheat has occurred The trim air switch is off","D":"The trim air valve is closed failed The trim air valve is commanded closed because of a zone supply duct overheat has occurred"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Air, Controls and Indicators, Air Conditioning System, Air Conditioning Panel, Item 4. The real exam features this answer as Ã¢â‚¬Ëœall of the aboveÃ¢â‚¬â„¢"},{"id":"92883","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which aircraft system is not to be used during refuelling?","options":{"A":"Resetting electrical generators or their associated circuit breakers","B":"Satcom and HF radios","C":"HF Radios, Weather Radar, Strobes","D":"Broadband communication system"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Limitations Non AFM operational information (HF radios) + OMA 8.2.1.2 Safety Precautions during refueling (strobes + weather radar)"},{"id":"93375","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"How many feet vertical deviation indicates the VNAV deviation scale displayed during VNAV PATH descent?","options":{"A":"+/- 200","B":"+/- 100","C":"+/- 400","D":"+/- 800"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"93446","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What happens if the autopilot disengage bar is selected down? (select most correct answer)","options":{"A":"Autopilot and flight directors are disabled","B":"Bank angle protection, autoland and autopilot are disabled","C":"Bank angle protection and autopilot are disabled","D":"Autopilot, flight directors and autoland are disabled"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Mode Control Panel, Autopilot Flight Director System Controls"},{"id":"93556","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"Who is responsible for making sure that flight time limitations are adhered to?","options":{"A":"The airline and crew members","B":"The airline only","C":"Crewmembers only","D":"GCAA"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.3.1 + OMA 7.3.2"},{"id":"93601","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"Vaccinations must be administered at least how many hours prior to a flight?","options":{"A":"48 hours","B":"12 hours","C":"24 hours","D":"36 hours"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 6.1.20 Vaccination and Immunisation"},{"id":"93753","lastEdit":"11/12/2023","category":"other","question":"Which statement is correct regarding standard engine out procedures?","options":{"A":"Maintain runway heading, climb at V2 to V2+25, at or above minimum acceleration height, initiate acceleration","B":"Maintain runway track (compensating for wind), climb at V2+5 to V2+25, at or above minimum acceleration height, initiate acceleration","C":"Maintain runway track (compensating for wind), climb at V2 to V2+15, at or above minimum acceleration height, initiate acceleration","D":"Maintain runway heading, climb at V2+5 to V2+15, at or above minimum acceleration height, initiate acceleration"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.3.6.1 Standard Engine Out Procedure"},{"id":"93788","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"The memory items for Engine Severe Damage Separation L/R are:","options":{"A":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull, Thrust lever - idle","B":"Thrust lever - idle, Autothrottle arm switch - off, Engine fire switch - pull, Fuel control switch - cutoff","C":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - idle, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull","D":"Thrust lever - idle, Autothrottle arm switch - off, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull"},"answer":"C","reference":"QRH NNC Engine Severe Damage Separation L/R"},{"id":"93908","lastEdit":"12/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"When can the conversion of reported meteorological visibility to RVR table be used?","options":{"A":"When takeoff or landing minima is greater than 800m and RVR is not reported","B":"When calculating take-off minima that is greater than 500m and RVR is not reported","C":"When calculating landing minima that is greater than 800m and RVR is not reported","D":"When calculating take-off minima that is greater than 800m and visibility is not reported"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.4 Conversion of Reported Meteorological Visibility to RVR/CMV"},{"id":"94102","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the altitude source for transponder altitude reporting when the ALT SOURCE selector is in the ALT position?","options":{"A":"Air data modules","B":"SAARU","C":"IFSD","D":"ADIRU"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Management Nav, Controls and Indicators, Transponder Panel (Note this question is only for one type of transponder, the other type uses Left = ADIRU data, and Right = SAARU data)"},{"id":"94276","lastEdit":"07/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"In the case of a 4-man crew operation for a Long Range Variation flight, what is the protocol for managing a delay that exceeds 4 hours?","options":{"A":"A delay exceeding 4 hours allows for an extraordinary extension of up to 22 hours FDP, above 22 hours FDP a waiver may be issued by DSVP-FO or his designee","B":"A delay exceeding 4 hours allows for an extraordinary extension of up to 22 hours FDP, no extensions are available beyond the 22 hour limit","C":"Commander's discretion may be used for an FDP extension of up to 24 hours, however a formal report must be made to the GCAA within 72 hours","D":"The flight must be cancelled or a replacement crew found"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 7.E.7 Unforeseen circumstances after reporting time"},{"id":"94609","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"interview","question":"On an LRV flight, you're running out of duty time, what options do you have remaining?","options":{"A":"Utilize in flight relief from off duty flight crew travelling as pax","B":"Apply commanders discretion","C":"Apply for a waiver from DSVP-FO","D":"Burnout policy"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 7.E.8 Other unforeseen circumstances"},{"id":"94862","lastEdit":"05/03/2024","category":"both","question":"What indicates that the correct emergency access code has been entered for flight deck access?","options":{"A":"The flashing of a red DENY light and a single chime sound indicate the correct emergency access code has been entered, and the door remains locked indefinitely","B":"Illumination of the blue SECURE light and a continuous buzzer sound indicate the correct emergency access code has been entered, and the door is programmed to unlock after 30 seconds","C":"Annunciation of the flight deck chime and illumination of the amber AUTO UNLK light indicates the correct emergency access code has been entered, and the door is programmed to unlock after 30 seconds","D":"Annunciation of the flight deck chime and illumination of the green OPEN light indicates the correct emergency access code has been entered, and the door unlocks immediately"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Airplane General, Doors Windows Seats, Doors and Windows, Flight Deck Door"},{"id":"95031","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"Secondary external power never powers the right main bus","options":{"A":"BLANK","B":"BLANK","C":"True","D":"False"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM 6.20 AC Electrical System Power Sources"},{"id":"95216","lastEdit":"07/01/2024","category":"both","question":"On which CDU page can the GPS data be enabled/disabled?","options":{"A":"POS REF 3/3","B":"POS INIT 1/3","C":"ACT RTA PROGRESS 3/3","D":"The GPS position data function cannot be disabled"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Flight Management Naviation, Navaid Inhibit or Enable"},{"id":"95265","lastEdit":"08/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What are the memory items for Fire Engine on Ground L/R?","options":{"A":"There are no memory items","B":"Thrust levers - idle, Parking brake - set, Advise the cabin, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull, Engine fire switch - rotate to the stop and hold for 1 second","C":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - idle, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull","D":"Autothrottle arm switch - off, Thrust lever - idle, Fuel control switch - cutoff, Engine fire switch - pull, If the fire engine message stays shown - rotate to the stop and hold for 1 second"},"answer":"A","reference":"QRH NNC Fire Engine on Ground L/R (not to be confused with Fire Engine L/R)"},{"id":"95309","lastEdit":"30/12/2023","category":"tech","question":"You line up in fog with RVR's 125m 125m 125m, you require 125m for departure and the runway has high intensity runway centreline lights. How many centreline lights do you need to depart?","options":{"A":"6 lights","B":"3 lights","C":"8 lights","D":"9 lights"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.1.5.3.2 Takeoff Minima (see note 3 below table referencing all RVR's must be achieved and a 90m visual segment)"},{"id":"95312","lastEdit":"23/11/2024","category":"interview","question":"During hotel checkout, the Purser informs you that a cabin crew member woke up in the First Officer's bed without consent. What steps should you take to handle the situation while ensuring flight safety and proper procedure?","options":{"A":"Verify the situation discreetly. If a crime is suspected, contact law enforcement. Assess the crew's fitness to fly and replace/remove them if necessary. Notify CDM for investigation","B":"Immediately cancel the flight and wait for the local police to arrive and resolve the issue","C":"Assume it is a private matter and proceed with the flight without further action","D":"Allow the First Officer to operate the flight since their role is critical and leave the cabin crew member behind at the hotel, ensuring the flight departs on time"},"answer":"A","reference":"NO REFERENCE - A technique for a common interview question"},{"id":"95691","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What happens if you push the CAB transmitter select switch twice within one second?","options":{"A":"A pre-recorded message is sent to a pre-selected cabin station","B":"The second push cancels the selection","C":"A priority call is placed to a pre-selected cabin station","D":"A conference call is initiated with all cabin stations"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, Controls and Indicators, Audio Control Panel"},{"id":"95697","lastEdit":"19/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is an APV approach?","options":{"A":"Augmented precision approach and vertical guidance","B":"Approach procedure with vertical guidance (e.g. ILS)","C":"Approach procedure with vertical guidance (e.g. RNAV)","D":"Advanced precision approach with vertical guidance"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.3.2.2 Approach Procedure with vertical guidance - note it can't be ILS as that is a precision approach"},{"id":"95804","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"The minimum height for a turn is? (excluding when procedurally required)","options":{"A":"400 AGL","B":"200 AGL","C":"500 AGL","D":"1000 AGL"},"answer":"A","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.13 Initial Turns"},{"id":"95874","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"You plan a CAT3B autoland, which EICAS does NOT affect your approach and landing?","options":{"A":"SGL SOURCE RADALT","B":"SINGLE SOURCE AIR DATA","C":"SINGLE SOURCE ILS","D":"SGL SOURCE DISPLAYS"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCTM 5, Approach and Missed Approach, ILS Approach, AFDS Autoland Capabilities"},{"id":"96292","lastEdit":"10/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When can the aircraft not be taxiied from the right hand seat?","options":{"A":"When the taxiways, aprons or runways are contaminated or a 180 degree turn is required","B":"When the parking guidance system is calibrated to the left hand seat or a 180 degree turn is required or reduced engine taxi out (RETO) operations are required","C":"When the parking guidance system is calibrated to the left hand seat or a 180 degree turn is required","D":"When the parking guidance system is calibrated to the left hand seat or a 180 degree turn is required or the RVR/visibility is less than 500m"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.1.7 Taxi"},{"id":"96398","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the FAULT light in the L ENG primary HYDRAULIC PUMP switch indicate?","options":{"A":"Left engine is faulty","B":"Engine EGT is high or engine speed is low","C":"Left engine primary fuel pump is inoperative","D":"Hydraulic pump pressure is low or temperature is high"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Hydraulics, Controls and Indicators, Hydraulic Panel (Item 6)"},{"id":"96441","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"Where can you find the navigation specification for an airway?","options":{"A":"Lido under the specific country regulations","B":"Lido mPilot App, select the map near an airway, select NAV, select the airway identifier and see the information under NAVSPEC","C":"Boeing 777 Flight Management System","D":"RAIG Overflight Guide"},"answer":"B","reference":"Lido mPilot app"},{"id":"96578","lastEdit":"19/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the flight operations mission?","options":{"A":"To operate Emirates aircraft in the safest and most cost effective way","B":"To operate Emirates aircraft in the most flexible and most cost effective way","C":"To operate Emirates aircraft in the most economical and efficient manner","D":"To operate Emirates aircraft in the safest and most efficient manner"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 1.1 Flight Operations Mission Goals and Values"},{"id":"96585","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"interview","question":"When can a commander disregard FOLD and use OLD for landing performance?","options":{"A":"When the non normal checklist directs you to use OLD","B":"When VPNC authorizes","C":"When deemed necessary, such as abnormal/non normal situations","D":"When ETOPS certified"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.2.6.4.2 In flight landing distance requirements - Boeing"},{"id":"96634","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"both","question":"What will the autopilot do if you override the control column?","options":{"A":"Deviate from the flight path until the control column is released","B":"Engage in TRK HOLD and FPA","C":"Disengage","D":"Engage in ATT and V/S"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, System Description, Autopilot Flight Director System, Autopilot Disengagement"},{"id":"96686","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"After landing with a red bomb threat warning where should you plan to disembark the aircraft?","options":{"A":"On the runway","B":"At a remote parking location","C":"At the terminal stand","D":"On the taxiway"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 10.5.4.3 Actions Prior to Threat Classification"},{"id":"96750","lastEdit":"10/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Which weather information should you use to assess the probability of landing success when landing at an aerodrome?","options":{"A":"If more than three hours from the aerodrome weather forecasts should be used, within three hours from the aerodrome actual weather reports and trend may be used","B":"If more than two hours from the aerodrome weather forecasts and actual weather reports should be used, within two hours from the aerodrome actual weather reports and trend may be used","C":"If more than three hours from the aerodrome weather forecasts and actual weather reports should be used, within three hours from the aerodrome actual weather reports and trend may be used","D":"If more than two hours from the aerodrome weather forecasts should be used, within two hours from the aerodrome actual weather reports and trend may be used"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.7.2 In Flight Fuel Management"},{"id":"96839","lastEdit":"20/08/2024","category":"interview","question":"During the cruise the flight deck number 1 left hand window shatters and you cannot see anything through it, which non-normal checklist can assist you?","options":{"A":"CABIN ALTITUDE","B":"WINDOW DAMAGE FWD L","C":"WINDOW HEAT FWD","D":"WINDOW DAMAGE FWD R"},"answer":"B","reference":"NNC WINDOW DAMAGE FWD L"},{"id":"96847","lastEdit":"24/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What is the typical hazard area and duration of microbursts?","options":{"A":"Extend over 5 miles in diameter and last for 30-45 minutes","B":"Span approximately 10 miles in diameter with a duration of 20-30 minutes","C":"Have a hazard area of 2.5 miles or less in diameter and a duration of 10-15 minutes","D":"Cover less than 1 mile in diameter and persist for 5-10 minutes"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMC 10.2.2.1.1 Windshear Definitions"},{"id":"96856","lastEdit":"14/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"Above which airport elevation does the OMC 12.5.3 High Elevation Destinations procedure come into effect?","options":{"A":"2000 feet","B":"4000 feet","C":"3000 feet","D":"5000 feet"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMC 12.5.3 High Elevation Destinations B777 and B77F"},{"id":"96880","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"other","question":"An altitude that ensures adequate reception of relevant navigation facilities and ATS communications is the definition of what?","options":{"A":"MEA","B":"MSA","C":"MGA","D":"MTCA"},"answer":"A","reference":"LIDO 1.4.2.11.1.5"},{"id":"96902","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"When flying a 2D approach in LNAV and FPA or V/S, the FAF crossing altitude is 1950 feet. What altitude do you select in the MCP when 5 miles away from the FAF? And when do you set the missed approach altitude?","options":{"A":"1900 feet and set the missed approach altitude 300 feet above MDA","B":"1900 feet and set the missed approach altitude 300 feet below the missed approach altitude and after the FAF","C":"2000 feet and set the missed approach altitude 300 feet above MDA","D":"2000 feet and set the missed approach altitude 300 feet below the missed approach altitude and after the FAF"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Sup Procedure, Instrument Approach using vertical speed or FPA (set the MCP altitude to the nearest 100 foot increment below each altitude constraint) + (approximately 300 feet above MDA...MCP set missed approach alt)"},{"id":"96971","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is wheel to rudder cross-tie?","options":{"A":"A function which enables aircraft steering through nose wheel and rudder pedals on ground only","B":"A function which provides the capability to control the initial effect of an engine failure using yaw inputs only","C":"A function which provides the capability to control the initial effect of an engine failure using roll inputs only","D":"A function which connects the main gear aft axle steering with the rudder pedals"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Controls, System Description, Normal Mode Yaw Control, Wheel to Rudder Cross tie"},{"id":"97081","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What are the flight crew responsibilities during fuelling?","options":{"A":"Establish communication with the mechanic by means that remain available during fuelling operations, Be prepared to initiate passenger evacuation if necessary, Alert the fire services if a fuel spillage has occurred","B":"Establish communication with the engineer by means that remain available during fuelling operations, Be prepared to initiate passenger evacuation into the terminal, Ensure that mood lighting is not used in the cabin until refuelling is completed","C":"Establish communication with the dispatcher by means that remain available during fuelling operations, Be prepared to initiate passenger evacuation into the terminal, Make the fuelling PA informing the passengers that refuelling is taking place and that seat belts shall not be fastened","D":"Establish communication with the engineer by means that remain available during fuelling operations, Be prepared to initiate passenger evacuation if necessary, Inform Cabin Crew of the completion of fuelling operations by switching the seat belt sign on"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.3 Refuelling or Defuelling when passengers embarking, on board or disembarking"},{"id":"97149","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does EICAS APU SHUTDOWN message mean?","options":{"A":"APU is cooling down and will shortly shutdown","B":"APU has to be manually shutdown due to a fault","C":"APU is out of fuel","D":"APU has shutdown automatically"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, EICAS Messages, EICAS Alert Messages (no explicit reference to automatic shutdown)"},{"id":"97174","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What is the status of the below TCAS indication? (Filled white diamond with minus 05 next to it, and a down arrow)","options":{"A":"TCAS proximate traffic: Traffic is below the airplane and descending","B":"TCAS other traffic: Traffic is below the airplane and climbing","C":"TCAS proximate traffic: Traffic is above the airplane and climbing","D":"TCAS other traffic: Traffic is above the airplane and descending"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Systems, Flight Instruments, Navigation Displays, Typical ND Map Displays, ND Symbology"},{"id":"97271","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"In what positions should the INBOARD DSPL selectors be during pre-flight stage?","options":{"A":"CM1 on MFD, CM2 on MFD","B":"CM1 on PFD, CM2 on NAV","C":"CM1 on MFD, CM2 on NAV","D":"CM1 on PFD, CM2 on MFD"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - First Officer + FCOM Normal Procedures, Amplified Procedures, Preflight Procedure - Captain"},{"id":"97535","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"The flight directors are off for takeoff, what happens when TOGA switches are pressed after 80 knots?","options":{"A":"Nothing","B":"The flight directors are automatically shown","C":"The thrust de-rate is removed","D":"The thrust de-rate is removed and flight directors are automatically shown"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM Systems, Automatic Flight, Controls and Indicators, Autothrottle Disconnect and TOGA Switches"},{"id":"97648","lastEdit":"01/11/2023","category":"other","question":"Cruising at FL350 you enter severe turbulence, what speed do you fly?","options":{"A":"M0.83 or 280 knots, whichever is lower. Maintaining 15 knots of above the minimum manoeuvring speed when airspeed is below M0.82","B":"M0.82 or 270 knots, whichever is lower. Maintaining 15 knots of above the minimum manoeuvring speed when airspeed is below M0.82","C":"M0.83 or 270 knots, whichever is lower. Maintaining 15 knots of above the minimum manoeuvring speed when airspeed is below M0.82","D":"M0.82 or 280 knots, whichever is lower. Maintaining 15 knots of above the minimum manoeuvring speed when airspeed is below M0.82"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Limitations Severe Turbulent Air Penetration Speed"},{"id":"97774","lastEdit":"04/01/2025","category":"interview","question":"What does PRESFR remark mean when used in a United States METAR?","options":{"A":"Pressure fluctuating rapidly","B":"Present fog risk","C":"Pressure falling rapidly","D":"Present freezing rain"},"answer":"C","reference":"LIDO 3.190.15.1.4 Abbreviations Used by National Weather Service - see PRESFR"},{"id":"97851","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"When will the EICAS ANTI-ICE ON message be displayed?","options":{"A":"TAT above 10 Celsius, all anti-ice selectors on and ice is detected","B":"TAT below 10 Celsius, all anti-ice selectors off and no ice is detected","C":"TAT below 10 Celsius, all anti-ice selectors on and no ice is detected","D":"TAT above 10 Celsius, all anti-ice selectors on and no ice is detected"},"answer":"D","reference":"QRH NNC Anti-Ice On"},{"id":"97890","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is auto-relight?","options":{"A":"Auto-relight opens the start valve automatically if the engine fails to start","B":"Auto-relight provides hung start protection by deactivating the ignitor","C":"Auto-relight provides flameout protection by activating the AutoStart system","D":"Auto-relight provides flameout protection by activating the respective engine ignitors"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Engines APU, Engine System Description, Engine Start and Ignition System, Auto Relight"},{"id":"97936","lastEdit":"04/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does the illuminated FLT Interphone CALL light on the audio control panel indicate?","options":{"A":"A SELCAL is incoming","B":"Someone is calling the flight deck on VHF radio","C":"The FLT transmit switch is stuck in the ON position","D":"A ground crew technician is calling the flight deck"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Comms, Controls and Indicators, Audio Control Panel"},{"id":"97975","lastEdit":"06/11/2023","category":"other","question":"What does EICAS BOTTLE DISCH APU and APU BTL DISCH on overhead panel indicate during preflight?","options":{"A":"These are normal indications prior to APU start","B":"APU fire bottle squibs are inoperative","C":"Ground maintenance is servicing the APU fire bottle","D":"APU fire bottle has discharged"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Fire Protection, System Description, APU Fire Protection, APU Fire Extinguishing"},{"id":"98066","lastEdit":"19/07/2024","category":"tech","question":"What controls the pack flow control valves when there is a complete loss of cabin temperature controllers or all engine and APU electrical power fails?","options":{"A":"The left and right packs","B":"The trim air valves and recirculation fans","C":"The air supply and cabin pressurization controllers","D":"The forward and aft outflow valves"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM - Systems Description - Air Systems - Air Conditioning System Description - Temperature Control - Temperature Control with loss of trim air"},{"id":"98105","lastEdit":"05/04/2024","category":"both","question":"After take-off, when is the automatic wing anti-icing operation inhibited, and how can this inhibition be overridden, including the role of the Flight Management Computer (FMC) in this process?","options":{"A":"Automatic wing anti-icing is inhibited during takeoff and initial climb until either the Flight Director, Autopilot, and/or Flight Management Computer TAKEOFF mode is not active, or 5 minutes have elapsed after liftoff. This inhibit can be overridden by the flight crew by manually selecting the Wing Anti-Ice to ON, which may result in reduced performance","B":"The automatic wing anti-icing is inhibited for a fixed period of 10 minutes after take-off, regardless of FMC TAKEOFF mode status, and cannot be manually overridden","C":"The automatic wing anti-icing is inhibited for a fixed period of 5 minutes after take-off, regardless of FMC TAKEOFF mode status, and cannot be manually overridden","D":"Automatic wing anti-icing is inhibited during takeoff and initial climb until either the Flight Director, Autopilot, and/or Flight Management Computer TAKEOFF mode is not active, or 10 minutes have elapsed after liftoff. This inhibit can be overridden by the flight crew by manually selecting the Wing Anti-Ice to ON, which may result in reduced performance"},"answer":"D","reference":"FCOM Systems, Anti-Ice Rain, System Description, Anti-Icing Systems, Wing Anti-Icing"},{"id":"98342","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What is Final Reserve Fuel?","options":{"A":"Fuel required to fly for 30 minutes at holding speed at 1500 feet above aerodrome elevation in forecast conditions, calculated on the estimated mass on arrival at the destination alternate","B":"Fuel required to fly for 30 minutes at holding speed at 1500 feet above aerodrome elevation in standard conditions, calculated on the aircraft maximum landing mass on arrival at the destination alternate","C":"Fuel required to fly for 30 minutes at holding speed at 1500 feet above aerodrome elevation in standard conditions, calculated on the estimated mass on arrival at the destination alternate","D":"Fuel required to fly for 45 minutes at holding speed at 1500 feet above aerodrome elevation in forecast conditions, calculated on the aircraft maximum landing mass on arrival at the destination alternate"},"answer":"C","reference":"OMA 8.1.7.1.5 Final Reserve Fuel"},{"id":"98547","lastEdit":"14/01/2025","category":"other","question":"Which ND mode does NOT display weather radar information?","options":{"A":"VOR","B":"APP centered","C":"MAP","D":"ILS"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCOM, Systems, Flight Instruments, Controls and Indicators, EFIS Control Panels, EFIS Control Panel ND Controls"},{"id":"98562","lastEdit":"05/02/2024","category":"other","question":"What are the Flight Crew duties during fuelling?","options":{"A":"Be ready to evacuate, establish communications with the dispatcher by a means that remains available, inform the cabin crew of completion of fuelling by informing the Purser","B":"Establish communications with the dispatcher by a means that remains available, inform the cabin crew of completion of fuelling by switching on the seatbelt sign, ensure at least three cabin doors are designated and be made available for a possible evacuation","C":"Ensure at least one passenger door is designated and made available for a possible evacuation, inform the cabin crew of completion of fuelling by switching on the seatbelt sign, establish communications with the engineer by a means that remains available","D":"Inform the cabin crew of completion of fuelling by switching on the seatbelt sign, establish communications with the engineer by a means that remains available, be ready to evacuate"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.2.1.3 Refuelling or Defuelling when passengers embarking, on board or disembarking"},{"id":"98567","lastEdit":"01/02/2024","category":"interview","question":"When approaching an airport in CAVOK weather without GPS and the ILS is out of service, which approaches remain available?","options":{"A":"ILS, VOR/DME, Visual","B":"RNP, VOR/DME, Circling (coded), Visual","C":"Surveillance Radar Approach, VOR/DME, Visual","D":"VOR/DME, Circling (coded), Visual"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.3.20.2.17 Selection of Approach Procedure"},{"id":"99067","lastEdit":"23/01/2025","category":"other","question":"When flying inside an ETOPS segment you check the weather and find your ETOPS alternate has gone below approach minima, what is your course of action? (assuming another ETOPS alternate is not suitable)","options":{"A":"Divert","B":"Continue or re-route","C":"Re-route","D":"Return to departure airport"},"answer":"B","reference":"OMA 8.5.4.2 In Flight Minima"},{"id":"99099","lastEdit":"29/03/2024","category":"other","question":"What is an INAD?","options":{"A":"An inadmissible passenger, the Captain must be informed of their location onboard","B":"Instruction Notice for Airline Dispatch, must be signed by the Captain and a copy retained on ground before departure","C":"Investigation Notes And Documents, must be stored in the flight deck and handed over to ground staff on arrival","D":"An inadmissible passenger, must be offloaded and the dispatcher informed"},"answer":"A","reference":"OME 11.5.18.1 Aviation Security, Aviation Security, Security Measures, Inadmissible, Inadmissible Passengers"},{"id":"99358","lastEdit":"03/11/2023","category":"tech","question":"What is the sequence of steps to use FLCH to climb to FL250 at 280 knots?","options":{"A":"Set 280 knots in the IAS/MACH window, push FLCH switch, then set FL250 in the altitude window","B":"Set FL280 in the altitude window, push FLCH switch, then set 250 knots in the IAS/MACH window","C":"Set FL250 in the altitude window, push FLCH switch, then set 280 knots in the IAS/MACH window","D":"Push FLCH switch, set FL250 in the altitude window, then set 280 knots in the IAS/MACH window"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Supplementary Procedures, Automatic Flight, AFDS, Flight Level Change Climb or Descent"},{"id":"99564","lastEdit":"20/11/2023","category":"other","question":"When a tire failure occurs in flight, when is towing necessary?","options":{"A":"After more than two failures on one axle","B":"After more than one failure or unusual vibration","C":"After more than one failure or unusual noise","D":"After more than two failures on one gear"},"answer":"B","reference":"FCTM 8 Non Normal, Landing Gear, Landing on a flat tire"},{"id":"99615","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"What is the prescribed rate of descent for Continuous Descent Operations (CDO) according to Germany's aviation regulations?","options":{"A":"300 feet per minute","B":"500 feet per nautical mile","C":"500 feet per minute","D":"300 feet per nautical mile"},"answer":"D","reference":"LIDO CRAR, Germany 3.72.3.3 Continuous Descent Operations (CDO)"},{"id":"99664","lastEdit":"07/09/2024","category":"tech","question":"A crewmember should not fly within 12 hours of a no-compression dive. Up to how many hours are required if the dive required decompression stops?","options":{"A":"18","B":"36","C":"12","D":"24"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 6.1.14 Deep Diving"},{"id":"99890","lastEdit":"14/05/2024","category":"tech","question":"The flight deck receives conditioned air from which system?","options":{"A":"The left engine bleed air system","B":"APU conditioned air","C":"Right pack ram air","D":"Centre bleed system"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM 2.20 Air distribution: Ã¢â‚¬Ëœthe flight deck receives 100% fresh conditioned air from the left packÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ - which is in turn fed by the left bleed in normal circumstances. A poorly worded question but it features in the real exam"},{"id":"99906","lastEdit":"21/03/2024","category":"tech","question":"What is the purpose of dedicated batteries used by flight control power supply assemblies?","options":{"A":"To prevent power interruptions to the related flight control DC bus. The batteries have limited capacity and are incorporated to supply power for brief periods during PSA power source transfers","B":"To prevent power interruptions to the related flight control DC bus. The batteries are incorporated to supply power during electrical malfunctions","C":"As a temporary backup to hydraulic systems","D":"To enable a reduced flight envelope with a complete loss of electrics and hydraulics"},"answer":"A","reference":"FCOM 6.20 Flight Control DC Electrical System"},{"id":"99927","lastEdit":"11/07/2024","category":"interview","question":"When a flight has the destination as an ETOPS alternate, which preflight weather minima apply?","options":{"A":"The charted minima for the downgraded approach (if CAT 2/3 then CAT 1 minima, if CAT 1 then non precision minima)","B":"The charted minima +400 feet added DA/MDA and 1500m visibility","C":"The charted minima","D":"The ETOPS en-route alternate aerodrome minima"},"answer":"D","reference":"OMA 8.5.4 ETOPS Weather Requirements (the previous allowance to use charted minima has been deleted from the OMA)"},{"id":"99981","lastEdit":"15/01/2025","category":"other","question":"What determines the pack outlet temperature?","options":{"A":"The master cabin temperature control","B":"The zone requiring the warmest temperature","C":"The zone requiring the coolest temperature","D":"The average demand of all zones"},"answer":"C","reference":"FCOM Systems, General, Air, Air Conditioning System Description, Temperature Control"}];